(2, 'Downing Street today is seen as the powerhouse of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland. It is where the Prime Minister and the Chancellor of the Exchequer live and where Cabinet meetings are usually held, namely in the Cabinet Room of 10 Downing Street, the Prime Minister\'s official residence.<br><br>\r\nWhat isn’t well known is that Downing Street didn’t become the residence of the Prime Minister until 1732. So, what was there before then?<br>\r\nIn the middle ages Downing Street itself didn’t even exist. It’s vague what was on the site originally but there is evidence towards a brewhouse called ‘The Axe’ that was owned by the Abbey of Abingdon. By the 16th Century ‘The Axe’ sadly fell into disuse.<br><br> In 1581 Sir Thomas Knyvet built the first residential house roughly on the site of Number 10. It was known as ‘The House on the Back’ at the time. Sir Thomas Knyvet was a favourite of Queen Elizabeth I and was actually the person responsible for arresting Guy Fawkes after the gunpowder plot against King James I of England and VI of Scotland.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Portrait of Sir George Downing painted c. 1675–1690 by Thomas Smith, The Fogg Museum.jpeg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/The_Old_Palace_of_Whitehall_by_Hendrik_Danckerts.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/800px-Robertwalpole.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:50px; position: relative; left:-10px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Portrait of Sir George Downing painted c. 1675–1690 by Thomas Smith, The Fogg Museum\r\n					<span>\r\n						Thomas Smith (d. 1691, active 1670s–1680s) - <a href=\"https://harvardartmuseums.org\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color:inherit;\">harvardartmuseums.org</a>\r\n					</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The Palace of Whitehall by Hendrick Danckerts c. 1660–1679. Viewed from the west side of St James\'s Park, the \"House at the Back\" is on the far right; the octagonal building next to it is the Cockpit.\r\n					<span>Hendrick Danckerts / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Sir Robert Walpole accepted George II\'s gift of the house at the back and two Downing Street houses on behalf of the office of First Lord of the Treasury.\r\n					<span>Workshop of Jean-Baptiste van Loo (Wikimedia Commons)</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\nIt wasn’t until the 1680’s when Sir George Downing, 1st Baronet, started to build in Downing Street. Downing started to acquire land around the site through leases to build a row of townhouses and a cul-de-sac. Sir Christopher Wren was even brought in to design the houses. Although the houses were large, they were built quickly and cheaply and built on soft soil with shallow foundations. Even the fronts had facades with lines painted on the surface to imitate brick mortar. It is said that Sir George Downing never lived in the townhouses himself and retired to Cambridge where he died a few months after they were completed in 1684.<br><br> Right before Downing Street became the official residence of the Prime Minister - or the First Lord of the Treasury as it was known then - the last person to live in one of the three properties which comprise of 10 Downing Street today was called Mr. Chicken. There is no other information on Mr. Chicken other than his name and that he moved out in 1732 after Sir Robert Walpole convinced him to. It was after he moved out that King Charles II presented both houses to Walpole as a personal gift. Walpole didn’t accept the property as a gift unless the King made it available to him and all future First Lords of the Treasury in their official capacity. This title can be seen engraved on the letterbox on the black front door today even though the title ‘Prime Minister’ was introduced in 1905.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Gates-at-the-main-entrance-of-Downing-Street,-Westminster,-London..jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/4446148131_f03549c784_b.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/1200px-Barack_Obama_and_Gordon_Brown_in_10_Downing_Street.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Churchill_V_sign_HU_55521.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1;margin-bottom: 0px; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 4 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Gates at the Main Entrance of Downing Street, Westminister, London.\r\n\r\n					<span>Garry Knight / Entrance of Downing Street / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Downing Street <span>\r\n					Robert Sharp / London / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					President Barack Obama is welcomed to 10 Downing Street in London by British Prime Minister Gordon Brown, April 1, 2009\r\n					<span>Official White House Photo by Pete Souza</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Winston Churchill emerging from Number 10 holding up the \"V\" sign for \"Victory\"\r\n					<span>British Government / Collections of the Imperial War Museums / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>', 'Downing Street', '2018-07-26 9:15 pm', 'figure0748-108.gif', 'topics', '51.503181', '-0.126289', 0, 5, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 6),
(3, 'In 1948, the British Nationality Act declared that all Commonwealth citizens (inhabitants of former British colonies), had the right to freely to enter and settle in Britain. Due to the ‘depressed economic situation’ in Jamaica at this time, when an advertisement in the Daily Gleaner offered passage to Britain for £28.10, many West Indians seized the chance to seek further employment and education opportunities in the ‘Mother country’.  Following a 22-day journey from Jamaica, on June 22nd 1948, the SS Empire Windrush arrived in Britain, docking just outside of London in Tilbury, Essex.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Empire-Windrush.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The \'Empire Windrush\' arriving in London, England in 1948 bringing Immigrants from the Caribbean to the UK.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nStarting life as a German cruise boat, the Empire Windrush eventually wound up in Kingston, Jamaica, where it then set sail for the British Isles, officially carrying 492 Caribbean passengers, although this number is believed to be greater as the ship contained a number of stowaways.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nOf this number, many had already visited British shores - 120 were in fact ex-servicemen who had fought with British forces during the war.  As post-war prosperity kicked-in, British industry found itself lacking the manpower to meet economic expansion. Many British employers thus looked to the former colonies in order to supply the labour needed to facilitate the rejuvenation of British industry.\r\n\r\n<h1> From Jamaica to Britain </h1>\r\nPassengers of the Empire Windrush and those that were to follow, set their sights on the British Isles for a number of reasons. For many, like Clinton Edwards who had served with the RAF during the war, “the opportunity for jobs was better than back home”.  Arthur Curling, also a former member of the British Airforce, felt that after his experience of traveling outside of the Caribbean, Jamaica simply felt “too small”.  Whilst many intended to settle in Britain permanently, others planned to move back after learning a trade or simply viewed Britain as a stepping stone on their way to America.  But regardless of individual motivations for the journey, for those undertaking the now historic voyage, coming to Britain represented the start of a new chapter.\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/WINDRUSH-GENERATION.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Jamaican immigrants welcomed by RAF officials from the Colonial Office after the ex-troopship HMT ‘Empire Windrush’ landed them at Tilbury\r\n        <span>\r\n			(Picture: PA)\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPrior to entering Britain, many passengers had self-organised employment and accommodation.  With the government apparently keen to ‘disperse’ the newcomers as quickly as possible, upon arrival those who had made such prior arrangements were issued free travel permits to get to them where they needed to go.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThose without such plans were transported from Tilbury to London and hastily sheltered at the Deep Shelter at Clapham South, which had been re-opened for the purpose.  180 steps below ground, this subterranean shelter had previously acted as a place of refuge for many Londoners during the blitz.  But in 1948, at the behest of the Colonial Office, it became the temporary home of 236 expectant individuals.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAt the opening of the shelter, the newcomers were greeted by a welcome tent where each resident was ‘checked-in’, allocated a bunk and issued with a blanket and linen sheet.  After descending into what one passenger described as “the bowels of South London,” the group became acquainted with their first British home-base.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/New-Arrivals.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/New-arrivals-2.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/clapham_south_old9.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					The new arrivals were interviewed by the Ministry of Labour and National Service Office to help them find work.\r\n					<span>Source: Mirror.co.uk // Topfoto</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Underground bunk beds with Windrush passengers.<span>\r\n					Source: BBC. </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Jamaican immigrants using the shelter as a hostel in July 1948. \r\n					<span>Source: subbrit.org.uk</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nOne passenger noted: <mark>We curiously eyed the network of poorly lit, clammy, musty tunnels that had been offered as residence. It was primitive and unwelcoming, like a sparsely furnished rabbit’s warren. </mark>\r\n<br><br>\r\nFortunately, few of the deep shelter’s new inhabitants were subjected to these surroundings for too long. Utilising the local labour exchange in Cold harbour Lane, Brixton, within a month nearly all had secured accommodation and employment.  Taking up positions in a range of environments including the NHS and transport services, the new arrivals found work in essential industries that were key to post-war regeneration.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nOutwardly, the Colonial Office congratulated themselves for a job well done. However, as had been the case since the imminence of the ship’s arrival, internal conversations were less encouraging.\r\n<br><br>\r\nAfter learning of the Windrush’s imminent arrival, many alarmed MPs expressed their concern to Prime Minister Atlee, stating:\r\n“The British people fortunately enjoy a profound unity without uniformity in their way of life, and we are blest by the absence of a colour racial problem. An influx of coloured people domiciled here is likely to impair the harmony, strength and cohesion of our public and social life.”\r\n<br><br>\r\nHowever, after the war, in a bid to move away from a pre-war ‘imperial dominance’, Britain was eager to demonstrate its commitment to the creation of a fairer society. As part of such commitment, the Labour government desired to forge a new, more familial relationship with Commonwealth countries.  It was amidst this collaborative spirit that the 1948 Nationality Act and Commonwealth recruitment drives emerged.\r\n<br><br>\r\nUnfortunately, the unwelcoming attitude expressed by certain MPs was also manifest in numerous British newspapers. News of the hostility reached the Caribbean, prompting concern over the potentially negative treatment was awaiting migrants. In response the Atlee government was keen to publicly alleviate any unease.  As historian Kenneth Lunn notes, any indication of restrictions or attitudes “which smacked of a ‘colour bar’”, risked provoking charges of racism that the government wished to avoid.\r\n<br><br>\r\nBut, whilst the British government was anxious to avoid appearing unwelcoming, at the same time a governmental feeling existed within Whitehall that a precedent should not be set. Many MPs wished to avoid providing too warm a welcome. They did not want to run the risk of encouraging others to follow suit and turning the country into what was described as “an open reception centre for immigrants”.  A further governmental concern was that the migrants be dispersed across the country as soon as possible.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe logic being that if the new arrivals were scattered widely enough, their presence would be less likely to attract negative attention, such as had already been seen in port communities such as Liverpool which was home to an existing black community.  As the Windrush approached, tensions arose between the Colonial Office, the Home Office and the Ministry of Labour - each department was keen to avoid assuming responsibility for facilitating the newcomers’ imminent arrival.  On the outside an apparent open door policy prevailed. Behind closed doors tensions about the implications of the new arrivals were bubbling.\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nYet, no formal policy in relation to West Indian immigration was formulated. Despite a recorded deterioration in race relations during the immediate post war years, and an awareness of hostile public attitudes towards black settlement, the government failed to enact legislation against racial discrimination.  Concerns over the treatment of the West Indian migrants were voiced. Yet, for various reasons, no solid action was taken to safeguard the reception and treatment of migrant communities.\r\n<br><br>\r\nWithin this period of ambivalence, although the official line was that the new arrivals had been settled and dispersed with apparent ease, in reality the country’s new inhabitants received a less than warm welcome. Many experienced extreme racism and intolerance from certain areas of society, denied access to certain employment opportunities and better housing on basis of their skin-colour.   As a result of this discrimination, many of the West Indian migrants ended up settling in “the meanest housing” of inner city London in areas such as Brixton and Notting Hill where they faced “slum landlords, high rents and overcrowding”.  Making the line the official governmental line of ‘success’ difficult to understand.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h1> Long-term Impact </h1>\r\nThe way post-war governmental approaches to immigration have shaped the longer-term experiences of the Windrush community. In light of the 2018 ‘Windrush Scandal’ and the wrongful deportation of a number of individuals, it is evident that the after-shocks of the poor treatement of the Windrush generation experienced in the years proceeding 1948 is still being felt today.\r\n<br><br>\r\nFollowing the 1948 Nationality Act, those arriving from Commonwealth countries were legally British subjects, however for many who came to Britain between 1948 and 1971, the experience has not always reflected this. As British citizens, those arriving with the Windrush generation were not immigrants, but migrants. Yet following their arrival, race became a marker used to strip these legal citizens of social acceptance.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/We-are-not-illegal.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:-30px;\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Windrush scandal is a 2018 British political scandal concerning people who were wrongly detained, denied legal rights, threatened with deportation, and, in around 63 cases, wrongly deported from the UK. Many of those affected are members of the Windrush generation.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Image: © Peter Marshall / Global Look Press.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nWhilst Britain had long been a multicultural country, the arrival of the Windrush signalled the advent of substantial and permanent black communities in Britain.  Headlines may have read ‘Welcome Home’, but in reality, beyond the initial arrival of the first new arrivals, there was a lack of governmental policy in place designed to maintain support and integration for those settling in Britain from Commonwealth nations.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nDespite this, plans were in place to recruit from the Caribbean in order to satisfy the need for labour in key industries, such as London transport which was actively advertising vacancies in Barbados.  By 1958, there were around 125,000 Caribbean workers in Britain, with a disproportionate amount of these individuals represented in semi and unskilled roles. Due to the absence of official support, in addition to a concentration of black migrants in certain industries, migrants were left to secure housing through an “informal network of support”.  This led to a clustering of black migrants in certain urban areas, which made their presence seem greater and caused alarm to many of the local white population.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h1> Racism </h1>\r\nAs Caribbean migration grew, so too did the racist attitude of many white Britons towards the growing black communities. Claiming that the newcomers were taking jobs from capable White Britons, during the 1950s there was an increasingly hostile attitude towards black people. The growing concern over the ‘dangers of unrestricted immigration’ was reflected within the media, the tone of which had shifted from support of unrestricted migrant labour to one of suspicion.  It was not uncommon for black citizens to face discrimination in a number of public environments including, hotels, shops, schools or housing.\r\n<br><br>\r\nFascist groups such as Oswald Mosley’s fascist Union Movement, Colin Jordan’s White Defence League and the League of Empire Loyalists added fuel to the fire. Yet there was still no recourse from the law to address the mounting racism within the country, which led to violent clashes during the 1958 Notting Hill Riots.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Oswald-Mosley.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/1958 Notting Hill race riots.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/KBW.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Oswald Mosley, leader of the British Union of Fascists, at a rally in East London.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The Notting Hill race riots were a series of racially motivated riots that took place in Notting Hill, England, between 29 August and 5 September 1958.\r\n					<span>\r\n					Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Young lady points to \'Keep Britain White\' graffiti at the International Personnel training centre in Balham.\r\n					<span>Source: Neil Kenlock // Tate</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\nIn response to growing racial tension at the influx of new arrivals, in 1962, the Commonwealth Immigration Act was passed in order to curb the number of those travelling from Commonwealth countries into Britain.  The act introduced a system that required hopeful migrants to obtain government-issued work permits before they could enter.  But it was not until 1965 that policy directly addressing racial discrimination was made when the Race Relations Act came into effect making racial discrimination unlawful in public spaces.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nRelating to both British citizens and visitors, the law prohibited any form of discrimination based on a person’s colour, race or ethnic origins. Whilst there were those who resisted such reform, it was criticised for not going far enough. For example, it did not cover housing or employment where the issue was often most prevalent. This led to the passing of the Race Relations Act 1968 which sought to address areas such as housing, employment and advertising which were previously omitted.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"side-note\">\r\nThe Race Relations Act 1968 was an Act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom making it illegal to refuse housing, employment, or public services to a person on the grounds of colour, race, ethnic or national origins. It also created the Community Relations Commission to promote \'harmonious community relations\'. Wikipedia\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 1971 the Immigration Act gave all Commonwealth Citizens already living in the UK indefinite leave to remain. In a further bid to control the number of people settling in the UK, the law also put an end to freedom of movement for Commonwealth citizens.  However, the Home Office never issued paperwork for those granted leave to remain to confirm their status, nor did they keep a record of those affected by the act.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nFast forward a number of decades and the ‘Windrush Scandal’ appears to be a part of the wider continuum of black British experience. After being invited to Britain to provide vital support in the post-war reconstruction efforts, many British citizens have found themselves having their legal status questioned.  In addition to the absence of records created and issued during the 1970s, it has come to light that in 2010 the landing cards completed by incoming Commonwealth citizens, which were being stored by the Home Office, had been destroyed.  This lack of paperwork has led to serious problems for many of the Windrush generation. In 2012, strict changes to immigration law designed to target illegal immigration required that people provide the documentation confirming their right to work, rent or have access to healthcare.\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Hosstile-Environment.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:-30px;\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The UK Home Office hostile environment policy is a set of administrative and legislative measures designed to make staying in the United Kingdom as difficult as possible for people without leave to remain, in the hope that they may \"voluntarily leave\".\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikipedia\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nAlthough legal citizens, many of the Windrush generation unable to produce the necessary paperwork have suddenly found their legal status questioned. The number of those affected remains unclear, as many of the Windrush generation travelled on parental passports and never applied for travel documents of their own. After being born or living in Britain for decades, a number of individuals have been wrongfully threatened with deportation to countries they may have not seen for 50 years.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nFor some, the image of hundreds of Caribbean-born individuals filing off the ship’s gangplank in 1948 has become synonymous with “the beginning of modern British multicultural society”.  It is estimated that following the arrival of the Windrush and its passengers in 1948, by 1971 nearly half a million West Indian-born individuals left their homes to settle in Britain. This Caribbean diaspora has come to be known as the Windrush Generation.\r\n<br><br>\r\nWhen this piece of Black & British history has been given close attention, there has been a tendency to depict the arrival of the Windrush as a watershed moment in the history of black migration to Britain, prompting questions of race and the formation of the modern British identity.  It has been depicted as the ‘symbolic point of origin’ from which narratives surrounding British citizens of African descent should stem.\r\n<br><br>\r\nAccording to this perspective, 1948 is extoled as the opening chapter of the tumultuous road to becoming contemporary multicultural Britain. However, recent years have witnessed concerted efforts to re-think this narrative. As Barnor Hesse reminds us in his book Un/settled Multiculturalisms, the portrayal of Black Britain as a post-war phenomenon is misleading, overlooking the individual stories of people of African descent who settled in Britain prior to 1948.\r\n<br><br>\r\nFurthermore, it suggests that racial tension within Britain is a relatively ‘recent’ issue resulting from the demographic upheaval of the post-war years, when in fact the problem of racism in Britain has a much longer history. To gain a deeper understanding of Britain’s migration history is to gain a better understanding of our current identity. Failure to do so is to perpetuate the historical amnesia that leads to the ignorance and prejudice that we must work to eradicate.\r\n', 'Windrush Generation', '2018-08-05 7:32 am', 'Windrush_Picture.jpg', 'topics', '', '', 0, 1, 0, 0, 2, 1, NULL, 6),
(4, 'Situated at the junction of Lexington Street and Broadwick Street is The John Snow, a public house that has honoured its nineteenth-century namesake since 1958. This site proves both a historic and modern appreciation for the work on public health by Dr John Snow, making it an important piece of London’s medical and social history. Snow was credited with advancing epidemiology (the study of the spread of disease) and moving past outdated theories of contagion. <br><br>\r\n   \r\n\r\nThe pub itself stands on Broadwick Street, previously known as Broad Street, around which Snow famously surveyed an outbreak of cholera in 1854. After successfully tracing the disease back to a contaminated water pump the handle was removed and instances of cholera, although already declining, continued to wane. A replica of this handleless pump was erected nearby on Broadwick Street in 1992 and was, along with The John Snow and various commemorative plaques in the area, a popular icon of the physician’s important contributions to public health. The replica was removed in 2015 due to ongoing building improvements, however has yet to return and is instead marked by a piece of red granite.\r\n\r\n        <br>\r\n       <div align=\"center\" class=\"article-img-wrapper\">\r\n            <img class=\"img\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/John-Snow.jpg\">\r\n            <div class=\"caption\">\r\n                <i>Dr. John Snow (1813-1858), British physician. (Wikimedia Commons)</i>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n    \r\nBorn to a farming family in York, England in 1813, it can definitely be said that Snow was from humble beginnings. A commemorative plaque and water pump similar to those on Broadwick Street mark his origins in North Street, York, over 200 miles north of The John Snow in the capital. \r\n<br />\r\nAt the age of fourteen Snow worked as a medical apprentice in Newcastle, England, and witnessed the Newcastle cholera epidemic of 1831-32. Whether this peaked his interest in the prevalent and deadly disease is unclear, but nevertheless Snow went on to train as a physician in the years following. \r\n         \r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nHis prowess within medicine is evident from his various memberships of colleges and societies: the Royal College of Surgeons; the Westminster Medical Society (later the Medical Society of London); and a founding member of the London Epidemiological Society. During his life he published his findings in several papers, both on his epidemiological studies and pioneering experimentation on medical anesthetic. \r\n         \r\n<br /><br />\r\nSnow’s curiosity of health and disease also infiltrated his personal life; he was a vegetarian, teetotaler, and purified his water through distillation. These quirks supposedly aided his health and he campaigned for them to be recognized, going as far as to refer to alcohol as a “physical evil” in an address given in 1836. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nDespite his health-conscious lifestyle, Snow died an early death aged only 45. The cause of death is speculated over; suggestions range from a stroke, to over-exposure to experimental chemicals, and even his extreme health-habits. \r\n<br /><br />\r\n<h3>Cholera and the Broad St. Pump</h3>\r\n<br />\r\nCholera in the 1800s was rife due to poor sanitation and a lack of knowledge as to how exactly it could be contracted. Pandemics hit England and Scotland several times throughout the century and caused widespread panic due to the fast-acting nature of the disease. The main symptoms of cholera are vomiting and diarrhea, leading quickly to dehydration and potentially death when untreated. Anxiety over contagion lead to a Board of Health releasing local reports on supposed disease prevention. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe leading theory on how cholera spread was known as “miasma”, meaning “pollution” or bad air. It was thought that diseases could be spread by foul-smelling, toxic gases - a logical theory as disease appeared to spread faster around open sewage, rotten meat, rats, and generally poor conditions. The germ theory at this point had yet to be discovered, meaning advice tended towards moving away from the pollution.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nJohn Snow published his contrary speculations on how cholera seemed to spread in his 1849 pamphlet entitled “On the Mode of Communication of Cholera”. He put forward that miasmic theory did not sufficiently explain the spreading pattern and time of symptoms known with cholera, meaning that the disease may not be spread by bad smells or inhalation of contaminated air. He posed that perhaps open sewers coming into contact with drinking water was to blame. After several case studies of parishes around the Thames, and also cities further afield, Snow published a more comprehensive text on his new theory. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nInterestingly, of the several case studies looked at by Snow, the outbreak on Broad St. was one that did not originally fit his hypothesis. He tested the drinking water of the area and found it to be relatively pure, meaning he “hesitated to come to a conclusion”. After retesting, however, he found that the impurity of the water fluctuated from high to low, meaning his theory of water contamination causing the outbreak may have still been possible. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nAfter acquiring a list of deaths from the Soho General Register Office Snow plotted the number of deaths caused by cholera in the area on a map, and found them to be concentrated around a water pump on Broad Street (only 10 of 83 deaths that he counted at this point occurred in houses closer to a different street pump than Broad Street - half of these cases informed Snow they drank from the Broad Street pump anyway, another 3 were likely to have attended a school near the pump). \r\n\r\n<h3>Snow describes the famous conclusion and consequence:</h3>\r\nThe result of the inquiry was then was, that there had been no particular outbreak or increase in cholera, in this part of London, except among the persons that were in the habit of drinking the water of the above-mentioned pump well.I had an interview with the Board of Guardians of St. James’s parish, on the evening of Thursday, 7th September, and presented the above circumstances to them. In consequence of what I said, the handle of the pump was removed the following day.\r\n<br><br>\r\nJohn Snow’s focus on practical prevention of cholera, rather than fruitlessly studying the disease itself, slowly ushered in a new era of public health. His understanding of water contamination as opposed to miasmic theory was slow to be accepted as it was a huge shift in thinking and had huge repercussions on everyday life (in the location of cesspits, for example). It would not be until Robert Koch discovered the bacterium responsible for cholera almost three decades later that Snow’s research was more readily accepted. \r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h3>Anaesthesia</h3>\r\n\r\nAlongside his research into the spread of cholera, John Snow is also credited with bringing medical anaesthesia into fashion. Having experimented using both ether and chloroform on animals, Snow studied the benefits and potential risks of both. He built on various designs of other scientists to perfect an “anaesthetic inhaler”, where the patient could simply breath in without worrying about correct concentrations and dosages.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 1853 Snow administered chloroform to Queen Victoria during the birth of her eighth child, Leopold. Due to reservations over the new anaesthetic inhaler Snow used the “open-drop method”; where material would be placed over the patient’s nose and mouth and chloroform dropped on the surface so the patient can inhale the vapour. Snow’s casenotes describe the Queen after the birth to have been “very cheerful and well, expressing herself much gratified with the effect of the chloroform.” \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nHesitancies over numbing the pain of childbirth existed prior to this event due to biblical emphasis on the ‘curse of Eve’: having given into temptation in the Garden of Eden Eve would be cursed to have pain in childbirth. Some believed that the easing of this pain was deliberately going against the word of God, however Queen Victoria’s example paved the way for further use of medical anaesthesia in other types of surgery and dentistry as well as obstetrics. \r\n', 'John Snow Public House', '2018-08-21 8:18 pm', 'john_snow.jpg', 'topics', '51.5132742', '-0.1387813', 0, 3, 3, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 5);
