(8, ' Sir Nigel Gresley designed the iconic Flying Scotsman and Mallard steam engines while working for the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) from 1923 -1941.  One of the ‘Big Four’ companies that operated British railways from 1923 to their nationalization in 1948, the headquarters of the LNER could be found inside King’s Cross station.\r\n<br><br>\r\nFlying Scotsman was the first locomotive to reach 100mph on a test run on 30 November 1934. The Class A3 4-6-2 Pacific locomotive defines the ‘age of steam’, and the countries love for itcontinues today with people lining the route and queueing to see itduring its inaugural run, after a £4.2m 10-year long refit from King’s Cross to the National Railway Museum in York, on 25 February 2016. The engine is named after ‘The Flying Scotsman’ route it carried passenger trains along, which runs along the East Coast Mainline from King’s Cross to Edinburgh Waverly (from England’s capital to Scotland’s capital).\r\n<br><br>\r\nMallard broke the world speed record on 3 July 1938, which was previously held by the Flying Scotsman, by reaching 126mph. The Class A4 4-6-2 Pacific steam locomotive Mallard is a distinctive and striking blue steam engine that was in service until 1963. \r\n<br><br>\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Sir Nigel Gresley.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/2-Sir-Nigel-Gresley-on-Flying-Scotsman-1-may-1928-Phil-Marsh-collection.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Flying_Scotsman_in_Doncaster.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/2011-04-24_SirNigelGresley.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"4\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/gesley-with-namesake.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 5 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:50px; position: relative; left:-10px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Sir Nigel Gresley \r\n					<span>\r\n						Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n					</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Sir Nigel Gresley on Flying Scotsman on May 1st 1928.\r\n					<span>Source: Phil Marsh Collection / <a href=\"http://Rails.co.uk\" style=\"color:#fff; text-decoration:none\">Rails.co.uk</a></span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The Flying Scotsman was the first locomotive to reach 100mph on a test run on 30 November 1934.\r\n					<span>Source: Richard / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Sir Nigel Gresley doing the Forth Circle route approaching Stirling from Alloa.\r\n					<span>Source: Gavin Cameron / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Gesley photographed at the Doncaster Works in March 1938 with the A4 Pacific 4498 he designed and which was named after him.\r\n					<span>Source: Courtesy of the National Railway Museum, York</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <br>\r\nGresley’s impact on British Railways, his engineering skills, and his work with the LNER has led to the installation a bronze statue commemorating the 75th anniversary of his birth. The statue commissioned by the Gresley Society Trust, designed and created by Hazel Reeves, was unveiled on the 5th April 2016. Originally this design was going to include a mallard duck on the ground next to Gresley to represent one of his famous creations, but the final decision was to not include this feature. The removal of the duck provoked online anger resulting in 3200 people signing a petition to have the duck reinstated, and some ‘protestors’ holding up rubber ducks on sticks at the unveiling, and placing a wooden duck in the space where it was originally proposed.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nLess noticeable, as you may not have access to the platform or you’re running to or from your train, an English Heritage Blue Plaque commemorating Gresley and his work for the LNER until his unexplained death in 1941 can be found on the wall of the former LNER offices next to platform 8. The plaque was originally placed on the western outside wall of the station in 1997, but was covered in 2004, removed in 2009 for the reconstruction of the station, and was finally placed in its current spot in 2013.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Statue_of_Sir_Nigel_Gresley,_King\'s_Cross_Station.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/stream_img.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/stream_img (1).jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/stream_img (2).jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1;margin-bottom: 0px; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 4 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Statue of Sir Nigel Gresley at Kings Cross Station.\r\n\r\n					<span>Alan Stanton / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Sculptor Hazel Reeves stands next to her statue of railway engineer Sir Nigel Gresley.  <span>\r\n					Credit: Press Association </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					A group of people holding plastic ducks at the unveiling of railway engineer Sir Nigel Gresley on the 75th anniversary of his death at King\'s Cross railway station, London\r\n					<span>Credit: Press Association</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The statue shows him holding a copy of The Locomotive magazine, which carries a description of Mallard. The sculptor, Hazel Reeves, said her work shows Sir Nigel \"in a moment of quizzical reflection\", adding, \"he\'s looking out towards the future.\r\n					<span>Credit: Press Association / Link: itv.com</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>', 'Sir Nigel Gresley Statue', '2018-08-05 5:13 am', 'Sir Nigel Gresley Statue – St Pancaras.jpg', 'topics', '51.5316509', '-0.1266011', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 4),
(10, 'For 1600 years, London was a walled city, covering a square mile from what is now Tower Hills to Blackfriars. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOriginally built as a defensive structure, the city wall was constructed by the Romans to protect the strategically important town of Londinium from the Picts. Much of the wall was dismantled during the 1700s, however hardy sections can still be glimpsed, standing proudly as bastions of London’s ancient past. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nUnbeknownst to many, a substantial portion of the wall remains within the courtyard of The Grange City Hotel on Cooper’s Row. The Roman wall here survives up to a height of 14.5 feet (4.4 metres) and is characterized by the normal arrangement of regular courses of dressed rag-stone, inter-spaced approximately every four courses with red tile bonding layers. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nAs with much of London’s Roman wall, this section remained in use for many years after the Romans fled the city and abandoned Roman Britannia. During the Medieval period the wall was heightened by 21 feet (6.2 metres) and it is this part of the wall that still remains visible above modern ground level at Cooper’s Row. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe double staircase climbing visibly up the wall hints at the wall’s continued significance as a defensive structure, an impression strengthened by the arched loopholes which were to be used by archers should the city come under attack.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFollowing the Medieval period, the wall began to lose its importance as a defensive structure and was slowly swallowed up by surrounding buildings. However, it is evident that some parts of the wall still retained an element of significance during this time, with Cooper’s Row itself owing it’s name to the coopers (barrel makers) who stored their casks in recesses of the city wall in this area.', 'Roman wall at Cooper\'s Row', '2018-08-05 3:01 pm', 'coopers-row-roman-wall.jpg', 'topics', '51.509944', '-0.076010', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL),
(11, 'The Putney Bridge pillbox was built into the existing bridge during the Second World War. It is a hexagonal bricked two-storey structure –with small openings (embrasures) suitable for positioning firearms. These constructions were colloquially called ‘Pillboxes’, in reference to their shape.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\" style=\"\">&nbsp;</span></font></p><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Putney Bridge pillbox.jpg\" class=\"img-responsive\"></div><p style=\"\"></p><div style=\"\">\r\n    \r\n \r\n    \r\n    <p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><i><font color=\"#ffffff\">View of the Putney Bridge pillbox from the platform at Putney Bridge station</font></i></p><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></div><div style=\"\">\r\n    \r\n    \r\n<h1>Why were pillboxes built?</h1>\r\nIn 1940 over 28,000 pillboxes were hastily built in strategically important locations, like canals, junctions, and bridges, across Great Britain. They made up a series of defensive ‘stop-lines’. Pillboxes made up Britain’s final line of defence in the event of a German invasion – a very real threat in the aftermath of the evacuation of British and Allied troops from the beaches of Northern France in late May and early June 1940, known as the Dunkirk evacuation.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe pillbox on Putney Bridge is of the type 22 design. Most structures followed set guidelines but were altered depending on the local area’s availability of materials and its environment. Many pillboxes were constructed from concrete, with walls up to 30cm thick! – one of the reasons around 6000 of them still survive hidden amongst British urban and rural landscapes today.\r\n\r\n</font></p><p class=\"p1\"><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/TYpe-22-plan-214x300.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></div></div><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></div><div style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n    \r\n    Design of a standard Type 22 Pillbox. <a href=\"http://www.pillbox-study-group.org.uk/\">(Copyright: Mike Osborne)</a></div><div style=\"text-align: left;\"><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></div><div style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n    \r\n<h1>The Legacy of the Pillbox:</h1>\r\n\r\nFor many people the pillbox symbolises the courage and spirit of those on the home front. They were to be manned by the Local Defence Volunteers (the Home Guard/ LDV), made up of men too young, old or infirm to sign up to fight in Europe. By the end of July 1940 there were over one and a half million volunteers for the LDV nationwide.Nazi Germany’s planned invasion never happened – but these pillboxes are a haunting reminder of the threat to Britain in the 1940s.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></font></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"\"><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></span></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"></font></span></p>\r\n    <div align=\"center\"  style=\"text-align: center;\">View of the Putney Bridge pillbox from the footpath</div><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left; \"><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><font color=\"#ffffff\"><img src=\"http://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/put2-1200x800.jpg\" class=\"img-responsive\"></font></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n    \r\n    </p><p class=\"text-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><i>View of the Putney Bridge pillbox from Ranelagh Gardens SW6</i></p><p class=\"p1\"><i><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></i></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><font color=\"#ffffff\">Opening times/ access:</font></b></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><font color=\"#ffffff\">The public are not allowed inside the pillbox due to its location on a busy tube line – but you can get some great views of it from the platform and the Putney Bridge footpath.</font></p><h4><b><font color=\"#ffffff\">Find out more:</font></b></h4><p class=\"p2\"><font color=\"#ffffff\">H. Wills, <i>Pillboxes: a study of UK defences, 1940</i>(London, 1985)</font></p><p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n    \r\n    \r\n    </p><p class=\"p2\"><font color=\"#ffffff\">M. Osborne, <i>Defending Britain: Twentieth-Century military structures in the landscape</i>(Stroud, 2004)</font></p><p class=\"p1\"><i><font color=\"#ffffff\"><br></font></i></p><p class=\"p1\"><i><br></i></p></div> ', 'Putney Bridge Pillbox', '2018-08-05 3:31 pm', 'Putney Bridge pillbox.jpg', 'topics', '51.4674882', '-0.2145016', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL);
