(12, 'Throughout history, women have been subject to discrimination and mistreatment. As the world has evolved and progressed life has gradually improved for women thanks to the devoted, brave and determined efforts of women’s activists. In the early twentieth century the women\'s suffrage movement led this fight in the United Kingdom.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe 1832 Great Reform Act, defined British voters primarily as ‘male persons\'. Women were not permitted to vote due to their husbands, or male relatives, being responsible to represent their views in all political matters. This was the first time it had explicitly been stated by law that women were not allowed to vote. In that same year, the first petition on women’s suffrage was presented to Parliament by Mary Smith.\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Mary-Smith.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Mary Ellen Smith, from a 1918 publication. She was the first female Speaker in the British Empire.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nOver thirty years later, the election of John Stuart Mill in 1865 gave the suffragists hope for change and recognition, as Mill was believed to support the right for women to vote. However, the all-male House of Commons rejected John Stuart Mill’s Second Reform Bill petition, which contained over 1500 signatures. This petition, which would have allowed women to vote on the same property terms as men, was rejected by 194 votes to 73.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAfter the dismissal of this amendment, the women’s suffrage campaign gained momentum. This was evident in the formation of several formal suffrage societies across England and Ireland, which then amalgamated to form the National Society for Women\'s Suffrage (NSWS). The first public meeting about women’s suffrage was held in Manchester\'s Free Trade Hall in 1868. Among the audience was 15-year-old Emmeline Goulden, who was to become an ardent campaigner for women\'s rights, and who would later become the wife of Dr. Pankhurst, becoming Mrs Emmeline Pankhurst.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/John-Stuart-MIll.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/The_Free_Trade_Hall,_Manchester.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/emmiline-pankhurst.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Painting of John Stuart Mill. A member of the Liberal Party, he was also the first Member of Parliament to call for women\'s suffrage.\r\n					<span>Source: George Frederic Watts / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The first public meeting about women’s suffrage was held in Manchester\'s Free Trade Hall in 1868. <span>\r\n					Source: Wikimedia Commons. </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Among the audience was 15-year-old Emmeline Goulden, who was to become an ardent campaigner for women\'s rights, and who would later become the wife of Dr. Pankhurst, becoming Mrs Emmeline Pankhurst. \r\n					<span>Image Source: The British Museum</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\nLittle progress was made by the suffragettes during the following years. In 1869, the Municipal Franchise Act provided single women ratepayers rights to vote in local elections; twenty-five years later, the 1895 Local Government Act permitted women who owned property the right to vote in local elections. Women, however, recognised that more could – and needed to – be done to grant them their basic political freedoms. Owing to the failure of the 1884 Third Reform Act and the ineffectiveness of the National Society for Women\'s Suffrage (NSWS), the NUWSS (National Union of Women\'s Suffrage Societies) spearheaded by Millicent Fawcett, was formed in 1897.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nKnown as ‘suffragists’, they employed a fair and legal approach in their campaign of convincing the government to give voting rights to middle-class property-owning women. This involved peace walks, petitions, confronting Members of Parliament, sharing pamphlets, conducting speeches, and letter writing campaigns. Their peaceful and gradualist nature was not only a reflection of their leader, who did not want women to be considered unfit for politics due to unruly behaviour, but also due to the structure of the leadership of the union which comprised mainly of middle-class women that were cautious of not ruining their reputation.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Millicent-fawcett.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n        <p>“ I would rather be a rebel than a slave.\" </p> <small>Emmeline Pankhurst</small>\r\n    </blockquote>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Emmeline Pankhurst & the WSPU</h2>\r\n<br>\r\n\r\nImpatient with the gradualist approach, factions were created in the National Union of Women\'s Suffrage Societies. In 1903, some members of the union, led by Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughters Christabel and Sylvia, set up a separate society that became known as the Women\'s Social and Political Union (WSPU). Pankhurst believed drastic measures were required, and further claimed it would take an active organisation with working-class women to draw attention to the cause. This was the birth of a militant campaign with “Deeds not Words!” and “Votes for Women!” adopted as slogans.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Pankhurst-and-her-daughters.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/emmiline-pankhurst-and-the-wspujpg.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/emmiline-pankhurst-older.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/banners.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 4 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					In 1903, some members of the union, led by Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughters Christabel and Sylvia, set up a separate society that became known as the Women\'s Social and Political Union (WSPU).\r\n\r\n					<span>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Meeting of Women\'s Social & Political Union (WSPU) leaders, c.1906 - c.1907\r\n					<span>\r\n					Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Oil Painting of Emmeline Pankhurst\r\n					<span>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					WSPU Members making banners\r\n					<span>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\nIn October 1905, the arrest of Christabel Pankhurst and Annie Kenney at liberal meeting held at the Manchester Free Trade Hall marked the beginning of the militant campaign. Having interrupted the meeting of prominent liberal politicians by asking them what their stands were about women’s voting rights, they were charged with obstruction and spitting on a police officer. On refusal to pay the fine imposed by the court, they went to prison and this generated publicity for the cause.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 1906, the Daily Mail coined the name ‘suffragette’ to describe the predominantly younger women who advocated more radical tactics. The “ette” ending was supposed to belittle Annie Kenney and her fellow WSPU members. Instead, the WSPU proudly adopted the name, saying \"suffraGETtes\" (stressing the GET while they pronounced the term), to imply that they were adamant to achieve their goals. From 1909, the sale of the \"Pank-A-Squith\" (Pankhurst and Asquith) board game was used to raise money and gain publicity for the cause. The board game’s principle strategy required players to lead their suffragette figure from their home to Parliament, past the obstacles faced from Prime Minister H. H. Asquith, and the Liberal government.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Annie_Kenney_and_Christabel_Pankhurst.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:-30px;\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Annie Kenney and Christabel Pankhurst were dedicated suffragettes who paved the way for others. They were the first to be arrested, in Manchester in 1905.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nIt may be surprising to discover that the suffrage campaign was not simply a feminine movement, meaning that principles were not only fought for by women. Many men were committed to the cause, and actively participated in the campaign. Notable examples include Frederick Pethick-Lawrence, George Lansbury MP, and Keir Hardie MP who regularly raised the issue of women enfranchisement in the House of Commons.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 1906, James Keir Hardie introduced Frederick and Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence to Emmeline Pankhurst. An apartment in Clement’s Inn, between Lincoln’s Inn Fields and Aldwych was home to them both, and it became the headquarters of the fledgling Women’s Social and Political Union (WSPU). With the organisation only admitting female members, Frederick was not an official member. As a barrister, he represented WSPU in legal matters and stood bail for more than one-hundred members.\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/1.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/2.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/3.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Mrs Emmeline Pankhurst and Mrs Mabel Tuke photographed in Mrs Pankhurst\'s office in Clements Inn.\r\n					<span>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Christabel and Emmeline Pankhurst on the roof at Clement’s Inn, London, October 1908. A note on the back of the photo says that they were hiding from the police. <span>\r\n					Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					WSPU offices at Clement\'s Inn, 1911.\r\n					<span>Credit: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\nThe couple contributed to the proper structure and organisation of WSPU, with Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence being credited as the originator of the WSPU campaign colours, purple, white and green; she memorably described as ‘purple for dignity, white for purity and green for hope’ in 1908. They were also committed in giving WSPU sizeable financial contributions. In 1907, Frederick founded the WSPU periodical, ‘Votes for Women’ with Emmeline and himself as joint editors. This periodical, which sold over 20,000 copies each week, helped recruit WSPU members and win public support for the cause.\r\n<br><br>\r\nIn 1912, large-scale smashing of shop windows along Oxford Street, led to the arrest of the couple even though they had nothing to do with the event. They were made culpable for the event and sentenced to nine-months’ imprisonment. Sued for the cost of the damage, they went in to a period of bankruptcy. With Emmeline in Holloway Prison, and Frederick in Brixton Prison, both were force-fed, and subjected to ill-treatment.\r\n<br><br>\r\nIn October 1912, Emmeline and Frederick were expelled from the WSPU for they were no longer in agreement with the extreme militant tactics. Despite the split, they were still loyal and committed to the cause.  Both continued to edit and publish ‘Votes for Women’ and their Clement’s Inn home in London which served as office for WSPU continued to serve as a recuperating clinic for suffragettes who had just been released from the prison.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Pethick-couple.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\nFrederick Pethick Lawrence (far left) and His wife, Emmeline (far right). The Pethick-Lawrences founded the publication Votes for Women in 1907. The couple was arrested and imprisoned in 1912 following demonstrations that involved breaking windows, even though they had nothing to do with the event. After being released from prison, the Pethick-Lawrences were expelled from the WSPU by Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughter Christabel, because of their ongoing disagreement over the more radical forms of activism that the Pethick-Lawrences opposed. Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>Sophia - The Suffragette Princess</h1>\r\n\r\nBorn in Belgravia in 1876, Princess Sophia Duleep Singh, the daughter of an exiled Punjabi Maharaja and the treasured goddaughter of Queen Victoria, was a prominent woman of colour and a pivotal figure in the women’s suffrage movement. It was not until she and her sisters sneaked into India in 1903, to see the celebration of the accession of King Edward VII, that she changed from a vacuous socialite to a political activist. On her visit to India, she came face to face with all that her family had lost, saw abject poverty and experienced racism at first hand. She attributed these factors to the severity of the British colonial rule. In 1909, Singh came back to England with an awakened sense of dispossession, and discovered the appeal for votes for women irresistible, and so she soon joined the Women’s Social and Political Union.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Sophia-and-Her-Sisters.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sophia\'s father.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Sophia-selling-paperss.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					The last of the empire: Daughters of Maharajah Duleep Singh; Bamba, Catherine and Sophia — photographed in 1892.\r\n\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Sophia\'s father, Maharajah Duleep Singh, was born in Lahore in 1838, and came to the throne of the Punjab at the age of five years.\r\n					<span>\r\n					 Image Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>Princess Sophia Duleep Singh selling subscriptions for the Suffragette newspaper outside Hampton Court in London, April 1913.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nAs a suffragette, Singh donated and raised vast amounts of money for the organisation, including when violence and arson attacks were prominent. Singh vandalised her census paper, defied court judgments awarded against her, and as a member of the Women’s Tax Resistance league, refused to pay her taxes. Living in Hampton Court in an apartment in Faraday House, given to her by Queen Victoria, she sold the suffragette’s newspaper ‘The Vote’ outside Hampton Court.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nOn one occasion, she threw herself at Prime Minister Asquith’s car, slamming a ‘Votes for Women’ pamphlet against his window but was released without charge. Despite Singh\'s activism as a suffragette, she was never arrested as she was a royal and her arrest would have attracted maximum attention to an ‘unwanted’ political cause. Singh marched next to Emmeline on 18 November 1910, an event that would become known as the Black Friday.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h1> Suffragettes, Violence and Militancy </h1>\r\n\r\nMembers of the Suffragettes were prepared to use violence to reach their designed goal of women’s political freedoms. Their militant tactics involved the interruption of anti-suffrage ministers, arson attacks on post box contents and empty public places, and window smashing. To protest the Church of England, who were not in support of women’s voting rights, the WSPU were known to place bombs inside Westminster Abbey, St. Paul’s Cathedral and other Anglican churches.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nGolf courses, cricket pitches, horse racing tracks and places where the affluent frequented were also destroyed when unattended. On 19 February 1913, one of the two bombs which was targeted at Pinfold Manor in Surrey, which was being built for Chancellor of the exchequer, David Lloyd-George, exploded, causing significant damage. Further targets included train stations, houses of anti-suffrage ministers, and libraries.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/The Daily Mirror.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sufragettes-arson-attacks.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Painting.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/wargrave.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"4\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/2nd-paiting.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 5 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					The front page of The Daily Mirror, 19 November 1910, showing a suffragette on the ground, having been hit by a policeman.\r\n\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Police survey Saunderton Railway Station after a suffragette arson attack, March 9th, 1913.\r\n					<span>\r\n					 Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>J.S. Sargent, Detail of the portrait of Henry James O.M. after being damaged by a suffragette, May 1914.\r\n					<span>Photo: R.A. © Royal Academy of Arts, London.</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>On 1st June 1914 the church of Wargrave was set on fire. It is alleged that the suffragette movement was responsible as postcards charging the authorities with torturing women were found near the church.\r\n					<span>Source: The Berkshire Record Office // Wargrave parish records (ref. D/P145/28/14)</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>The National Museum, London Detail from a photo published in 1914 (before the repairs) showing damage done to Rokeby Venus by Mary Richardson, a suffragette.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nIn 1908, owing to the absence of Prime Minister Herbert Asquith, 500,000 activists rallied through Hyde Park in London and proceeded towards Downing Street. Suffragettes continued to damage property in Downing Street and further chained themselves to railings at the Prime Minister’s residence to gain the Prime Minister’s attention. On 18 November 1910, despite making it to the second reading, Prime Minister Herbert Asquith decided not to proceed with the Conciliation Bill, which would have provided women with the ability to vote. This response was met with a protest from suffragettes, who viciously protested outside Parliament.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nDue to the involvement of police and male vigilantes, the protest resulted in failure. Many women became injured and some protesters lost their lives for the cause. Many male and female protesters were also arrested during the rally. Marked as the ‘Black Friday of British women’s suffrage campaign’, the rally on 18 November 1910 gained publicity and sympathetic support for the WSPU, and increased support from newspapers through pictures of unarmed women being assaulted.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/march.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        In 1908, owing to the absence of Prime Minister Herbert Asquith, 500,000 activists rallied through Hyde Park in London and proceeded towards Downing Street\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: BBC.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nOn the 2nd April 1911, the Suffragette organisation urged women to boycott the census, which was controlled by the Liberal government. With the rallying call of, “If women don’t count, neither shall they be counted”, the censuses boycott emerged from the Women’s Freedom League campaign for non-violent ‘passive resistance’ against the government. This saw many women deface their census schedule, or spend the night away from home to avoid being counted. Women kept moving from place to place, hid, or gathered at the home of a census resister. One house in Manchester resulted in it being renamed “census lodge”, as it housed many census evaders.\r\n\r\n<br> <br>\r\n\r\nIn London, some gathered for a midnight picnic of roast fowl, sweetmeats and tea at Wimbledon Common. Others spent the night walking, talking and singing at Trafalgar Square. A vegetarian restaurant in Covent Garden stayed open to provide refreshments. In many parts of the nation – namely Cardiff, Bristol, Liverpool, Ipswich, Cheltenham, Reading and Maidstone – suffragettes hosted overnight events with the sole purpose of boycotting the census.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Census.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       	Suffragettes gathered in Manchester Census Lodge to Boycott the 1911 Census.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n        <p>“ If I am intelligent enough to fill in this census form,</p><p> I can surely make an x on a ballot form\" </p> <small>Miss Kate Gillie (April 1911)</small>\r\n    </blockquote>\r\n\r\nMany women vandalised the census by defacing their forms or by completing them with inappropriate answers. One notable example includes Mary Howey of Hertfordshire, who inscribed a large “votes for women” on her form, and listed her occupation as “artist and suffragette”. Another example includes Miss Davies, a suffragette from Birkenhead who wrote on her form the name of a male servant, and added that there were no other persons present within the home.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe same night, Emily Wilding Davison, who would tragically lose her life two years later, hid in a broom cupboard in the Houses of Parliament for 46 hours. Though caught and arrested she was released without charge. Boycotting the census showed a lot of courage as protesters expected a fine of £5 or a month’s imprisonment. However, no person was prosecuted, theoretically due to the large-scale number of suffragettes involved, and due to the criticism, that would have occurred if this was the case.\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/census-slip.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       	The Census form has been returned blank and in place of household details, a large \'Votes for Women\' flyer has been stuck. To add extra insult, stamps advertising a \'census meeting\' the previous evening have been stuck on along with the handwritten slogan \'no persons here, only women\'.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nNevertheless, public outrage towards the suffragettes was present. A letter to The Times labelled the boycott as a \"crime against science\", while the political magazine Punch joked: \"the suffragettes have definitely taken leave of their census\". Despite many women boycotting the census, their efforts were negligible in nullifying the census as many were counted while on the streets and some households listed the name of their missing occupants. Nevertheless, whilst it did not nullify the census results it gave public attention to the injustices of the British voting system, the suffragette movement and its campaign for ‘Votes for Women’.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h1> Cat and mouse: Force Feeding the suffragettes </h1>\r\nBetween 1905 and 1914, around 1000 suffragettes had been arrested and given prison sentences of anywhere from 3 days to several months. However, suffragettes were willing to go to prison, and some used hunger strikes as a powerful tool to protest their arrest and to demand the status of political suffragettes in custody. The Government’s response to hunger strikes were to force-feed those who participated, this involved individuals being strapped down and a tube unpleasantly forced down the throat or nostril to ensure that food could be pumped into the stomach.\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/forcefeeding.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:-30px;\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Forceful Feeding through the nose of women suffragists prisoners pronounced as dangerous by many leading members of the medical profession. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nForce feeding suffragettes not only caused a public outcry, as forced feeding was traditionally used to feed criminal inmates, but the demeaning and dangerously invasive procedure damaged the long-term health of victims. For example, Lady Constance Lytton, who disguised herself as a ‘Jane Warton’ to gather evidence on differential treatment, was force-fed several times and never fully recovered from her ordeal. Lytton suffered a stroke in 1912 and died in 1923. This ultimately gained publicity for the women’s suffrage campaign.\r\n\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n        <p>I shall never while I live forget the suffering I experienced during </p> <p> the days when those cries were ringing in my ears </p> <small>EMMELINE PANKHURST</small>\r\n    </blockquote>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn 1913, with the motive of preventing suffragettes from dying as martyrs in police custody, the government introduced the Prisoners Temporary Discharge for Ill Health Act, commonly known as the ‘Cat and Mouse Act’. It was designed to provide for the release of suffragettes whose hunger strikes and forced feeding had brought them illness, as well as their arrest and re-imprisonment as soon as they had regained strength.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn response to the ‘Cat and Mouse Act’, Edith Garrud, who was one of the western world’s first female martial arts teachers, taught self-defence classes that protected women from being rearrested and sent back to jail. Garrud was known to protect prominent members, such as Emmeline Pankhurst. Members of Garrud’s classes orchestrated the \"escapes\" of several suffragettes from police surveillance during 1913 and early 1914. The \"Battle of Glasgow\" was one of the notable events in which suffragettes were violent with the police. This saw about thirty suffragettes clash with an estimated fifty police officers on the stage of St. Andrew\'s Hall in Glasgow, Scotland.\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Cat-and-Mouse-Act.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       	The Cat and Mouse Act gained notoriety amongst women\'s suffrage organisations in the UK in the early 1910s\r\n        <span>\r\n			Photo: Schlesinger Library on the History of Women in America\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1> Emily Wilding Davidson: The \"Suffragette\" Derby </h1>\r\n\r\nOn 4th June 1913, the London born Emily Wilding Davidson, who had been arrested nine times and force-fed forty-nine times, decided to disrupt the Epsom Derby to draw attention to the women’s suffrage campaign. Davidson famously stepped out in front of Anmer, a horse owned by King George which resulted in her being knocked down. She died after four days due to a fractured skull and internal injuries. Owing to reports, it was not clear if she intended to kill herself for the cause.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nWith a return train ticket and a ticket to a dance slated for the evening in her bag, reports suggested she possibly wanted to attach a WSPU banner to the horse’s bridle. Her death was iconic to the women’s suffrage campaign and she became a martyr to the cause. Thousands of women attended her funeral and lined the streets as her coffin was moved to its final resting place. She was laid to rest at Morpeth, Northumberland, and her grave was inscribed with the suffragette’s “Deeds Not Words” slogan.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Emily.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/derby.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/emily-funeral.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					In 1906, Emily Davison joined Emmeline Pankhurst\'s \"Women\'s Social Political Union (WSPU). She was a brave and sometimes violent campaigner. She broke up meetings and carried out arson attacks.\r\n\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					On June 4, Emily Wilding Davison stepped onto the track at the Epsom Derby and collided with King George V’s horse, Anmer. She suffered a fractured skull and died four days later died days later.\r\n					<span>\r\n					 Image: Arthur Barrett/Hulton Archive/Getty Images</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>On June 14, 1913, Davison\'s body was transported from Epsom to London; Her coffin was inscribed \"Fight on, God will give the victory\". \r\n					<span>LSE Library / Available on Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn August 1914, the First World War began. As a result, the Government released the suffragette prisoners, and Emmeline Pankhurst convinced her fellow suffragettes to suspend their militant activities and actively support the government in war efforts as a united nation. Around one-million women took up men’s work while they fought in the Great War.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nWhether it was due to the sympathy, the support the suffrage got from the public or women’s vital contribution during the war, one thing was certain; a new reform had to be passed to modernise political standings and include women in the nation’s vital political decisions. Many of the returning soldiers were no longer entitled to vote, as they did not meet existing property qualifications.\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/World-war.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/world-war-2.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/World-War-5.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					A female munitions worker in a British factory during World War One, which was one of the catalysts for women finally getting the vote.\r\n\r\n					<span>Image: Tom Marshall/mediadrumworld.com</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Around one-million women took up men’s work while they fought in the Great War.\r\n					<span>\r\n					 Image: The Imperial War Museum</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>Emmeline Pankhurst convinced her fellow suffragettes to suspend their militant activities and actively support the government in war efforts as a united nation.\r\n					<span>Image: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nThe need for the enfranchisement of women was also finally recognised by most members of parliament from all three major parties. Therefore, on 6th February 1918, the Representation of the People Act was passed. This extended suffrage to men over the age of twenty-one (removing most property qualifications), British women over the age of 30 that were property owners, members of the local government register, and university graduates.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nOn 21st November 1918, the Parliament (Qualification of Women Act) 1918 was passed. This allowed women to be elected to Parliament. The main reason for the age differential was to ensure that, following the loss of men in the war, women did not become the majority voters. Even though just over eight million women met this criterion, it only represented forty-percent of the total population of women in the nation. Furthermore, in 1928, the Representation of the People (Equal Franchise) Act granted all women over the age of twenty-one voting rights. This was the first time that women had achieved electoral equality with men.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/woman.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       	Finally in 1918, Parliament passed an act granting the vote to women over the age of 30 who were householders, the wives of householders, occupiers of property and graduates of British universities. About 8.4 million women gained the vote.\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', ' The Women’s Suffrage Movement', '2018-08-05 6:46 pm', 'womansufferage.jpg', 'topics', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `articles` (`articlesid`, `text`, `articletitle`, `dateUploaded`, `articleImage`, `appearin`, `latitude`, `longitude`, `view`, `likes`, `dislikes`, `featured`, `position`, `visible`, `categoryid`, `authorid`) VALUES
(13, 'The disease we today term “the plague” is caused by the Yersinia pestis bacteria and has three identified strains: bubonic plague (affecting the lymphatic system), pneumonic plague (affecting the lungs), and septicaemic plague (affecting the blood).\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nBubonic plague is perhaps the most well-known strain as it refers specifically to the disease’s most infamous symptom; the bubo. This is an often-painful swelling of infected lymph nodes in the groin, neck or armpit. Other symptoms vary according to the specific strain of the plague, but if suffering from the disease today one can expect flu-like symptoms that may quickly become fatal if untreated.  This can, however, now be effectively treated with antibiotics and has a much higher survival rate than in previous centuries.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/First-plague-pit-image.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        This plague patient is displaying a swollen, ruptured inguinal lymph node, or buboe. After the incubation period of 2-6 days, symptoms of the plague appear including severe malaise, headache, shaking chills, fever, and pain.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlthough we know this particular disease simply as “the plague”, it has in fact been known by various other names throughout history. During the early modern period (approximately 1500 to 1750) it was known as the plague during various pandemics, but prior to this it was most often referred to as “the pestilence” by chroniclers.  We know this medieval outbreak as “the Black Death”, but this is also a modern term. It can confusingly imply two separate diseases rather than two separate outbreaks; however recent DNA testing of medieval Black Death victims has confirmed the presence of the plague-causing bacteria Yersinia pestis.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe disease was caused by flea bites transferring the disease to rodents that arrived on Britain’s shores from plague-ridden countries. It was understood during the plague’s peak that these ships appeared to carry the plague but unclear as to how – the germ theory had not yet been formed. The best explanation of contagion during this period was known as “miasma”; the inhaling of toxic or infectious gases. The relative understanding of contagion led to the quarantining of certain ships for 40 days to ensure they were free from disease before coming to shore. The practice originated from medieval Venice, and comes from the Italian for “40 days”: quranta giorni.\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Yersinia-Perstis.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:-30px;\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A scanning electron micrograph depicting a mass of Yersinia pestis bacteria in the foregut of an infected flea.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n	<p> The victims ate lunch with their friends, and dinner with their ancestors in paradise </p> <small> Boccacio </small>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<h1> How do we know about the early modern plague? </h1>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3> Bills of Mortality: </h3>\r\n\r\nThese are statistic reports produced to list numbers and causes of deaths in a specific area. Around plague pandemics similar publications known as the “Lord Have Mercy Upon Us” broadsheets were used specifically to communicate death tolls and other information on the plague around London. These publications demonstrate a rising culture of statistics around this period, possibly to install a sense of order around the rising panic.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Figure below tells us that 3,880 people died from the plague between August 15th-22nd 1665 in this particular area of London. This accounts for a huge 73% of deaths in this specific week, giving us a rare statistic value of just how prevalent the disease was, and just how terrifying such a pandemic must have been in the absence of an effective treatment.\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Bill-of-Mortality.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Diseases and Casualties this Week, Bill of Mortality, 1665.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Welcome Collection / Accessed June 3rd 2018\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nAside from important information on the plague, the Bills of Mortality also give us an invaluable insight into contemporary disease culture. Some conditions are recognisable, such as “Consumption” or “Scurvy”, but some we can only guess at, such as “Rising of the Lights”. Indeed, one poor person is simply listed to have died “Suddenly”. Do we even know that every listed death by “Plague” is the plague as we know it? Unfortunately, the answer is most likely no.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nCauses of death at this point were identified by “searchers” who did not have official medical training, but quickly checked corpses and passed the speculated cause of death on for the Bills of Mortality.  Despite uncertainty over disease identification, the value of the publication as a source through which to view the plague or other diseases is not diminished. It gives us a chance to view these conditions as they existed and affected the population in 1665 rather than comparing them to modern equivalents, or even wonder if there is a modern equivalent. Just because we can identify the plague by its name in the early modern period does not mean it was experienced in the same way as it is today, and the unidentifiable conditions on the Bills of Mortality remind us of that.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h1> Personal memoirs </h1>\r\n\r\nAs much as Bills of Mortality tell us about how many people died of the plague, they tell us virtually nothing of personal experiences. Unfortunately, a primary source with this type of information is extremely hard to come by; if a person experienced plague it is unlikely that they would be concerned with writing it down. Indeed, although literacy rates appear to have steadily increased over this period, the majority of the population were if not completely illiterate, then only capable of reading.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n There are occasionally small glimpses of the disease within diaries kept at the time of the plague, but rarely at length. We see one of these in the writings of one of the most famous English diarists in history: Samuel Pepys.\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Samuel.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Samuel Pepys was famous for the diary he kept for a decade while still a relatively young man. It provides a combination of personal revelation and eyewitness accounts of great events, such as the Great Plague of London.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nAlthough gaining fame for his account of the Great Fire of London, it is often forgotten that this event occurred around the same year as the final plague pandemic, 1665-66. Consequently, Pepys mentions his experiences with the plague but, as mentioned before, his lack of proximity is reflected in these experiences being limited to a line or two. On 14th September 1665 he wrote of one of these experiences:\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"side-note\">\r\n	 My meeting dead corpses of the plague, carried to be buried close to me at noonday through the City in Fanchurch Street. To see a person sick of the sores carried close by me by Gracechurch in a hackney-coach\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlthough this seems to be a very limited excerpt, we can still learn several things from it. When looking specifically at plague pits, for example, the passage tells us that the dead were carried through Fanchurch Street (most likely modern-day Fenchurch Street, London, EC3M 4BS), meaning there may have been a burial pit nearby. As for contemporary symptoms, it tells us that the sores were possibly one of the most identifiable and diagnostic for the plague. The passage may be short, but is still an important piece of the puzzle.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h1>Medical/Supernatural Treatises </h1>\r\n\r\nThe prevalence of the plague in the 17th century led to many papers and reports being written on the disease by physicians, healers, supernaturalists and scientists alike (the distinctions between these different professions were much blurrier than they are today). These works were likely to be intended for circulation amongst the scholarly rather than for the general population; broadsheets tended to inform the literate masses, and ordinances from the monarch and reports from local councils were read out in public places for the rest.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAstrologer John Gadbury published his musings on causes of plagues in 1665. His explanations had a mainly supernatural basis, as can be seen by his focus on the alignments of the planets, and concerned various major plague outbreaks that had occurred in history.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"side-note\">\r\n\r\nIn the year 1603, the Pestilence was inconsiderable in its increase, until the last week in June, and the month of July, at which times the fiery Planet Mars came to the opposite point of the Moon.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nGadbury’s discourse discusses the plague at length, and gives us some vague but usefully corroborative symptoms:\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"side-note\">\r\n\r\n“Physicians tell us, that the Plague is a disease most Malignant and Pestilential ; a Fever in the highest in the highest degree, which doth putrifie and corrupt, both the Solid and Fluid parts of the body ;  which have done, by an (almost) uncontrolable and unrepellable siccity, dries and destroys the Natural Powers, then seizeth or preyeth upon the vitals , and so lets in the everlasting Enemy, DEATH.”\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/John_Gadbury.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Philosopher John Gadbury.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nThis particular source may seem somewhat indistinct and spiritual when attempting to piece together various bits of information on the physical aspects of the plague in history, such as its symptoms and how different geographical locations were affected. It is, however, still an extremely useful source; this is partly for the same reasons as the usefulness of the Bills of Mortality.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nMuch in the same way the Bills of Mortality show us that individual experiences of historical disease may be so different from our modern ones that we are unable to properly empathise them, Gadbury’s treatise presents a valid contemporary view of the physical aspects of the plague that we may potentially find difficult to use.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIt demonstrates the inherent interlinking of natural and supernatural causes within disease culture at the time, as shown with the constant undertone of sin and judgement. Moreover, the significance of religion is made similarly obvious through this sinful narrative.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe notion that supernatural explanations may be vital in understanding natural aspects of the plague can help us uncover details that may otherwise have gone unexplained if the focus were solely on modern interpretation of physical elements of the disease.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThis includes tiny details such as the layout and spacing of victims in a plague pit; the regular, careful positioning of the victims indicate that proper burials were vital even in densely filled plague pits, most likely because of the constant presence of religion and tradition, and the role of the parish.\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<h1> Official documents </h1>\r\n\r\nPlague pandemics tended to cause disorder, panic and subversions of social orders (given that no-one, not even those that were wealthier, were safe from the disease). Ordinances issued by the monarch can be seen as attempts to dampen this chaos through information and guidelines.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nCharles II published “Rules and Orders” on the prevention of the plague in 1665 to control the contagious nature of the disease. The document is specifically for the instruction of “Justices of Peace, Mayors, Bayliffs, and other Officers”, i.e., those in charge of lay people.\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Rules-and-Orders.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Charles II, \"Rules and Orders\".\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: National Archives, Accessed June 12th 2018\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nBecause of this, the document is not necessarily concerned with how an individual may protect him or herself from sickening, but how households, villages, etc, can protect themselves.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIt is a practical document, meaning we can see what details were deemed to be important enough to pass on from the highest-level authority to his subjects. We can see various historical concepts covered in other sources, such as:\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Miasma (the belief that disease spread through bad-smelling air). Rules 6 & 7 dictate that “convenient Fumes to correct the Air be burnt” in public places, and that “no unwholsom Meats, stinking Fish, Flesh, musty Corn” may be sold.</li>\r\n	<li> Specific symptoms that searchers should look out for. Rule no. 10 dictates that local areas should be prepared to identify and care for the sick and that searchers should identify the plague by the “usual… Swellings or Risings under the Ears or Arm-pits [buboes], or upon the Groynes; Blains, Carbuncles, or little Spots, either on the Breast or back, commonly called Tokens.”</li>\r\n	<li>The significance of religion and the supernatural. As mentioned with regard to John Gadbury’s astronomical treatise on the plague, cures and explanations that we may think of spiritual rather than medical were used readily and expected to protect as effectively as any physical treatment. Rule no. 12 dictates that on any affected household undergoing quarantine should “have a Red Cross, and Lord have mercy upon us, in Capital Letter affixed on the door”.  That such a practical report would include such religious treatments against the plague again shows how these acts were as important at the time as those more medical, such as quarantine. The final line of the report asks that everyone take heed of these orders and maintain regular prayers and fasts in order to reverse God’s punishment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe report also gives us more information on the elusive plague pits. Rule no. 13 dictates where and how plague victims should be buried: \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<div class=\"side-note\">\r\n“in some other convenient place [than church yards], and that a good quantity of unslaked Lime be put into Graves with such bodies, and that such Graves be not after opened within the space of a year or more, less they infect others.”\r\n</div>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlso mentioned in the orders, that we have not seen in aforementioned primary sources, is the first glimpses of the welfare state. Given the belief that sin and punishment were the major causes of the plague pandemic, the orders ensure that <b>“such visited poor may have sufficient Relief; want and nastiness being great occasions of the Infection.”</b>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nCoupled with the careful burials we see in plague pits, it can be ascertained that the plague may have fostered a culture of respect and care rather than one of isolation, which is often assumed from the fear of contagion.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h1> Popular Literature </h1>\r\n\r\nOne of the most interestingly comprehensive overviews of the plague pandemic of 1665-6 comes from the author Daniel Defoe, in his novel entitled Journal of the Plague Year. The novel follows the main character, simply referred to as H. F., during the pandemic in London.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nWhen compared to other primary sources used to understand the plague, Journal of the Plague Year certainly seems to corroborate. Defoe writes on the physical symptoms:\r\n\r\n<div class=\"side-note\">\r\n	“The swellings, which were generally in the neck or groin, when they grew hard and would not break, grew so painful that it was equal to the most exquisite torture; and some, not able to bear the torment, threw themselves out at windows”… “or otherwise made themselves away, and I saw several objects of that kind.”\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Plague-Victims.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n\r\nWe can liken this description of buboes to those given in other non-fiction sources, e.g., Charles II’s “Rules and Orders” and John Gadbury’s London’s deliverance predicted, being relatively detailed and graphic. This, however, also plays into the literary techniques of the novel, hence why it may be a slight exaggeration. To ‘make oneself away’ during this period, for example, literally meant to kill oneself.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nSuicide was seen as a religious crime against God – self-murder – and so whether this would have regularly occurred in a population readily believed to be being punished for their sins with the plague anyway, is debatable. It is due to these images of Defoe’s imagination within the text that it is unclear where it lies on the fiction/non-fiction spectrum.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nDespite Defoe’s guiding hand, the work is often read as non-fiction and used for various details on the physical aspects of the plague; online history guide Historic UK has used it as one of their sources to map the locations of various plague pits.  Indeed, Journal of the Plague Year references death tolls, burial registers and plague pits that, to a certain extent, do seem to be grounded in reality, as with his dimensions of the Aldgate plague pit.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nRegardless of whether we can cross-reference every detail given by Defoe on the plague, it provides an interesting contemporary popular view of how the disease was experienced. In other words, because the novel was written within living memory of plague year, Defoe would have had little reason to exaggerate or change objective details such as plague pit dimensions; these could easily have been checked. We can assume they are relatively accurate, and hence use it as the last important piece of the puzzle in the understanding of the early modern plague.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Plague Pits', '2018-08-05 7:52 pm', 'Plaque_Pits_Image.jpg', 'topics', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 5),
(14, 'First established in 1976, the Museum of London is amongst the most popular of London’s museums as its collection covers the capitals history as far back as the prehistoric sight of the city, right up to the modern London we see today. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocated a stone through away from St Paul’s Cathedral and on the sight of the London Wall, the museum provides visitors with a fascinatingly extensive insight into the evolution of the capital through some of the best and worst periods in British History. The museum of London is a definite must-see for visitors wishing to obtain a more in-depth insight into London’s history, and is a perfect day out for families too. \r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-gecko.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-interior.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-interior-2.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Museum of London Exterior\r\n					<span>Source: Francesco Camardo // Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					How revolutions in technology, fashion, and culture have transformed London <span>\r\n					Source: Museum of London </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Discover a city rebuilding itself after the Great Fire\r\n					<span>Source: Museum of London</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3>\r\nThis museum is free to enter. Any exhibitions and events however, may be subject to admission fees. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3>\r\nThe museum is open Monday-Sunday (10am-6pm) \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3>\r\nYes, photography is allowed at this museum. However, flash is not allowed due to the age of some of the exhibits.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3>\r\nYes, this museum has interactive technology. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Roman_London.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        You could discover how Londinium came to life and what daily life was like for Romans in the city 2,000 years ago\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Museum of London\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3>\r\nYes, this museum has a variety of different facilities available for children. For example, volunteer run ‘hands on history’ sessions are run by volunteers which give children the chance to interact hands-on with historical artefacts. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/families/visit-museum-london\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Families </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Guides:</h3>\r\nA full floor plan and guide (in several languages) are available online to download. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/museum-london/plan-your-visit/floor-plan\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Floor Plan </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>1. Bucklersbury Mosaic (250 AD):</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Bucklersbury-Mosaic.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Large mosaic floor with semi-circular end, from Bucklersbury, 3rd century AD, Queen Victoria Street, Londinium, Roman London, Museum of London\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nThis beautiful multi-coloured roman pavement was first discovered in Bucklersbury (in the City of London) in 1869. The mosaic has survived almost completely intact, and its few missing sections have been restored. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOriginally a heating system would have passed underneath this mosaic floor, consisting of a central channel radiating with smaller channels which hot air would pass through to go up inside the walls through the tiles. Don’t miss this incredible piece of ancient history in the Roman London gallery. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>2. Unic Taxi (1908):</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/unic-taxis-hidden-history.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       The Unic taxi was the first licenced petrol-driven taxi to arrive in London in 1903, with this specific vehicle being licensed for the use of taxi in 1908. \r\n\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source:  Mike Peel // Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Unic taxi was the first licenced petrol-driven taxi to arrive in London in 1903, with this specific vehicle being licensed for the use of taxi in 1908. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe early Edwardian period saw a technological revolution, with the mass development of motor vehicles bringing over 2,000 motor-cabs to the city which threatened the traditional modes of transportation such as horse-drawn hansoms and four wheeled growlers. See for yourselves the beautiful predecessor of the modern taxi in the ‘Modern London’ gallery.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>3. London 2012 Cauldron:</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/london_2012_cauldron_hidden_history.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Thomas Heatherwick’s London 2012 Cauldron is the star of this gallery. With dramatic footage and exclusive testimony, we recapture its journey from design to the climactic opening and closing ceremonies.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source:  Museum of London\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nOn the night of the 27th July 2012, the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic cauldron (designed by Thomas Heatherwick) was revealed for the first time to the world. At the climax of the incredible opening ceremony, the cauldrons 204 stems dramatically rose up in the air to form a beautiful feature in the centre of the Olympic stadium in Stratford, which became a defining moment of the ceremony. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo this day, the 2012 Olympics remains an pivotal historical landmark in British history- So don’t miss this wonderful atmospheric installation with light, sound and video nestled in the centre of the ‘Modern London’ floor.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> \r\nYes, this museum has several food and drink facilities such as London Wall Bar and Kitchen, Benugo Entrance Hall Café and Benugo Sackler Hall Café. There is also a museum lunch space for families to bring their own food and drink. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> \r\nGuided tours and talks are available at this museum however, there is a fixed charge for the different tours. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/application/files/1614/7888/5118/Group_tours_201617.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Tours </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> \r\nThe nearest stations to the Museum of London are Barbican station (5-minute walk) and St Paul’s station (5-minute walk) \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> \r\nBuses 4, 8, 25, 56, 100, 172, 242, 521 all stop near the museum. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> \r\nMuseum of London, 150 London Wall, London EC2Y 5HN\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\nThere are a small number of disabled parking spaces for Blue and Orange Badge holders although spaces must be booked in advance. Please call 02078145552 to book, or email: \r\n\r\n<a href = \"mailto: access@museumoflondon.org.uk\"> acesss@museumoflondon.org.uk</a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> \r\nAssistance dogs are welcome to museum and portable induction loops are available at the front desk. Some of the theatres are fitted with induction loop systems, and there is a selection of subtitled and BSL interpreted videos in the galleries. \r\n<br /> \r\nFree monthly BSL and captioned tours are also available each month. \r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h4> \r\nMagnifying glasses are available from the information desks, as well as large print guides for the permanent and major exhibitions. Free monthly gallery tours for visitors with visual impairments are also available. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4>\r\nWheelchairs and mobility scooters are available to borrow during your visit, please book them in advance from the above number. Folding seats are also available to borrow at any time. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nLifts and escalators are available from street level near the London Wall roundabout, as well as a lift and staircase at noble street. Fully accessible toilets and lifts are available on all floors of the museum. \r\n', 'Museum of London', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'museum-of-london.jpg', 'topics', '51.517809', '-0.096676', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),
(15, 'Adjacent to the Royal Hospital Chelsea (the home of the Chelsea pensioners) the National Army Museum is the central museum for the history of the British Army. Reopened in 2017 after a £23.74 million re-development programme, the museum is the perfect location for those wishing to explore the extensive and thought-provoking history of the British Army through five themes ‘Soldier, Army, Battle, Society and Insight’. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is also worth noting that the museum is interactive in its exploration of important themes, which makes it a unique and ideal location for families and schools to visit. \r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-1.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-2.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-3.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					The National Army Museum was first conceived in the late 1950s, and owes its existence to the persistent hard work of Field Marshal Sir Gerald Templer, who did most of the fundraising for it.\r\n					<span>Source: Flickr</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					It was established by Royal Charter in 1960, with the intention of collecting, preserving, and exhibiting objects and records relating to the Regular and Auxiliary forces of the British Army and of the Commonwealth, and to encourage research into their history and traditions. <span>\r\n					Source: National Army Museum // Flickr </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The museum tells the story of the British Army from the time of the Battle of Agincourt to the early 21st century.\r\n					<span>Source: National Army Museeum</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3>\r\nThis museum is free to enter. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3>\r\nThe museum is open Monday-Sunday (10am-5:30pm)  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3>\r\nYes, photography is allowed at this museum. However, flash is not allowed due to the age of some of the exhibits.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3>\r\nYes, this museum provides a wonderful and interactive experience for visitors by using technology to obtain an uniquely personal journey through the museums several themes.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/exhibition.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A book on the work of Abram Games during the Second World War, written by his daughter Naomi Games, will be available to purchase in The Shop at £16.99. #AbramGames\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: National Army Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3>\r\nAs previously mentioned, the museum is unique in its use of technology and interactive exhibits which make important topics relatable and more understandable for younger audiences. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/families\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Families </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Guides:</h3>\r\nA guidebook is available to buy in the souvenir shop, or online. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>1. Napoleon’s Horse ‘Marengo’ (1831):</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Napoleon-Horse-Marengo.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Napoleon\'s horse Marengo, National Army Museum, London.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: National Army Museum // Flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nYes, you saw that right, the Skeleton of Napoleon’s actual horse is on display in the Battle gallery of the museum! As horses were historically crucial to aiding soldiers in battle, it comes as no surprise that Marengo saw the notorious Emperor through some of his greatest triumphs and defeats in his history as ruler of France.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA grey Arab horse by breed, Marengo was named after the French victory at Marengo (in Italy) in 1800, however, he was captured by the British following French defeat at Waterloo and died in 1831. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>2. The Robes of Lawrence of Arabia (1916):</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/The-Robes-of-Lawrence-of-Arabia.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Robes belonging to T.E Lawrence: These are the actual robes worn by Colonel Thomas Edward Lawrence (1888 - 1935) during the first world war. He was also know as Lawrence of Arabia.\r\n\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: National Army Museum // Flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nFew soldiers have greater legend and cultural iconography attached to them quite like Colonel TE Lawrence, otherwise known as Lawrence of Arabia. Posted to Hejaz (in modern Saudi Arabia) in the First World War liaise with the Hashemite forces, Lawrence’s unique diplomatic skills and willingness to adapt to the cultural norms of his foreign allies made him popular amongst Arab leaders, which led to the great success of his campaign and gave birth to the consequential legend.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLawrence’s adoption of Arab dress and culture was unique for the period and fascinated the public, sealing the distinct imagery we now see in films such as ‘Lawrence of Arabia’ (1962). The silk robe on display in the museum was worn by Lawrence in 1916, and the jambiya dagger attached to the robe was awarded to him following the attack of Aqaba – Don’t miss out on seeing a real glimpse into the legend in the ‘Army’ gallery of the museum.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>3. Signboard from ‘Hellfire Corner’ in Ypres (1918)</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Signboard-from-Hellfire-Corner-in-Ypres.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Wooden painted signboard from \'Hellfire Corner\' at Ypres, 1918. This sign was used to mark \'Hellfire Corner\', a busy junction on the Menin Road, which ran from Ypres in Belgium to the frontline trenches. It was a very dangerous place, being within easy range of the German guns.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source:  National Army Museum // Flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nAs we are now in the final year of the centenary of the First World War it only seems fitting to mention this signboard, which is a clear representation of the destruction caused by war and a symbol of why we must continue to remember all those who have lost their lives as a result.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocated in Ypres (Belgium) British soldiers dubbed a busy junction on a road that led to the trenches ‘Hellfire Corner’ where this exact signboard stood. The damage to the sign is a testament to its location’s namesake, as a dozen bullet holes are scattered across the board, acting as a clear reminder of the human cost of warfare.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> \r\nYes, this museum has a café (Open Monday to Friday 10am-4pm and Saturday to Sunday 10am-5pm) \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> \r\nA highlights tour guide is available on the National Army Museum website (please see the link below) \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/plan-visit/highlights-tour\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Highlights </a>\r\n<br />\r\nGroup and private tours are also available (please see the link below) \r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/plan-visit/groups/enquiry-form\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Group Tours </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> \r\nThe nearest tube station is Sloane Square, which is a 10-minute walk from the museum. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> \r\nBus 107 stops outside the museum.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> \r\nNational Army Museum, Royal Hospital Road, Chelsea, London, SW3 4HT.\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-4.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-5.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-6.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Visitors in Special Forces Exhibition\r\n					<span>Source: National War Museum</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Special forces exhibition <span>\r\n					Source: National War Museum </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Inside the National Army Museum\r\n					<span>Source: National War Museum</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> \r\nInduction loops are provided in all public areas of the museum such as the Welcome Desk, the Templer Study Centre and the Foyle Centre.\r\n<br /> \r\nIn addition, when audio is used in the galleries an induction loop is also available.\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h4> \r\nNo direct information can be found on the National Army Museum’s website, so please contact the Museum on the below number or by filling in the form also available from the link below.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/contact-nam\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Contacts </a>\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4>\r\nFixed seating is available throughout all of the museum’s galleries, as well as a lift which is accessible on and to every floor. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nAssistance dogs are welcome, and disabled access toilets are located on the ground and lower ground floor.\r\n', 'National Army Museum', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'national-army-museum.jpg', 'topics', '51.4862408', '-0.1601986', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 4, 1),
(16, 'Located on Great Queen Street, the site of the current Freemasons’ Hall has been the headquarters for English and Welsh Freemasons since 1775. The current building was built in 1932 in memorial to the 3,000 members of the Freemasons who were killed in the First World War. It is still an active location for Freemason meetings, events and ceremonies.<br><br>\r\nThe building is one of the UK’s finest examples of Art Deco architecture and is an important location for the preservation of the history of Freemasonry, with a library and museum which are free and open to visitors. Hidden in plain sight to visitors of the city, the current museum space was opened in 2016 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Freemasonry and follows the ‘Three Centuries of English Freemasons’ beginning in 1717 to the present day.<br><br>\r\nOn display in the gallery are a collection of fascinating objects, books and documentations such as ceremonial jewels, early constitutions and the standout golden ‘Grand Masters Throne’ which was created for King George IV in 1791, an object which cannot be missed. Down the hall from the museum is the library, also open to visitors, which offers a collection of over 65,000 books which cover the dense history of British Freemasonry where visitors can sit and read, use the computers and even search their own family histories for links to Freemasonry.<br><br>\r\nFor those interested in the history of the hall itself, free tours are offered up to five times per day and are an excellent chance for visitors to see inside the Grand Temple and ceremonial areas still used by the Freemason’s today.', 'Freemasons\' Hall and London Museum', '', 'Header Image 2.jpg', 'topics', '51.515178', '-0.121531', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1);
