(17, 'Sequestered away on the western side of London’s picturesque Green Park stands a monument devoted to the commemoration of Britain’s most controversial Second World War heroes: the members of RAF Bomber Command.\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nVisitors to the park may be surprised to discover an impressive, classic portico style marble structure waiting for them. Inside the building stands a poignant sight as seven 9ft tall bronze men form the centre piece of the monument. \r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThe memorial has been designed to be more than just another pretty London shrine; it’s primary purpose is to ensure there is a permanent tribute to the 55,573 Bomber Command servicemen who died in the defence of both the city and Britain.\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Bomber_Command_Memorial_-_panoramio.jpg\" alt=\"Nature\" class=\"responsive\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>The Monument </h1>\r\nThe monument holds several interesting features – the first being the buildings open nature, ensuring the men are exposed to the sky, allowing light to cascade down and illuminate them. This clever blend of architecture and symbolism becomes even more powerful at night if visitors look up and spot the phrase “per ardua ad astra”. \r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThe Latin motto used by the RAF during the war translates as: “through adversity to the stars”. Another feature is the structure’s ceiling, constructed using salvaged sections of a Handley Page Halifax III aircraft used by Bomber Command. The plane in question was shot down over Belgium during an operation that cost the lives of eight crewmen on the 28th of May 1944. Its incorporation into the memorial adds a poignant connection to the past. \r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/2013-05-12_London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/cieling.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					RAF Bomber Command Memorial in London Green Park.\r\n\r\n					<span>Zeisterre / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Exterior of the Memorial in 2013. <span>\r\n					Tim Rademacher / Wikimedia Commons </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The RAF motto at the Bomber Command Memorial. / johnny essex geograph.org.uk\r\n					<span>Johnny Essex / Geograph.org.uk</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nCommemoration of RAF Bomber Command remains a controversial topic thanks to the operations they were charged to undertake during the closing phases of the war. <mark>Some historians have questioned whether the bombing of civilian targets such as Dresden were the only way to speed up Allied victory. </mark>\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nWhile Winston Churchill boldly proclaimed that Britain’s bombers would provide the means of victory in 1940 – a quote that can be found on the inside western wall of the memorial – they have ultimately been minimalised and airbrushed out of British memory due to the murky nature of their mission.\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Fotothek_df_ps_0000010_Blick_vom_Rathausturm.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Lancaster_I_NG128_Dropping_Blockbuster_-_Duisburg_-_Oct_14,_1944.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bomber_command_memorial_ruins.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bomber_command_memorial_pictures_of_destruction.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"4\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/this memorial.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 5 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Dresden, 1945, view from the city hall (Rathaus) over the destroyed city.\r\n					<span>Deutsche Fotothek / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					A Lancaster releases the main part of its load, a 4,000 lb (1,800 kg) HC \"cookie\" and 108 30 lb (14 kg) \"J\" incendiaries. <span>\r\n					Credit: Wikimedia Commons </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Over ninety percent of the city center was destroyed.\r\n					<span>Bundesarchiv, Bild 183-Z0309-310 / G. Beyer / CC-BY-SA 3.0</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Frauenkirche ruins with a figure of Martin Luther that survived the bombings.\r\n					<span>Bundesarchiv, Bild 183-60015-0002 / Giso Löwe / CC-BY-SA 3.0</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Lord Lieutenant Of East Sussex, Peter Field, dedicated the memorial to the 55,573 airmen who lost their lives.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\nIt is perhaps for this reason that along the monuments northern side is an engraving that alludes to this difficult subject; “this memorial also commemorates those of all nations who lost their lives in the bombings of 1939-1945.” \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is no accident that that the seven bronze men have been immortalised in sombre contemplation, as each of the seven men walk away from their mission it seems they are reflecting on the impossibly difficult act they have undertaken in the name of peace - humanising them once again. It seems that the monument has been created in part to rehabilitate Britain’s forgotten heroes, as well as being mindful of the civilians killed by their actions.\r\n<br><br>\r\nOpened in 2012 by Her Majesty the Queen, it had taken sixty-six years for the 125,000 men of Bomber Command to receive the acknowledgment. The members of RAF Bomber Command played a pivotal role in the defence of London; they now stand watch again over the Capitol.\r\n', 'Bomber Command Memorial', '2018-08-21 5:52 pm', 'w_1200.jpg', 'topics', '51.503389', '-0.148922', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 2),
(18, 'When exploring a city, we are often told to “look up” to admire the architecture of the buildings frequently taken for granted. I am telling you to look down. Walk into the middle of Charing Cross Road where an island opposes Old Compton Street and look down into the grate. A rusted and faded blue sign lingers beneath the busy road, marking the territory as “Little Compton Street”. How the sign got there is still a mystery, but we do know where it used to be.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe portion of Old Compton Street between Greek Street and Charing Cross Road was the domain of this humble Victorian street sign. Archival evidence dating back to 1763 speaks of assault charges and bail, however, insurance documents show that the street itself was wholly unremarkable such as a milliner at number 7 and a tobacconist at number 12.\r\n<br><br>\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Little-Compton-Street.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/TheMetalGrill.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/EvidenceofLittleComptonStreet.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Peering into the GrillEvidenceofLittleComptonStreet.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 4 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:50px; position: relative; left:-10px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					A traffic island on London’s Charing Cross Road.\r\n					<span>\r\n						Source Wikimedia Commons\r\n					</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The Metal Grill.\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Evidence of Little Compton Street.\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Peering into the Grill\r\n					<span>Source: Paul Tiny Jackson / Unusual Encounters Blog</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <br>\r\nIt was at one of the many pubs along this street that two poets are said to have frequented on a regular basis to overdose on gin and absinthe. Around 1872, *Paul Verlaine and Arthur Rimbaud* ﬂed their native France to escape Verlaine’s wife and son and to embark upon what would become a volatile, torrid, and eventually life-threatening aﬀair. The exact location of this pub has been debated but the general consensus is that the Hibernia Stores on 5-7 Old Compton Street (now 23-25 Old Compton Street) was the setting for their frivolity.\r\n<br><br>\r\nTheir time in London clearly had a profound eﬀect on their literary works; many of the verses of Rimbaud’s Les Illuminations are set against the backdrop of the West End. In a way, the obscurity and hidden manner of Little Compton Street’s sign is a reﬂection and an ode to the forbidden nature of Rimbaud and Verlaine’s relationship. Bar Soho now stands in the place of the Hibernia Stores with revellers likely unaware that they follow in the drunken footsteps of illustrious French poets.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/800px-Henri_Fantin-Latour_-_By_the_Table_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Around 1872, Paul Verlaine (seated, far left) and Arthur Rimbaud (seated, second to left) ﬂed their native France to escape Verlaine’s wife and son and to embark upon what would become a volatile, torrid, and eventually life-threatening aﬀair.\r\nSource: Painting by Henri Fantin-Latour / Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\nA map dated March 1889, 16 years after the departure of Rimbaud and Verlaine, detail the layout of the miniature street. Complete with house numbers, we see that the area was ﬂooded with shops which are now restaurants and bars. The public house, on the other hand, still stands, over 200 years later.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe underground street sign now serves as a location prompt to utility workers as they scuttle beneath the whirring of the world overhead. However it is also a reminder that the romantic past of London shines through its electric urbanisation.\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Watercolour by John Phillips Emslie, 1886, depicting Crown Street (now Charing Cross Road) and the junction with Old Compton Street..jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Charles Booth’s Poverty Map of London, circa 1890s. Little Compton Street is highlighted in yellow..jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Insurance plan map, 1889, showing shops (S), dwellings (D), hardware stores (H.W.) and a public house (P.H.).jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1;margin-bottom: 0px; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">Watercolour by John Phillips Emslie, 1886, depicting Crown Street (now Charing Cross Road) and the junction with Old Compton Street. © City of London\r\n					<span>London Metropolitan Archives http://collage.cityoflondon.gov.uk</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Charles Booth’s Poverty Map of London, circa 1890s. Little Compton Street is highlighted in yellow.\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Insurance plan map, 1889, showing shops (S), dwellings (D), hardware stores (H.W.) and a public house (P.H.)\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>', 'Hidden Little Compton Street', '2018-08-21 6:50 pm', 'littlecamp.jpg', 'topics', '51.5138757', '-0.1294837', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, NULL),
(19, 'In an area of open parkland in the south-east corner of Hampstead Heath in north-west London there is still a strong feeling of being very much a part of countryside. And yet, when standing at the viewpoint of Parliament Hill there is this sudden shift of being miles away from the big city. Approximately 6 miles out of the city of London the 791-acre heath, which is an amalgam of the grounds of several large houses that were once in the area, is the summit of Parliament Hill which provides a fantastic view towards London and is a focal point for locals and visitors alike. \r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament-Hill-hiddenhistory-london.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>The Land</h3>\r\n<br />\r\nIt has been long suspected that the mound on top of the hill was a Bronze Age (2500 until c. 800 BC) burial barrow. The hill itself was part of a manor in 1133 during Henry I reign. He decided to give the land to Baron Richard de Balta. A grant was confirmed by Westminster to Richard de Balta of ‘land of the fee of Westminster of Hampstead’ for rent of two pounds a year. This also included Abbot William de Humez (1214-22) being assigned the two-pound rent ‘from the manor of Hampstead’ to the abbey’s kitchen. It’s not clear if the grant was of the whole manor or of the estate within it. During Henry II reign the manor appears to have been passed onto Alexander de Barentyn who was the King’s butler. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs time went on the plots of land in the manor were sold off. Especially in the early 19th century. Although the hill remained mainly common land, The Metropolitan Board of Works (which was created to help provide infrastructure to cope with London’s rapid growth) acquired Hampstead Heath for the people in 1875, which didn’t include Parliament Hill. Thirteen years later Parliament Hill was added to Hampstead heath for £300,000. The Manorial rights of the land remained in private hands until the mid-20th century. The manorial rights lapsed under Sir Spencer Pocklington Maryon Wilson. Though the estate itself was purely a formal position without any real power. It was then passed on to Shane Gough, 5th Viscount Gough. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n</div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_london.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_during_sunset.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_romantic_scene.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Parliament Hill is an area of open parkland in the south-east corner of Hampstead Heath in north-west London. The hill, which is 98 metres high, is notable for its views of the capital\'s skyline.\r\n\r\n					<span>Flickr / Londonmatt</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The area that was known as Traitors\' Hill, may have acquired its current name during the English Civil Warin the 17th century. When it was occupied by troops loyal to the English Parliament. <span>\r\n					Source: Wikimedia Commons </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					A legend states that this was the site from where Guy Fawkes and Robert Catesby, of the Gunpowder Plot on November the 5th 1605, planned to watch the destruction of Parliament.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nHampstead Heath including Parliament Hill was host to livestock. The cattle were reared to be sold through Smithfields the London meat market up until the 1940’s. The grass there today is bred farm grasses, which just shows a legacy from a time when the heath was an agricultural resource. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGreater London Council managed Parliament Hill, which, was then taken over by Camden Council until 1989 when the City of London Corporation took ownership. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>What’s in the Name?</h3>\r\n\r\nIn ancient times, long before Parliament Hill got its name it was referred to as Traitors Hill, possibly due to it being an execution site. A legend states that the hill is connected with the Gunpowder plot to blow up Parliament. <mark>It’s believed that Guy Fawkes and Robert Catesby planned to watch Parliament being destroyed from the top of the hill on the 5th of November 1605.</mark> As intriguing as this is, especially in relation to the name Traitors Hill, the theory is unsubstantiated.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt was also suggested that the name Traitors Hill came about in the mid-17th century during the English Civil War. Troops loyal to Parliament would occupy the hill. With the modern houses of Parliament seen from the viewpoint, those who were against King Charles I and his views on the Irish insurrection would use the hill as a point of defence. It isn’t clear, if the name changed during the civil war or after but the name ‘Parliament Hill’ did come into existence. \r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Gunpowder_Plot_conspirators_hidden_history.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>It’s not just about the View.</h3>\r\n\r\nParliament Hill is best known for its viewpoint at the top. Measuring 98.1 metres (322 ft) high, providing beautiful views across London. The view, which can be captured in one panorama, is one of three viewing locations on Hampstead heath that has been identified in Greater London Authority\'s London View Management Framework. This is in recognition of the significant views towards St Pauls Cathedral and Victoria Tower at the Palace of Westminster. The viewpoint is also at times referred to as “kite hill” due to the popularity of flying kites on a sunny day. However, there is more to the area then meets the eye. Parliament Hill not only has some key landmarks but also holds various sporting events. It is also home to a flock of Flamingos.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/a_boy_flies_a_kite_on_parliament_hill.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A boy flies a kite on the summit of Parliament Hill, Hampstead Heath. Kite flying is one of many outdoor activities pursued on Hampstead Heath. The breezy summit of Parliament Hill offers one of the best kiting spots. Henry Grant also photographed enthusiasts flying model airplanes on the heath.\r\nSource: Henry Grant Collection/Museum of London\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>The Parliament Hill Lido</h3>\r\n\r\nThe Parliament Hill Lido can be found at the bottom of the hill next to Gospel Oak railway station. The pool turned 80 years old in 2018 and is popular with locals as a place to exercise or just cool off in an outdoor pool. On the 20th of August 1938 the now Grade II-listed Lido was opened. At the time it was the most expensive of the 13 outdoor pools in London County Council that was built between 1920 and the outbreak of the Second World War. When it originally opened diving-boards adorned its sides as well as a slide. However, today the offering is more simplistic. In 1990 Historic England listed the lido under the Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990 as amended for its special architectural or historic interest. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2005 the Lido underwent an extensive refurbishment. It now boasts a new stainless-steel liner (the only one of its kind in an outdoor pool in the UK) and reflective qualities that not only help retain heat, but also gives the water an extra shimmer. The pool isn’t just for families and wetsuit-clad fitness fiends, the lido will also be used for forthcoming triathlons. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n</div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_lido_hidden_history_london_3.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_lido_hidden_history_london_2.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_lido_hidden_history_london.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					By August 1938 the now Grade II-listed Lido was the most expensive of the 13 outdoor pools in London County Council that was built between 1920 and the outbreak of the Second World War.\r\n					<span>Photography: John Weller (Wild Swimming Spain)</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The pool isn’t just for families and wetsuit-clad fitness fiends, the lido will also be used for forthcoming triathlons. <span>\r\n					Source: Wikimedia Commons </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Built in 1938 and Grade II-listed, this is the only stainless steel lined outdoor pool in the country. Diving into it is like entering a giant shiny metal bowl.\r\n					<span>Photography: Dominick Tyler from the Book Wild Swim</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Parliament Hill Bandstand</h3>\r\n\r\nOut of everything to see at Parliament Hill, there is nothing that has as much history as the Bandstand. The bandstand that stands today was actually built in the 1990’s as the original was rundown. The original however, was based on the other side of Kite Hill on the banks of Highgate Ponds in the early 1900’s. The Bandstand was the subject of many attractive posters and black and white snapshots, which proved that the spot was quite the tourist attraction and as a place to see and be seen.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday’s bandstand can be found next to the Farmers Markets and Cricket ground. The current design is based on the original. There is no particular record of when the original and sizeable circular seating area around disappeared from Parliament Hill Fields, however there was a post-war carbuncle that was certainly in operation in the current location from the 1950’s.\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bandstand_at_parliament_hill_hidden_history.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The bandstand that stands today was actually built in the 1990’s as the original was rundown.\r\nSource: Julian Osley / Bandstand, Parliament Hill Fields\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\nIn the late 1960’s Camden Council organised a series of free concerts at the bandstand. Beginning in September 1968, on a rainy Wednesday the Jefferson Airplane and Fairport Convention played to only a few hundred tuned-in people. The following summer the council progressed their free Camden Festival concept further by putting on three weekly parties throughout May. The first band to perform at the festival was Pink Floyd. The band were squeezed into the corrugated iron shed while battling the feedback from their PA. <br /> <br /><mark>The following week the crowd doubled in size.</mark> This was partly due to John Peel mentioning the events on his radio shows and by week three Fleetwood Mac played with 25,000 people turning up. Sadly, Fleetwood Mac only played a couple of songs before being forced off the stage due to a group of people causing trouble. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn recent years more celebrities have brought attention to the bandstand. In 2006 Booker Prize-winning local author Alan Hollinghurst fought a long and ultimately fruitless battle to have a programme of Sunday afternoon brass, jazz and Japanese music performed at the bandstand blocked. The grounds of the “intolerable noise nuisance” ABBA’s Benny Anderson also brought international attention to the bandstand by performing some of the pop classics he penned in a ‘comeback gig’ as part of a Swedish cultural celebration. \r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_hiddenhistory_london_bandstand.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<br />\r\nTo hear more about the Pink Floyd gig ‘The Archive’ has documented stories of those who were present which, can be accessed <a href=\"http://www.ukrockfestivals.com/pinkfloyd5-9-69.html\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a>\r\nThe bandstand today is a focal point for a lot of the Heath events and like previous generations of school kids it is still a popular meeting spot during the week. The heath’s famous lone bagpiper still plays out tunes at the bandstand during most of the early mornings. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Parliament Hill School</h3>\r\n\r\n<mark>The Community School for Girls opened in 1906.</mark> As of 2013 the secondary school and sixth form for girls had 1,250 students enrolled with ages between 11 and 18. The school is part of the successful SASWAP sixth form consortium, which focuses strongly on the academic qualifications.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/parliament_hill_school.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Parliament Hill School is a secondary school and sixth form for girls located in the Borough of Camden in London, England. In 2013, there were 1,250 students on roll, between the ages of 11 and 18.\r\nSource: Parliament Hill School / Facebook\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nOther amenities at Parliament Hill are grass tennis courts, an athletics track, a cricket pitch, angling and cycling facilities and there is even an area for bowls and croquet. Beside the cricket pitch is the Parliament Hill London Farmers Market, which is open every Saturday from 10am-2pm. On the other side there is an adventure playground for the kids. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nParliament Hill is one of the focal points of Hampstead Heath overall and provides Londoners a small piece of the countryside while living in the capital city. There are even parts of the hill that are still unmown in the summer which are crisscrossed by a network of pathways. Parliament Hill can be seen as a less popular place to visit compared to other sites, however, it provides a natural haven to north Londoners and its history is rich for those who wish to seek it.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Parliament Hill', '2019-02-26 3:39 pm', 'Parliament-Hill.jpg', 'topics', '51.5596682', '-0.1618931', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, NULL),
(20, 'Sitting against an adjoining wall in Postman’s Park – aptly named as it was once the site of the headquarters of the General Post Office where the postmen used to go during their breaks – this little-known monument remembers the lives of 62 people who died selflessly trying to save another. \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThis memorial to everyday heroism and self-sacrifice was proposed by the painter and sculptor, George Frederic Watts, in a letter to the editor of The Times in 1887 as part of the celebrations of Queen Victoria’s Golden Jubilee. He, like many wealthy people in the late Victorian period, believed in the need for social reform for the poor in England, and in turn saw a need to actively remember the heroism of ‘ordinary’ people. In his letter he wrote:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark> “The character of a nation as a people of great deeds is one, it appears to me, that should never be lost sight of. It must surely be a matter of regret when names worthy to be remembered and stories stimulating and instructive are allowed to be forgotten… It is not too much to say that the history of Her Majesty’s reign would gain a lustre were the nation to erect a monument, say, here in London, to record the names of these likely to be forgotten heroes”. <small> George Frederic Watts</small>\r\n</mark>\r\n \r\n<br>\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/George_Frederic_Watts\'s_Memorial_to_Heroic_Self_Sacrifice.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nDespite this initial suggestion for the memorial, it wasn’t officially opened until 30 July 1900. In 1898, Watts was invited by the vicar of St Botolph’s church – the space being their former churchyard – to create the monument in the now public park. So, in 1899 the construction began of the 50ft long 9ft high shelter by J. Simpson and Son for the tablets at the cost of £402. Benches were also installed to encourage the public to stay a little longer. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSpace was made available for 120 tablets (in rows of 24), though only 54 tablets have been installed so far. Each tablet is made up of small tiles and records the name(s) of the deceased with the details and date of the events making them worthy of remembrance. Only 4 of these plaques were installed when the monument was opened. The remainder of the first row included 9 installed in 1902, and 11 more along with T. H. Wren’s memorial to Watts in 1905 following his death the year before. All 24 of these tablets were designed by the ceramicist William De Morgan. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Postman\'s_Park_Wall_of_Heroes.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<br />\r\nA further 29 tablets were designed by Royal Doulton, 24 of which were installed altogether in 1908 filling a second row. Another 5 Doulton-style tablets were added on the next row from 1919-1930, which included replacement of a De Morgan tablet with incorrect information. A further tablet in the original De Morgan style created by Fred Passenger was slotted into the old spot for the incorrect tablet in 1931. Finally, the 54th tablet was added much later in 2009, commemorating Leigh Pitt who died saving a boy from drowning in 2007.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOne of the people featured in the memorial is Alice Ayres, who died in 1885 while trying to save three children under her care from an upper-story of a burning house. Two of the three children survived, and Alice died in the process of trying to save herself as she fell awkwardly after jumping out the window. She was one of the most famous additions to the memorial and had already been commemorated in other ways across the country around the time of her death – this included in memorials, artwork and a street was renamed after her near to where she died on Union Street in 1936. Her name was also used as an alias in the play (and 2004 film) Closer.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/alice-ayres.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/alice-ayres-memorial-tablet.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/ayres-street.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/London-fire-brigade.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"4\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Closer-alice-ayres-hidden-history.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 5 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Alice Ayres (pictured above) was an English nursemaid honoured for her bravery in rescuing the children in her care from a house fire. \r\n\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Alice Ayres\'s memorial tablet, designed by William De Morgan and added to the Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice in 1902\r\n					<span>\r\n					 Source: Wikimedia Commons.</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>In 1936 the new Labour administration of the London County Council renamed White Cross Street, near the scene of the Union Street fire, to Ayres Street in tribute to Alice Ayres, a name it retains today.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>The Chandlers\' house at 194 Union Street no longer stands, and the site is occupied by part of the Union House office complex; immediately opposite the site of the fire is the present-day headquarters of the London Fire Brigade.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>In the movie, Closer, Jude Law and Natalie Portman\'s characters visit the park. Natalie\'s character uses Alice\'s Identity as her own.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you find you want to get to know them better, we absolutely recommend you that you read  <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Heroes-Postmans-Park-Self-Sacrifice-2015-09-01/dp/B01FKUO11S/\" target=\"_blank\">Dr John Price’s Heroes of Postman’s Park: Heroic Self-Sacrifice in Victorian London,</a> where he delves into the lives of each person remembered in the memorial. You can hear him in an interview about his research here. You can also follow the Friends of Watts Memorial on Twitter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/wattsmemorial\" target=\"_blank\">@WattsMemorial </a> to see upcoming events and to find out how you can support them.\r\n', 'The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice', '2019-02-28 6:21 am', 'watts-memorial-app.jpg', 'topics', '51.516742', '-0.097334', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 4);
INSERT INTO `articles` (`articlesid`, `text`, `articletitle`, `dateUploaded`, `articleImage`, `appearin`, `latitude`, `longitude`, `view`, `likes`, `dislikes`, `featured`, `position`, `visible`, `categoryid`, `authorid`) VALUES
(21, 'Nelson’s death at Trafalgar secured his position as one of Britain’s most heroic figures. His signal “England expects that every man will do his duty” has been regularly quoted, paraphrased and referenced right up to the modern day. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is because of that, that Admiral Nelson has had numerous monuments erected in his honour cementing not only his memory but also his legacy. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Horatio_Nelson_painting_hidden_history_uk.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Vice-Admiral Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson was a British flag officer in the Royal Navy. He was noted for his inspirational leadership, grasp of strategy, and unconventional tactics, which together resulted in a number of decisive British naval victories, particularly during the Napoleonic Wars.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBorn Horatio Nelson on the 29th September 1758 in Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, he was the 6th of 11 children of a clergyman. Joining the navy at the tender age of 12, he moved swiftly through the ranks and became Captain at 20. Nelson saw service in the West Indies, the Baltic region and Canada. In 1787 he married Frances Nisbet in Nevis. Once he returned to England with his bride however, he spent the next 5 years on half-pay, frustrated at the lack of a command. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt wasn’t until 1793, when Britain entered the French Revolutionary Wars that Nelson was given command of HMS Agamemnon, a 64-gun third-rate ship of the line of the British Royal Navy.  He served in the Mediterranean, assisted capturing Corsica and saw battle a Calvi where he lost the sight in his right eye. In 1797 in the Battle of Santa Cruz de Tenerife he lost his right arm.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nNelson was well known for his bold action and at times, disregard of orders given from his superiors. It is this disregard for orders which brought him victories against the Spanish off Cape Vincent in 1797 and in The Battle of Copenhagen four years later. His excuse for not ceasing fire when ordered, was due to the fact that he put his telescope to his blind eye and subsequently claimed he did not see the signal to withdraw.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/The_Battle_of_the_Nile.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Destruction of L\'Orient at the Battle of the Nile\"\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<mark>In 1798 at the Battle of the Nile, Nelson successfully destroyed Napoleon’s fleet and thus his bid for a direct trade route to India.</mark> His next posting was in Naples where he ended up falling in love with Emma, Lady Hamilton. Both considered each other soul mates but they remained in their respective marriages. They had a child named Horatia, in 1801. It was in the same year that Nelson was promoted to Vice-Admiral.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNelson’s leadership from 1794 to 1805 saw the Royal Navy prove its supremacy over the French. The most famous engagement, at Cape Trafalgar, saved Britain from the threat of invasion by Napoleon. Before the Battle of Trafalgar on 21 October 1805 Nelson sent out the famous signal to his fleet <mark>“England expects that every man will do his duty”.</mark> \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nA few hours later while leading the attack on the combined French and Spanish fleet a musket shot fired from the fighting top of the French ship Redoubtable badly wounded him.  Three hours later he passed away from his wound. Once the battle was over his body was preserved in brandy while heading back to England where he was given a state funeral.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nTo read in more detail about the Battle of Trafalgar please go to the British Battles website.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/fall_of_nelson_horatio_Battle_of_Trafalgar_hh_hidden_history_london.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Painter Denis Dighton\'s imagining of Nelson being shot on the quarterdeck of Victory.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>The Monument</h3>\r\nTaking centre stage in Trafalgar Square Nelson’s Column towers at 18 ft. 1 in (5.5m). Nelson’s Column was built between 1840 and 1843, after William Railton won a protracted competition to design the structure. The original decision to award Railton the contract was overturned, but his design emerged triumphant in the re-run. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOther changes included the monument being built entirely out of sandstone. However, this plan changed shortly before construction started. William used Dartmoor granite, which brought the total weight of the statue to approximately 2,500 tonnes.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/nelson\'s_column_slide1_hidden_history_london.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/nelson\'s_column_under_construction_hidden_history_london.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/nelson\'s_column_close_up_hidden_history_london.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Nelson’s Column cost £47,000 to built in the 1840s, which is the equivalent of between £3 million and £4 million today. Most of the money came from private investors, with the Tsar of Russia footing more than a quarter of the bill on his own.\r\n\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Nelson’s Column was constructed out of Dartmoor granite and weighs around 2,500 tonnes. It was originally meant to be built entirely out of sandstone, but the plan was changed shortly before construction started.<span>\r\n					Source: Wikimedia Commons </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The 18 ft 1 in (5.5 m) statue of Admiral Nelson which stands on top of the column, designed by Sir Edwin Landseer, is built out of sandstone rather than granite\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\nOver the years the height of the monument has changed. The original proposal was for a 203ft (62m) column, however, due to concerns over the stability and cost the construction plans were scaled back. Robert Peel the then-prime minister stated that it would be ‘extremely inconvenient should the monument fall in that crowded part of the metropolis.” But the height of the column changed again in 2006 when it was discovered the structure was 169 feet - roughly 16 foot smaller than what everyone had thought. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSince its construction there have been numerous people who have climbed the column. The first was in the 1840’s when the 14 stonemasons who were responsible for hoisting the statue onto the top of the column made sure that they had a dinner party on the pedestal before they finished placing the statue. Throughout the years countless stunt people and political activists have climbed the column. An anti-apartheid campaigner climbed the column in the 1970s and more recently, Greenpeace protesters managed to fix a dust mask to Nelson’s face to highlight their concerns about air pollution. \r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/nelson-statue.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Close up shots of the statue.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe reason for the statue of Nelson himself facing down Whitehall, towards the admiralty is that he ultimately is looking in the direction of Cape Trafalgar in southern Spain. A reminder to all that it was he who ensured victory over Napoleon. The Admiral sculpture itself is actually smaller than people believe. French sightseers in the early days were said to be delighted that the statue actually depicted Napoleon. Up close the statue itself reflects how Horatio Nelson appeared in later life with just one arm and one eye. There were fears that the remaining arm would be lost after a lightning strike in 1896, brass straps were affixed and stayed there for a century. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInterestingly, the Nazis loved Nelson’s Column as a big, powerful monument symbolizing imperial conquest. The German Luftwaffe were even ordered not to bomb the Column as they hoped to move it to Berlin if they won the Second World War. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2006 the Column was refurbished at a cost of approximately £420,000, which was considerably more, then the initial outlay. It was actually during these renovations that the monument was found to be shorter than first thought.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Trafalgar-Square-2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The column looking south towards Whitehall and the Palace of Westminster.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Medals and Titles Awarded</h3>\r\n\r\nNelson’s titles were inscribed on his coffin and were read out at the funeral by Garter King at Arms, Sir Isaac Heard. They were: The Most Noble Lord Horatio Nelson, Viscount and Baron Nelson, of the Nile and of Burnham Thorpe in the County of Norfolk, Baron Nelson of the Nile and of Hilborough in the said County, Knight of the Most Honourable Order of the Most Honourable Order of the Bath, Vice Admiral of the White Squadron of the Fleet, Commander and Chief of his Majesty’s Ships and Vessels in the Mediterranean, Duke Bronté in the Kingdom of Sicily, Knight Grand Cross of the Sicilian Order of St Ferdinand and of Merit, Member of the Ottoman Order of the Crescent and Knight Grand Commander of the Order of St Joachim.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdmiral Nelson also received large naval Gold medals for the battles of St. Vincent, the Nile and posthumously, Trafalgar. Nelson was the only recipient of three such medals. \r\nAdmiral Nelson received the General Service Medal (1793-1840) with the clasp “Trafalgar” in 1847 along with members of the crews - who were still alive and able to apply for the medal - of the British ships at the Battle of Trafalgar. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Tomb_of_Horatio_Nelson_on_Saint-Paul_Cathedral.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Tomb of Horatio Nelson at Saint Paul Cathedral.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile as a Colonel of the Royal Marines from 1795 to 1797 he was voted a Freeman of the cities and boroughs of Bath, Salisbury, Exeter, Plymouth, Monmouth, Sandwich, Oxford, Hereford and Worcester. On the 30 July 1802, The University of Oxford, in full Congregation, bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Civil Law upon Nelson.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKing Ferdinand created Nelson Duke of Bronte of the Kingdom of Sicily in July 1799. After experimenting with the signature “Bronte Nelson of the Nile”, he signed himself “Nelson & Bronte” for the rest of his life. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNelson died without any legitimate children. The titles “of the Nile and of Burnham Thorpe in the County of Norfolk” became extinct upon his death. However, in 1801 the barony created “of the Nile and of Hilborough in the County of Norfolk” which passed by a special remainder and included Nelson’s father and sisters and their male issue, to the Reverend William Nelson, Nelson’s older brother. William Nelson was created Earl Nelson and Viscount Merton, of Trafalgar and Merton in the county of Surrey in November 1805. This was in recognition of his late brother’s services. He also inherited the dukedom of Bronte.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/NelsonTomb.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Arrival of Admiral Lord Nelson\'s funeral carriage for internment at St. Paul\'s Cathedral, London. Ensigns captured from the Spanish and French fleet during the Battle of Trafalgar hang from the galleries.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Lions</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Nelson’s Testimonial Committee originally commissioned the 4 lions at the base of the statue. However, their creation was plagued with delays and prevarication. The lions were intended to be in stone or granite roughly 20 feet long. The idea wasn’t met with universal agreement. John Graham Lough was originally asked to be the sculptor, but due to the lack of funding and various artistic arguments prevented their execution at the same time as the erection of the monument. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe issue dragged on until 1846 when enough funds finally became available to commission the four bas-reliefs at the base of the column. 12 years later in 1858 the House of Commons allocated £6000 for the lions to be completed. The plan was to invite six sculptors to submit models for one to be selected. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/lions-nelson.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Two of the Lions designed by Sir Edwin Landseer\'s (English painter and Sculpturer) that guard the outside diagonals of Nelson\'s Column.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nHowever, the Board of Works had very different intentions. They announced the appointment of Sir Edwin Landseer. This appointment raised eyebrows as although Landseer was well known for his paintings of animals, which included stags and dogs and was favoured by Queen Victoria (he was commissioned to paint her and her family), his skills and knowledge of sculpture was questionable. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Times newspaper at the time wrote that while acknowledging his skill at painting, they observed that <mark>“Sir Edwin never had a chisel in his hand in his life, and never yet, we believe, attempted to model anything.”</mark>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurther delays were caused by Landseer’s ill health and financial problems. While newspapers referred to ‘a scandal’ and ‘national disgrace’, and the lions became the subject of jokes and questions were asked in parliament. Confusion over the costs didn’t help, as an additional £11,000 was required for their casting. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the 31st of January 1867, the bronze lions were finally unveiled in Trafalgar Square. Ironically ‘The Times’ - which had been rather scathing a few years earlier - was full of praise for the lions. However, some critics disliked them. Reynolds Newspaper wrote “Although admirable in most respects, has certainly some glaring defects”. There was this belief that their character was more like a sphinx than a lion. Other critics, however, were just thankful that the whole affair was finally over. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/lions-at-the-base.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       The Lions at the Base of the Nelson Column, Trafalgar-Square. Illustration for The Illustrated London News, 9 February 1867.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Look and Learn\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nThe lions were added almost 25 years after the monument was erected. Today they all sit in the same position but are not identical. In 2011, a survey was conducted which suggested that due to the number of tourists clambering over them that they had suffered from significant erosion. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNelsons Column today is the main feature of Trafalgar Square and plays host to thousands of tourists, performances and protest rallies every year.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Nelson\'s Column', '2019-02-28 8:29 am', 'nelsons-column.jpg', 'topics', '51.507759', '-0.127716', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, NULL),
(22, 'For hundreds of years, Spitalfields has welcomed different waves of refugees. One of the first mass groups to settle there were Huguenot weavers who migrated to England following religious persecution spurred on by the revocation of the Edict of Nantes in 1685 by King Louis XIV. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis revocation made practicing Protestantism in France illegal and led to tirades of violence against those following the religion. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThey came to London as it offered business and employment opportunities. Using the skills of their craft they had learnt in France, many of them entered into the silk weaving industry.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOthers however, set up businesses in different areas of London such as Soho, working as goldsmiths, silversmiths, instrument makers, sculptors and gunmakers. <mark>Spitalfields became the centre of the silk industry.</mark>\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Louis-XIV-of-France.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/hugenots-massarcre.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Huguenot-weavers.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"3\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/dennis-severs.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"4\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/dennis-sever-house-outside.jpg\">\r\n	</div>	\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2\" style=“opacity:1; ”>\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content\" style=\"padding: 0; opacity:1;”>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\nfont: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\nline-height: 1.1;\r\nposition: relative;\r\ntop: -17px;\r\nline-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 5 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:50px; position: relative; left:-10px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					The devoutly Catholic Louis XIV believed his faith should be the sole religion of his country. He revoked the Edict of Nantes in 1685 through his issuance of the Edict of Fontainebleau, and ordered the destruction of Protestant churches, the closure of Protestant schools, and the forced baptism of children into the Catholic faith. \r\n					<span>\r\n						Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n					</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The St. Bartholomew\'s Day massacre of 1572 was a targeted group of assassinations and violence, directed against the Huguenots (French Protestants) during the French Wars of Religion. Modern estimates for the number of dead across France vary widely, from 5,000 to 30,000.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Female silk weavers at work in Spitalfields in 1893. The industry in east London was founded by Huguenot refugees.\r\n					<span>Source: www.independent.co.uk</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Dennis Severs (16 November 1948, Escondido, California – 27 December 1999, London) was drawn to London by what he called \"English light\", and made his home in the dilapidated property in Folgate Street in 1979. \r\n					<span>Source: johngibsonis.com / Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					Dennis Severs\' House in Folgate Street, London is a \"still-life drama\" created by the previous owner Dennis Severs as a \"historical imagination\" of what life would have been like inside for a family of Huguenot silk weavers.\r\n					<span>Source: Wikimedia Commons</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n    \r\n<h1>Dennis Severs\' House</h1>\r\nOne of the properties connected to these Huguenot refugees in Spitalfields is Dennis Severs’ House. Dennis Severs, an artist from California, purchased the property in 1979. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBetween this time and his death in 1999, he furnished the space to recreate the ‘living image of the eighteenth-century house’, complete with an imaginary family, the Jervis family, to occupy the house. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEach room tells a chapter of the Jervis families story from 1724 to 1914.  The house is therefore not a museum exactly, but acts more as a piece of living history and performance art with the story of a Huguenot family at its centre. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou can book onto tours of the house <a href=\"https://www.dennissevershouse.co.uk/the-tour/\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a> to learn more about his life and work in the house, give Severs’ excellent memoir, 18 Folgate Street: The Life of a House in Spitalfields, a read. \r\n\r\n<br>\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Dennis-Severs-House-full.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile you’re stood in front of the house, look up. You will see a wooden spool suspended from the wall. This was installed in 1985 by the residents of Spitalfields on the former houses of Huguenot weavers to celebrate the tercentenary of Revocation of the Edict of Nantes. As you wander around Spitalfields make sure to keep an eye out for more of these spools.\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nIf you want to get more acquainted with this historic community, you can find information about some great events and tours led by the Huguenots of Spitalfields <a href=\"http://www.huguenotsofspitalfields.org/\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a> They have also compiled a <a href=\" http://www.huguenotsofspitalfields.org/about-the-huguenots/huguenot-families.html\" target=\"_blank\">list of the names and address</a> of Huguenot weavers in London.\r\n\r\n', 'Dennis Severs’ House', '2019-03-01 6:48 am', 'Dennis-Severs-House.jpg', 'topics', '51.520959', '-0.077685', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 4),
(23, '\r\nAs you stand on Waterloo Place and marvel at the amazing architecture of the buildings and the fantastic statues and sculptures around you lower your gaze to the pavement in front of The Athenaeum Club and take a look at the two unassuming slabs of stone.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese are the Duke of Wellington mounting steps.  Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington was famous not only as the man who led the British and Prussians to victory against Napoleon in the Battle of Waterloo in 1815 but he was also British Prime Minister from 1828 to 1830 and again for a short time in 1834.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-bg-image\">\r\n	<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/duke_of_wellington_mounting_steps_hidden_history.jpg\">\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content visible no-padding\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:-30px;\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n      The Duke of Wellington’s horse mount on Waterloo Place.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Image: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn 1830 he was in his early 60\'s and climbing on and of his horse wasn\'t as easy as it once was so he requested that a set of mounting steps be erected outside The Athenaeum Club where he was a member to ease his mounting and dismounting, the stones have a plaque attached to them which reads, \'This horseblock was erected by desire of the Duke Of Wellington 1830.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you look directly across the road you will see another set of mounting steps in front of what was The United Services Club of which Wellington was also a member.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMounting steps were a common feature up until the late 18th Century whereupon better roads were being built along with carriages to transport people so mounting steps began to fall out of popularity but as you can see in Waterloo Place some are preserved in situ as a lovely reminder of times past.\r\n', 'Duke of Wellington\'s Mounting Steps', '2019-03-01 7:49 am', 'Duke-of-Wellingtons-mouting-steps2.jpg', 'topics', '51.506824', '-0.132469', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 3);
