(24, 'Between 1973 and 1997 the Provisional Irish Republican Army (PIRA) carried out almost 500 attacks on the British mainland.  In London - their most frequently assaulted target - 15 soldiers, 5 Police Officers, and 29 civilians were tragically killed during this campaign.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe attacks carried out by the group where technically complex, well planned and ruthlessly executed by dedicated volunteers who sought the establishment of a free and united Ireland. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDespite the deployment of the full might of the British Army and security services, the PIRA were never conventionally defeated, and never surrendered.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Irish-Republican-armed-with-an-RPG-7-rocket-launcher.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A Volunteer of the Irish Republican Army with an RPG-7 rocket-launcher.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Image: © Rory Nugent\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nBut <mark> who exactly were the PIRA? </mark> What motivated them to carry out these deadly acts? And why, most crucially of all, is it important to remind ourselves of this very recent conflict, when the fight for a free and united Ireland was brought to the streets of London.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h1> 1916- The Easter Rising </h1>\r\nThe attacks on London were only one part of a 30-year conflict referred to as the <mark>‘The Troubles’,</mark> which started in the late 1960’s and ended in 1998 with the signing of a peace treaty called the Good Friday agreement. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDuring this time over 3,600 people would be left dead, while an additional 50,000 would be injured by the actions from all the sides involved. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe history leading up to the start of The Troubles is a complicated multidimensional one, that’s impossible to tell the full story of in this article, as it starts many centuries before the ‘The Troubles’ began. Instead we will be joining the tale at a critical historical junction in 1916, with <mark>the Easter Rising.</mark>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/1916_The_Irish_Rebellion.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/a-street-barricade-erected-by-the-rebels-in-Dublin-during-the-Rising.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/British-troops-armed-with-machine-guns-and-rifles.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					Irish volunteers march through the streets of Dublin before the April 1916 Easter Uprising in this Historical Image. \r\n					<span>Source: National Library of Ireland </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					A street barricade erected by the rebels in Dublin during the Rising. <span>\r\n					Source: Wikimedia Commons. </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					British troops armed with machine guns and rifles behind a moveable barricade composed of household furniture and which could easily be pushed foreward, in a street in the central section of Dublin. \r\n					<span>Source: Bettmann</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nOn the 24th of April 1916, against the backdrop of the First World War, a group of Irish Nationalists staged a six-day rebellion against Britain. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEven though their attempt to establish their primary goal of a self-ruling Ireland was quickly crushed, they did in fact manage to successfully set off a chain reaction that would inspire future generations to follow in their footsteps. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Irish Nationalists who launched that uprising themselves went on to directly form the first Irish Republican Army since the 1860s, a fighting force that would fight in the Irish War of Independence and successfully contribute to the creation of the Irish Free State in 1922. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/IRA-girls-searching-a-man-Belfast-1971.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        IRA girls searching a Man in Belfast 1971.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe reason why the IRA did not cease at this point is down to the fact that almost every attempt to solve the Irish dispute, at various points in history, has failed to match up to expectations of everyone involved. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWithin the seemingly victorious IRA there existed a considerable contingent who were unhappy with both the act of 1922 and the preceding 1920 Government of Ireland Act. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBoth pieces of legislation had contributed to the partition of Ireland, an outcome that in the minds of some was considered a failure as it had not given the group its originally desired single independent state. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"videoWrapper\">\r\n    <!-- Copy & Pasted from YouTube -->\r\n    <iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Q67O-QcD2Iw\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1> Irish Republican Army </h1>\r\n\r\nThe polarised view of the aftermath of 1922 prompted many IRA members to create their own separate organizations, with one faction in particular once again assuming the title of the Irish Republican Army. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis IRA would go on to operate in both parts of Ireland for the next four decades, most notably <mark> declaring war on Britain </mark> in 1939 and beginning an armed campaign in Northern Ireland in 1942. Despite this, the IRA of the middle part of the century remained relatively small up until the end of the 1960s.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe creation of Northern Ireland had not been a clean and simple affair, by the 1960s, the situation within the new nation was still fraught. On one side of the divide there were the Unionists, a predominantly Protestant group that believed the nation was best served by remaining within the United Kingdom. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/the-creation-of-northern-ireland.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The creation of Northern Ireland had not been a clean and simple affair. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOpposing them were the Catholic Republicans, a group of people who felt marginalised within society at that time and subsequently saw Northern Ireland’s future as being intrinsically linked with the Republic of Ireland, and not with the UK. Against the backdrop of this struggle, a wave of violence between the two groups gradually transformed into open conflict in 1968. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy the August of 1969 the violence between the two groups became so disruptive that the British government felt the need to intervene through the deployment of troops under Operation Banner.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe army was expected to be a neutral player in the Troubles, one that would keep the peace and show no bias to either of the two viewpoints. For a brief period of time that appeared to be the case, however the heavy-handed way in which British troops dealt with civil unrest prompted many Catholics to view the troops as a foreign force to be feared and actually encouraged an escalation in hostilities in response. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"videoWrapper\">\r\n    <!-- Copy & Pasted from YouTube -->\r\n    <iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/gRVzMgzQZw0?start=436\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>So Who were the IRA? </h1>\r\n\r\nThe rapidly deteriorating situation in Northern Ireland in the 1960s subsequently led to a split in the ranks of the group that resulted in the formation of the Provisional Irish Republican Army in 1969. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn testament to both the longevity of the driving philosophy of the IRA of 1916, and the continued presence of hardship in Northern Ireland, this new group once again sought the creation of a single united self-ruling Ireland. The old IRA would also continue to exist, albeit in a diminished manner under the guise of the ‘official IRA’.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEven though both groups held similar motivations and were equally prone to the use of violence, the PIRA pushed both of these elements so much further that they would become infamous on both sides of the Irish Sea. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/who-are-the-ira-irish-republican-army.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/join-the-ira.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/girl-in-the-ira.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					The IRA began as an alternative name for the Irish Volunteers, the official army of the emergent Irish state and its new parliament which in 1919 declared Ireland a free republic in defiance of Britain.\r\n					<span>Source: The Irish Times // Topfoto</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					The IRA was blamed for half of more than 3,600 deaths during three decades of conflict in the British-ruled province during three decades of violence that largely ended with the 1998 Good Friday Agreement.<span>\r\n					Source: Reuters </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					An IRA fighter in West Belfast during the 1970\'s. Women were an active part of both Republican and Loyalist groups during the Northern Ireland conflict commonly known as \'The Troubles\'. \r\n					<span>Source: The Female Soldier Blog</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe PIRA fully embraced their paramilitary roots and held true to the distinction that they were an army, so much of their identity was enshrined within that one word that it would subsequently fuel and justify their mission for over thirty years. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSeán Mac Stíofáin, one of the groups co-founders who served as the PIRA’s chief of staff till 1972 once boldly declared, <mark>‘you’ve got to have military victory first and then politicize the people afterwards.’</mark>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFrom this it becomes clear that the PIRA were fully prepared to dogmatically use whatever military force it could muster in order see the full withdrawal of the United Kingdom from Northern Ireland. They viewed themselves as being at war and were as a result ready to act in a manner that befitted their outlook. \r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Provisional-ira-members-recieving-training.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Provisional Irish Republican Army (PIRA) is a radical terrorist group formed in 1969 as clandestine armed wing of Sinn Fein, a legal political movement dedicated to removing British forces from Northern Ireland and unifying Ireland.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Image: Flickr / Provisional Irish Republican Army\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1> Bloody Sunday </h1>\r\nTo achieve their goal of a free and united Ireland, the PIRA first set out to become a major military force within Northern Ireland itself. Engagements with the British Army, Unionist Paramilitaries, and even occasionally the Official IRA became a routine occurrence. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInitially the group avoided conducting attacks and operations based outside of their Northern Irish heartlands. However, the events of the 30th of January 1972, immortalised forever as <mark>‘Bloody Sunday’</mark>, would change that, and the course of the conflict forever. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDuring a peaceful protest, members of the British Parachute Regiment opened fire on a crowd of protesters that had gathered in Londonderry (Derry), tragically killing 14 civilians and injuring a further 14, after believing they had been fired upon themselves from within the crowd.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</div></div></div></div></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"picture-carousel\" style=\"position: relative; top: 0; left: 0;\">\r\n<div class=\"carousel-wrapper-inner slider\" data-loadend=\"slidetracker()\">\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"0\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/21-July-1972-bloody-friday.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n	\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"1\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/NORTHERN-IRELAND-Londonderry-30th-January-1972-As-the-shooting-starts-on-Bloody-Sunday-people-fall-to-the-ground.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<div class=\"div\" data-team-id=\"2\">\r\n		<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/NORTHERN-IRELAND-Derry-Rioters-throw-stones-at-a-British-armored-car-1972-Gilles-Peress.jpg\">\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- controls -->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; height: 100%; z-index: 99;\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"left-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"right-arrow-box\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arrow-down.png\" >\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"about-page contents article-info-list2 visible\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-lg-8 team-info article-content no-padding visible\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper2\" align=\"left\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-2\">\r\n        	<h3 style=\"padding: 0px;\r\n			font: normal 1.125em/1.1 GaramondPremrPro,serif;\r\n			line-height: 1.1;\r\n			position: relative;\r\n			top: -17px;\r\n			line-height: 6px;\"> <span class=\"slide-tracker\">1</span> of 3 </h3>\r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class=\"col-lg-10\" style=\"padding:0px;\">\r\n			<ul class=\"data-list\" style=\"min-height:20px; position: relative; left:-10px; min-height: 50px;\">\r\n				<li class=\"team-active default\">\r\n					21 July 1972 became known as Bloody Friday after at least 20 bombs were planted and detonated by the IRA’s Belfast brigade. Nine people were killed and more than 130 injured in the attacks.\r\n					<span>Source: BBC</span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					NORTHERN IRELAND. Derry: Londonderry. 30th January 1972. A victim, Barney McGuigan, lies in a pool of blood as the shooting stops on Bloody Sunday.<span>\r\n					Source:  Gilles Peress </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n				<li>\r\n					NORTHERN IRELAND. Derry. Rioters throw stones at a British armored car. 1972. \r\n					<span>Source: Gilles Peress </span>\r\n				</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Widgery Tribunal, hastily held by the British government and completed in only 12 weeks, concluded that the troops’ actions had been ‘bordering on reckless’, but crucially, accepted their testimonies that they had opened fire in reaction to armed gunmen. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe findings of the enquiry shocked the Northern Irish community as many eye-witness reports, including those given by Irish and British journalists, contradicted the supposed official timeline. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA follow up enquiry concluded in 2010 would overturn the original report, instead declaring the army had acted unjustifiably and had been the first ones to open fire, significantly, at unarmed civilians.  However, the damage had already been long since done. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the aftermath of Bloody Sunday the PIRA ratcheted up its armed campaign, undoubtedly rejuvenated by a raft of new recruits who had been horrified by the actions of the British Army. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile the Official IRA beat their former partners to the punch with a deadly attack on a military barracks in the Aldershot area of England only a few weeks after Bloody Sunday, it would not take the PIRA long to join in too.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the 8th of March 1973 the PIRA retaliated in full force with its first operation in England, killing one person and injuring 265 others with car bombs in London, an attack that was a deadly first blow and a sign of things to come for the British capital.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/The-scene-after-an-IRA-bomb-Old-Bailey.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The scene after an IRA bomb exploded outside the Old Bailey in central London in 1973 which killed one person and injured 200 people.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn many ways Bloody Sunday acted as the perfect justification for the PIRA to target London and reinforced the ideologies they already held. Innocent civilians had been killed by the British army and demand for retaliation against the establishment on the British mainland was high within the PIRA. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>Why target London? </h1>\r\n\r\nFor the PIRA, the start of the bombing campaign in London was about more than just getting revenge. An assault on the capital made sense from a strategic point of view as there were several crucial ways in which attacks on the city were able to help advance their agenda. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn short, by expanded their bombing campaign, the PIRA believed they would create the three elements necessary to facilitate the creation of a free united Ireland: fear, support, and pressure. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFirstly, it brought the war out of its Irish confines, and directly onto the streets of England, thus creating fear. The support would be created because it also provided an opportunity for the group to generate more exposure through propaganda. Pressure would also be created through the general public’s fear, and the significant damage to the UK economy the campaign would cause. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Wormwood-Street-London-Irish-Republican-Army.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Bishopsgate bombing which occurred on 24 April 1993.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe support part of this plan might seem unusual for a paramilitary force, but as a relatively small group the PIRA needed to publicise itself and its mission. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe ranks of the organisation were made up of volunteer recruits, therefore successful operations in London - one of the most famous cities in the world - naturally acted as the perfect advert to attract new members. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore importantly than this though was the fact the PIRA, at least in the initial phases of the Troubles, had a small support base in the UK it believed it could tap into. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/resistance-ira.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The murals of Falls Road in West Belfast in Northern Ireland.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBritish backing for the Republicans can be bizarrely exemplified by John Lennon, who amongst penning a song entitled ‘Sunday Bloody Sunday’, also appeared at a London protest march in 1972 carrying a sign inscribed with the words: ‘For the IRA against British Imperialism.’ \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTommy McKearney, a former member of the PIRA explains in his book that, <mark>‘it seemed to many Irish Republicans that only by detonating explosives in England would they keep the British population aware of what their government was doing.’</mark>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe rationale behind this was that hitting London would generate headline news stories about the Troubles on an international level, the publicity it got would highlight the groups plight and in turn generate more support like that seen at the solidarity marches. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUnder a presumed mountain of pressure from supporters and those also reacting in fear, the British government would eventually be forced to withdraw the UK from Northern Ireland.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis master plan was too naïve and failed to achieve the PIRA’s desired results, the government stood strong on the topic for the duration of the conflict. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/john-lennon.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        John Lennon at a London protest march in 1972 carrying a sign.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe group also never received the level of public backing it needed, the Troubles coincided with a difficult period of history for the British working-class, who were naturally too preoccupied with more pressing domestic issues. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA fourth element that influenced the PIRA’s decision to divert some of their attention across the Irish Sea, was the fact it gave the group the opportunity to attack softer targets. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe success the group had enjoyed in Northern Ireland had proven to be a double-edged sword, as the security forces that opposed them had been forced to up their game. In comparison, London - and other locations on the UK mainland - were less prepared, more vulnerable and now viable targets.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDespite being on home ground in Northern Ireland, the PIRA was also unable to fully get the upper hand on the British Armed Forces and Royal Ulster Constabulary, who thanks to superior numbers and resources, were able to establish a foothold in the region. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis therefore put the IRA Army Council (the decision-making body of the PIRA) in a difficult position and forced it to look elsewhere for opportunities to strike at its opponents. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<!-- Copy & Pasted from YouTube -->\r\n    <iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/gZCF8OREz9A?start=100\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A collection of news reports from Thames News detailing the IRA\'s attacks and events in London throughout the period of The Troubles. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Thames News\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nOperations on the British mainland and London in particular became a viable alternative for this reason as they made sense from a military perspective. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe city, despite being 500 miles away from the PIRA’s South Armagh heartland, was less secure and prepared for attacks at that time, and was consequently the perfect place to initiate a guerrilla warfare-based campaign against the British establishment. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAcross the entirety of the Troubles fifteen British Army personnel lost their lives during the PIRA’s coordinated assaults on London’s military establishments.  What is alarming to consider is the fact that the majority of these people were actually killed on just one fatal day. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the 20th of July 1982 PIRA were able to detonate two bombs within a couple of hours of each other in Hyde Park and Regents Park. These places of natural beauty quickly became more reminiscent of a battlefield as eleven soldiers and seven military horses lost their lives in the blasts. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe assaults were so successful because the PIRA had opportunistically taken advantage of the more relaxed atmosphere of the city. The eleven soldiers killed had been conducting their daily duties, in full display of the general public. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe four lost in Hyde Park had been conducting the daily Changing of the Guard, while the seven killed in Regents Park had been performing music from Oliver!. Despite being in the middle of a bloody conflict both of the events had still been advertised to the public, and were consequently ripe for the PIRA to target.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe PIRA made no attempt to hide why it chose to attack London, in the groups various <mark>‘Green Book’</mark> induction manuals it explicitly laid out a list of strategy guidelines for new recruits to adhere to. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe opening bullet point makes direct reference to the ideas we have already explored, stating all IRA attacks were part of; ‘A War of attrition against enemy personnel which is aimed at causing as many casualties and deaths as possible so as to create a demand from their people at home for their withdrawal.’ \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/greennbook.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Green Book is a training and induction manual issued by the Irish Republican Army to new volunteers. It was used by the post-Irish Civil War Irish Republican Army (IRA) and Cumann na mBan, (“League of Women”), along with later incarnations such as the Provisional IRA (PIRA). It includes a statement of military objectives, tactics and conditions for military victory against the British government.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe manuals second point further explains the rationale behind many of the PIRA’s other attacks when it says; ‘A bombing campaign aimed at making the enemy’s financial interest in our country unprofitable while at the same time curbing long term financial investment in our country.’ \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs an internationally renowned trade hub, the center of British affluence and home to much of the establishment, London was the perfect place for the PIRA to inflict as much economic damage on Britain as it could. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />Economic warfare was a corner stone of the groups campaign throughout the entirety of the Troubles, with establishments such as the London branch of Harrods being attacked multiple times. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne Active Service Unit – the sleeper cells the PIRA relied on to covertly conduct their mainland attacks – became so infamous for its coordinated assaults on the British businesses in the 1970s that it earned itself the nickname of the Balcombe Street Gang. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis group of volunteers alone were responsible for approximately 40 attacks, most of which were carried out in or around London, with their destructive capability being best demonstrated by their assault on the Walton’s Restaurant on the 18th of November in which two members of the public were tragically killed. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>The Weapons of War </h3>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/MortarTest-1994.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        This is a test firing of a Mark 15 Barrack Buster Mortar used by the IRA in the mid 90\'s. It carried around 75 kg (165 lb) of home-made explosives and had a range of 75 to 275 metres (246 to 902 ft). The IRA used the Mark 10 design during the Downing Street attack, which had a smaller explosive charge between 44-200 pounds (20 -100 Kgs) of explosives but had multiple barrels.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe PIRA were able to routinely inflict heavy losses on the city of London, like those seen during the Walton’s attack, through the deployment of a varied and sophisticated arsenal of weapons. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAndy Oppenheimer, an historian who has examined the operational practices of the IRA explains that over time the Provisional army became highly efficient in the use of those tools, ‘They were in the IRA for life and learned their skills over many years. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThey had a proper training program where each engineer passed on their knowledge to others in a classroom.’ These where not amateurish or opportunistic individuals but highly trained and adaptable, this in turn ensured they were able to undertake a wide array of different missions, ranging from assassination and shootings, to bombings and mortar attacks. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat’s more, over the course of the Troubles the group was able to develop and upgrade their often homemade weapons. The car bomb, a sinister staple of their arsenal that was used in attacks such as the one in Hyde Park in 1982 and was often rigged with a timer or remote control detonator, eventually gave way to the much more destructive fertiliser bomb. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/hyde-park-deaths.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Carcasses of horses of the Household Cavalry lie in the road following the Hyde Park bomb attack \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Corbis // Independent.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nSix attacks carried out towards the end of the conflict in the 1990s that used these new weapons have been cited by historians such as Paul Rogers as a marked beginning of a new phase in the war, and perfectly demonstrate the phenomenon of weapon development in action. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Baltic exchange attack on the 10th of April 1992 - the first lorry based fertiliser bomb attack on the British mainland – was at that time the biggest detonation in London since the Luftwaffe’s assaults during the Second World War, scarily it was trumped again almost exactly a year later. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Bishopsgate attack on the 24th of April 1993 saw the deployment of a massive 1 tonne ANFO bomb, a tool originally conceived to clear large areas of space in heavy industries such as mining. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo put that into perspective, a regular car bomb like the one used in the Harrods attack in 1983 often weighed around 30lb, a mere fraction compared to the 2204lb bomb that was unleashed a decade later. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe fallout from the Bishopsgate blast was so devastating that a large mushroom cloud billowed out above the 15-foot wide crater that had been left behind in the spot where the vehicle had once stood, photos of the devastation taken in the immediate aftermath of the destruction also bare a haunting similarity to those taken during the height of the Blitz.  \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bishopgate-bombing.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The fallout from the Bishopsgate blast was so devastating\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: City of London Police.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe 1993 attack on Bishopsgate would also hold the unsavoury record of being the single most financially costly attack in world history for a considerable amount of time, with the estimated £1 billion worth of damage only being surpassed by the September 11th attacks on the United States in 2001.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe PIRA never stood still during the Troubles, to effectively wage its war against the British establishment it was essential for the group to be resourceful, the relentless development and evolution of their weapons being the ultimate showcase of this. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe pace at which they continued to break new ground was remarkable, with this arms race there naturally came an increased sense of boldness. Political assassinations were frequently attempted or enacted by the PIRA, as was the case in 1979 when Queen Elizabeth II’s cousin Lord Louis Mountbatten had been killed. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, thanks to their weaponry they audaciously came within touching distance of completing one of their main objectives in 1991. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe 7th of February of that year could have easily gone down in British history as a day of infamy, as on that specific Thursday, the IRA chose to deploy a carefully prepared mortar attack on 10 Downing Street, the very heart of British politics. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/downing_st_mortar.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Mortar attack on 10 Downing street.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThree giant 4 ½ foot long shells were propelled towards a packed Cabinet meeting from a homemade mortar, which had been stored in the back of a modified Ford Transit van. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe projectiles would ultimately fail to meet their mark and subsequently dealt minimal damage, the nearest shell would however, fall a mere 30 metres away from the entirety of the British Cabinet. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe event was still a landmark occasion, whilst mortars had been used frequently in Northern Ireland this instance was the first recorded deployment of such a weapon on English soil. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Real Irish Republican Army, an offshoot of the PIRA formed following the Good Friday Agreement, would continue to break historic new ground in a similar fashion to its forbearer on the 20th of September 2000, when a RPG-22 anti-tank rocket was launched harmlessly at the headquarters of MI6. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3> The consequences of the London attacks </h3>\r\nThere can be no real debate that the biggest consequence of the PIRA’s long reign of terror in London was a tragic list of casualties. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe groups staunch commitment to their mission and ability to deploy sophisticated weapons meant that forty-eight men and women were killed in the city across the entirety of the conflict.  Twenty-eight of these victims, a clear majority, were unarmed innocent civilians going about their daily lives. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition to the fifteen soldiers we previously talked about in this article, it should also not be forgotten that five members of the Metropolitan Police Force were also killed as they actively sought to keep the population of the capital safe. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Bombing-in-Belfast.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        \r\n        <span>\r\n			\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEven though the PIRA never explicitly declared any desire to kill members of the public, some historians have suggested it is doubtful that they were naive enough to believe their attacks posed no threat to their lives. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA regular element of their attacks on the city’s businesses was the issuing of an indirect coded warning to the police, even in circumstances where these messages were received a subsequent successful evacuation was still never guaranteed. As was the case of an attack on the 9th of February 1996 when two civilians were killed by a PIRA bomb following an unsuccessful evacuation order.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe reason why so many people were caught up in the groups activities was because they routinely sought to inflict financial damage to the capital as a part of their economic warfare campaign. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile they undoubtedly inflicted large financial damages to the pockets of London’s establishments, and even as Rogers’s has pointed out likely damaged the city’s tourist reputation, they failed to achieve their ultimate goal.  The British government ultimately had a much larger pool of wealth to tap into than the PIRA, and at no point did the Troubles become a war they could not financially afford. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe steadfast determination of the citizen’s of London to carry on in the face of financial ruin was further demonstrated by the owners of the Harrods’s department store, who after being attacked by the PIRA in 1983, defiantly reopened their store only three days after it had been defaced. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn a less quantifiable level, the city of London is most likely now better able to deal with acts of aggression in the present, as a result of the IRA’s relentless campaign. In a way, initiatives such as the ‘ring of steel’ - a system of checkpoints constructed around the city designed to monitor incoming vehicles and check for PIRA bombs - can be viewed as a precursor to similar measures used to prevent attacks in the 21st century, and demonstrates how the city has learnt from the past. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/p-check.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Members of the Royal Regiment of Wales perform a Personal Check (P Check) in 1979. The police and military had the right to stop any member of the public and perform identity checks. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Flickr.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe gates outside of Downing Street, installed in reaction to the PIRA also serve to further illustrate this, and the lasting impact of the Irish Republican Army. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Conclusion: The Good Friday Agreement</h3>\r\n\r\nEven though the Irish Republican Army’s bombardment of London ultimately failed to secure the group its vision of a unified independent Ireland, it is important to remember they were never truly beaten as a fighting force. As has been mentioned, the IRA considered itself to be an army, it is therefore significant that there was no military surrender or capitulation on their part. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Good Friday Agreement, signed in 1998, was a major landmark political achievement that has shaped the relationship between the United Kingdom, Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland ever since, with continued peace and harmony between all parties involved being the most welcome consequence.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, the IRA continued to function - in numerous forms - as an organisation all the way up to 2005, with many of its former members likely still being alive and informally active in their communities to this day as a result. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/good-friday-agreement.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The front cover of the Good Friday Agreement, signed by the participants.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Whytes.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nWhile the Good Friday Agreement had demanded the complete disarmament of all paramilitary groups it would take the IRA nearly a decade to comply and formally end its campaign in the mid-2000s. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe legacy of the Irish Republican Army’s decades long assault on the British capital has mostly been put to the back of the British public’s conscious since then. In a way this is perfectly understandable, new threats that are often more complicated to understand have risen up to replace them.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, as Britain is currently in the complicated and ugly process of rediscovering its place in Europe the topic of Northern Ireland and Ireland will undoubtedly continue to crop up. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAgainst this current backdrop it is therefore more important than ever to keep in mind the events of the Troubles of the past, so as to ensure the same bloodshed is not witnessed again in Ireland and the United Kingdom.\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Further Reading:</h3>\r\n\r\nIf you only have a limited amount of time to delve into the complicated topic of the Troubles, I would highly recommend you check-out <a href=\"https://www.amazon.co.uk/Bandit-Country-IRA-South-Armagh/dp/0340717378\" target=\"_blank\">Toby Harnden’s Bandit Country </a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe book is a thoroughly engrossing gateway into the topic and offers a perfect window into the world of the IRA and is an essential read for those interested in the subject. \r\n', 'The Troubles - The IRA\'s London Bombing Campaign', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'the-troubles-new.jpg', 'topics', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL, 2);
INSERT INTO `articles` (`articlesid`, `text`, `articletitle`, `dateUploaded`, `articleImage`, `appearin`, `latitude`, `longitude`, `view`, `likes`, `dislikes`, `featured`, `position`, `visible`, `categoryid`, `authorid`) VALUES
(38, 'Housed in the former crypt of a nineteenth century church, the Royal London hospital is home to a plethora of outstanding artefacts relating to the hospitals 278-year history in the East-End of London. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nFrom figures such as Joseph Merrick (The Elephant Man), Jack the Ripper and Edith Cavell, this museum is a must-see when in the Whitechapel area for a unique insight into the medical developments and phenomena experienced since the creation of the hospital in 1740. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/royal-london-image1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/royal-london-image6-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3>\r\nFree entry to the museum.\r\n  \r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3>\r\nTuesday- Friday (10am-4pm).\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3>\r\nYes, photography is allowed in the museum however, please be cautious when using flash due to the age of some of the artefacts.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3>\r\nNo, there is no interactive technology at this museum.\r\n\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3>\r\nUnfortunately, due to the museums small size, there are no direct facilities for kids. However, the museum makes for a fascinating trip for all ages if you\'re in the area. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3> Guides:</h3>\r\nNo guides are available at this museum, however an ‘I am human’ walking tour of the Royal London Hospital is available with free downloadable audio guide available online, which takes visitors on the journey of Joseph Merrick (The Elephant Man) using sources and histories taken from the hospitals archive. \r\n<br />\r\n(Accompanying information leaflets are also available to download online or are available at the museum).\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.bartshealth.nhs.uk/the-royal-london-hospital-museum-and-archives\" target=\"_blank\"> Royal London Hospital Museum </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>1. Replica Skeleton of Joseph Merrick. </h3>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/royal-london-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Replica Skeleton of Joseph Merrick. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nJoseph Merrick was born in Leicester in 1862 with severe facial and body deformities which coined him to be labelled as the ‘Elephant Man’ when he was exhibited at a freak show. After meeting Dr. Frederick Treves of the Royal London Hospital, Merrick went to live at the hospital where he died aged 27 of Asphyxiation. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDue to Merrick’s close history with the hospital, the museum has subsequently placed a replica of his skeleton on display for visitors to observe the extent of deformities which so deeply puzzled medical professionals of the period.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Copy of a ‘Jack the Ripper’ letter. </h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/royal-london-image3-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Copy of a ‘Jack the Ripper’ letter. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDon’t miss a copy of a letter and envelope addressed to Dr Openshaw (a pathological curator at the London hospital in 1888) which is signed ‘Jack the Ripper’. The letter arrived with half a kidney which supposedly belonged to Catherine Eddowes the fourth of the canonical five ‘ripper’ victims, who was murdered on 20th September 1888.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlongside these photographs is a sketch which was taken from the mortuary on the day of Eddowes murder, and depicts the brutal wounds inflicted onto her on that fateful night. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>3. The original headstone of Edith Cavell. </h3> \r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/royal-london-image4-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       The original headstone of Edith Cavell.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nEdith Cavell was a nurse who served in the battlefield of Belgium in the First World War, who went beyond her duty to help many wounded soldiers escape occupied Belgium to reach safety. She was caught and arrested by the Germans in 1915, and subsequently executed by a German firing squad the same year. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNext to a bust of Cavell in the museum, lies the original wooden cross which marked her grave upon her execution, which remains a testimony to her heroic acts have not been forgotten. A memorial to Cavell can be found just outside the National Portrait Gallery in London.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> \r\nNo, unfortunately there are no food and drink facilities at this museum. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> \r\nNo, unfortunately there are no tours available at this museum. \r\n\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> \r\nThe closet station to the museum is Whitechapel underground station which is a 7-minute walk.\r\n\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> \r\nDue to the location of the museum, it is easier to get the bus to Whitechapel station and walk from there.\r\n<br /> \r\ncheck <a href=\"https://tfl.gov.uk/modes/buses/\" target=\"_blank\"> here </a> for the bus routes to the station from your location. \r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> \r\nThe Royal London Hospital Museum, St Augustine with St Philip\'s Church, Newark St, Whitechapel, London E1 2AA.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/royal-london-image5-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Inside the Royal London Museum.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Royal London Hospital Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\n\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h3> \r\nUnfortunately, due to the size and demand of the museum, there are no specific access arrangements for deaf or hard of hearing people. However, please do contact a member of staff if you require assistance in accessing the museum.\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h3> \r\nUnfortunately, due to the size and demand of the museum, there are no specific access arrangements for deaf or hard of hearing people. However, please do contact a member of staff if you require assistance in accessing the museum.\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h3>\r\nThe museum is accessible for wheelchair users with ramped access and lift access. There is also one disability accessible toilet which is on the same level as the Museum.', 'Royal London Hospital Museum', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'royal-london-museum-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '51.517384', '-0.060198', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL),
(39, 'Located just around the corner from the National Gallery, The National Portrait Gallery was opened in 1856 and houses a collection of portraits, photographs, sculptures etc of hundreds of important British historical figures. The Gallery moved to its current location in 1896, with the purpose of promoting ‘through the medium of portraits the appreciation and understanding of the men and women who have made and are making British history and culture’. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday the Gallery displays around 1,400 portraits which date back from the 1400’s with portraits of Henry VIII, all the way up to present day figures that we all know and love today. The National Portrait Gallery is a MUST see for art and history enthusiasts alike, as it offers a much-more personal insight into some of the most important figures in British History! \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-portrait-gallery-image1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the gallery.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: NPG, London.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3>\r\nThis Gallery is free to enter. Temporary exhibitions may, however, have an admission free, so please check online before visiting. \r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3>\r\nFrom Monday-Sunday, the Gallery is open from (10am-6pm). On Fridays the Gallery is open later from (10am-pm).  \r\n\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3>\r\nYes, Photography is allowed in the Gallery. However, please do not use flash due to the delicate condition and age of some of the portraits. (Photography in temporary exhibitions may be different, so please ask a museum steward upon your visit).\r\n\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3>\r\nDue to the age of the Gallery, there are no interactive technologies available.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-portrait-gallery-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the gallery.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: NPG, London.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3>\r\nThe National Portrait Gallery hosts a range of family friendly events and activities, so please see the link below for more information about them.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.npg.org.uk/learning/families/ \" target=\"_blank\"> The National Portrait Gallery / Families </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Guides:</h3>\r\nThe Gallery offers visitors a £3 Audio Guide (in several languages), which features commentary of over 300 portraits on display, as well as film from the gallery’s curators which highlight the key portraits within the collection. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\n(Audio guides include an introductory and highlights tour in BSL or with Subtitles, and for visitors with visual impairment, audio-descriptions of selected collections are available on raised-button players, free of charge). \r\n \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>1. Prince Albert, Prince Consort of Queen Victoria </h3>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-portrait-gallery-image3-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Prince Albert\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: NPG, London.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe all know the famous story of the love between Queen Victoria and Prince Albert, and this stunning portrait of the Prince helps encapsulate the man behind the history. Born in Germany in 1819 to Ernest Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha and Princess Louise of Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg, Prince Albert is perhaps most famed for his marriage to his cousin, Queen Victoria who he married in 1840. Victoria devoted her life to her beloved Albert, and together they ruled over Britain until 1873 until his untimely death. Throughout his life in England, Albert was a noted patron of the arts and was responsible for the Great Exhibition of 1851. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis portrait is a replica which was commissioned for the Gallery by Queen Victoria herself, and is based on a portrait which was painted of the Prince in 1859. Trustees were initially anxious to represent Albert in the collection however, after discreet enquires the portrait was hung and presented to the Gallery by Victoria in 1867 – How could you say no to a Queen? \r\n\r\n<br />\r\nFun Fact- 2019 marks 200 years since the Birth of Prince Albert, so how could we not include this stunning portrait in our must-see portraits at the Gallery?\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>2. William Shakespeare (1564-1616)</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-portrait-gallery-image4-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        William Shakespeare\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: NPG, London.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nBorn in 1564 in Stratford-Upon-Avon, William Shakespeare is the most celebrated English poet and playwright in history. Shakespeare spent most of his working life in London, both and an actor and a playwright, his works were immensely popular in public theatres and the court. In 1599 Shakespeare (along with four other men) bought a single share for the famous Globe Theatre, which is now called ‘Shakespeare’s Globe’ in homage to the playwright. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Globe is located in Southwark (although it is a reconstruction) and visitors can tour the iconic theatre and learn more about Shakespeare’s history and ties to the theatre and the City. This painting is an important one, as it is the image, we primarily see being associated with Shakespeare however, this image is not a definite portrait of him.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNot much is known about the portrait however, many believe it may have been painted by John Taylor and that it has good claim to be a life portrait of Shakespeare. The portrait is known as ‘Chandos Portrait’, after a previous owner, and it was the first ever portrait which was acquired by the National Portrait Gallery in 1856. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Dame Christabel Pankhurst (1880-1958)</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-portrait-gallery-image5-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A portrait of Christabel Pankhurst, by Ethel Wright.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: NPG, London.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nFollowing the centenary of the Woman’s Suffrage Movement in 2018, this striking portrait of Christabel Pankhurst is a must see for visitors of the Gallery. After studying law at Manchester University, Christabel joined the Womens Social and Political Union (WSPU) which was established by her mother Emmeline Pankhurst in 1903.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe WSPU’s main aim was to campaign for Women’s right to vote, and as Christabel was a charismatic and persuasive speaker, she was in charge of organising rallies, processions and campaigns of civil disobedience such as bombing and arson attacks. Her contribution was recognised in 1936, when she was made a Dame in honour of her dedication to female emancipation. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis portrait was first shown at the Womens Exhibition which was organised by the WSPU in 1909- Note the integration of the Suffragette tricolour, which represented loyalty and dignity, purity and hope, which all WSPU members were encouraged to strive for and integrate themselves into their every-day lives. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> \r\nYes, there are food at drink facilities at the Gallery. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPortrait Restaurant offers breakfast, lunch, afternoon tea or dinner, with incredible views of Trafalgar Square down to the Houses of Parliament. \r\nPortrait Café serves light snack food such as sandwiches, salads, soups, cakes and coffee. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/national-portrait-gallery-image6-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Inside the National Portrait Gallery.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: NPG, London.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Friday Lates Bar opens every Friday from 6pm-8:30 and offers beers, prosecco, wine or gins.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> \r\nYes, Tours are available at the National Portrait Gallery. \r\nYou can customise and plan your own tour based on Time Period, Theme or Recent Acquisitions online on the Gallery website (please see the link below) \r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/explore/tours \" target=\"_blank\"> The National Portrait Gallery / Tours </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> \r\nThe nearest tube stations are Charing Cross (approx. a 3-5-minute walk) and Leicester Square (approx. a 5-6-minute walk). \r\n\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> \r\nRoutes 3, 6, 9, 11, 13, 15, 23, 24, 87, 91, 139, and 176 stops at Trafalgar Square.\r\n\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> \r\nNational Portrait Gallery St Martin’s Place, London, WC2H 0HE.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\nConcessionary rates apply to young people aged 12-18, disabled visitors, senior citizens, ES40 cardholders and students in full-time education. Carers are entitled to free admission. Children under 12 are free.\r\nTo discuss any additional access requirements please email: education@npg.org.uk or call 020 7306 0055.\r\n\r\nFor more in-depth Information about accessibility, please see the National Portrait Gallery’s Access Guide below; \r\n<a href=\"https://www.npg.org.uk/assets/files/pdf/access/NPG_AccessGuide_2018.pdf \" target=\"_blank\"> The National Portrait Gallery </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h3> \r\nFree BSL Gallery tours are held on the second Friday of every month at 7:30pm. Audio Guide are also available in British Sign Language free of charge. \r\n<br /> \r\nThere are induction loops at the Information Desk in the Main Hall and in the Ondaatje Wing Theatre.  Portable induction loops are in the Shops, Café, Restaurant, Education Studio, Orange Street reception and the Heinz Archive and Library.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h3> \r\nFree picture description Gallery talks for blind and partially sighted audiences on the last Thursday of every month at 2pm \r\n<br />\r\nLarge print guides, maps and magnifying glasses. are available at the Information Desk, as well are \r\nGuide dogs are welcome.\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h3>\r\nThe main entrance at St Martin’s Place has one step, and Step-free access is via the Shop entrance on St Martin’s Place.\r\n<br />\r\nThe Gallery has four accessible, unisex toilets located on Floors 0, -2, -3, 3.\r\n<br />\r\nManual wheelchairs are available from the Information Desk or to book a wheelchair in advance contact the above number. Benches and portable stools are available, so please see a member of staff upon your visit to the Gallery for more information. ', ' The National Portrait Gallery ', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'national-portrait-gallery-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '51.509554', '-0.128004', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 4, NULL),
(40, 'Located within the Bank of England itself, this museum is a fascinating insight into the history of the bank from its foundation in 1694 to the present day. As the United Kingdom’s central bank, the Bank of England has a unique role in our economy, as it works to keep inflation steady and low and ensures that the financial system is stable and protected from economic instability – pretty important stuff! \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nSet in a reconstruction of the Stock Office built by Sir John Soane (architect for the bank 1788-1833) the museum is about more than just money, with its unique insight into the banks extensive 300-year history, people and architecture which make for an interesting and informative day out (for all the family).\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Outside the Bank of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the Bank of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3>\r\nThis museum is free to enter.  \r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3>\r\nThe museum is open Monday- Friday (10am-5pm) and last entry is at 4:30pm.   \r\n\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3>\r\nYes, photography is allowed of this museum, although please be wary of using flash. \r\n\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3>\r\nYes, this museum has interactive technology.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image3-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the Bank of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3>\r\nThis museum is well equipped for children, with interactive exhibits, technology and games for them to play and learn with.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3> Guides:</h3>\r\nFree printed guides are available at the information desk upon entry, audio guides are also available on a first-come, first-served basis.\r\n \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>1. Regal Coinage Collection. </h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image4-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Regal Coinage Collection.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn 1932, the Bank of England began a project to compile a representative collection of British Regal Coinage (Coins with the reigning monarch’s face engraved onto them) which date back as far as 1694 when the bank was established to present day. Although the making of coins is the responsibility of the Royal Mint, the collection is an incredible display of British monarchical reign and cannot be missed. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>2. London Good Delivery Bar. </h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image5-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Bank Of England Museum Gold Bar Weight.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn 1750, The Bank of England set up the London Good Delivery List for gold which formally recognised those refineries which produced gold to the required standard. Essentially, the Good Delivery system is a way in which the LBMA (London Bullion Market Association) ensure that the standards for gold (and now silver) are maintained and kept in the bullion trade. See for yourself first hand a real gold bar and have your go at trying to lift it in the Rotunda room. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>3. An Iron Chest (c.1700). </h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image6-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Great Iron Chest.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nLocated in the Early Years gallery of the museum, this iron chest is the oldest piece of surviving furniture in the Bank of England and is referred to in a book from 1735 as ‘the great iron chest in the parlour’. Chests such as this one were the predecessors of the modern safe, have a look at this beautiful piece of economic history as you pass through. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> \r\nDue to the age and location of the museum there are no food and drink facilities available. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> \r\nYes, talks are provided for small groups, as well are presentations for larger groups. See the link below for more information.\r\n\r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/book-a-presentation\" target=\"_blank\"> Bank of England Museum / Tours </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image7-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Bank of England gold vaults.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> \r\nThe nearest tube is Bank station, which is a short walk (dependant on the exit).  \r\n\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> \r\nBus routes 8, 11, 21, 23, 25, 26, 43, 76, 133, 141, 242 and 388 run past the Bank of England. \r\n\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> \r\nBank of England Museum, Bartholomew Lane, London, EC2R 8AH.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h1>Accessibility:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h3> \r\nInduction loops are available at the front desk, and some of the videos in the museum’s galleries are subtitled. Please ask museum staff for more information. \r\n<br />\r\n(Visitors can also as for a signed video introduction to the museum at the information desk). \r\n\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h3> \r\nBlind or partially sighted visitors can pre-book and audio described tour of the museum, which are led by expert guides (tours are for a maximum of six people and are also available for solo visitors). For more information please see the link below. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/plan-your-visit/accessibility \" target=\"_blank\"> Bank of England Museum </a>\r\n<br />\r\nGuide dogs are welcome at the museum, and staff are happy to provide water. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h3>\r\nThe museum is accessible to wheelchair users, see below for more in-depth information and guides for accessibility. \r\n\r\n<br>\r\nManual wheelchairs are available from the Information Desk or to book a wheelchair in advance contact the above number. Benches and portable stools are available, so please see a member of staff upon your visit to the Gallery for more information. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/plan-your-visit/accessibility \" target=\"_blank\"> Bank of England Museum </a>\r\n<br />\r\nUnfortunately, due to the location of the museum there are no disabled parking places close by.', ' The British Museum', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'british-museum-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '51.519607', '-0.126882', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL),
(41, 'Located within the Bank of England itself, this museum is a fascinating insight into the history of the bank from its foundation in 1694 to the present day. As the United Kingdom’s central bank, the Bank of England has a unique role in our economy, as it works to keep inflation steady and low and ensures that the financial system is stable and protected from economic instability – pretty important stuff! \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nSet in a reconstruction of the Stock Office built by Sir John Soane (architect for the bank 1788-1833) the museum is about more than just money, with its unique insight into the banks extensive 300-year history, people and architecture which make for an interesting and informative day out (for all the family).\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Outside the Bank of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the Bank of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3>\r\nThis museum is free to enter.  \r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3>\r\nThe museum is open Monday- Friday (10am-5pm) and last entry is at 4:30pm.   \r\n\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3>\r\nYes, photography is allowed of this museum, although please be wary of using flash. \r\n\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3>\r\nYes, this museum has interactive technology.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image3-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Inside the Bank of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3>\r\nThis museum is well equipped for children, with interactive exhibits, technology and games for them to play and learn with.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3> Guides:</h3>\r\nFree printed guides are available at the information desk upon entry, audio guides are also available on a first-come, first-served basis.\r\n \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h3>1. Regal Coinage Collection. </h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image4-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Regal Coinage Collection.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn 1932, the Bank of England began a project to compile a representative collection of British Regal Coinage (Coins with the reigning monarch’s face engraved onto them) which date back as far as 1694 when the bank was established to present day. Although the making of coins is the responsibility of the Royal Mint, the collection is an incredible display of British monarchical reign and cannot be missed. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>2. London Good Delivery Bar. </h3> \r\n<br>\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image5-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Bank Of England Museum Gold Bar Weight.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br>\r\nIn 1750, The Bank of England set up the London Good Delivery List for gold which formally recognised those refineries which produced gold to the required standard. Essentially, the Good Delivery system is a way in which the LBMA (London Bullion Market Association) ensure that the standards for gold (and now silver) are maintained and kept in the bullion trade. See for yourself first hand a real gold bar and have your go at trying to lift it in the Rotunda room. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>3. An Iron Chest (c.1700). </h3> \r\n<br>\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image6-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Great Iron Chest.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nLocated in the Early Years gallery of the museum, this iron chest is the oldest piece of surviving furniture in the Bank of England and is referred to in a book from 1735 as ‘the great iron chest in the parlour’. Chests such as this one were the predecessors of the modern safe, have a look at this beautiful piece of economic history as you pass through. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> \r\nDue to the age and location of the museum there are no food and drink facilities available. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> \r\nYes, talks are provided for small groups, as well are presentations for larger groups. See the link below for more information.\r\n\r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/book-a-presentation\" target=\"_blank\"> Bank of England Museum / Tours </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bank-of-england-image7-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Bank of England gold vaults.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bank of England Museum\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> \r\nThe nearest tube is Bank station, which is a short walk (dependant on the exit).  \r\n\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> \r\nBus routes 8, 11, 21, 23, 25, 26, 43, 76, 133, 141, 242 and 388 run past the Bank of England. \r\n\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> \r\nBank of England Museum, Bartholomew Lane, London, EC2R 8AH.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\n\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h3> \r\nInduction loops are available at the front desk, and some of the videos in the museum’s galleries are subtitled. Please ask museum staff for more information. \r\n<br />\r\n(Visitors can also as for a signed video introduction to the museum at the information desk). \r\n\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h3> \r\nBlind or partially sighted visitors can pre-book and audio described tour of the museum, which are led by expert guides (tours are for a maximum of six people and are also available for solo visitors). For more information please see the link below. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/plan-your-visit/accessibility \" target=\"_blank\"> Bank of England Museum </a>\r\n<br />\r\nGuide dogs are welcome at the museum, and staff are happy to provide water. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h3>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h3>\r\nThe museum is accessible to wheelchair users, see below for more in-depth information and guides for accessibility. \r\n\r\n<br>\r\nManual wheelchairs are available from the Information Desk or to book a wheelchair in advance contact the above number. Benches and portable stools are available, so please see a member of staff upon your visit to the Gallery for more information. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/museum/plan-your-visit/accessibility \" target=\"_blank\"> Bank of England Museum </a>\r\n<br />\r\nUnfortunately, due to the location of the museum there are no disabled parking places close by. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Bank of England Museum', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'bank-of-england-museum-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '51.514322', '-0.087331', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, NULL),
(42, 'Brighton Palace Pier, opened on 20 May 1899, was built as a pleasure pier to entertain and delight the high number of visitors brought by Britain’s growing railway \r\n\r\nnetwork. Designed by Richard Saint George Moore on behalf of the Brighton Marine and Palace Pier Company, it was the third pier to be built in Brighton; alongside the \r\n\r\nOld Chain Pier and the West Pier. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe latter of these was also a pleasure pier, making Brighton the ultimate sea-side resort.\r\nIn 1891 construction of the Palace Pier began, but was slow due to financial problems. During a storm in 1896 the Old Chain Pier was destroyed, its debris causing much \r\n\r\ndamage to the new pier and delaying construction further. \r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Public-Advertisement-Palace-Pier.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Advertisement for Palace Pier amusements, 3 September 1903\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Brighton Pier\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\n<h4>Features of the pier.</h4>\r\nThe Palace Pier cost an astonishing £137,000 to build and was 1500 feet long (457.2 metres). In its early years it featured illuminated archways, as well as rooms for \r\n\r\nreading, dining, and smoking. There was a landing place for steam boats and a section for bathers, free between 7am and midday (Brighton Gazette - 3 September 1903). \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA 1500 seat theatre opened at the seaward end of the pier in April 1901, and after it was refurbished in 1911 it hosted an array of music hall stars. A pleasure garden \r\n\r\nwas added in the centre of the pier in 1910. \r\n  \r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Brigton-Palace-Pier.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Illustration of the \r\n\r\nBrighton Palace Pier shortly before it opened, 11 January 1899 (The Sketch)\r\n        <span>	Source: Brighton Pier\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Brigton-Palace-Pier-1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Illustration of the \r\n\r\nBrighton Palace Pier in 1901\r\n        <span>	Source: James Gray Collection / The Regency Society\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\n<h4>The twentieth century and beyond</h4>\r\nThe pier continued to develop its entertainment functions; the 1930s saw the introduction of dodgems and a big wheel. During World War Two the pier was closed and \r\n\r\nguarded by soldiers to prevent its use as a landing point by enemy troops. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter the War the Palace Pier continued to attract visitors, becoming ever more prominent as its popular neighbour, the West Pier, began to fall into disrepair \r\n\r\nfollowing a change in ownership in the 1960s. New arcade games like Space Invaders were introduced in the 1980s, propelling the pier into the modern age. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday the pier is 1733 feet long (525 metres) and still privately owned; it features video arcades, slot machines, sea-side stalls and a fairground and is an iconic \r\n\r\npart of the sea-front.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Visitor information:</h4>\r\nThe pier is open every day, except for Christmas day. Opening times are between 10:00 and 22:00 in the summer months (1 April and 31 October), and 10:00 and 17:00 in \r\n\r\nthe winter months (1 November to 31 March). For detailed opening times for rides and amusements visit: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.brightonpier.co.uk.\" target=\"_blank\"> Brighton Pier </a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Find out more:</h4>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://piers.org.uk/\" target=\"_blank\"> National Piers Society </a>\r\n\r\nWest Pier Trust,<a href=\"https://www.westpier.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\"> West Pier </a> The West Pier Centre is located in one of the seafront arches across from the old \r\n\r\npier.\r\n', 'Brighton Palace Pier, Brighton.', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Brighton-Palace-Pier-2-web2.jpg', 'topics', '50.8168555', '-0.1389267', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(44, 'Outside the Ministry of Defence buildings on Whitehall you will find a memorial dedicated to Field Marshal William Slim (Bill Slim). He stands alongside two other celebrated British commanders from the Second World War, Field Marshal Bernard Montgomery of El Alamein fame and Field Marshal Alan Brooke who was Prime Minister Winston Churchill’s foremost military advisor and part of the Combined Chiefs of Staff from 1942 onwards.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Bill-Slim.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Field Marshal William Joseph Bill Slim, 1st Viscount Statue, Whitehall, London.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBill Slim was born on the 6th August 1891 in Bristol but spent his teenage years in Birmingham. Between the age of 19 and 23 he found employment teaching at a Primary School amongst other jobs but he also found the time to take his first tentative steps into the military by joining Birmingham Universities Officer Training Corps in 1912. Two years later and with the outbreak of the First World War he was commissioned as a 2nd Lieutenant in the Royal Warwickshire Regiment.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the First World War he was injured twice, initially in Gallipoli and then for a second time in Palestine. He came through the conflict and was awarded the Military Cross for his actions in Mesopotamia having also attained the temporary rank of Major in the 6th Gurkha Rifles.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn the interwar years Slims military career progressed and by 1939 at the start of the Second World War he had been promoted to Colonel and given command of the 10th Indian Infantry Brigade who saw action in the East African campaign against Germany\'s allies Italy. However, he was injured for the third time in January 1941 and missed the majority of this campaign.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bill-slim-image.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Field Marshal William, Viscount Slim, in Service Dress, 1967.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Leonard Boden, National Army Museum Collection\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhilst recovering he served on the General Staff at GHQ in Delhi before in May 1941 he once again got promoted, this time to the acting rank of Major General and took charge of the 10th Indian Infantry Division who took part in the Anglo-Iraqi War, the Syrian-Lebanon Campaign and the Invasion of Persia. He was mentioned twice in dispatches in 1941 and received the Distinguished Service Order for his victory at Deir ez-Zor.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn May 1942 promotion once again beckoned and Slim became an acting Lt-General with command of the Burma Corps which he had actually been in charge of since March 1942. It is his time in charge of Burma Corps that has cemented his status as one of Britain\'s greatest military leaders.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAt the time Burma was being threatened by the might of the Imperial Japanese Army who had been steamrolling anything that stood in their way creating an air of invincibility and despite Slim wanting to fight the only logical action he could take was to order a fighting withdrawal to Manipur in India over 1600 km away that took 100 days to carry out and was the longest retreat ever carried out by a British Army.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHaving retreated to relative safety he was given command of 14th Army and charged with reshaping it in time to stop the Japanese march into India which had itself slowed down due to weather and supply line issues.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bill-slim-image-2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        British 3-inch mortar detachments support the 19th Indian Division\'s advance along the Mawchi Road, east of Toungoo, Burma. The mortar proved the most effective weapon in jungle warfare.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis all came to a head in March 1944 with the battles of Imphal and Kohima where the 14th Army not only stood toe to toe against the Japanese but had given them their largest defeat up to this point in the war and ground them down causing unsupportable casualties, eventually forcing them to retreat in disarray in July. This provided the springboard for the eventual campaign to regain Burma which was launched in 1945.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Battle of Imphal-Kohima was voted as the ‘Greatest British Battle’ surpassing the likes of D-Day and Waterloo in a poll taken by the National Army Museum in 2013 due to the way it turned the tide of the war in the Far East.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBy the end of the war Bill Slim was promoted to General and was Commander of Allied Land Forces Southeast Asia. He returned to the UK as head of the Imperial Defence College. And in February 1947, he was appointed an aide-de-camp to King George VI. He retired from the army in May 1948, however was brought out of retirement in January 1949 and given the rank of Field Marshal with the position of Chief of the Imperial General Staff (CIGS), he relinquished this role in November 1952 and in December of the same year became the Governor-General of Australia. He returned to Britain in 1959.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOn the 14th December 1970, 1st Viscount Slim, KG, GCB, GCMG, GCVO, GBE, DSO, MC, KStJ passed away in London aged 79 years old, he was given a full military funeral at St Georges Chapel, Windsor.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/bill-slim-image-3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Field Marshal William Joseph Slim, 1st Viscount Slim, usually known as Bill Slim, was a British military commander and the 13th Governor-General of Australia. Slim saw active service in both the First and Second World Wars and was wounded in action three times.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe statue was unveiled on the 28th April 1993 by Queen Elizabeth II. It was sculpted by Ivor Robert-Jones, stands over 3 metres tall and is made of bronze atop portland stone.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn an interesting twist the sculptor actually served in World War Two under Field Marshal Slim in the Burma Campaign and he was also the creator of the world-famous Winston Churchill statue which stands in Parliament Square.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Further Reading</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\nBurma ’44 by James Holland and Slim, Master of War: Burma 1942-1945 by Robert Lyman\r\n', 'Bill Slim\'s Statue Whitehall', '2019-02-28 8:29 am', 'bill-slim-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '51.503807', '-0.125847', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0);
