(46, 'The Clifton Suspension Bridge was designed by the prolific Victorian engineer Isambard Kingdom Brunel and first opened to the public over 150 years ago, after a long period of construction.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn 1829 a competition was opened to design a bridge to cross the river Avon and gorge, funded by the Society of Merchant Venturers from an initial bequest from William Vick, a Bristol wine merchant in the year 1753. The first round of entries saw all the designs rejected, including that from a 23 year old Brunel.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOne year later the competition re-opened and Brunel’s design won. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Construction of the bridge</h4>\r\nWork on the bridge began in 1831, but it was hindered by cold weather, riots and financial issues; at one point the project was abandoned completely before restarting and The Times reported that Bristolians must have felt its completion was “an unattainable ideal- a sort of phantom project that haunted the shores of the Avon…” These issues meant that when Brunel died in 1859 he never saw the bridge completed.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWilliam Henry Barlow and John Hawkshaw took over the venture upon Brunel’s death and the bridge was finally opened to a jubilant crowd of 150,000 people on 8 December 1864. At the time it was the longest and highest chain bridge in the world (The Times, 9 December 1864).\r\n  \r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/clifton-suspension-bridge1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The construction of the Leigh Tower in Somerset and the Clifton Tower in Gloucestershire. Brunel’s original plans included sphinxes atop the towers, but these were never built\r\n        <span>	Source: Clifton Suspension Bridge Trust.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/opening-of-the-bridge-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Opening of the bridge, The Illustrated London News, 17 December 1864, Vol. 45, No. 1292, p. 597.\r\nFrom The Illustrated London News Historical Archive, 1842-2003\r\n<span>	Source: History Today\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\n<h4>Legacy</h4>\r\nToday, the bridge is an icon of the City of Bristol and is crossed daily by around 11,000 vehicles. It is managed by the Clifton Suspension Bridge Trust and is grade I listed.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Opening times/ access:</h4>\r\nThe Observatory Hill in Clifton offers fantastic views of the bridge. The Visitor’s Centre, on the Leigh Woods side of the bridge, is free and open 10:00 – 17:00 every day. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFree tours of the bridge are on Saturdays at 3pm. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere is a £1 toll to cross the bridge in a vehicle under 4 tonnes, but pedestrians and cyclists can cross for free. \r\nPre-booked historical tours also run to the Leigh Woods Vaults, a series of vaulted chambers under the Leigh Tower.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese are limited and can be booked via:\r\n<a href=\"https://www.cliftonbridge.org.uk.\" target=\"_blank\"> The Clifton Suspension Bridge </a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Find out more:</h4>\r\nJ. Christopher, Brunel in Bristol (2003).\r\n<br />\r\n“Opening Of The Clifton Suspension bridge.\" The Times, 9 December 1864, p. 7. The Times Digital Archive.\r\n', 'The Clifton Suspension Bridge', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Clifton_Suspension_Bridge-web.jpg', 'topics', '51.4549291', '-2.6299998\r\n', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(47, 'The Anglo Saxon Royal Cemetery at Sutton Hoo is a unique 6th to 7th century burial ground of high status individuals. Around twenty earthen burial mounds make up the cemetery and, while they may seem unremarkable from the surface, archaeologists have discovered far more beneath the surface. These mounds were designed to be seen and to make a statement about the status of the individuals interred beneath them. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, many of the mounds were damaged as a result of being robbed during the Tudor period – something which is woefully common for visible burial mounds as they would often be looted in pursuit of ‘treasure’. Since then, however, numerous investigations have taken place surrounding the mounds. The first proper excavation was conducted in 1939 by self-taught archaeologist Basil Brown, commissioned and organised by the landowner, Edith Pretty. It was this first dig that uncovered the great ship burial of Mound One and made Sutton Hoo a centre of archaeological exploration ever since. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Helmet from the Sutton Hoo ship-burial, England. 7th century AD.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: British Museum // Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Burial Mounds</h3>\r\n\r\nThe most famous of the mounds is Mound One, where an immense 90ft ship burial was first unearthed in 1939. There are actually two ship burials at Sutton Hoo - the lesser known being under Mound Two. Unfortunately, this burial was disturbed by looters, but iron ship rivets reveal the presence of a small boat under the mound. This style of burial reflected contemporary practices in 7th century Sweden, showing a connection between Anglo Saxons in (what is now known as) East Anglia and cultures elsewhere in northern Europe. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe funerals would’ve been “performative” with lavish grave goods, ceremony and the construction of the immense mounds would have been made by hand. Not only was the burial packed with an abundance of rich grave goods, but the committal of an entire ship to the ground would have been an amazing spectacle. It would have cemented in their memory the royal status and significance of the individual buried. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Burial mound at Sutton Hoo, Suffolk, UK. This mound has been reconstructed to its supposed original height.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile we cannot be sure exactly who was buried, it is generally accepted that this is the likely resting place of Rædwald, ruler of the East Angles and the first king to rule as overlord over England as a whole. According to Bede’s Historia Ecclesiastica, Rædwald was amongst the earliest Anglo Saxon rulers in England to be baptised and he is credited with playing a significant role in the establishment of Christianity within the ruling classes. His new faith, however, earned the disapproval of his household and queen, who tried to coax him back to his pagan Gods (Plunkett 2005). \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nRædwald maintained elements of his pagan lifestyle and allowed the East Angles to worship both the Christian and the traditional Anglo-Saxon religions if they desired, something the devout Bede criticised him for. As a result of the immense wealth, status and religious associations of the individual under Mound One, it’s clear to see why Rædwald is such a strong candidate.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Artefacts in focus</h3> \r\n\r\nFortunately, not all the mounds were looted and this meant that, upon excavation, archaeologists uncovered a trove of rich grave goods in their original position. These grave goods (objects placed in a grave alongside a body) can be used to give us an insight into the wealth of the individual. For example, the grave is full of military equipment and valuable weapons, indicating their role as a warrior king within Anglo Saxon society. Similar equipment is found underneath Mound Seventeen, where a young warrior is poignantly buried alongside their horse and an abundance of weapons – their horse would have been sacrificed for the funeral which would have been a spectacular albeit grisly ritual display.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nChristian faith is also demonstrated in several of the items that accompanied the individual to the grave. These objects are amongst the main reasons that the grave is thought to belong to Rædwald. As religious beliefs can play such a huge part in people’s understanding of death and the afterlife, objects with religious motifs and associations are common finds, especially at times of religious transition such as Anglo Saxon period. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image4.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Burial chamber of the Sutton Hoo ship-burial, England. Reconstruction shown in the Sutton Hoo Exhibition Hall.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor example, ten nested silver bowls from the Eastern Empire were found alongside two Byzantium silver spoons with the names of the Apostles ‘Paul’ and ‘Saul’ engraved on them, in Greek. These are suggested to be possible baptismal gifts, buried as a symbol of Rædwald’s conversion to Christianity. There are also symbols of crosses on brooches, and a secret chamber hidden in the back of the gold Great Buckle that may have housed a Christian relic. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Great Buckle is an incredible example of master goldsmithing, with interwoven ribbon animal decoration and fine detailing. Perhaps the most exquisite artefacts found in the grave are a pair of fine filigree worked shoulder clasps, inlayed with garnets, millefiori designs, interlacing ribbon animal decoration and filigree surrounds. The motifs on the buckle are packed full of Anglo Saxon symbolism, cementing Rædwald’s cultural identity.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Sutton Hoo helmet is perhaps the most recognisable artefact from the grave. As well as its striking appearance and precious materials, it is laden with symbolism. It has been argued that the helmet makes reference to one-eyed Odin from Norse Mythology (Price and Mortimer 2014), due to imagery represented across northern Europe. If you look closely, you will notice a deliberate absence of gold foils over the left eye of the helmet and over the left eye of an animal head near the crow. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image5.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Sutton Hoo helmet reconstructed.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the low light of a feasting hall, this would result in the illumination of the right eye, and the casting of a shadow over the left – a powerful allusion to Odin and possibly declaring the wearer to be of the same status as the pagan god.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe placement of drinking horns (a common Anglo Saxon grave good) in the grave may have also served to create an image of the “worthy dead” (Pollington 2011: 21) as the possession and use of feasting equipment marked an individual’s place within society. The feasting equipment and lyre paint an image of a mead hall, full of music and celebration, with Rædwald as the gracious host. The funeral itself may have included some mead-fuelled celebration of the life of the deceased. Evidence of funerary feasting at the grave-side is common at Anglo Saxon burial sites (Lee 2007), and it may have been part of a transitionary ritual to aid passing into the afterlife.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>‘Ghosts’ in the sand</h3> \r\n\r\n\r\nTaphonomy’ is the study of the preservation, decay or changes to archaeological material after it has been deposited in the ground. A detailed, forensic approach to excavation and study of excavated material allows archaeologists to reconstruct the story of what has happened to organic material before, during and after burial. Soil conditions, burrowing animals, climate and even gnawing dogs can have a huge impact on survival of organic material.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAt Sutton Hoo, the acidic soil conditions meant that the great oak ship did not survive its 1400 years in the soil and the bones of Rædwald had long-since decayed. How, then, did archaeologists claim to ‘find’ the great ship burial and burials? \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image6.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Sand Bodies of Sutton Hoo.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: P.M.Sabin Moore Blog\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n‘Ghosts’ of the organic materials appeared as staining in the acidic yellow sand - archaeologists have to have a keen eye for changes in soil colour and texture, so they were able to spot these anomalies and excavate around them, creating ‘sand people’ (similar in appearance to some of the Pompeii casts) or identifying the structure of the ship. These were inhumation burials, but cremation burials were also uncovered at Sutton Hoo. Cremations are likely to have been the earliest at the site (Carver 1998) and are found under several mounds, as well as in the surrounding area. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs well as visible staining, decaying organic material can leave invisible traces of phosphates in the soil. In 1967, soil analysis from Mound One revealed a significant spike in the phosphate levels, indicating that there had once been a body in the grave but it had dissolved in the acidic environment.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Visiting Sutton Hoo</h3> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image7.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Sutton Hoo Exhibition Hall with Helmet sculpture\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nMany of the artefacts from across the Sutton Hoo site can be seen in the British Museum, but replicas and original are also housed in the Sutton Hoo visitor centre. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDue to a development project currently being undertaken at the National Trust site, the visitor centre and cemetery reopen to the public from late spring to early summer of 2019. A viewing platform is also being constructed at the National Trust site, so visitors will be able to fully appreciate the significance of the burial ground. Learn more: at www.nationaltrust.org.uk\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlan your visit, follow updates on the development or visit Sutton Hoo roadshow events through the National Trust website: https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/sutton-hoo', 'Sutton Hoo Royal Burial Mounds', '2019-02-28 8:29 am', 'sutton-hoo-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '52.0893194', '1.3384194', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, 4),
(48, 'Rising majestically from the north end of the Palace of Westminster is the ‘Clock Tower’ as it was originally called, this changed in 2012 when it was renamed ‘Elizabeth Tower’ in recognition of Queen Elizabeth II’s Diamond Jubilee. However, to millions of people around the world it will always be called ‘Big Ben’.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/big-ben-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A picture of Big Ben\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: James Cullen // Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n‘Big Ben’ is actually the name for the largest of the 5 bells contained within Elizabeth Tower, it weighs 13.7 tonnes and at one point was the largest bell in England standing over 2.2 metres tall and 2.7 metres wide.  It was cast at the Whitechapel Bell Foundry in East London on 10th April 1858.  The chimes you hear on the hour are believed to have been inspired by an aria (I Know that My Redeemer Liveth) in Handels ‘Messiah’. Try saying these words over the chimes.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/big-ben-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The Clock tower, standing 96 meters tall.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Clock Tower was completed on 31 May 1859, it stands 96 metres tall and contains 11 floors. 334 steps take you up to the belfry, however, under renovation plans a lift will be installed for visitors not quite fancying the climb.  Although currently closed for the renovation, tours are believed to be resuming in 2020 if everything goes to schedule. The tower was designed by the rather grand sounding Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin, an English architect who also designed the interior of the Palace of Westminster as well as churches in England, Ireland and as far away as Australia.  He died in 1852 and never seen his finished masterpiece.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/big-ben-image5.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nEach clock face on the tower is 23ft (seven metres) in diameter and composed of around 312 sections of opal glass. An hour hand is 9.2ft (2.8m) in length; a minute hand is 14ft (4.3m).\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/big-ben-image4.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Big Ben Clock Face.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nBy looking at Big Ben you can easily tell when parliament is in session.  Above the clockface is a light called the ‘Ayrton Light’, this is illuminated during the times parliament is in session.  At present it has been switched of due to renovation works.\r\nBig Ben is sure to remain a cultural British icon for many years to come.  It has however skirted with catastrophe.  During the Second World War a German bomb clipped the top of the tower during a raid doing minor structural damage but thankfully not enough to bring her down.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Big Ben', '2019-02-28 8:29 am', 'big-ben-header-image.jpg', 'topics', '51.5007292', '-0.1246254', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, 4),
(49, 'The Roman town of Venta Icenorum ‘market place of the Iceni’ was established c.70 AD as the capital of the Iceni tribe – the tribe made infamous in 61 AD when their queen, Boudicca, led a revolt against Roman rule. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDuring the Roman occupation large parts of Britain were organised into civitas reipublicae, which were political communities formed from the local citizens in a district. This process formalised the Iron Age tribal districts into permanent Roman administrative units which were ruled and managed from the civitas capital.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn response to the Boudiccan revolt, the Romans decided it would be prudent to establish a new civitas capital, Venta Icenorum, in this troublesome area to prevent further issues.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Boadicea_Haranguing_the_Britons.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\"> An engraving by William Sharp published in 1793, based on Boadicea Haranguing the Britons (called Boudicca, or Boadicea) by John Opie\r\n        <span>	Source: wikimedia commons </span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\nWhilst Venta Icenroum was never elaborate, it became an important trading centre. Trade allowed the town to grow in wealth, thereby permitting the construction of major public buildings, such as a forum, basilica and baths. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSimilarly, Venta Icenorum was not so modest that it did not benefit from the mod-cons of the day, the town was also supplied with running water, evidenced by the discovery of wooden water pipes and drains uncovered during excavations at the site.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhilst much of Venta Icenorum lays preserved under the ground, visitors can view the remains of the town’s defensive walls and ditches, which still protectively encircle the site.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/venta_cartoon_representation.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\"> A cartoon reconstruction of the building of the Roman town wall in the late AD 200s. Because the wall was built through the town rather than around it, several buildings were demolished to make way for the new defences. The remains of these buildings and the existing ground surface were then levelled to form the foundation on which the wall was built.\r\n        <span>	Source: john peterson // flickr </span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\nThe remains of tower-like bastions, designed as both watch towers and as platforms to mount artillery, indicates the walls were not merely there to demarcate the town’s boundaries, they were also a means of defence should there be further local uprisings. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOf these bastions, only one now survives, near the site of the west gate, however evidence of others can still be glimpsed in front of the south wall. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nVenta Icenorum remained occupied throughout the Roman occupation, however once Rome’s forces were withdrawn in 5th century AD, the town was abandoned and remained uninhabited during subsequent historical periods.\r\n <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe site is in the care of Norfolk Archaeological Trust and is open all year round – entrance is free. Visitors can follow several walks around the Roman defences and the Caistor Roman Town free augmented reality app (available on Google Play and the App Store) allows visitors to see a reconstruction of the town on the landscape and examine some of the artefacts found there.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Venta_Icenorum_view_from_southwall.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Venta Icenorum view from the south wall <span Source: wikimedia commons </span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\nFree parking is available a short walk from the site, however additional facilities can be found only 3.5 miles away in the city of Norwich.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br />\r\nHistoric England (n.d.) ‘Venta Icenorum’, Pastscape, online.\r\n<a href=\"https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=132757\" target=\"_blank\"> Venta Icenroum </a> \r\n', 'Caistor Roman Town, Venta Icenroum\r\n', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Venta_Icenorum_-_Market_Place_of_the_Iceni.jpg', 'topics', '52.5835036', '1.2911621', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(50, 'Lying hidden beneath the A1(M) motorway just off the Welwyn by-pass, Welwyn Roman Baths are the fascinating 3rd century remains of the bathing complex that once formed part of the Dicket Mead Roman villa. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe villa has not been fully excavated, however it is believed to have been occupied for 150 years during which time it was a self-sufficient farm that included a main residence, bath house, outbuildings and minor dwellings. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe remains of the baths lie encased and protected in a steel vault that was constructed 9 metres underground, an ingenious structure that can be reached through a steel tunnel that guides visitors on their journey through time to the Roman past below.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Welwyn Roman Baths. <span Source: Matt Brown // flickr </span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\nWhilst bathing was a social pastime in Roman Britain, with many people visiting the local bath house to wash, gossip and complete business transactions, private baths were still coveted by the elite. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThey may have been smaller than public baths, however in a society where power and hierarchy was everything, private baths allowed their owners to bathe with only those they deemed to be suitable. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nArchitecturally, private baths were very similar to their larger counterparts and included the requisite warm room (tepidarium), hot room (caldarium) and cold room (frigidarium). Remarkably well-preserved examples of all three rooms can be viewed at Welwyn, along with a hypocaust (underfloor heating) system which was used to circulate hot air around the complex. \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Welwyn Roman Baths. <span Source: Matt Brown // flickr </span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\nAccompanying the remains of the baths are numerous Roman finds from the site and local area, including building materials, painted panels, ceramic figures and a 1st century skeleton of a woman who is believed to have been a victim of ritual human sacrifice. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdditionally, a permanent exhibition tells the story of the site including its excavation in the 1960s and 70s by the Welwyn Archaeological Society.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe site is managed by Welwyn Hatfield Museum Service and is open weekends, bank holidays and school holidays between January and November. There is a fee to visit the site (Adult £3.50, Child 50p), however they do offer a 50% discount for a second adult living at the same address.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFree parking is available on site, as well as visitor toilets and a picnic area and refreshments can be bought from nearby Welwyn Village.\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Welwyn Roman Baths. <span Source: Matt Brown // flickr </span>\r\n		</div> </div>\r\n\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHistoric England (n.d.) ‘Welwyn Roman Baths’, Pastscape, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.britainexpress.com/counties/herts/roman/welwyn-roman-baths.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Welwyn Roman Baths </a> \r\n<br />\r\n\r\nRoss, D. (n.d.) ‘Welwyn Roman Baths’, Britain Express, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.britainexpress.com/counties/herts/roman/welwyn-roman-baths.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Welwyn Roman Baths </a> \r\n\r\n<br />\r\nWelwyn Hatfield Museum Service (n.d.) Roman Baths Welwyn, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.welhat.gov.uk/media/5248/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-Guide-English-/pdf/wrb_english_guide.pdf?m=634786535820000000\" target=\"_blank\"> Welwyn Roman Baths </a> \r\n', 'Welwyn Roman Baths', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image3.jpg', 'topics', '51.8281645', '-0.2102497', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(51, 'Originally an Iron Age hillfort, Ham Hill was one of the first native settlements to be ceased by the Claudian invasion forces in 43 AD. The remains of this fort \r\n\r\nindicate it was an immense structure, with a circumference of 3 miles and an area of 210 acres, consequently the Roman’s conquest of the site is likely to have been a \r\n\r\nsignificant cog in the invasion machine. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, its location on the top of a hill ensured that the Romans were able to establish a permanent fortification and effective vantage point from which to quash \r\n\r\nand manage the local Durotriges tribe. \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Ham Hill War Memorial <span>\r\n			Source:Steve // flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nA significant number of Roman military artefacts have been found both on Ham Hill and in the surrounding area, with the majority identified as legionary in origin. \r\n\r\nConsequently, whilst there are no physical remains of the Roman fort, the quality and quantity of the finds, along with the site’s dominance over the surrounding area, \r\n\r\nmakes it very likely that a fort was built here. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, the absence of the expected v-shaped defensive ditches or building foundations usually found at the sites of Roman forts is most likely a result of the \r\n\r\nsite only being used during the initial stages of the Claudian campaigns. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce the invasion forces had conquered the south of Britain, they quickly moved on to Wales and Northern Britain, levelling and abandoning forts they no longer \r\n\r\nrequired as they left to prevent re-use by any local dissident forces.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A mountainous view of Ham Hill <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nWhilst Ham Hill had strategic significance during the early years of the Roman occupation, it was not used again until after the Romans left Britain in 5th century AD. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nArchaeological finds from the site and surrounding area suggest the presence of various settlements from as early as the Saxon period, however evidence has failed to \r\n\r\nconfirm whether the fort was used as a military base again. \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image4.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Sunset at Ham Hill <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe site is managed by South Somerset District Council and is open all year round, weather permitting – entrance is free. There is extensive free parking available and \r\n\r\nplenty of hilly landscapes, leafy woodlands and grassy meadows to explore. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToilets are available at the Ham Hill Centre and refreshment facilities can be found at the Price of Wales pub which is located nearby. \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image5.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\"> Landscape of Ham Hill <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nArchaeology Magazine Online (2013) ‘Ham Hill’s Ramparts Excavated’, Archaeology, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.archaeology.org/news/1277-130906-england-ham-hill-iron-age-ramparts\" target=\"_blank\"> Ham Hill</a>\r\n<br />\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br />\r\nRoman Britain (n.d.) ‘Ham Hill’, Roman Britain, online \r\n<a href=\"http://www.roman-britain.co.uk/places/ham_hill.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Ham Hill</a>\r\n<br />\r\nSomerset Military Museum (n.d.) ‘Ham Hill Hillfort’, Somerset Military History, online\r\n<a href=\"http://www.sommilmuseum.org.uk/ham-hill-hillfort/\" target=\"_blank\"> Ham Hill</a>\r\n<br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.historic-uk.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/ham-hill.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"> Ham Hill</a>\r\n', 'Ham Hill', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'ham-hill-image1.jpg', 'topics', ' 50.948775', '-2.744622\r\n', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(52, 'The town of Letocetum, also known as Wall, lay on the Roman road of Watling Street and developed when the army built a military post here during their campaigns into Wales. As was often the case, a civilian settlement (vicus) grew nearby and quickly expanded once construction of Watling Street was completed in the late 1st century AD. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSituated on the boundary of two native British tribes (the Coritani and the Cornovii), Letocetum is likely to have developed as the main trading centre between the two tribes. This, along with the presence of Watling Street, ensured that the town became a key staging post on the road from London to Wroxeter and Chester. \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Letocetum-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Robbed-out Roman stone from Letocetum used in a \'modern\' wall <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\nWith so many visitors passing through Letocetum, a mansio (guest house) was built, the remains of which can be viewed at the site. A mansio resembled a very large house, but with addition of extended bathing facilities and accommodation for horses. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEvidence from the site indicates that the mansio at Letocetum was focused around a central courtyard with a formal garden which acted as an informal gathering place for both guests and locals.  \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Letocetum-image2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Letocetum Roman baths from St John\'s Wall <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nAdjacent to the mansio are the remains of Letocetum’s bath house, which, according to the archaeological record, was in constant use for over 150 years. Whilst the baths underwent several modifications during this time, the structure conformed to the standard format found in bath houses across Roman Britain – comprising a cold bath, heated rooms, changing rooms and exercise hall. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe bath house was used by both the local inhabitants and the travellers visiting the mansio, consequently it continued to be an important feature of daily life in Letocetum until the town’s eventual decline in the 4th century. \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Letocetum-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">St John\'s Church, Wall <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\nThe site is managed by English Heritage and is open all year round and is free to enter. There is also a volunteer-run museum on site, which houses finds from various archaeological digs conducted on the site and in the local area.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe museum is open to visitors on the last weekend of each month from March to October. Free parking is available nearby, however for additional facilities the cathedral city of Lichfield is only a short drive away.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Letocetum-image4.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Wall Staffordshire Letocetum Roman Bath-house <span>\r\n			Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br /> \r\n<a href=\"https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=304404\" target=\"_blank\"> Historic England (n.d.) ‘Letocetum’, Pastscape, online \r\n</a>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryMagazine/DestinationsUK/Letocetum-Wall-Roman-Site/\" target=\"_blank\"> Johnson, B. (n.d.) ‘Letocetum (Wall Roman Site)’, Historic UK, online</a>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n<a href=\"http://www.roman-britain.co.uk/places/letocetum.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Roman Britain (n.d.) Letocetum, online</a>\r\n', 'Letocetum', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Letocetum-Roman-Baths-and-Museum-Exterior2.jpg', 'topics', ' 52.656460', '-1.857371\r\n', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(53, 'Corbridge Roman Town was once a bustling supply town and military base where local Romans and civilians were able to pick up supplies and provisions. The town was a vibrant outpost of the Roman Empire that prospered throughout Britain’s occupation, only diminishing once the Roman’s left in the early 5th century. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nVisitors to Corbridge can still walk along the once lively streets past the remains of the town’s granaries, markets, workshops and temples.\r\n \r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Corbridge-Roman-Town-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Image showing the stonework at Corbridge Roman Town <span>\r\n			Source:Ken Fitzpatrick // flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nNamed Coria by the Romans, Corbridge is only one of two towns to be located on Hadrian’s Wall, making it an important example of a frontier settlement and fort. Characteristic of Roman forts, the remains at Corbridge provide evidence of many of the buildings expected in such locations. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nExcavations have revealed the remains of a Principia (headquarters building), Praetorium (the commanding officer’s house), barracks and defences, with the earliest buildings dating from the late 1st century. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThere have been many famous finds (viewable in the site museum) that pertain to the town’s significance as a military outpost, but of particular interest is the Corbridge Hoard which includes fine examples of the worldly goods of a Roman soldier – armour, weaponry, tools, wax writing tablets and papyrus. \r\n \r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Corbridge-Roman-Town-image2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">An inward view of the stonework at Corbridge Roman Town <span>\r\n			Source:Ken Fitzpatrick // flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe remains of Corbridge Roman town are also accompanied by a museum which displays some of the 34,000 extraordinary finds of the Corbridge collection. Life on the Roman frontier is made tangible in the varying artefacts on display.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA 2nd-3rd century gaming board with counters and die and ornately decorated drinking vessel provide material evidence of the interests and hobbies enjoyed by soldiers, whilst inscribed alters and tombstones suggest that numerous deities from across the empire had an influential presence in the town.  \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Corbridge-Roman-Town-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Acient architectural stonework ruins at Corbridge Roman Town <span>\r\n			Source:Ken Fitzpatrick // flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe site is in the care of English Heritage and is open all year round, however during the winter opening times are limited to Saturdays and Sundays only. There is an entrance fee (Adult £7.90, Child £4.70, Family £20.50) to enter the site for non-members of English Heritage, however this includes access to both the site and museum. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nAn outdoor picnic area, shop and toilets are available on site and free parking for 20 cars is located at the site, with additional tourist parking available 1 ¼ miles away in the town of Corbridge.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Corbridge-Roman-Town-image4.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Landscape view of Corbridge Roman Town <span>\r\n			Source:Ken Fitzpatrick // flickr\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br /> \r\n<a href=\"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/corbridge-roman-town-hadrians-wall/\" target=\"_blank\"> English Heritage (n.d) ‘Corbridge Roman Town’, online  \r\n</a>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://hadrianswallcountry.co.uk/visit/corbridge-roman-town\" target=\"_blank\"> Hadrian’s Wall Country (n.d.) ‘Corbridge Roman Town’, online </a>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=55220\" target=\"_blank\"> Historic England (n.d.) ‘Corbridge Roman Town’, Pastscape, online </a>\r\n', 'Corbridge Roman Town', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Corbridge-Roman-Town1.jpg', 'topics', '54.978400', '-2.033160', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(54, 'Sitting just outside of the village of Aldborough, the remains of the Roman town of Isurium provide a tantalising glimpse of this location’s past significance. On this site sat the 1st century capital of the Romanised Brigantes, an administrative headquarters established to allow the tribe to govern and control the regional population. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocated directly adjacent to Dere Street, the military road that ran from York to Corbridge, this location ensured a direct and strategic link with both the important city of York to the South and Hadrian’s Wall to the North.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Roman_Pavement_Mosiac.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Roman Pavement Mosiac <span> Source:wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nIsurium acted as the only civitas capital of the North, an important role that allowed the Brigantes to independently govern the region whilst under the supervision of the Roman provincial administration based in Londinium. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIts important role is evident in some of the town features that have been uncovered by archaeologists, such as the remains of the town wall which was built and well maintained throughout Britain’s Roman occupation. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, houses of a high standard, believed to have been built during the 4th century, suggest Isurium was a well-appointed town with connections, through Dere Street, to the rest of the North and beyond.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Mosaic_depicting_the_She-wolf.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Mosaic depicting the She-wolf with Romulus and Remus, from Aldborough, about 300-400 AD <span> Source: wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe town’s significance can be additionally gleaned from the beautiful mosaics that have been found in situ at the site. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOf particular interest is the mosaic of the muses, a rare example of a Roman mosaic with Greek inscription, which is the only example of its kind in Britain, thereby hinting at the cultural and literary sophistication of its owner.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA portion of this tantalising find, displaying Thalia, the muse of comedy, is now housed and can be viewed in the site’s museum.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Aldborough_Parish_Church.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Aldborough Parish Church <span> Source: wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nThe site is in the care of English Heritage and is open from early April to late September each year. There is an entrance fee (Adult £4:50, Child £2.90, Family £12.50) to enter the site for non-members of English Heritage, however this includes access to both the site and museum. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAn outdoor picnic area, shop and toilets are available on site and free tourist parking is located 1 mile from the site in the nearby village of Boroughbridge. \r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Village_Green_Aldborough.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">Village Green of Aldborough <span> Source: wikimedia commons\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br /> \r\n<a href=\"http://www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk/yorkshire/aldborough_town_castle.html\" target=\"_blank\"> castlesfortsbattles.co.uk (n.d.) ‘Aldborough Roman Town’, online </a>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n<a href=\"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/aldborough-roman-site/\" target=\"_blank\"> English Heritage </a>\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n<a href=\"http://romanaldborough.co.uk/project-1/\" target=\"_blank\"> Friends of Roman Aldborough (2016) ‘The Aldborough Mosaics’, online </a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=55220\" target=\"_blank\"> Historic England (n.d.) ‘Aldborough Roman Town’, Pastscape, online  </a>\r\n', 'Aldborough Roman Site, North Yorkshire', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'aldborough-main-image.jpg', 'topics', '54.09079', '-2.033160', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL);
