(55, 'A monument on the Victoria Embankment, commissioned and paid for by the Battle of Britain Historical Society, commemorates those who were part of the Battle of Britain in 1940 during the Second World War. This 82ft long memorial made of both granite and bronze was installed in 2005, and was unveiled on 18th September that year by HRH Prince Charles and the Duchess of Cornwall, marking the 65th anniversary of the event. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/battle-of-britain-monument-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       The Battle of Britain Monument in London is a sculpture on the Victoria Embankment overlooking the River Thames in central London, England which pays tribute to those who took part in the Battle of Britain during World War II.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Bas Boerman // Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe sculptor, Paul Day wanted the monument designed with two large panels facing in opposing directions – one panel commemorates the achievements of the armed force, while the other remembers the wider effect of the War on the British nation.  The imagery of the monument therefore depicts several scenes not only of the battle, with allied airmen running towards their planes to intercept the Luftwaffe, but also of other elements of the War. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis includes spotters of enemy planes, ground technical staff, women in munition factories, and people caught up in The Blitz in London.  A comprehensive list of the different elements of the memorial’s imagery can be found <a href=\"http://bbm.org.uk/the-monument/background/description-of-monument-scenes/\" target=\"_blank\"> here.</a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/battle-of-britain-monument-image2.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        A part of the Battle of Britain Monument, along Victoria Embankment. The quote is from a 1940 speech by Winston Churchill and reads: \"Never in the field of human conflict was so much owed by so many to so few.\"\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Daniele Nicolucci // Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe monument features a famous quote in a wartime speech in 1940 by Winston Churchill, British Prime Minister from 1940-1945, where he refers to the work of the air force during the Battle of Britain: <mark> ‘never in the history of human conflict was so much owed by so many to so few’. After this speech the Battle of Britain airmen were popularly referred to as ‘The Few’.</mark>  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe two parts of the monument feature the names of the 2,936 airmen and ground crew from 14 different countries who were engaged in combat during the Battle.  The full list of these airman, with biographies of around 2,000 of them can be found <a href=\"http://bbm.org.uk/the-airmen\" target=\"_blank\"> here.</a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/battle-of-britain-monument-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Close Up of the monument.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore details of the Battle of Britain, the memorial, and the process of creating and unveiling it can be found at  <a href=\"https://bbm.org.uk\" target=\"_blank\"> the official website.</a> . You can also see a 360 degrees view of part of the monument <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V_CyrFyBwFQ\" target=\"_blank\"> here.</a>  ', 'Battle of Britain Monument\r\n', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Battle-of-britain-header.jpg', 'topics', '51.5030278', '-0.1233611', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(56, 'Bramall Lane, Sheffield is the oldest professional football stadium in the world. Built in 1855 as a cricket ground, it hosted its first football game in 1862, between Hallam FC and Sheffield FC. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Sheffield Independent (30 December 1862) covered the game, including details about a skirmish: “At one time it appeared likely that the match would be turned into a general fight” after one of the players was accidentally hit by another. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe injured party “threw off his waistcoat and began to ‘show fight’ in earnest…They were surrounded by partisans and for a few minutes there was every appearance of a general fight amongst players and spectators.” \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Bramall-lane-cricket-football-ground-1955-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\"> Bramall Lane Stadium\r\nSource: Unknown\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe ground was predominately used for cricket but continued to play host to regular football matches. In 1878 the world’s first floodlit football match was played there in front of nearly 30,000 spectators. John Tasker provided electricity for the event, as a means to promote his electrical light company. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nStages with lamps and reflectors were built in the corners of the ground. Behind each goal was placed a portable engine, each of which drove two dynamo machines that powered the lights. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Leeds Mercury (15 October 1878) reported that “…the rays, which were of great brilliancy, lighted nearly the whole of the ground, and the players could be seen almost as clear as at noonday,” noting that “the illuminating power was equal to 8,000 standard candles, and the cost per hour for each light is 31s. 2d.” \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe excitement and novelty of the event was made apparent: “When the light was turned on the great crowd cheered loudly, and then watched the game with great interest. Some amusement was caused by the brilliance of the light, which dazzled the players sometimes, and caused some strange blunders.”\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/Football-by-the-Electic-Light-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\"> Bramall Lane Stadium\r\nSource: Sheffield Independent\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Modern day</h3>\r\nToday Bramall Lane is home to Sheffield FC, formed in 1857, they are recognised as the oldest football club in the world. Before they became part of the Football Association (FA) in 1878, the club initially played under ‘Sheffield Rules’; these greatly influenced the FA’s own regulations, introducing the likes of free kicks following a foul, throw-ins, and corners to the game. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThroughout the twentieth century the stadium continued to host cricket matches (until 1973), as well as Rugby League games, boxing matches, and music concerts.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Opening times/ access:</h3>\r\nThe Museum is open for visitors from 1.30pm on Saturday match-days, £3 for adults and £2 for concessions. Match day tours are available with the club historian, £6 for adults and £4 for concessions. \r\nDetails here: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.sufc.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\"> Bramall Lane</a>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Find out more:</h3>\r\nG. Armstrong and J. Garrett, Sheffield United FC: The Biography (Sheffield, 2006).\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPodcast from Outside Write, a Football Travel, History and Culture Website, featuring an interview with Richard Tims, the Chairman of Sheffield FC: \r\n<a href=\"http://outsidewrite.co.uk/football-travel-podcast-episode-four/\" target=\"_blank\"> Bramall Lane</a>', 'Bramall Lane', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'Bramall-lane-Stadium-1.jpg', 'topics', '53.370376', '-1.4736924', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(57, 'A peculiar site peppered around London are odd looking metal fences. To a casual passer-by the oddness would not be picked up on but have a closer look and you can see metal fences that have peculiar curves in their horizontal bars. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThese are not a fancy design template ordered up en masse in post-war Britain but are in fact recycled WW2 Air Raid Precautions Department (ARP) steel stretchers that have been recycled as street fencing. The unusual curves are the stretcher handles.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Arp Stretchers converted into fences.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n60’000 of these stretchers were produced during WW2 to cater for expected casualties from German bombing raids and come the end of the conflict they were very much surplus to requirements.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n  \r\nAt this point London was rebuilding and upcycling these stretchers was seen as a fantastic opportunity to replace metal railings that had (during the war) been collected to use towards the war effort.  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Stretchers in use.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nSadly, the number of surviving metal stretcher fences is falling due to their upkeep and the effects of the weather on them over the years but a lot of examples still exist today.  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIf you find yourself in this area be sure to keep an eye out for the wartime stretcher fences.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image3-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Stretcher fences at Down\'s estate.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>', 'The ARP Stretcher Fences', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'arp-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(58, 'Grey Abbey, which lends its name to the village in which its situated, is a ruined 12th century Cistercian priory. While it may lie in ruins, visitors can still gather a sense of what life was like for monks living in Anglo Norman Ulster. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/grey-abbey-image1-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n      Grey Abbey.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Background</h3>\r\n\r\nIn 1193, Affreca de Courcy (née Guðrøðardóttir) founded the Abbey as a daughter house of Holmcultram, housing Cistercian monks from Cumberland. As a result of her religious patronage in life, Affreca was buried at the abbey and an effigy tomb erected. Although the abbey may lie in ruins, this effigy tomb can still be seen in the north wall of the choir.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nAffreca was the daughter of the King of Man and wife of John de Courcy, the latter of whom was a key figure in the Anglo-Norman invasion of East Ulster. De Courcy is credited with the establishment of numerous sites and strongholds across the region, including Cathedral Hill, the Mound of Down, Inch Abbey, Carrickfergus and Dundrum, before his fall from power at the hands of Hugh de Lacy and King John. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/grey-abbey-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n      Photo of the mannequin of Affreca de Courcy at Carrickfergus Castle. Original caption: She\'s looking toward the Isle of Man.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>History of the Abbey</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\nDespite its use as a priory from its founding in 1193, the stonework construction of the Abbey was not completed until 1230. Once completed, it was the first fully gothic style building in Ulster and it is great architectural importance. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nThe Cistercian monks who colonised the abbey maintained close ties with the Cumberland church throughout the years, with abbots from Grey Abbey becoming abbots at Holmcultram in 1222 and 1237. However, the abbey’s history is otherwise quite sparse. We do, however, know that it was destroyed and damaged many times. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nFirstly, it was almost entirely destroyed at the hands of Edward Bruce’s forces during his invasion (1315-1318). During the Elizabethan era, the monastery was destroyed during military operations and, in 1572, the site was burnt by Brian O’Neill to prevent it acting as refuge for English colonists.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n \r\n\r\nBy the late medieval period, Grey Abbey had fallen into decline and, along with hundreds of other monasteries and parishes, it fell to Henry VIII’s Dissolution of the Monasteries in 1541. The Abbey lay in relative ruin until it (and its surrounding estate) was granted to the Montgomery family in 1607. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/grey-abbey-image3-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     The Dissolution of the monasteries was an event that happened from 1536 to 1540, when English King Henry VIII took away the land and money that the nuns and monks of the Roman Catholic church owned. ... He decided to create his own religion - the Church of England.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nIn 1626, Sir Hugh Montgomery undertook extensive refurbishments and converted the Abbey into a parish church that served the local community until 1778. As a result of the Montgomery family’s custodianship, there are several memorial plaques in their name throughout the nave.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nThe Abbey is now in the care of the Northern Ireland Environment Agency as a scheduled monument, meaning it is afforded protection under the state. The Friends of the Abbey group also run guided tours of the Abbey and look after the Physic Garden and Visitors’ Centre.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Things to look out for</h3>\r\n\r\nThe Physic Garden is located at the entrance to the Abbey, by the Visitors’ Centre. It was designed to reflect the medicinal gardens usually found in medieval abbeys and monasteries. In the past, herbs and plants would’ve been cultivated in these kinds of gardens to produce medicines and dyes, with many Cistercian monks becoming skilled botanists. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/grey-abbey-image4-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     The Physic Garden is located at the entrance to the Abbey, by the Visitors’ Centre.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nTheir herbal remedies were used to treat a whole host of common ailments, with knowledge of herbalism deriving from Greek, Egyptian, Roman and Arabic texts as well as their own trial-and-error. Many modern medicines derive from plant sources, such as the use of Yew trees to produce chemotherapy drugs or poppies for the production of morphine. \r\n\r\n<br /><br /> \r\n\r\nIf you’re visiting in the summer, during an especially dry period, you might be able to see parch marks in the grass around the cloister. These follow the original walls and mark features of the abbey that no longer survive above the surface. Sub-surface features can affect the growth of grass and other plants, by affecting the amount of moisture in the soil – this shows up as ‘crop marks’ or ‘parch marks’. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nMarks like these often help archaeologists identify new sites – during the especially dry summer of 2018, hundreds of new features were identified in the landscape across the UK and Ireland.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nThe gothic architecture of the Abbey is breath-taking, with dramatic arches, doorways and windows surviving amongst the ruins. Not only is it visually superb, but it is also architecturally significant, as Grey Abbey was the first fully gothic style building in the whole of Ulster. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/grey-abbey-image5-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     The gate to the grounds is open from 8:30am – 8pm. \r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n\r\nFrom its completion in 1230, the structure remained virtually unchanged until alterations in the 15th century saw its tower and chancel raised in height. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nOn the south side of the nave are several impressive buttresses. However, upon closer inspection of the stonework, it becomes clear that these are modern additions. In the early 20th century, the nave faced collapse and in order to stabilise it, the Ministry of Public works carried out conservation work and constructed these buttresses. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nDuring conservation or reconstruction of a site through modern additions, it is common practice to set them apart by using different coloured stone, mortar or different masonry patterns. This can also be seen throughout the Abbey in reconstructed and repaired walls.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Visitor Information</h3>\r\n\r\nAdmission is free, although donations are encouraged to fund the upkeep of the grounds. There is a small Visitors’ Centre at the entrance, with an abundance of displays and activities – there’s even the chance to dress up as a Cistercian monk. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nIf you are driving to the site, there is a free-to-use car park and the area is well sign-posted.\r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nIn terms of accessibility, there is pedestrian and wheelchair access from the car park to the Visitors’ Centre and Physic Garden, but gravel and grass throughout the rest of the site might be difficult for some. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nThe site is open from 8.30am-8pm on weekdays, and 10am-8pm over the weekend. We definitely recommend visiting in the spring or summer to see the grounds in full bloom!\r\n', 'Grey Abbey', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'grey-abbey-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '54.5358333', '-5.560522', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `articles` (`articlesid`, `text`, `articletitle`, `dateUploaded`, `articleImage`, `appearin`, `latitude`, `longitude`, `view`, `likes`, `dislikes`, `featured`, `position`, `visible`, `categoryid`, `authorid`) VALUES
(59, 'Before the information age, serial killers didn’t make news apart from in the town they were acting. There have been plenty of repeat murderers throughout history dating back to the 2nd century BC and have been mentioned in Greek mythology, but only a select few stick in our heads: Ted Bundy, the Zodiac killer, and Jack the Ripper.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image1.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Images of Ted Bundy and the Zodiak Killer.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nActive from August to November 1888, Jack the Ripper managed to become one of the most famous serial murderers in history with a victim count of five women in Whitechapel, London. The canonical victims, i.e. those known to have been killed by Jack the Ripper with their death dates are as follows: <mark>Mary Ann “Polly” Nichols (31st August), Annie Chapman (8th September), Elizabeth Stride and Catherine Eddowes (30th September), and Mary Jane Kelly (9th November).</mark>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDespite the passing of 130 years, the killer’s identity is still a mystery and was known as the Whitechapel Murderer until Scotland Yard received a letter on the 29th September 1888. The “Dear Boss” letter, written in neat, Roundhand script with red ink, features the writer taunting the police - <mark>“they won’t fix me just yet. … How can they catch me now.” - and finally signed “Yours truly Jack the Ripper”.</mark> The publication of this letter meant that his nickname caught like wildfire and was henceforth used by people from all levels of society.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image2-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        The first page of the \"Dear Boss\" letter.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nAccording to the Illustrated Police News on the 20th October 1888, police were sifting through “upwards of seven hundred letters” all relating to the Jack the Ripper case.  It can be estimated that over 1000 letters were sent by the end of the case. By the end of October, he had murdered four of the canonical five women and police were no closer to finding him. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMost of these letters, some 300 of which are still kept at the Corporation of London Records Office, were deemed as hoaxes. There is a small handful, however, that is taken seriously by experts and those interested in the cold case: the aforementioned <mark>“Dear Boss” letter</mark>, the <mark>“Saucy Jacky” postcard</mark>, and the <mark>“From Hell” letter</mark> (also known as the Lusk letter as it was directed to George Lusk). \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAll of these were signed “Jack the Ripper” and the content was such that the police paid special attention to them. The Lusk letter from 15th October 1888 in particular was concerning; <mark>a human kidney accompanied it </mark> which was significant as two weeks earlier, Catherine Eddowes was found murdered with her left kidney missing.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image3.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n        Facsimile of the front of the \"Saucy Jacky\" postcard.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAlthough this may seem proof, it has never been ascertained whether or not this was Catherine’s kidney. Earlier this year it was claimed that “Saucy Jacky” and “Dear Boss” were written by the same hand due to linguistic similarities and handwriting consistencies. \r\n\r\n<h3>Letters and Clues </h3>\r\n\r\nIn addition to the letters, even though they may have all been fake, or those deemed as fake may have been authentic (put simply: nobody knows), there was one other piece of potentially worthwhile evidence. In the stairwell of 108-119 Model Dwellings in Goulston Street, a piece of cloth was found by Constable Alfred Long. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis filthy scrap was part of Catherine Eddowes apron, who was killed mere hours prior, and was stained with blood. Above the apron on the wall or jamb of the building’s entrance was written <mark>“The Juwes are the men that will not be blamed for nothing”.</mark> Transcriptions differ as we have no photographic evidence; the police thought it best to wash the message away to avoid stirring any anti-Semitic tensions given that the area had a large Jewish community. But, like many clues connected with the Jack the Ripper case, we have no way of knowing if this graffiti is actually linked to the murders.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image4-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Copy of graffito in Goulston Street, attached to Metropolitan Police Commissioner Sir Charles Warren\'s report to the Home Office on the Whitechapel murders.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>The Police</h3>\r\nThoroughly disturbed from the beginning, the police formed the Whitechapel Vigilance Committee. Led by George Lusk (yes, the same man who received a random kidney in the post), groups of volunteers patrolled the East End streets at night in an attempt to catch the elusive killer. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image5-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       George Lusk, President of the Whitechapel Vigilance Committee.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOn top of this, the Metropolitan Police (most notably the Whitechapel H division), City of London Police, and Scotland Yard were hard at work interviewing countless witnesses and suspects without any real leads. The key witness statements they obtained lacked immense amounts of detail which made it difficult to form a precise picture of what had happened. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nRecently experts have deduced that he must have been a very typical, ordinary person with the ability to blend into the background without arousing any suspicion which only adds to the difficulties the police faced.  Timing was also not in the Metropolitan Police’s favour: they were put under great stress as there were shifts and instability in leadership which damaged officer morale. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the technology and procedures available at the time were not sufficient for this kind of investigation. Fingerprinting, Crime Scene Investigation, crime scene photography, and forensics were all to be discovered several years later - fingerprinting was only implemented as standard procedure in 1901 - without these thorough investigative techniques we use today, it would have been extraordinarily difficult to find the murderer. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image6-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Use of fine powder and brush to reveal latent fingerprints.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIf these murders happened now, the Ripper would have been found after the first murder. DNA profiling is a gift to crime scenes, it is the control+F of perpetrator identification.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Suspects</h3>\r\nAs the police did not have enough evidence to prosecute any suspect, the public let their imaginations run wild and numerous theories, both feasible and a little less believable, were thought up. At the time the police had their suspects, the favoured one being <mark> George Chapman (born Seweryn Kłosowski)</mark> who emigrated to London from Poland just before the murders began. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHe also had a track record of poisoning his wives. Also from Poland was <mark>Aaron Kosminski.</mark> This man spent a great deal of time in an insane asylum but there isn’t really anything to firmly suggest he murdered several women. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image7-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       George Chapman (December 14, 1865 - April 7, 1903) was the English name taken by serial killer Seweryn Antonowicz Kłosowski.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThen we have <mark>‘Leather Apron’, whose real name was John Pizer or Piser,</mark> also of Polish origin. There was absolutely no evidence for him being the murderer apart from the fact that he may have committed minor assaults on prostitutes and in fact, he had alibis for two out of five murders.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPerhaps the most curious suspect was <mark>Francis Tumblety,</mark> he was a quack doctor from the United States with an impressive moustache if the photographs and drawings are anything to go by. He is said to have been a misogynist with a strong loathing for prostitutes in particular and once showed a friend his display of preserved uteri at a dinner party. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image8-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Photo of Francis Tumblety.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis along with the American nature we have seen in the alleged authentic letters, plus a knowledge of human anatomy, all points to a likely suspect. The uterine collection, however, has not been proved, nor has the authenticity of the letters. Once again, evidence falls through.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe press and public had their opinions, of course. <mark>Thomas Neill Cream</mark> was a name that cropped up often. He was also a doctor specialising in abortions - bonus point for female anatomical knowledge; and had previously poisoned several women - another point for being able to kill someone; all signs so far point to him being a likely suspect. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nExcept, he was in Illinois between 1881 and 1891 serving time for his crimes, meaning there was no way he could have been in London in 1888 terrorising Whitechapel. There is apparently the possibility, according to some Jack the Ripper enthusiasts, that Cream had a double who killed the five, or more, women in London. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image9-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Photo of Dr. Thomas Neill Cream.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nDespite the unlikelihood of him being Jack the Ripper, it is alleged that his last words before execution were <mark>“I am Jack…” </mark>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOther suspects include males who personally knew the victims, such as <mark>George Hutchinson and Joseph Barnett</mark> who both knew Mary Jane Kelly. More outlandish suspects, who were suggested long after the murders but not taken seriously by scholars, include <mark>Lewis Carroll and Walter Sickert.</mark>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image10.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Walter Sickert; his Persuasion painting.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nThe former because of some anagrams found in his work, and the latter because he was known to have an interest in the Ripper murders and painted Jack the Ripper’s Bedroom and the subject of his Camden Town Murder paintings connect him to the population of the East End.  \r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nArthur Conan Doyle and Inspector Abberline even proposed that it was not Jack the Ripper the police were searching for, but rather <mark>Jill the Ripper</mark> - either that Jack was posing as a woman to avoid detection or that the killer was a midwife or abortionist. This theory was born after the murder of Mary Kelly based on a testimony by Mrs Maxwell.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOne of the most famous popular suspects is the <mark> Duke of Clarence and Avondale (also known as Prince Albert Victor Christian Edward, or Eddy for short)</mark> and was Queen Victoria’s grandson.  Theories surrounding him differ but can all be nullified by the fact that he was at Balmoral during the murders of Elizabeth Stride and Catherine Eddowes. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image11-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Prince Albert Victor.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn 2017, a controversial new theory was put forth: that Jack the Ripper was actually H.H. Holmes, commonly referred to as ‘America’s First Serial Killer’. A series entitled American Ripper, shown on the History channel, explores the determination of Holmes’ great-great-grandson to prove his theory that the two killers were one and the same. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nGranted, there is no record to show that Holmes was in America during the Whitechapel murders, and there is proof he visited London at some point. He also fits the vague descriptions eye witness accounts gave at the time, he had extensive medical knowledge, and went on to kill somewhere between 20 and 200 people from 1891 to 1894, some murders may have been committed during his youth as well. Once again however, the evidence and claims are pure speculation.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image12-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Born Herman Webster Mudgett, also known as Dr. Henry Howard Holmes or H. H. Holmes.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn amongst all the far-fetched or tenuous theories, suspects without firm evidence against them, and quasi-scientific documentaries claiming they’ve finally found the killer, there is only one theory I have come across that puts forth reasonable claims with undeniably eery coincidences. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nCharles Cross was a carman who worked at the Broad Street Depot as a deliveryman and was found by the body of Polly Nichols after she had been killed. Christer Holmgren, a Swedish journalist, has studied the Jack the Ripper case for over 30 years and noticed what most of us had skimmed over. The documentary based on his theory explains the details and discrepancies that make it exceedingly difficult to dispute.   \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>The Victims</h3>\r\n<mark>Polly Nichols</mark> is usually considered the first victim, the woman before her being Martha Tabram who was found in George Yard Buildings with 39 stab wounds to her torso. Polly was found with her throat cut down to the spine and with a number of wounds to her lower abdomen in Buck’s Row. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark>Annie Chapman</mark> was found a little over a week later in a Hanbury Street back garden, also with her throat cut to the bone except the killer had now escalated his violence and mutilated her abdomen. Parts of her abdominal wall, navel, uterus, vagina, and bladder were missing from her body. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image13-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Newspaper detailing the events surrounding the murders.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<mark>Elizabeth Stride</mark> also had a near-severed head, along with <mark>Catherine Eddowes.</mark> Elizabeth, however, bore no further wounds and this is typically boiled down to the assumption the murderer was interrupted by the approaching footsteps of Louis Diemschutz.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis then explains Catherine’s murder committed 45 minutes later; her uterus and left kidney was not with the body. It is also with Catherine that we see facial wounds as well. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHowever, the most horrific and stomach-churning of the murders is that of <mark>Mary Jane Kelly.</mark> One almost condemns the use of crime scene photography in this case as it is inconceivable that someone would perform such brutality on another person. Another difference in Mary’s case is that she was killed and mutilated inside her own room as opposed to out on the street.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image14-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Mary Jane Kelly - Illustrated Police News\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nExactly why, though, nobody really knows but what we can assume is that the private room gave the Ripper more time to satisfy his bloodlust. She was unrecognisable by the time he had fled. Most of her organs had been removed and placed around her or next to her bed and large quantities of flesh were stripped off, exposing bone in the process. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis was truly the pinnacle of Jack the Ripper’s merciless reign and it had left its mark on the entirety of the district. What is perhaps most fascinating with his modus operandi is that he consistently strangled these women before cutting their throats and mutilating them which strongly suggests that he did not want to cause them pain. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nSuffocation is one of the most painless ways to die so it could be implied that the murderer felt some kind of sympathy towards the women and he was not completely sadistic. Alternatively, he knew that the blood would splatter if the women were still alive and they would be more likely to scream, leading to his capture.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image15-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n       Streets in White Chapel, where the murders took place.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nWhitechapel was not a desirable location for anyone. It is stereotyped as an over-crowded, impoverished, miserable place, covered by the soot and pollution from nearby coal factories and this stereotype is entirely true. Most inhabitants were poor, there were numerous pubs, sometimes two or more on one street which would feed the alcohol dependencies that many indulged. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHouses were small and it was not rare to have whole families of several members living in one room, perhaps taking in a lodger as they hadn’t enough money to live on.  Crime was rife, but rarely involved murder. Typically there was pickpocketing, assault, drunken offences and general petty crime so when murders began to happen with little space between, it really shook the population.  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWhen people noticed it was mainly prostitutes being targeted, this community began to honestly fear for their lives.\r\n\r\n<h3>Serial Killing in the 19th and 20th Centuries</h3>\r\n\r\nEven though Jack the Ripper eclipses most other serial killers, especially those during the same century, there were murderers that acted for a longer period of time or killed more people. At the beginning of the 19th century, Andreas Bichel killed two women between 1806 and 1808 after luring them to his fortune telling scam. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image16-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n      Picture of Andreas Bichel, The Bavarian Ripper.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHe attempted to kill three other women and has been dubbed the Mädchenschlächter, or ‘girl slaughterer’ and in the English speaking world, he is known as the Bavarian Ripper. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAcross the pond in Austin, Texas, the ‘Servant Girl Annihilator’ was guilty of 8 instances of murder and rape from 1884 until Christmas Eve 1885. He did not have the same victim profile that Jack the Ripper had; the three first women he killed were cooks and servants, the fourth was an 11 year old girl, then a heterosexual couple, and finally two women were murdered on Christmas Eve. Class and race seemed to have nothing to do with his attacks. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nThe murders only stopped when the police shot a man beating a woman in February 1886. The man died of his wound the next day. Curiously whilst Whitechapel residents speculated and feared Jack the Ripper, his Mexican counterpart was running amok from 1880-1908. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Mexican Ripper or El Chalequero, real name Francisco Guerrero Pérez, killed around 20 prostitutes through strangulation and mutilation and left them in the Consulado River. He was known for being a virulent misogynist with a particular hatred for prostitutes.  Strangely enough, during the very same months as Jack the Ripper, body parts were turning up in the River Thames and around East London.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image18.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     Picture of The Mexican Ripper, El Chalequero.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAt the time, the newspapers thought they were linked however it seems likely that the Thames Torso Murders, which took place between 1887-1889, were from other murderers. In these cases as well, whoever committed these murders was never found nor were there any clues or suspects.  In this sense, the dismemberment murders were even more of a mystery than the Jack the Ripper cases which the authorities and the media seemed to focus on. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShortly after the London murders, the French Ripper began his spree from 1894 to 1897. Joseph Vacher, after attempting to kill himself twice - one of which left him with a partially paralysed face and a dodgy eye - stabbed, mutilated and raped 11 victims (one woman, five teenage girls and five teenage boys) but blamed his murders on the claim he had been bitten by a rabid dog as a child. After confessing to his crimes, he was executed by guillotine on New Year’s Eve 1898.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image19-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     Picture of The French Ripper, Joseph Vacher.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe crimes of Jack the Ripper grotesquely manifested themselves in later murders throughout the following century, especially in Britain. During World War Two, Gordon Cummins decided to use the Blackout to his grim advantage. He joined the RAF and was participating in a training course in February 1942; he was in London for most of the month however his murderous rampage lasted a mere six days. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOver barely a week he killed four women and heartlessly mutilated three of them. There seemed to be a sexual emphasis to his murders and had he not left his gas mask or his belt at the scenes of attempted attacks, it is possible he would have gone on to kill more women.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHe was arrested on 16th February 1942 and was eventually executed in June that year. There have been two more Ripper-like serial killers in England since then: “Jack the Stripper” who was active 1964-65 and the Yorkshire Ripper who killed between 1975 and 1980. The former murdered six prostitutes who were found by the River Thames. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image20-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     Picture of Jack the Stripper.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAll were found stripped of clothing hence the unknown killer’s nickname and the fact that these murders are often referred to as the ‘Nude Murders’. The latter murderer is a man named Peter Sutcliffe, who killed 13 women. Media have the tendency to claim that prostitutes were the victims however out of all his victims, only six were sex workers, meaning he targeted women in general. He received 20 life sentences for his crimes and is currently serving time in HM Prison Frankland, Durham. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>The Sensation of Jack the Ripper</h3>\r\nThe modern murderers bring us to the modern age. Why exactly have we chosen to etch Jack the Ripper into our minds rather than any of the aforementioned murderers? It is in part to good timing and good publicity. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHe killed when transatlantic telegraphy was reliable and used frequently, meaning that the London news could be communicated across to North America as well as to Europe - something earlier criminals couldn’t do - and the local newspapers published letters allegedly from the killer himself. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nEarly on in the case he was given a name which is not only catchy but also adds drama and suspense, which the general public love. On top of this, the elusiveness he has succeeded in maintaining has only increased his infamy over the decades. With the years having turned into almost a century and a half, this relatively small serial killer case has become a worldwide murder mystery and regular people are attempting to achieve some kind of cold case fame through proving who Jack the Ripper was once and for all. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image21-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     Jack the Ripper (1987 video game).\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nWhether or not it will ever be possible to definitively say who the murderer was, we cannot say. Technological advancements, a sudden discovery of firm evidence, and maybe a time machine could help. There is something fundamentally unique about 19th century England, and especially Victorian London which has been so glorified it has become a fashion and craft movement in itself, known as steampunk. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBeing a chronological bridge between old and new in terms of technology and progress, the alluring magic of this romanticised era must have something to do with the popularity of Jack the Ripper and Victorian society in general.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image22-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     Jack the Ripper, Assasin\'s Creed Video Game.\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Assasin\'s Creed Video Game.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Language and Jack the Ripper</h3>	\r\nIt is the nature of human beings to crave answers and the massive question mark that is the identity of this murderer has led to decades of study on the part of armchair detectives. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBut if we are to continue discussing Jack the Ripper and the women he killed, it is worthwhile to look at the manner in which we speak about them and especially the language writers are choosing to use. The way in which we speak about the victims is of utmost importance. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nUsually they are only referred to as “prostitutes” or sometimes “women” which is admittedly a touch better, yet that is all we hear from them. If we do read about their lives in non-specialised publications, the writing makes it such that they led “a deeply impoverished existence in the slums”, for example.  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<div class=\"article-img-wrapper\" align=\"center\">\r\n        <img src=\"http://localhost:8888/apps_with_moorexa/hh/public/assets/images/jack-the-ripper-image23-web.jpg\" class=\"img\">\r\n        <div class=\"caption\">\r\n     The Canonical Five\r\n        <span>\r\n			Source: Wikimedia Commons.\r\n		</span>\r\n		</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis wording, whilst sounding good from a journalistic point of view, creates a particular setting in the reader’s mind and provides them with prejudices and assumptions that may not have been reality. It can cause the reader to forget about the individuals and prevent sympathising with them.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNewspaper and magazine articles and documentaries in recent times have overly dramatised the events of Autumn 1888 to the point of farcical theatricality, all for the sake of viewers and readers. It is through this exaggerated interpretation that the media have belittled the women he murdered, linguistically undermining them and reducing them to mere objects in the situation.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThey fade away into the shadow of their killer. Language shapes the way we view the world and subsequently our opinions on it. Immediately identifying these women as ‘prostitutes’ is not only historically inaccurate but it is damaging to their identities as women. It implies that this is what they did as a job regularly and perhaps we don’t realise that unlike some sex workers today, they were more or less forced into it. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe victims tried to make money through other means, such as selling their possessions, cleaning, crocheting, and selling sex was really a last resort to stop them from starving and living on the streets. Furthermore, sex workers are a consistently marginalised part of society and a slew of misinformed myths surround them and their work. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs Kate Lister succinctly phrases it, the word ‘prostitute’ has always been ‘linked to a state of dishonour’ thanks to its first definition and usage. There has also always been an air of violence and abuse surrounding sex workers which further adds to the perceived justification of the horrors they endured. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThis term ‘sex worker’ may seem like anachronistic political correctness however language needs to evolve as we reflect upon our society. The role of the historian is to look back on history as objectively as possible but how can we do that if we use words loaded with negative implications? \r\n', 'Jack the Ripper', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'jack-the-ripper-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(60, 'William Wilberforce (d.1833), abolitionist and social reformer, was born at Wilberforce House in 1759. As the Member of Parliament for Yorkshire, Wilberforce famously campaigned against the slave trade. \r\n<br />\r\n<br /><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nToday’s building, conveniently located next to the quayside and high street, was originally on the site of a merchant’s house built in c.1590 for the Lister family, exporters of lead. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nJohn Lister and his son, also John, both became Mayors of Hull and the latter was knighted. The family was prestigious enough to entertain Charles I, who stayed at the house in 1639. The current structure was built in 1656. From 1709, John Thornton, a merchant of lead and cloth, owned the house. The merchant’s apprentice, William Wilberforce, the grandfather to the abolitionist, married Thornton’s daughter, and the house passed onto the Wilberforce family in 1732. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMerchants of Hull tended to carry out their trade with the Baltic states and Europe, differing from Bristol and Liverpool who had a large stake in the slave trade.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>The abolitionist</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nWilberforce was educated at Cambridge, where he met the future Prime Minister William Pitt and entered political life. He was a talented orator and represented the abolitionist cause in Parliament, introducing Bills and campaigning for twenty years.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHis influence aided the passing of the Foreign Slave Trade Abolition Bill in 1807, which prohibited the slave trade in the British Empire. Slavery itself was, however, still able to continue. Wilberforce continued campaigning for the abolition of slavery until he retired from politics in 1825. He died on 29 July 1833, just three days after the act to emancipate all slaves in the British colonies passed through the House of Commons.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/wilberforce-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Wilberforce\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>William Wilberforce by the artist Anton Hickel. <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>The House as Museum</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nWilberforce House was opened as Britain\'s first slavery museum in 1906, after it was acquired by the local authority. It is Grade II listed and features permanent displays on the slave trade and its abolition, as well as exhibits relating to the social history of Hull and modern slavery. The front garden is home to a statue of Wilberforce, originally unveiled in 1884 and restored in 2011. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/wilberforce-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Wilberforce\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Wilberforce House with William Wilberforce’s statue outside. <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Visitor information:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nWilberforce House is situated on the High Street in Hull. Open Monday to Saturday, 10am-5pm; Sundays 1.30pm-4pm. Admission is free.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Find out more:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nJ. Oldfield, Chords of Freedom: Commemoration, Ritual and British Transatlantic Slavery (Manchester, 2007).\r\n<br><br>\r\nI. Rutherford, History of Wilberforce House (Hull)\r\nP. Chrystal, Hull in 50 Buildings (Stroud, 2017)', 'Wilberforce House', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'wilberforce-image1-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '53.7441893', '-0.3320974', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(61, 'The first passenger funicular railway in Britain was opened in the seaside town of Scarborough in 1875 by the Scarborough South Cliff Tramway Company, linking The Spa and seafront promenade to the South Cliff. It would be the first of five cliff railways for the popular resort. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDesigned by William Lucas and built by the Crossley Brothers of Manchester, the original system was powered by seawater pumped by two Crossley gas engines and operated by a brakeman in the top station; the system was later replaced by steam engines in 1879 and then electric in the 1940s. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/lift-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Scarborough\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>View of the cliff lift from below.<i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>The cultural origins of the cliff lift</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nSpa waters were discovered in the cliffs in the 1620s by Mrs Thomasin Farrer, a member of the gentry, who noticed the water stained the stones russet-brown. Scarborough soon became fashionable amongst the upper classes for the waters perceived curative effect. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy the end of the century Scarborough was a popular seaside resort: in 1700 a local businessman, Dicky Dickenson, opened the first ‘spaw’. Lodging houses and hotels were formed in Georgian times and a popular music hall and saloon were added in the Victorian period. There were, however, problems with accessibility for an increasing number of visitors due to the seafront being next to the cliffs. In the 1820s a bridge had been built to connect the resort to the town centre. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTowards the end of the century, technological improvements in railways meant that funiculars could be utilised to help visitors navigate the resort. 1400 passengers were carried on the first day of business on 6th July 1875, allowing them to avoid walking the steep 224 steps to the top, for just 1d. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nA visitor to the resort commented on its effectiveness at the end of a day by the seafront, “The anthem played by the band was the signal to go, and moving southward, much as we felt inclined to linger, reached the Cliff tramway, and were in the space of minute placed safely and without fatigue on the top of the cliff” (The Dundee Evening Telegraph - 24 June 1881). The success of the cliff railway influenced the construction of other funiculars across the country.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/lift-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Scarborough\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The roof of the tramway read ‘224 steps avoided for 1d’. Victorian view of the Children’s Corner on South Bay Beach, unknown artist. S<i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>The cliff lift in modern day</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe surrounding South Cliff Gardens, The Spa, and the cliff railway are all grade II listed. The Spa is now a conference and entertainment centre and the lift runs into the evenings when there are events on.  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Visitor information:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe cliff lift has varied open times, but is usually open between 10:00 and 17:00. \r\n<br>  <a href=\"https://www.discoveryorkshirecoast.com/Scarborough-Cliff-Lift-Spa/details/?dms=3&venue=1710874\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n<br>\r\nPrices single/return: Adult £1/£1.60; Child 60p/£1; under 5’s free.\r\n<br>\r\nAnother funicular, The Central Tramway, is also still in operation, connecting Foreshore Road and Marine Parade. For more details see here: <a href=\"http://www.centraltramway.co.uk/\">Click Here</a>\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h3>Find out more:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nD. Fowler, Scarborough Snippets (Online, 2013).\r\nStories from Scarborough, Creative Archive Blog by Sarah Coggrave: <a href=\"https://storiesfromscarborough.wordpress.com/tag/tram/\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe Friends of South Cliff Gardens community group website: \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.friendsofsouthcliffgardens.com/\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n \r\n', 'South Cliff Lift, Scarborough', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'lift-image1-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '54.2742996', '-0.3967651', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(62, 'The impressive remains of Ravenglass Roman bath house are the tallest and most substantial to be found in northern Britain. Built around 130 AD, the bath house served the nearby fort and civilian settlement (vicus) at Ravenglass.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe fort’s location at Ravenglass harbour gave the site strategic importance, as such it was used as an operating base for the British arm of the Classis Britannica (Roman navy). Its role as a naval base continued throughout the Roman occupation, despite numerous incidents involving local tribes which resulted in the fort being either attacked or burnt down.\r\n \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/ravenglass-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Ravenglass\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Ravenglass Bathhouse <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nNevertheless, the continued presence of the Roman military allowed a large vicus to develop north of the fort, which thus required the existence of a sizeable bath house to accommodate the burgeoning local population.\r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\nAs with all bath houses of the period, the baths at Ravenglass would have represented an important symbolic custom and daily ritual in the lives of the local area’s Romanised inhabitants. Interestingly, bath houses were of less importance in Roman Britain, however evidence suggests they were still an intrinsic part of life for those living within or nearby forts. \r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\nArchitecturally, Roman bath houses were some of Iron Age Britain’s most sophisticated buildings, with each bathhouse containing the requisite changing room (apodyterium), warm room (tepidarium), hot room (caldarium), cold room (frigidarium) and open exercise yard (palaestra). Excavations at Ravenglass indicate the presence of such rooms, with two rooms including under-floor hypocaust (heating systems) uncovered at the site.\r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\nThe site is in the care of English Heritage and is open every day – entrance is free. There is charged public car parking in the town of Ravenglass from which the bath house is conveniently signposted. The site does not have its own facilities, however there are numerous places to eat and relax in Ravenglass. For those wishing to extend their visit, the forts of Hardnott and Ambleside, which were once linked to Ravenglass by a Roman road, are nearby.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h3>Secondary sources</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br><br>\r\nCastlesfortsbattles.co.uk (n.d.) ‘Ravenglass Roman Fort’, online <a href=\"http://www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk/north_west/ravenglass_roman_fort.html\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nBirley, E. (1958) The Roman Fort in Ravenglass, Transactions of Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society, 58, online \r\n<br><br>\r\n<a href=\"https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-2055-1/dissemination/pdf/Article_Level_Pdf/tcwaas/002/1958/vol58/tcwaas_002_1958_vol58_0005.pdf\">Click Here</a>\r\n<br><br>\r\nEnglish Heritage (n.d) ‘Ravenglass Roman Bath House’, online <a href=\"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/ravenglass-roman-bath-house/#beforeyougo\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nHadrian’s Wall Country (n.d.) <br>\r\n‘Ravenglass Roman Bath House’, online <br> <a href=\"http://hadrianswallcountry.co.uk/visit/ravenglass-roman-bath-house\">Click Here</a>', 'Ravenglass Roman Bath House', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'ravenglass-image1-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '54.350720', '-3.404212', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL),
(63, 'Visitors to the village of Piercebridge will find not one, but two Roman sites to enjoy - a Roman bridge and a Roman fort. \r\nThe first bridge to be built at Piercebridge was constructed to cross the River Tees at the point where the Roman road, Dere Street met the river. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nBuilt during the 1st Century AD, the location became particularly popular with merchants who wished to benefit from the trade links offered by both the river and road. Around 150 AD the wooden bridge was destroyed by flooding, thus the Roman army built a new, predominantly stone bridge further downstream, the remains of which are what can be seen today. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/piercebridge-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Piercebridge\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Bridge <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nLater, during the 3rd century AD, a large fort was built to the south of the bridge to house auxiliary cavalry. Believed to be called Morbium by the Romans, the fort conformed to the traditional ‘playing card’ layout with a headquarters in the centre surrounded by the requisite barracks, workshops, granaries and hospital. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAll Roman forts were built to adhere to specifications outlined by specially trained surveyors and architects. Whilst no British forts can be attributed to any one surveyor or architect, unique evidence uncovered at Piercebridge has identified Attonius Quintianus as a military surveyor working in Britain’s northern territories at this time.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nFollowing the withdrawal of Rome’s forces during the 5th century AD, the fort and bridge were initially used by the local populace. However, the bridge later became disused following the river’s change of course, whilst the fort’s use subsequently dwindled and in later years the current village of Piercebridge developed directly above what remained.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/piercebridge-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Piercebridge\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Fort <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nWhilst much of the site is covered by the existing village, interesting remains are still visible, of note are the foundations of the vicus’ bathhouse and the fort’s drainage system. Furthermore, aspects of the fort’s defensive structures can be seen, such as the remains of the ‘V’ shaped ditch that circled the fort to ensure optimum use of the Roman javelin that was thrown from the walls during an attack. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nBoth the bridge (English Heritage) and fort (Darlington Borough Council) are open every day - entrance to each site is free. Free parking for both sites is available in the car park of the nearby George Hotel. Whilst neither site has its own refreshment facilities, Piercebridge has a selection of cafes and pubs, along with a village green perfect for picnics. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h3>Secondary sources</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br><br>\r\nBritain Express (n.d) ‘Piercebridge Roman Fort and Bridge’, online <a href=\"https://britainexpress.com/counties/durham/roman/piercebridge.htm\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n \r\n<br><br>\r\nCastlefortsbattles.co.uk (n.d.) ‘Piercebridge Roman Fort and the River Tees/Dere Street Roman Bridge’, online  <a href=\"http://www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk/north_east/piercebridge_roman_fort_roman_bridge.html\">Click Here</a>\r\n<br><br>\r\nEnglish Heritage (n.d.) ‘Piercebridge Roman Bridge’, online\r\n<a href=\"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/piercebridge-roman-bridge\">Click Here</a>\r\n\r\n', 'Piercebridge Roman Fort and Bridge', '2019-03-01 3:54 pm', 'piercebridge-image1-mobile.jpg', 'topics', '54.533620', '-1.671957', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, NULL, NULL);
