INSERT INTO `locations` (`locationid`, `articlesid`, `article_title`, `article_image`, `article_text`, `latitude`, `longitude`, `categoryid`, `actual_location`, `company_url`) VALUES
(1, 48, 'Big Ben', 'big-ben-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Rising majestically from the north end of the Palace of Westminster is the &#39;Clock Tower&#39; as it was originally called, this changed in 2012 when it was renamed &#39;Elizabeth Tower&#39; in recognition of Queen Elizabeth II&#39;s Diamond Jubilee. However, to millions of people around the world it will always be called &#39;Big Ben&#39;.\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\">\r\n\r\n<sub><q>A picture of Big Ben. <i>Source: James Cullen // Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n&#39;Big Ben&#39; is actually the name for the largest of the 5 bells contained within Elizabeth Tower, it weighs 13.7 tonnes and at one point was the largest bell in England standing over 2.2 metres tall and 2.7 metres wide.  It was cast at the Whitechapel Bell Foundry in East London on 10th April 1858.  The chimes you hear on the hour are believed to have been inspired by an aria (I Know that My Redeemer Liveth) in Handels &#39;Messiah&#39;. Try saying these words over the chimes.\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\">\r\n<sub><q>The Clock tower, standing 96 meters tall. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Clock Tower was completed on 31 May 1859, it stands 96 metres tall and contains 11 floors. 334 steps take you up to the belfry, however, under renovation plans a lift will be installed for visitors not quite fancying the climb.  Although currently closed for the renovation, tours are believed to be resuming in 2020 if everything goes to schedule. The tower was designed by the rather grand sounding Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin, an English architect who also designed the interior of the Palace of Westminster as well as churches in England, Ireland and as far away as Australia.  He died in 1852 and never seen his finished masterpiece.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\">\r\n<sub><q>Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\nEach clock face on the tower is 23ft (seven metres) in diameter and composed of around 312 sections of opal glass. An hour hand is 9.2ft (2.8m) in length; a minute hand is 14ft (4.3m).\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\">\r\n<sub><q>Big Ben Clock Face. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\nBy looking at Big Ben you can easily tell when parliament is in session.  Above the clockface is a light called the &#39;Ayrton Light&#39;, this is illuminated during the times parliament is in session.  At present it has been switched of due to renovation works.\r\nBig Ben is sure to remain a cultural British icon for many years to come.  It has however skirted with catastrophe.  During the Second World War a German bomb clipped the top of the tower during a raid doing minor structural damage but thankfully not enough to bring her down.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '51.5007292', '-0.1246254', 0, '', ''),
(2, 47, 'Sutton Hoo Royal Burial Mounds', 'sutton-hoo-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'The Anglo Saxon Royal Cemetery at Sutton Hoo is a unique 6th to 7th century burial ground of high status individuals. Around twenty earthen burial mounds make up the cemetery and, while they may seem unremarkable from the surface, archaeologists have discovered far more beneath the surface. These mounds were designed to be seen and to make a statement about the status of the individuals interred beneath them. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, many of the mounds were damaged as a result of being robbed during the Tudor period – something which is woefully common for visible burial mounds as they would often be looted in pursuit of ‘treasure’. Since then, however, numerous investigations have taken place surrounding the mounds. The first proper excavation was conducted in 1939 by self-taught archaeologist Basil Brown, commissioned and organised by the landowner, Edith Pretty. It was this first dig that uncovered the great ship burial of Mound One and made Sutton Hoo a centre of archaeological exploration ever since. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Helmet from the Sutton Hoo ship-burial, England. 7th century AD.<i>Source: British Museum // Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Burial Mounds</h3>\r\n\r\nThe most famous of the mounds is Mound One, where an immense 90ft ship burial was first unearthed in 1939. There are actually two ship burials at Sutton Hoo - the lesser known being under Mound Two. Unfortunately, this burial was disturbed by looters, but iron ship rivets reveal the presence of a small boat under the mound. This style of burial reflected contemporary practices in 7th century Sweden, showing a connection between Anglo Saxons in (what is now known as) East Anglia and cultures elsewhere in northern Europe. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe funerals would’ve been “performative” with lavish grave goods, ceremony and the construction of the immense mounds would have been made by hand. Not only was the burial packed with an abundance of rich grave goods, but the committal of an entire ship to the ground would have been an amazing spectacle. It would have cemented in their memory the royal status and significance of the individual buried. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q> Burial mound at Sutton Hoo, Suffolk, UK. This mound has been reconstructed to its supposed original height.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile we cannot be sure exactly who was buried, it is generally accepted that this is the likely resting place of Rædwald, ruler of the East Angles and the first king to rule as overlord over England as a whole. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAccording to Bede’s Historia Ecclesiastica, Rædwald was amongst the earliest Anglo Saxon rulers in England to be baptised and he is credited with playing a significant role in the establishment of Christianity within the ruling classes. His new faith, however, earned the disapproval of his household and queen, who tried to coax him back to his pagan Gods (Plunkett 2005). \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nRædwald maintained elements of his pagan lifestyle and allowed the East Angles to worship both the Christian and the traditional Anglo-Saxon religions if they desired, something the devout Bede criticised him for. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs a result of the immense wealth, status and religious associations of the individual under Mound One, it’s clear to see why Rædwald is such a strong candidate.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Artefacts in focus</h3> \r\n\r\nFortunately, not all the mounds were looted and this meant that, upon excavation, archaeologists uncovered a trove of rich grave goods in their original position. These grave goods (objects placed in a grave alongside a body) can be used to give us an insight into the wealth of the individual. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFor example, the grave is full of military equipment and valuable weapons, indicating their role as a warrior king within Anglo Saxon society. Similar equipment is found underneath Mound Seventeen, where a young warrior is poignantly buried alongside their horse and an abundance of weapons – their horse would have been sacrificed for the funeral which would have been a spectacular albeit grisly ritual display.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nChristian faith is also demonstrated in several of the items that accompanied the individual to the grave. These objects are amongst the main reasons that the grave is thought to belong to Rædwald. As religious beliefs can play such a huge part in people’s understanding of death and the afterlife, objects with religious motifs and associations are common finds, especially at times of religious transition such as Anglo Saxon period. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q> Burial chamber of the Sutton Hoo ship-burial, England. Reconstruction shown in the Sutton Hoo Exhibition Hall.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nFor example, ten nested silver bowls from the Eastern Empire were found alongside two Byzantium silver spoons with the names of the Apostles ‘Paul’ and ‘Saul’ engraved on them, in Greek. These are suggested to be possible baptismal gifts, buried as a symbol of Rædwald’s conversion to Christianity. There are also symbols of crosses on brooches, and a secret chamber hidden in the back of the gold Great Buckle that may have housed a Christian relic. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Great Buckle is an incredible example of master goldsmithing, with interwoven ribbon animal decoration and fine detailing. Perhaps the most exquisite artefacts found in the grave are a pair of fine filigree worked shoulder clasps, inlayed with garnets, millefiori designs, interlacing ribbon animal decoration and filigree surrounds. The motifs on the buckle are packed full of Anglo Saxon symbolism, cementing Rædwald’s cultural identity.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Sutton Hoo helmet is perhaps the most recognisable artefact from the grave. As well as its striking appearance and precious materials, it is laden with symbolism. It has been argued that the helmet makes reference to one-eyed Odin from Norse Mythology (Price and Mortimer 2014), due to imagery represented across northern Europe. If you look closely, you will notice a deliberate absence of gold foils over the left eye of the helmet and over the left eye of an animal head near the crow. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Sutton Hoo helmet reconstructed.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the low light of a feasting hall, this would result in the illumination of the right eye, and the casting of a shadow over the left – a powerful allusion to Odin and possibly declaring the wearer to be of the same status as the pagan god.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe placement of drinking horns (a common Anglo Saxon grave good) in the grave may have also served to create an image of the “worthy dead” (Pollington 2011: 21) as the possession and use of feasting equipment marked an individual’s place within society. The feasting equipment and lyre paint an image of a mead hall, full of music and celebration, with Rædwald as the gracious host. The funeral itself may have included some mead-fuelled celebration of the life of the deceased. Evidence of funerary feasting at the grave-side is common at Anglo Saxon burial sites (Lee 2007), and it may have been part of a transitionary ritual to aid passing into the afterlife.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>‘Ghosts’ in the sand</h3> \r\n\r\n\r\n\'Taphonomy’ is the study of the preservation, decay or changes to archaeological material after it has been deposited in the ground. A detailed, forensic approach to excavation and study of excavated material allows archaeologists to reconstruct the story of what has happened to organic material before, during and after burial. Soil conditions, burrowing animals, climate and even gnawing dogs can have a huge impact on survival of organic material.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAt Sutton Hoo, the acidic soil conditions meant that the great oak ship did not survive its 1400 years in the soil and the bones of Rædwald had long-since decayed. How, then, did archaeologists claim to ‘find’ the great ship burial and burials? \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Sand Bodies of Sutton Hoo.<i>Source: P.M.Sabin Moore Blog </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n‘Ghosts’ of the organic materials appeared as staining in the acidic yellow sand - archaeologists have to have a keen eye for changes in soil colour and texture, so they were able to spot these anomalies and excavate around them, creating ‘sand people’ (similar in appearance to some of the Pompeii casts) or identifying the structure of the ship. These were inhumation burials, but cremation burials were also uncovered at Sutton Hoo. Cremations are likely to have been the earliest at the site (Carver 1998) and are found under several mounds, as well as in the surrounding area. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs well as visible staining, decaying organic material can leave invisible traces of phosphates in the soil. In 1967, soil analysis from Mound One revealed a significant spike in the phosphate levels, indicating that there had once been a body in the grave but it had dissolved in the acidic environment.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Visiting Sutton Hoo</h3> \r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image7-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Sutton Hoo Exhibition Hall with Helmet sculpture. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMany of the artefacts from across the Sutton Hoo site can be seen in the British Museum, but replicas and original are also housed in the Sutton Hoo visitor centre. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDue to a development project currently being undertaken at the National Trust site, the visitor centre and cemetery reopen to the public from late spring to early summer of 2019. A viewing platform is also being constructed at the National Trust site, so visitors will be able to fully appreciate the significance of the burial ground \r\n\r\n(Learn more: www.nationaltrust.org.uk/sutton-hoo/projects/releasing-the-story-of-sutton-hoo). \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlan your visit, follow updates on the development or visit Sutton Hoo roadshow events through the National Trust website: https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/sutton-hoo\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '52.0893194', '1.3384194', 0, '', ''),
(3, 44, 'Bill Slim\'s Statue Whitehall', 'bill-slim-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Outside the Ministry of Defence buildings on Whitehall you will find a memorial dedicated to Field Marshal William Slim (Bill Slim). He stands alongside two other celebrated British commanders from the Second World War, Field Marshal Bernard Montgomery of El Alamein fame and Field Marshal Alan Brooke who was Prime Minister Winston Churchill’s foremost military advisor and part of the Combined Chiefs of Staff from 1942 onwards.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Bill-Slim-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Field Marshal William Joseph Bill Slim, 1st Viscount Statue, Whitehall, London.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nBill Slim was born on the 6th August 1891 in Bristol but spent his teenage years in Birmingham. Between the age of 19 and 23 he found employment teaching at a Primary School amongst other jobs but he also found the time to take his first tentative steps into the military by joining Birmingham Universities Officer Training Corps in 1912. Two years later and with the outbreak of the First World War he was commissioned as a 2nd Lieutenant in the Royal Warwickshire Regiment.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the First World War he was injured twice, initially in Gallipoli and then for a second time in Palestine. He came through the conflict and was awarded the Military Cross for his actions in Mesopotamia having also attained the temporary rank of Major in the 6th Gurkha Rifles.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn the interwar years Slims military career progressed and by 1939 at the start of the Second World War he had been promoted to Colonel and given command of the 10th Indian Infantry Brigade who saw action in the East African campaign against Germany\'s allies Italy. However, he was injured for the third time in January 1941 and missed the majority of this campaign.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bill-slim-image-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Field Marshal William, Viscount Slim, in Service Dress, 1967. <i>Source: Leonard Boden, National Army Museum Collection </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhilst recovering he served on the General Staff at GHQ in Delhi before in May 1941 he once again got promoted, this time to the acting rank of Major General and took charge of the 10th Indian Infantry Division who took part in the Anglo-Iraqi War, the Syrian-Lebanon Campaign and the Invasion of Persia. He was mentioned twice in dispatches in 1941 and received the Distinguished Service Order for his victory at Deir ez-Zor.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn May 1942 promotion once again beckoned and Slim became an acting Lt-General with command of the Burma Corps which he had actually been in charge of since March 1942. It is his time in charge of Burma Corps that has cemented his status as one of Britain\'s greatest military leaders.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAt the time Burma was being threatened by the might of the Imperial Japanese Army who had been steamrolling anything that stood in their way creating an air of invincibility and despite Slim wanting to fight the only logical action he could take was to order a fighting withdrawal to Manipur in India over 1600 km away that took 100 days to carry out and was the longest retreat ever carried out by a British Army.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHaving retreated to relative safety he was given command of 14th Army and charged with reshaping it in time to stop the Japanese march into India which had itself slowed down due to weather and supply line issues.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bill-slim-image-2.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>British 3-inch mortar detachments support the 19th Indian Division\'s advance along the Mawchi Road, east of Toungoo, Burma. The mortar proved the most effective weapon in jungle warfare. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis all came to a head in March 1944 with the battles of Imphal and Kohima where the 14th Army not only stood toe to toe against the Japanese but had given them their largest defeat up to this point in the war and ground them down causing unsupportable casualties, eventually forcing them to retreat in disarray in July. This provided the springboard for the eventual campaign to regain Burma which was launched in 1945.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Battle of Imphal-Kohima was voted as the ‘Greatest British Battle’ surpassing the likes of D-Day and Waterloo in a poll taken by the National Army Museum in 2013 due to the way it turned the tide of the war in the Far East.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBy the end of the war Bill Slim was promoted to General and was Commander of Allied Land Forces Southeast Asia. He returned to the UK as head of the Imperial Defence College. And in February 1947, he was appointed an aide-de-camp to King George VI. He retired from the army in May 1948, however was brought out of retirement in January 1949 and given the rank of Field Marshal with the position of Chief of the Imperial General Staff (CIGS), he relinquished this role in November 1952 and in December of the same year became the Governor-General of Australia. He returned to Britain in 1959.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOn the 14th December 1970, 1st Viscount Slim, KG, GCB, GCMG, GCVO, GBE, DSO, MC, KStJ passed away in London aged 79 years old, he was given a full military funeral at St Georges Chapel, Windsor.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bill-slim-image-3.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Field Marshal William Joseph Slim, 1st Viscount Slim, usually known as Bill Slim, was a British military commander and the 13th Governor-General of Australia. Slim saw active service in both the First and Second World Wars and was wounded in action three times. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe statue was unveiled on the 28th April 1993 by Queen Elizabeth II. It was sculpted by Ivor Robert-Jones, stands over 3 metres tall and is made of bronze atop portland stone.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn an interesting twist the sculptor actually served in World War Two under Field Marshal Slim in the Burma Campaign and he was also the creator of the world-famous Winston Churchill statue which stands in Parliament Square.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Further Reading</h3>\r\n\r\n\r\nBurma ’44 by James Holland and Slim, Master of War: Burma 1942-1945 by Robert Lyman\r\n', '51.503807', '-0.125847', 0, '', ''),
(43, 59, '29 Hanbury Street', 'hansberry-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'If you’re partial to a bit of vintage shopping or a proper curry, chances are you’ve wandered down Brick Lane, which means you’ve probably walked along Hanbury Street too as it connects Brick Lane with Commercial Street.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAnnie Chapman, the second victim of Jack the Ripper, was killed in the backyard of 29 Hanbury Street. She died aged 47 and was buried at Manor Park Cemetery; since her grave was buried over, a plaque now commemorates the approximate burial site.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Jack the Ripper portrayed wearing a deerstalker hat and long overcoat. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHer family life was far from idyllic. Her eldest daughter died age 12 from meningitis and her son was born disabled and put into a care home. She and her husband John both turned to drink to ease their woes. After mutually separating around 1885, John paid her 10 shillings a week to support her, she also sold her crochet work and flowers so she didn’t need to prostitute herself until her husband died around Christmas 1886.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe hallway of number 29 was treated as a public thoroughfare. It was not uncommon to see the front door wide open, even at night, and the back door never seemed to be locked. Anyone could go through to the yard as and when they pleased and people often kipped in the passage, landing, and stairs. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>29 Hanbury Street Passageway. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe house was split between tenants with the ground floor front room occupied by a cat’s meat vendor (to clarify, this was someone who sold meat to feed cats) and the first floor rooms rented by the Richardsons.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAn amateur detective took a tour of the Whitechapel murder sites and published his commentary in a series of instalments in The Sheffield Weekly Telegraph. His trip to Hanbury Street was published on the 10th November 1888 - about a month after Annie’s murder. The language used is powerful. The disparity between the East End and the rest of London is painfully clear as the author describes the pickpocket population:\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark>“They are the scum of the criminal class; they are the offspring of the foulest and most unbridled passions; they are the noxious fungi of the worst type of humanity.”</mark>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>September 1888 newspaper implicating a character they referred to as “Leather Apron” in the murder. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAccording to him, the area is filthy, squalid, full of prostitutes with beaten and bruised faces, and the majority of inhabitants are drunk. A large foreign community have flocked here too: predominantly Poles, Russians, and Germans. People don’t live here, he says, they “exist”. The street also reeked of fish due to the sheer amount of fried fish shops along the long road.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe evolution of Hanbury Street is undeniably impressive; you could even see it as a kind of redemption. The devastating poverty has been replaced by a rich and vibrant street art scene, with quirky shops and quality eateries. Despite the cultural renovation, the buildings remain much unchanged since the late 1800s. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image4.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Annie Chapman\'s plaque near her burial location in Manor Park Cemetery. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNumber 29 has been replaced by the iconic looming Truman Brewery, plonked down during the 1970s. Instead of beer and ale, the building now brews a lively gamut of events and markets. Don’t worry though, pints are still available at the surrounding bars.', '51.520362', '-0.072561', 0, '', ''),
(44, 59, 'Berner Street and Dutfield\'s Yard', 'dutfield-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Compared to most of the Jack the Ripper murder sites, Berner Street is amongst those that have changed the most. The original buildings were demolished and replaced with a primary school. Even the name of the street has been erased and instead we walk along Henriques Street. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nSimilarly to the majority of Whitechapel, this area was not affluent by any stretch of the imagination. Charles Booth’s Poverty Map shows Berner Street to be “Mixed. Some comfortable others poor” and “Poor. 18s to 21s a week for moderate family”. 18 shillings is worth about £73.84 in today’s money, and 21 shillings, or 1 guinea, is approximately £86.15 in terms of purchasing power.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nA short walk up from the Fairclough Street junction on the left hand side lay a small yard, accessed by a gate.  Nestled in between buildings either side, Dutfield’s Yard was home to businesses such as cart makers, cigarette makers, and tailors, the International Men’s Working Educational Club, and a smattering of other dwellings and cottages. It was also the final outing for Elizabeth Stride who was Jack the Ripper’s third victim on 30th September 1888.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMuch of what we know of Elizabeth’s life hails from official documents. Originally from Torslanda, Sweden, Elisabeth Gustafsdotter moved to Gothenburg in 1862 and was registered as a prostitute in March 1865. A month later she also gave birth to a stillborn daughter and from October and November she was treated at a hospital for venereal disease.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFor unknown reasons, she emigrated to London to work as a domestic servant, as alleged by Michael Kidney - her partner with whom Elizabeth had an on-and-off relationship from 1885.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAfter marrying Thomas Stride on 7th March 1869, the couple set up a coffee shop in Poplar which seemed to fair well until 1875 when it was bought by John Dale. By 1882 her marriage had fallen apart and she made a living predominantly through sewing and cleaning, with occasional sex work. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nEven though she cohabited with Michael Kidney, it was not rare for her to spend a few nights in the lodging houses, especially 32 Flower and Dean Street. Her lodgers described her as a quiet and kind woman, although she did often appear before the Thames Magistrate Court on account of drunk and disorderly behaviour. On the 26th September 1888, a group of women sat in the kitchen of no. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n32 talking about the Whitechapel murders, greatly worried they were at risk of becoming victims themselves. Dr Barnado later confirmed that Elizabeth was in fact one of the women he saw at this gathering. Three days later, at 1am on the 30th, her body was discovered by Louis Diemschutz on the north side of Dutfield’s Yard - now part of the school playground.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn life she had few friends or family so her funeral was very modest. Mr Hawkes, the undertaker at the East London Cemetery, paid for her funeral with funds from the church. Her grave is no. 15509 and can still be visited today.', '51.513780', '-0.065553', 0, '', ''),
(45, 59, 'Buck’s Row - Jack the Ripper’s First Murder', 'bucks-row-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Nestled between Whitechapel station, Whitechapel Sports Centre, and Swanlea School lies Durward Street. In 1888, however, it went by the name Buck’s Row and was the site of the first accepted Jack the Ripper murder. On the morning of 31st August 1888, Mary Ann Nichols, known as Polly, was found towards the middle of the street on the south side pavement, a few metres down from the old boarding school continues to stand tall today. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMarried to William Nichols in 1864, Polly was clearly unsettled in her domestic life. As stated in the London Daily News (3/9/1888), she separated from her husband “four or five times, if not six” according to William. The newspaper also reveals that she left her husband because he “‘turned nasty’ over another man”. This gives us the impression that Polly was obviously unhappy in her relationship. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bucks-row-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Bucks Row\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A grim discovery <i>Source: Wikimedia</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf she left William because of some kind of altercation, this suggests an intolerance on her part to aggressive and potentially abusive behaviour - traits that women admire and strive to embody today. In an age where women were expected to endure anything and everything in a marriage, Polly was able to leave her family and take care of herself. She left her husband for the final time in 1881, and by 1882 she had begun to support herself through sex work. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWilliam found out about her new means of income and consequently refused to continue paying her alimony.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBetween April 1882 and May 1888 she was mainly staying at Lambeth Workhouse, with short stints with family or other workhouses around East London. Having survived as an alcoholic for many years now, she tried hard to improve her life by taking up work as a domestic servant for the Cowdry family in Wandsworth. She wrote a caring letter to her father around May 1888 (quoted in the London Daily News 3/9/88):\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark><i>\"I just write to say you will be glad to know that I am settled in my new place, and going all right up to now. My people went out yesterday and have not returned, so I am left in charge. It is a grand place inside, with trees and gardens back and front. All has been newly done up. They are teetotalers and religious so I ought to get on. They are very nice people, and I have not too much to do. I hope you are all right and the boy has work. So good bye for the present.\"</i></mark>\r\n<br />\r\nfrom yours truly,\r\n<br />\r\nPolly\r\n<br />\r\n<i>\"Answer soon, please, and let me know how you are.\"</i>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bucks-row-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Bucks Row\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Mary Ann Nichols - Illustrated Police News, Sept 8, 1888. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs part of the inquest into her murder, her father expressed that he “was not aware that she had any enemies. She was always too good for that. Her only fault was being too good.”\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was buried in the City of London Cemetery where a memorial plaque now commemorates her.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bucks-row-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Bucks Row\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Mary Ann Nichols grave marker on Gardens way in the Memorial Gardens to the northeast of the Traditional Crematorium in the City of London Cemetery. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe evolution of this historical street does not just stop at a name change though. By the end of this year the Crossrail works should be complete and an impressive refurbished Whitechapel station will merge with its Victorian parent, with a bridge connecting it to Durward Street. According to the proposed plans, this bridge will intersect with where Polly’s body was found.', '51.520047', '-0.060378', 0, '', ''),
(46, 59, 'Castle Alley', 'old-castle-street-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'The autumn months of 1888 sent the East End into continuous terror; no one knew when Jack the Ripper would strike again. After the death of Mary Jane Kelly on the 9th November, the murders seemed to desist, but Whitechapel was still far from safe. On 17th July 1889, a body was found at 12:50am in Castle Alley. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNowadays, the site is on the west pavement where Pomell Way meets Old Castle Street. Alice McKenzie was around 40 years old when she was killed under a gas street lamp here. It rained shortly after she was abandoned. She had earned the nickname Clay Pipe due to her penchant for smoking and indeed, her clay pipe was found underneath her body.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPolicemen vigilantly patrolled through this alley on their beats and rarely left it unattended for more than five minutes, meaning whoever took Alice’s life knew the schedules of the police rounds. In typical Whitechapel murder fashion, there was no trace nor any clue as to who the killer was or where they had escaped to. A resident of the washhouse, the back of which faced the murder, said she heard nothing until the police whistle and someone knock on her door. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nAlice’s injuries were eerily similar to the victims of Jack the Ripper: her throat had been cut, her skirts crumpled up beneath her chin to reveal abdominal cuts. These wounds, however, were not as deep as the ones inflicted the year before. Given the climactic severity of the wounds found on Mary Kelly, this lighter touch with Alice seems highly dubious. Dr Bagster Phillips, who also attended the examinations of Mary Jane Kelly, Annie Chapman, and Elizabeth Stride, attested that the cause of death was blood loss not strangulation as in the previous cases, and also the injuries were unlike what he had seen before.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAt the inquest, the coroner revealed that if this wasn’t the work of Jack the Ripper, it was likely a copycat. This opinion is echoed in the East London Observer which also notes that Alice matched many criteria of the Ripper crimes, including living in a lodging house and being a prostitute. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAlice’s profession has not been confirmed however and her partner of six years, John McCormack as well as an acquaintance, Margaret Franklin, claimed that she was a washerwoman and charwoman in the Jewish community which was predominant in this area. She is described as industrious and hard-working.  Another testimony, from Elizabeth Ryder who lived at the same house in 54 Gun Street, said Alice was usually in bed by 10pm thus also discounting the assumption Alice was a prostitute.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe news of her death was international. Newspapers in North America, Jamaica’s Daily Gleaner, and Mexico’s El Foro reported on the crime, encouraging them to recall Jack the Ripper’s spree. The East London Observer even announced that the Théâtre du Château d’Eau at 50 rue de Malte in Paris would host a production based on the ominous perpetrator.\r\n', '51.515689', '-0.073482', 0, '', ''),
(47, 59, 'City of London Cemetery', 'maryann-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Until the mid 19th century, London churchyards and cemeteries were struggling with overcrowding, that is, until the City of London Cemetery opened its gates in 1856. With over 200 acres of land, this beautifully landscaped sanctuary homes the spirits of London’s mayors, artists, servicemen, and ordinary citizens. Anyone can be buried here regardless of religion or district.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPerhaps the most notable of burials here belong to Mary Ann Nichols and Catherine Eddowes: the  first and third victims of Jack the Ripper. Mary was buried on the 6th September in public grave 210752, which lies on the edge of the Memorial Garden; she is commemorated by a plaque as part of the cemetery’s heritage trail. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nJust over a month later on the 8th October, Catherine was buried in square 318 of public grave 49336. This spot has been transformed into a section of the Memorial Gardens used for cremated remains so Catherine now rests in front of Memorial Bed 1849, by Garden Way. Her grave is also marked with a plaque. Visitors regularly leave flowers and tokens on their grave markers.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nEdith Thompson, one of the last women to be hanged in the UK, is connected to the cemetery. She was married to Percy Thompson but began an affair with Frederick Bywaters. In 1922 Frederick stabbed Percy to death whilst he and his wife were on their way home from a show in Piccadilly Circus. Both Frederick and Edith were arrested for Percy’s murder. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThey had kept correspondence which revealed that Edith had previously attempted to kill her husband but failed. Following a controversial and difficult trial, Edith was later executed at Holloway Prison and Frederick at Pentonville Prison on the 9th January 1923. Percy Thompson was buried at the City of London Cemetery.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNot all the burials are such grim reminders, however. Throughout the grounds there lie exquisite memorials to an enormous gamut of figures, such as the Piano Lady grave dedicated to Gladys Spencer, a local music and dance teacher who passed in 1931, aged 34. Her grave features a Classical style female elegantly draped over the keys of a grand piano.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe grounds house Dame Anna Neagle, a British film and stage actress during the mid-20th century who rose to international celebrity due to her role as Queen Victoria in Victoria the Great (1937) and the sequel Sixty Glorious Years (1938). She went on to feature in Hollywood films too, most notably Spring in Park Lane (1948). \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was mostly known for playing strong women in her films and won a number of awards. She passed away in 1986 and was buried next to her husband in the cemetery; their grave was also unveiled by Princess Anne in March 2014.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere is also a stunning sculptural reproduction of Rubens’ Descent from the Cross to memorialise David Vigiland. Made from a 25 ton block of Carrara marble, the Vigiland memorial commemorates a seaman who died in Mombasa during the Second World War in 1946 and was reinterred in the City of London Cemetery in 1952.', '51.557947', '0.044521', 0, '', ''),
(48, 59, 'George Yard', 'george-yard-buildings-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Bank holidays have always been a cause for celebration and enjoyment; the 6th August 1888 was no exception. What may have started out as a pleasant day for most, ended in grief and shock for some. Crime was a constant concern in East London and around 1-2 murders a month were reported.  The news of the Bank Holiday murder spread like wildfire across London.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMartha Tabram was like many other women in the East End. Born in 1849, she drank heavily and tried to earn a living through selling trinkets and prostitution. She received most of her money through an allowance from her separated husband, Henry Tabram, whom she married when she was 20 years old. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe also bore him two sons in 1871 and 1872. It is alleged that she suffered from fits, precisely why we do not know, but her later partner, Henry Turner, knew that the fits were exacerbated by drinking. Henry Tabram gave her 12 shillings for three years before reducing it to half a crown (2s 6d). This harsh deduction was due to the fact that Martha was living with Henry Turner, who worked as a carpenter.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was living at Satchell’s Lodging House at 19 George Street in Spitalfields in August 1888 and was working on the streets that evening. She and a colleague had picked up clients and parted ways shortly before midnight. Martha went into George Yard, now Gunthorpe Street, and was found on the first floor landing of George Yard Buildings early the next morning. Alfred Crow was returning from work as a cab driver when he saw her body, but as he thought it was a homeless person, he continued up to bed.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBooth’s poverty map shows the Yard buildings to be ‘fairly comfortable’, however the other side of the street is black, meaning that these dwellings were the very poorest and housed criminals. The red building on the left hand side when facing north, just up the street from Canon Barnett Primary School, is the approximate site of Martha’s death.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe contemporary newspapers connected Martha’s murder to that of Emma Smith, who was viciously attacked by a gang in April, and later when Mary Ann Nichols was killed. They all came under the umbrella of the ‘Whitechapel Murders’ and some considered all three to be the doing of one individual. There is still debate as to whether Martha was a victim of Jack the Ripper as the majority of her wounds were to her stomach and groin, which became a “trademark” of the murderer. Furthermore, a large cut about 3x1 inches was incised into her abdomen. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was stabbed a total of 39 times with a small blade. As there were no signs of strangulation as would be typical of a Ripper victim, it was concluded that she died of blood loss. The first known victim, Mary Ann Nichols, was found in the same pose which further connects the two murders. Martha is often considered the first true victim of Jack the Ripper.\r\n', '51.557947', '-0.071643', 0, '', ''),
(49, 59, 'Miller\'s Court - Dorset Street', 'millers-court-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'There are only a few minute pockets of London that Charles Booth considered to be of the ‘lowest class’, ‘vicious’ and ‘semi-criminal’. Dorset Street and its narrow alleyways harboured this notorious reputation. Thick strokes of black coat the street on Booth’s poverty map from the late 19th century. The notebooks linked to this map describe Dorset Street as “the worst street in respect of - poverty, misery, vice - of the whole of London. A cesspool into which had sunk the foulest & most degraded.” \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nLodging houses, colloquially called doss houses, dominated the pavements and thus giving it the nickname ‘Dosset Street’. Miller’s Court was a small courtyard, accessed through an archway, featuring small rooms for rent. These were built by the lodging house landlord John Miller who owned numbers 30, 27, and 26, as he wanted to capitalise on the demand for cheap accommodation. The houses at 30 and 27 were later acquired by John McCarthy during the 1880s and 1890s.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe gentrification of the Spitalfields area in recent years has seen an end to the extreme poverty and horrific crimes and Dorset Street is no more. In 2015, the construction of the new Fruit and Wool Exchange began, consuming the space between Brushfield Street and White’s Row.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBorn around 1863 in Ireland, Mary Jane Kelly moved to London from Cardiff by 1884 and may have worked in a West End brothel. From there, it is possible she left with a client for France. The large English communities there had a high demand for prostitutes. The brothels were like traps; the women couldn’t go out without a chaperone, the money they earned was seldom enough, and leaving completely was scarcely an option. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMary returned to England quite quickly and ended up in Whitechapel. How and why she went there, along with much of her life, is unknown to us. From early 1888 Mary lived in Miller’s Court with Joseph Barnett, her partner with whom she had lived since 1887. In Summer 1888, Joseph lost his job and couldn’t support Mary anymore; she turned to prostitution and their relationship fell apart. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nJoseph continued to visit and send her money as often as possible. Her neighbour, Lizzie Albrook, recalled that “about the last thing she said was, <mark>‘Whatever you do, don’t you do wrong and turn out as I have.’</mark> ... She told me too she was heartily sick of the life she was leading, and wished she had money enough to go back to Ireland, where her people lived. I don’t believe she would have gone out as she did if she had not been obliged to do so in order to keep herself from starvation.” \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe macabre tourism we see today began soon after her murder by Jack the Ripper. McCarthy was offered £25 for a month’s use of the room by a showman and another expressed a desire to buy the bloodstained bed. Mary’s funeral, however, was an emotional affair with crowds throughout the streets. She is buried at St Patrick’s Cemetery in Leytonstone.\r\n', '51.518615', '-0.075037', 0, '', '');
