(50, 59, 'Mitre Square', 'mitre-square-header-image-mobile.jpg', 'Whilst the abhorrent event at Dutfield’s Yard transpired, Catherine Eddowes was released from custody in Bishopsgate police station. She was detained on account of drunkenness and, allegedly, pretending to be a fire engine on Aldgate High Street (although this may be a myth). At the inquest of her murder, those that knew her spoke of her character. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHer daughter, Annie Philips, was 23 years old at the time of the investigation. Her mother and father, Thomas Conway, separated 7-8 years prior due to Catherine’s drinking habits nevertheless she continued to ask her former partner for money on a regular basis. Despite the ending of their relationship, Catherine bore a crude tattoo on her left forearm of the initials ‘TC’. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAnnie admits her mother only knew she lived in Bermondsey and was not privy to the addresses of her sons - Annie’s brothers - who also lived in London. This was to deter Catherine from requesting financial aid from them as well.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIt is not a secret that Jack the Ripper famously murdered only prostitutes, however, her contemporaries attest to the contrary. When she moved to London, Catherine was in a relationship with John Kelly. They lived together at the lodging house owned by John Cooney at 55 Flower and Dean Street. Kelly was adamant that Catherine never “went out for immoral purposes”.  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe deputy of the house, Frederick Wilkinson, also confirms this and adds that she only seemed to be intimate with Kelly. Frederick knew Catherine and John for the duration of their seven year residence at the house, stating that they passed as man and wife. “I believe she got her living by hawking [pawning goods] about the streets and cleaning amongst the Jews in Whitechapel … She was a very jolly woman, always singing.”  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe died on the night known as the “double event” as she was killed approximately 45 minutes after Elizabeth Stride. On the morning of the 30th September, her body was found in Mitre Square, between the modern flower bed and the school’s rear gate. She was buried at the City of London cemetery, in the memorial garden where her remains are indicated by a memorial plaque.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOur modern steps share the ground with the original square as the Victorian stones may have been shuffled and relaid after a later recobbling. Originally the area was lined with warehouses and unoccupied houses. The square itself was once housed the cloister of Holy Trinity Priory, Aldgate before Henry VIII demolished it during the Dissolution of the Monasteries (1536-41). Mitre Street is roughly where the nave used to be.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWritten by John Francis Brewer in 1899, “The Curse upon Mitre Square A.D. 1530-1888” is a fictitious narrative tying the Tudor history with its contemporary events. It recounts the tale not of Jack the Ripper, but of a tempestuous monk whose spectral being haunts the Mitre grounds at night. It is at his hands that Catherine dies. The sensationalism of the time lives on through the scattering of details in these pages.', '51.513719', '-0.078026', 0, '', ''),
(51, 59, 'Swallow Gardens', 'swallow-gardens-header-image.jpg', 'Two years after the Jack the Ripper murders, Whitechapel had calmed down and returned to daily life. So did Frances Coles, she had lived in the East End for several years with her partner James Thomas Sadler until Friday 13th February 1891, when in the early hours on the morning, she lost her life near the Tower of London. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWe don’t know much about her life; by 1891 Frances became a prostitute, which she kept a secret from her family. Frances was close to her father and saw him on a weekly basis at church and her younger sister, Mary Ann, invited her for tea on the previous Boxing Day.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/frances-coles-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Frances Coles\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A portrait of Frances Coles. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere is a substantial amount of detail about the last two days of Frances’ life. On the 11th, she met Sadler in the Princess Alice pub in Whitechapel. He was 53 years old, a seaman and fireman on the SS Fez, and a former client of Frances. They spent the night together at Spitalfields Chambers, a lodging house at 8 White’s Row. The next day, from the early afternoon onwards, they decided to go on a pub crawl. By 7:30pm, Frances was drunk. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe went into a millinery shop to buy a black crepe hat for 2s 6d. Some hours later, Sadler was attacked and robbed in Thrawl Street whilst Frances stood by idly. Her lack of intervention led to an argument and the couple went their separate ways. Both ended up at their lodging house although neither could pay for the night, so they were forced to leave by 12:30am on the 13th.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/frances-coles-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Frances Coles\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>The Latest Mysterious murder of Whitechapel. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nAt 1:45am, Frances met with a colleague, Ellen Calana (also seen as Callana, Callanan, or Callagher) on Commercial Street. A man approached Ellen with a view to solicit her, however when she declined, he punched her and left her with a black eye. Undeterred, he solicited Frances who went with the man towards Minories, now Tower Gateway station. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was found with her throat cut and barely alive at 2:15am by PC Ernest Thompson in Swallow Gardens - a walkway beneath the railway arch between Chamber Street and Royal Mint Street. He heard a man’s footsteps walk off in the distance but due to legal procedure, he had to remain with Frances.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/frances-coles-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Frances Coles\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Railway Arch where she was murdered. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nA man named Duncan Campbell bought a knife from Sadler on Friday morning for 1 shilling. He noted that the handle was clammy and the blade stained, so he washed it, but noticed the water had reddened. Sadler was arrested for Frances’ murder the next day and was charged on the 24th February but was cleared a week later. He was able to prove he was not Frances’ killer nor was he Jack the Ripper, of which he was a suspect. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/frances-coles-image5.jpg\" alt=\"Frances Coles\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Approximate location of Swallow Gardens. <i>Source: Casebook </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nDr Phillips, by this point an expert in the Ripper murders and those thereafter, was convinced Frances was killed by another hand. However, there is still debate today over whether or not Sadler was the murderer, or whether Frances was a Ripper victim.\r\n', '51.510630', '-0.071441', 0, '', ''),
(52, 57, 'Hankey Place', 'hankeyplace.jpg', 'A peculiar site peppered around London are odd looking metal fences. To a casual passer-by the oddness would not be picked up on but have a closer look and you can see metal fences that have peculiar curves in their horizontal bars. \r\n\r\nThese are not a fancy design template ordered up en masse in post-war Britain but are in fact recycled WWII Air Raid Precautions Department (ARP) steel stretchers that have been recycled as street fencing. The unusual curves are the stretcher handles.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Arp Stretchers\"> <sub><q>Arp Stretchers converted into fences. <i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n60,000 of these stretchers were produced during WWII to cater for expected casualties from German bombing raids and come the end of the conflict they were very much surplus to requirements.\r\n  \r\nAt this point London was rebuilding and upcycling these stretchers was seen as a fantastic opportunity to replace metal railings that had (during the war) been collected to use towards the war effort.  \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Arp Stretchers\"> <sub><q>Stretchers in use <i>Source: wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSadly, the number of surviving metal stretcher fences is falling due to their upkeep and the effects of the weather on them over the years but a lot of examples still exist today.\r\n\r\nIf you find yourself in the following areas be sure to keep an eye out for the wartime stretcher fences.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Arp Stretchers\"> <sub><q>Stretcher fences at Down\'s estate. <i>Source: Wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />', '51.499726', '-0.088447', 0, '', ''),
