(101, 12, 'Suffragette Memorial - ChristChurch Gardens London', 'SuffragetteMemorial-ChristChurchGardensLondon.jpg', 'A picturesque scroll is located here at Christchurch gardens to commemorate the two largest organisations present in the fight for women\'s political freedoms: The Women\'s Social and Political Union, and the Women\'s Freedom League.', '51.4982036', '-0.1348329', 2, '', ''),
(102, 12, 'Statue of Millicent Fawcett', 'StatueofMillicentFawcett.jpg', 'Millicent Fawcett is nationally renowned as a prominent campaigner for the political rights of women in the first half of the Twentieth Century. This statue of Fawcett is the first statue of a female within Parliament Square. This statue is also significant for including the name and pictures of up to fifty-eight prominent Suffragettes, or Suffragette supporters. ', '51.5006009', '-0.1270455', 2, '', ''),
(103, 12, 'Monument to Emmeline Pankhurst', 'emmelinepankhurststatue2.jpg', 'Similarly, Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughter Christabel Pankhurst can be commemorated in Victoria Tower Gardens, where a statue of Emmeline was erected in 1930. ', '51.4979196', '-0.1253285', 2, '', ''),
(104, 12, 'George Lansbury Stone', 'GeorgeLansburyStone.jpg', 'As a vicious fighter for the rights of women, who merits recognition, George Lansbury\'s plaque is located here on 39 Bow Road. This is the former childhood home of the Labour politician Lansbury, whose unwavering support of the Women\'s Social and Political Union resulted in brief imprisonment. ', '51.5267492', '-0.0273469', 2, '', ''),
(105, 12, ' Caxton Hall', 'CaxtonHall.jpg', 'Caxton Hall was previously used by the Suffragettes as a base for the Women\'s Social and Political Union, the leading political group in the fight for women\'s rights. The WSPU has been linked to the organisation of hunger strikes, vandalism or arson. It is believed that Caxton Hall was used while the women members of the WSPU protested the male governing bodies of Westminster, notably through marches in Parliament Square.', '51.4985576', '-0.1349106', 0, '', ''),
(106, 12, 'Annie Besant Plaque', 'AnnieBesantPlaque.jpg', 'Formally a factory of female workers, this building has been renovated into living accommodation for the residents of London. One thing that is less known about this building, however, is that this factory had a unique heritage associated with the suffragette movement. A plaque for Annie Besant is situated here in memory of her unwavering determination in the fight for women\'s working rights. ', '51.5311017', '-0.0223754', 0, '', ''),
(107, 12, 'St George\'s Church', 'St.GeorgesChurch.jpg', 'Famous for sacrificing her life by throwing herself under the King\'s house on June 14, 1913, Emily Davidson was remembered and commemorated at St George\'s Church on Bloomsbury Way by thousands before her burial in Northumberland. ', '51.5175917', '-0.1245691', 0, '', ''),
(108, 12, 'Brompton Cemetery -Emmeline Pankhurst grave', 'BromptonCemetery-emmelinepankhurstgrave2.jpg', 'Emmeline Pankhurst was a leading individual in the Suffragette movement. Her grave is located within Brompton Cemetery, where she can be respectfully remembered and commemorated by members of the public.', '51.4839606', '-0.1891906', 0, '', ''),
(109, 12, 'Minnie Lansbury Memorial', 'MinnieLansburyMemorial.jpg', 'Minnie Lansbury, the first wife of Edgar Lansbury, died in 1922 while imprisoned for a dispute regarding tax in an area of poverty. Landsbury joined the Suffragette movement in 1915, and was elected alderman for a Labour Council in 1919. Her efforts and bravery are commemorated and remembered through a clock in her name located on Bow Road. Angela Lansbury, daughter of Edgar Lansbury, famously contributed a donation to ensure the restoration of the clock in 2008.', '51.5271379', '-0.0281776', 0, '', ''),
(110, 14, 'Museum Of London', 'museum-of-london.jpg', 'First established in 1976, the Museum of London is amongst the most popular of London’s museums as its collection covers the capitals history as far back as the prehistoric sight of the city, right up to the modern London we see today. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocated a stone through away from St Paul’s Cathedral and on the sight of the London Wall, the museum provides visitors with a fascinatingly extensive insight into the evolution of the capital through some of the best and worst periods in British History. The museum of London is a definite must-see for visitors wishing to obtain a more in-depth insight into London’s history, and is a perfect day out for families too. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-gecko.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Museum of London Exterior <i>Source: Francesco Camardo // Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<h4>Entry Fee: </h4>\r\nThis museum is free to enter. Any exhibitions and events however, may be subject to admission fees. \r\n\r\n<h4>Opening times:</h4>\r\nThe museum is open Monday-Sunday (10am-6pm) \r\n\r\n<h4>Photography allowed:</h4>\r\nYes, photography is allowed at this museum. However, flash is not allowed due to the age of some of the exhibits.\r\n\r\n<h4>Interactive technology:</h4>\r\nYes, this museum has interactive technology. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Roman_London.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>You could discover how Londinium came to life and what daily life was like for Romans in the city 2,000 years ago <i>Source: Museum of London</i></q></sub>\r\n<br>\r\n<h4>Facilities for kids:</h4>\r\nYes, this museum has a variety of different facilities available for children. For example, volunteer run ‘hands on history’ sessions are run by volunteers which give children the chance to interact hands-on with historical artefacts. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPlease see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/families/visit-museum-london\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Families </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Guides:</h4>\r\nA full floor plan and guide (in several languages) are available online to download. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/museum-london/plan-your-visit/floor-plan\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Floor Plan </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h3> \r\n\r\n<h4>1. Bucklersbury Mosaic (250 AD):</h4> \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Bucklersbury-Mosaic.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Large mosaic floor with semi-circular end, from Bucklersbury, 3rd century AD, Queen Victoria Street, Londinium, Roman London, Museum of London <i>Source: Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThis beautiful multi-coloured roman pavement was first discovered in Bucklersbury (in the City of London) in 1869. The mosaic has survived almost completely intact, and its few missing sections have been restored. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOriginally a heating system would have passed underneath this mosaic floor, consisting of a central channel radiating with smaller channels which hot air would pass through to go up inside the walls through the tiles. Don’t miss this incredible piece of ancient history in the Roman London gallery. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>2. Unic Taxi (1908):</h4> \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/unic-taxis-hidden-history.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>The Unic taxi was the first licenced petrol-driven taxi to arrive in London in 1903, with this specific vehicle being licensed for the use of taxi in 1908 <i>Source: Mike Peel // Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe Unic taxi was the first licenced petrol-driven taxi to arrive in London in 1903, with this specific vehicle being licensed for the use of taxi in 1908. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe early Edwardian period saw a technological revolution, with the mass development of motor vehicles bringing over 2,000 motor-cabs to the city which threatened the traditional modes of transportation such as horse-drawn hansoms and four wheeled growlers. See for yourselves the beautiful predecessor of the modern taxi in the ‘Modern London’ gallery.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>3. London 2012 Cauldron:</h4> \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/london_2012_cauldron_hidden_history.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Thomas Heatherwick’s London 2012 Cauldron is the star of this gallery. With dramatic footage and exclusive testimony, we recapture its journey from design to the climactic opening and closing ceremonies. <i>Source: Source: Museum of London</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nOn the night of the 27th July 2012, the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic cauldron (designed by Thomas Heatherwick) was revealed for the first time to the world. At the climax of the incredible opening ceremony, the cauldrons 204 stems dramatically rose up in the air to form a beautiful feature in the centre of the Olympic stadium in Stratford, which became a defining moment of the ceremony. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo this day, the 2012 Olympics remains an pivotal historical landmark in British history- So don’t miss this wonderful atmospheric installation with light, sound and video nestled in the centre of the ‘Modern London’ floor.\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Food and Drink facilities:</h4> \r\nYes, this museum has several food and drink facilities such as London Wall Bar and Kitchen, Benugo Entrance Hall Café and Benugo Sackler Hall Café. There is also a museum lunch space for families to bring their own food and drink. \r\n\r\n<h4>Tours:</h4> \r\nGuided tours and talks are available at this museum however, there is a fixed charge for the different tours. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/application/files/1614/7888/5118/Group_tours_201617.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Tours </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Nearest station/Tube:</h4> \r\nThe nearest stations to the Museum of London are Barbican station (5-minute walk) and St Paul’s station (5-minute walk) \r\n\r\n<h4>Bus routes:</h4> \r\nBuses 4, 8, 25, 56, 100, 172, 242, 521 all stop near the museum. \r\n\r\n<h4>Postcode/address:</h4> \r\nMuseum of London, 150 London Wall, London EC2Y 5HN\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-interior.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>How revolutions in technology, fashion, and culture have transformed London <i>Source: Museum of London</i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\nThere are a small number of disabled parking spaces for Blue and Orange Badge holders although spaces must be booked in advance. Please call 02078145552 to book, or email: \r\n\r\n<a href = \"mailto: access@museumoflondon.org.uk\"> acesss@museumoflondon.org.uk</a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> \r\nAssistance dogs are welcome to museum and portable induction loops are available at the front desk. Some of the theatres are fitted with induction loop systems, and there is a selection of subtitled and BSL interpreted videos in the galleries. \r\n<br /> \r\nFree monthly BSL and captioned tours are also available each month. \r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h4> \r\nMagnifying glasses are available from the information desks, as well as large print guides for the permanent and major exhibitions. Free monthly gallery tours for visitors with visual impairments are also available. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4>\r\nWheelchairs and mobility scooters are available to borrow during your visit, please book them in advance from the above number. Folding seats are also available to borrow at any time. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nLifts and escalators are available from street level near the London Wall roundabout, as well as a lift and staircase at noble street. Fully accessible toilets and lifts are available on all floors of the museum. \r\n\r\n', '51.517809', '-0.096676', 4, 'Loading from Locations', ''),
(121, 3, 'Windrush Square in London', 'Windrush-Square-Brixton-9.jpg', 'Windrush Square in the Brixton district of London was named after the ship Empire Windrush, which brought the first big group of postwar Caribbean immigrants to Britain in 1948.', '51.4604743', '-0.1173547', 0, '', ''),
(122, 3, 'Labour Exchange, Coldharbour Lane', 'DcMlFq-W0AUmAFx.jpg', 'The Labour Exchange (Job Centre) on Coldharbour Lane was a key location for the West Indian migrants travelling to Britain during the Windrush.', '51.4666105', '-0.104282', 0, '', ''),
(123, 13, 'Saint Paul’s Cathedral', 'new.jpg', 'Beneath the grounds of a Church of England parish church known as St Paul’s most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year. The church is in Shadwell, East London, and is not to be confused with St Paul’s Cathedral in the city centre (another plague burial site).Defoe describes the pit to have been one of five other plague pits for the parish of Stepney: There were no less than five other grounds made use of for the parish of Stepney at that time: one where now stands the parish church of St Paul, Shadwell, and the other where now stands the parish church of St John’s at Wapping, both which had not the names of parishes at that time, but were belonging to Stepney parish.”Few specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: They dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. A terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.', '51.509536', '-0.052122', 0, '', ''),
(124, 13, 'Tothill Street (formerly Tuttle Fields)', 'vlcsnap-2018-01-25-19h25m55s493-2.jpg', 'Beneath the ground of a busy side street known as Tuthill Street most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 17th century diarist Samuel Pepys in his well-known journal. The street leads to Westminster Cathedral and was formerly the site of Tuttle Fields. These lay south of St. James’s Park and west of the River Thames, close to Christchurch Gardens where another plague pit has been rumoured to sit\r\nPepys describes the pit to have been used to accommodate bodies that cannot afford to be buried in the newly-charging “New-Chapel”: I was much troubled this day to hear at Westminster how the officers do bury the dead in the open Tuttle-Fields, pretending want of room elsewhere; whereas the New-Chapel church-yard was walled in at the public charge in the last plague-time merely for want of room, and now none but such as are able to pay dear for it can be buried there.\r\nFew specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but contemporary writer Daniel Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits in his semi-factual novel The Journal of the Plague Year in 1722, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: “they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. A terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.”', '51.499720', '-0.131099', 0, '', ''),
(125, 13, 'New Street (Previously Hand Alley) London', 'image-5.jpg', 'Beneath the ground of a busy side street known as New Street most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year. The street branches of the main road of Bishopsgate Street and was formerly known as Hand Alley.\r\nThe street branches of the main road of Bishopsgate Street and was formerly known as Hand Alley. Defoe describes the pit to have mainly been for the plague dead of the parish of Bishopsgate but was obviously large enough to take some neighbouring surplus: “The upper end of Hand Alley, in Bishopsgate Street, which was then a green field, and was taken in particularly for Bishopsgate parish, though many of the carts out of the city brought their dead thither also, particularly out of the parish of St All-hallows on the Wall.”\r\nFew specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. A terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.\r\nDefoe also interestingly describes an incident in the years following the plague epidemic of 1665-6 in which the pit was accidentally excavated: “The houses in the same row with that house northward are built on the very same ground where the poor people were buried, and the bodies, on opening the ground for the foundations, were dug up, some of them remaining so plain to be seen that the women\'s skulls were distinguished by their long hair, and of others the flesh was not quite perished; so that the people began to exclaim loudly against it, and some suggested that it might endanger a return of the contagion; after which the bones and bodies, as fast as they came at them, were carried to another part of the same ground and thrown all together into a deep pit”.', '51.517216', '-0.079528', 0, '', ''),
(126, 13, 'Mount Mills, London', 'kk.jpg', 'Beneath the ground of an open area of wasteland known as Mount Mills most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year. The area lies near the intersection of Gosworth Road and Percival Street, and is now used as a carpark.  Defoe describes the pit to be a large overspill pit from neighbouring parishes: “A piece of ground beyond Goswell Street, near Mount Mill, being some of the remains of the old lines or fortifications of the city, where abundance were buried promiscuously from the parishes of Aldersgate, Clerkenwell, and even out of the city. This ground, as I take it, was since made a physic garden, and after that has been built upon.” \r\n\r\nNo specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: “they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. A terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.”\r\n\r\n', '51.526092', '-0.099504', 0, '', '');
