(140, 20, 'The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice', 'watts-memorial-app.jpg', 'Sitting against an adjoining wall in Postman’s Park – aptly named as it was once the site of the headquarters of the General Post Office where the postmen used to go during their breaks – this little-known monument remembers the lives of 62 people who died selflessly trying to save another. \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThis memorial to everyday heroism and self-sacrifice was proposed by the painter and sculptor, George Frederic Watts, in a letter to the editor of The Times in 1887 as part of the celebrations of Queen Victoria’s Golden Jubilee. He, like many wealthy people in the late Victorian period, believed in the need for social reform for the poor in England, and in turn saw a need to actively remember the heroism of ‘ordinary’ people. In his letter he wrote:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark> “The character of a nation as a people of great deeds is one, it appears to me, that should never be lost sight of. It must surely be a matter of regret when names worthy to be remembered and stories stimulating and instructive are allowed to be forgotten… It is not too much to say that the history of Her Majesty’s reign would gain a lustre were the nation to erect a monument, say, here in London, to record the names of these likely to be forgotten heroes”. <small> George Frederic Watts</small>\r\n</mark>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/George_Frederic_Watts\'s_Memorial_to_Heroic_Self_Sacrifice.jpg\" alt=\"The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nDespite this initial suggestion for the memorial, it wasn’t officially opened until 30 July 1900. In 1898, Watts was invited by the vicar of St Botolph’s church – the space being their former churchyard – to create the monument in the now public park. So, in 1899 the construction began of the 50ft long 9ft high shelter by J. Simpson and Son for the tablets at the cost of £402. Benches were also installed to encourage the public to stay a little longer. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSpace was made available for 120 tablets (in rows of 24), though only 54 tablets have been installed so far. Each tablet is made up of small tiles and records the name(s) of the deceased with the details and date of the events making them worthy of remembrance. Only 4 of these plaques were installed when the monument was opened. The remainder of the first row included 9 installed in 1902, and 11 more along with T. H. Wren’s memorial to Watts in 1905 following his death the year before. All 24 of these tablets were designed by the ceramicist William De Morgan. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Postman\'s_Park_Wall_of_Heroes.jpg\" alt=\"The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nA further 29 tablets were designed by Royal Doulton, 24 of which were installed altogether in 1908 filling a second row. Another 5 Doulton-style tablets were added on the next row from 1919-1930, which included replacement of a De Morgan tablet with incorrect information. A further tablet in the original De Morgan style created by Fred Passenger was slotted into the old spot for the incorrect tablet in 1931. Finally, the 54th tablet was added much later in 2009, commemorating Leigh Pitt who died saving a boy from drowning in 2007.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOne of the people featured in the memorial is Alice Ayres, who died in 1885 while trying to save three children under her care from an upper-story of a burning house. Two of the three children survived, and Alice died in the process of trying to save herself as she fell awkwardly after jumping out the window. She was one of the most famous additions to the memorial and had already been commemorated in other ways across the country around the time of her death – this included in memorials, artwork and a street was renamed after her near to where she died on Union Street in 1936. Her name was also used as an alias in the play (and 2004 film) Closer.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/alice-ayres.jpg\" alt=\"The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Alice Ayres (pictured above) was an English nursemaid honoured for her bravery in rescuing the children in her care from a house fire. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nIf you find you want to get to know them better, we absolutely recommend you that you read  <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Heroes-Postmans-Park-Self-Sacrifice-2015-09-01/dp/B01FKUO11S/\" target=\"_blank\">Dr John Price’s Heroes of Postman’s Park: Heroic Self-Sacrifice in Victorian London,</a> where he delves into the lives of each person remembered in the memorial. You can hear him in an interview about his research here. You can also follow the Friends of Watts Memorial on Twitter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/wattsmemorial\" target=\"_blank\">@WattsMemorial </a> to see upcoming events and to find out how you can support them.\r\n', '51.516742', '-0.097334', 0, '', ''),
(141, 22, 'Dennis Severs’ House', 'Dennis-Severs-House.jpg', 'For hundreds of years, Spitalfields has welcomed different waves of refugees. One of the first mass groups to settle there were Huguenot weavers who migrated to England following religious persecution spurred on by the revocation of the Edict of Nantes in 1685 by King Louis XIV. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis revocation made practicing Protestantism in France illegal and led to tirades of violence against those following the religion. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Louis-XIV-of-France.jpg\" alt=\"Dennis Severs\' House\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The devoutly Catholic Louis XIV believed his faith should be the sole religion of his country. He revoked the Edict of Nantes in 1685 through his issuance of the Edict of Fontainebleau, and ordered the destruction of Protestant churches, the closure of Protestant schools, and the forced baptism of children into the Catholic faith. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThey came to London as it offered business and employment opportunities. Using the skills of their craft they had learnt in France, many of them entered into the silk weaving industry.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOthers however, set up businesses in different areas of London such as Soho, working as goldsmiths, silversmiths, instrument makers, sculptors and gunmakers. <mark>Spitalfields became the centre of the silk industry.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hugenots-massarcre.jpg\" alt=\"Dennis Severs\' House\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The St. Bartholomew\'s Day massacre of 1572 was a targeted group of assassinations and violence, directed against the Huguenots (French Protestants) during the French Wars of Religion. Modern estimates for the number of dead across France vary widely, from 5,000 to 30,000. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h1>Dennis Severs\' House</h1>\r\nOne of the properties connected to these Huguenot refugees in Spitalfields is Dennis Severs’ House. Dennis Severs, an artist from California, purchased the property in 1979. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBetween this time and his death in 1999, he furnished the space to recreate the ‘living image of the eighteenth-century house’, complete with an imaginary family, the Jervis family, to occupy the house. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/dennis-sever-house-outside.jpg\" alt=\"Dennis Severs\' House\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Dennis Severs\' House in Folgate Street, London is a \"still-life drama\" created by the previous owner Dennis Severs as a \"historical imagination\" of what life would have been like inside for a family of Huguenot silk weavers. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nEach room tells a chapter of the Jervis families story from 1724 to 1914.  The house is therefore not a museum exactly, but acts more as a piece of living history and performance art with the story of a Huguenot family at its centre. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nYou can book onto tours of the house <a href=\"https://www.dennissevershouse.co.uk/the-tour/\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a> to learn more about his life and work in the house, give Severs’ excellent memoir, 18 Folgate Street: The Life of a House in Spitalfields, a read. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Dennis-Severs-House-full.jpg\" alt=\"Dennis Severs\' House\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nWhile you’re stood in front of the house, look up. You will see a wooden spool suspended from the wall. This was installed in 1985 by the residents of Spitalfields on the former houses of Huguenot weavers to celebrate the tercentenary of Revocation of the Edict of Nantes. As you wander around Spitalfields make sure to keep an eye out for more of these spools.\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nIf you want to get more acquainted with this historic community, you can find information about some great events and tours led by the Huguenots of Spitalfields <a href=\"http://www.huguenotsofspitalfields.org/\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a> They have also compiled a <a href=\" http://www.huguenotsofspitalfields.org/about-the-huguenots/huguenot-families.html\" target=\"_blank\">list of the names and address</a> of Huguenot weavers in London.\r\n', '51.520959', '-0.077685', 0, '', ''),
(142, 23, 'Duke of Wellington\'s Mounting Steps', 'Duke-of-Wellingtons-mouting-steps2.jpg', 'As you stand on Waterloo Place and marvel at the amazing architecture of the buildings and the fantastic statues and sculptures around you lower your gaze to the pavement in front of The Athenaeum Club and take a look at the two unassuming slabs of stone.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese are the Duke of Wellington mounting steps.  Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington was famous not only as the man who led the British and Prussians to victory against Napoleon in the Battle of Waterloo in 1815 but he was also British Prime Minister from 1828 to 1830 and again for a short time in 1834.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/The_Duke_of_Wellington..jpg\" alt=\"The Duke of Wellington Mounting Step\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Duke of Wellington is standing at half-length, wearing Field Marshal’s uniform, with the Garter star and sash, the badge of the Golden Fleece, and a special badge ordered by the Prince Regent to be worn from 1815 by Knights Grand Cross of the Military Division of the Order of the Bath who were also Knights Companion of the Order of the Garter.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub> \r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1830 he was in his early 60\'s and climbing on and of his horse wasn\'t as easy as it once was so he requested that a set of mounting steps be erected outside The Athenaeum Club where he was a member to ease his mounting and dismounting, the stones have a plaque attached to them which reads, \'This horseblock was erected by desire of the Duke Of Wellington 1830.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/duke_of_wellington_mounting_steps_hidden_history.jpg\" alt=\"Duke of Wellington Mounting Step\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>The Duke of Wellington’s horse mount on Waterloo Place. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIf you look directly across the road you will see another set of mounting steps in front of what was The United Services Club of which Wellington was also a member.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMounting steps were a common feature up until the late 18th Century whereupon better roads were being built along with carriages to transport people so mounting steps began to fall out of popularity but as you can see in Waterloo Place some are preserved in situ as a lovely reminder of times past.\r\n', '51.506824', '-0.132469', 0, '', ''),
(143, 21, 'Bomber Command Memorial', 'London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg', 'Sequestered away on the western side of London’s picturesque Green Park stands a monument devoted to the commemoration of Britain’s most controversial Second World War heroes: the members of RAF Bomber Command. \r\n<br></br>\r\nVisitors to the park may be surprised to discover an impressive, classic portico style marble structure waiting for them. Inside the building stands a poignant sight as seven 9ft tall bronze men form the centre piece of the monument. The memorial has been designed to be more than just another pretty London shrine; it’s primary purpose is to ensure there is a permanent tribute to the 55,573 Bomber Command servicemen who died in the defence of both the city and Britain. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Bomber_Command_Memorial_-_panoramio.jpg\" alt=\"Bomber Command Memorial\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Members of RAF Bomber Command. <i>Source: Available on Flickr / Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe monument holds several interesting features – the first being the buildings open nature, ensuring the men are exposed to the sky, allowing light to cascade down and illuminate them. This clever blend of architecture and symbolism becomes even more powerful at night if visitors look up and spot the phrase “per ardua ad astra”. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe Latin motto used by the RAF during the war translates as: “through adversity to the stars”. Another feature is the structure’s ceiling, constructed using salvaged sections of a Handley Page Halifax III aircraft used by Bomber Command. The plane in question was shot down over Belgium during an operation that cost the lives of eight crewmen on the 28th of May 1944. Its incorporation into the memorial adds a poignant connection to the past.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/2013-05-12_London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg\" alt=\"Bomber Command Memorial\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Exterior of the Memorial in 2013. <i>Source: Tim Rademacher / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Controversies</h2><br>\r\nCommemoration of RAF Bomber Command remains a controversial topic thanks to the operations they were charged to undertake during the closing phases of the war. Some historians have questioned whether the bombing of civilian targets such as Dresden were the only way to speed up Allied victory. While Winston Churchill boldly proclaimed that Britain’s bombers would provide the means of victory in 1940 – a quote that can be found on the inside western wall of the memorial – they have ultimately been minimalised and airbrushed out of British memory due to the murky nature of their mission.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Fotothek_df_ps_0000010_Blick_vom_Rathausturm.jpg\" alt=\"Bombing Dresdan\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Dresden, 1945, view from the city hall (Rathaus) over the destroyed city. <i>Source: Deutsche Fotothek / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIt is perhaps for this reason that along the monuments northern side is an engraving that alludes to this difficult subject; “this memorial also commemorates those of all nations who lost their lives in the bombings of 1939-1945.” It is no accident that that the seven bronze men have been immortalised in sombre contemplation, as each of the seven men walk away from their mission it seems they are reflecting on the impossibly difficult act they have undertaken in the name of peace - humanising them once again. It seems that the monument has been created in part to rehabilitate Britain’s forgotten heroes, as well as being mindful of the civilians killed by their actions.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/this memorial.jpg\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Memorial. <i>Source: Tim Rademacher / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nOpened in 2012 by Her Majesty the Queen, it had taken sixty-six years for the 125,000 men of Bomber Command to receive the acknowledgment. The members of RAF Bomber Command played a pivotal role in the defence of London; they now stand watch again over the Capitol.\r\n', '51.503389', '-0.148922', 2, 'LFL', '');
