(1, 'Downing Street', 'downing street,downingstreet,british prime minister,home of the british prime minister home,uk prime minister,uk prime minister home,history of downing street,downing street history,hidden history of downing street,10 downing street,hidden history', 'Downing Street today is seen as the powerhouse of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland. It is where the Prime Minister'),
(2, 'Windrush Generation', 'windrush generation,windrush,windrush boat,windrush postwar immigration,Empire Windrush passenger ship,windrush facts,windrush arrival,SS Empire windrush,windrush generation history,history of windrush generation,common wealth citizens history,hidden history of windrush generation,', 'The windrush generation. Following a 22-day journey from Jamaica, on June 22nd 1948, the SS Empire Windrush arrived in Britain, docking just outside of London in Tilbury, Essex. This was after the British Nationality Act declared that all Commonwealth citizens (inhabitants of former British colonies), had the right to freely to enter and settle in Britain.'),
(3, 'Sir Nigel Gresley Statue', 'Sir Nigel Gresley,Sir Nigel Gresley statue,Nigel Gresley,Nigel Gresley statue,Sir Nigel,Sir Nigel statue,Sir Nigel gresley train,Nigel,LNER,flying scotman,Flying Scotsman and Mallard steam engines history,mallard train history, mallard steam engines,flying scotman train', 'Sir Nigel Gresley designed the iconic Flying Scotsman and Mallard steam engines while working for the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) from 1923 -1941. One of the ‘Big Four’ companies that operated British railways from 1923 to their nationalization in 1948, the headquarters of the LNER'),
(4, 'Roman wall at Cooper\'s Row', 'Roman wall, Cooper\'s row, roman wall at cooper\'s row,cooper\'s row roman wall,', 'Originally built as a defensive structure, the city wall was constructed by the Romans to protect the strategically important town of Londinium from the Picts. Unbeknownst to many, a substantial portion of the wall remains within the courtyard of The Grange City Hotel on Cooper’s Row.'),
(5, 'Roman wall at Cooper\'s Row', 'Roman wall,cooper\'s row,roman wall at cooper\'s row,roman wall hisroy,cooper\'s row history,cooper\'s row roman wall,roman wall at cooper\'s row history,london wall', 'Originally built as a defensive structure, the city wall was constructed by the Romans to protect the strategically important town of Londinium from the Picts. Much of the wall was dismantled during the 1700s, however, hardy sections can still be glimpsed, standing proudly as bastions of London’s ancient past. Unbeknownst to many, a substantial portion of the wall remains within the courtyard of The Grange City Hotel on Cooper’s Row.'),
(6, 'Roman wall at Cooper\'s Row', 'roman wall,cooper\'s row', ''),
(7, ' The Women’s Suffrage Movement', 'Suffrage,women\'s suffrage,women\'s suffrage movement,suffragettes,suffrage history,women\'s suffrage history,women\'s suffrage movement history,history of suffrage,women’s suffrage campaign,history of women\'s suffrage,Mary smith,suffragists,John Stuart Mill,National Society for Women\'s Suffrage (NSWS),Emmeline Pankhurst,National Union of Women\'s Suffrage Societies', ''),
(8, 'Bomber Command Memorial', 'Bomber command memorial,RAF bomber command,second world war heroes,britain\'s second world war heroes,heroes of the second world war,history of bomber command me memorial,', 'Sequestered away on the western side of London’s picturesque Green Park stands a monument devoted to the commemoration of Britain’s most controversial Second World War heroes: the members of RAF Bomber Command.'),
(9, 'Plague Pits', 'plaque,plague pits,the plague,black death,the black death,bubonic plague,black plague,plague meaning,history of plague pits,history of the plague,history of plague', 'The disease we today term “the plague” is caused by the Yersinia pestis bacteria and has three identified strains: bubonic plague (affecting the lymphatic system), pneumonic plague (affecting the lungs), and septicaemic plague (affecting the blood).'),
(10, 'Parliament Hill', 'parliament hill, parliament,history of parliament hill,hampstead heath,parkland, history of parkland', 'In an area of open parkland in the south-east corner of Hampstead Heath in north-west London ...when standing at the viewpoint of Parliament Hill there is this sudden shift of being miles away from the big city. '),
(11, 'Hidden Little Compton Street', 'compton street,history of compton street,compton,location of compton street,little compton street,location of compton sign,compton street sign,sign of compton street,Old compton street,', 'Walk into the middle of Charing Cross Road where an island opposes Old Compton Street and look down into the grate...sign lingers beneath the busy road, marking the territory as “Little Compton Street”.'),
(12, 'John Snow Public House', 'john snow,dr john snow,epidemiology,john snow public house,history of john snow,history of dr john snow,snow,cholera', 'Situated at the junction of Lexington Street and Broadwick Street is The John Snow, a public house that has honoured its nineteenth-century namesake since 1958...Snow was credited with advancing epidemiology (the study of the spread of disease) and moving past outdated theories of contagion.'),
(13, 'Freemasons\' Hall and london Museum', 'freemason,freemason hall,london museum,freemasons history,free mason,history of freemason,history of freemason\'s hall,history of free mason,freemasons history,mason,museum of london,welsh freemasons,english freemasons,english and welsh freemasons,location for freemasons meetings,freemasons meetings,headquarters for english and welsh freemasons', 'Located on Great Queen Street, the site of the current Freemasons’ Hall has been the headquarters for English and Welsh Freemasons since 1775. It is still an active location for Freemason meetings, events and ceremonies.'),
(14, 'Freemasons\' Hall and london Museum', 'freemason,freemasons,freemasons hall,history of freemason,freemasons history', ''),
(15, 'The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice', 'watts,watts memorial,history of watts,history of watts memorial,the watts,hidden history of watts', 'This memorial to everyday heroism and self-sacrifice was proposed by the painter and sculptor, George Frederic Watts, in a letter to the editor of The Times in 1887 as part of the celebrations of Queen Victoria’s Golden Jubilee. He, like many wealthy people in the late Victorian period, believed in the need for social reform for the poor in England, and in turn saw a need to actively remember the heroism of ‘ordinary’ people.'),
(16, 'Nelson\'s Column', 'Nelson,nelson column,Britain’s heroic figures,history of nelson,history of nelson column,Trafalgar Square, nelson Trafalgar Square,column', 'Nelson’s death at Trafalgar secured his position as one of Britain’s most heroic figures. His signal “England expects that every man will do his duty” has been regularly quoted...As the main feature of Trafalgar square the column plays host to thousands of tourists, performances and protest rallies.'),
