(25, 'Putney Bridge Pillbox', 'Putney bridge,putney bridge,pill box,bridge pillbox,history of putney bridge pillbox,location of putney bridge pillbox,hidden history of Putney Bridge Pillbox', 'The Putney Bridge pillbox was built into the existing bridge during the Second World War. It is a hexagonal bricked two-storey structure –with small openings (embrasures) suitable for positioning firearms. These constructions were colloquially called ‘Pillboxes’, in reference to their shape. ');
INSERT INTO `mobile_articles` (`articlesid`, `articletitle`, `article`, `articleimage`, `visible`, `position`, `featured`, `parentid`, `longitude`, `latitude`, `include_on_map`, `show_in_topic`, `categoryid`, `author_id`, `actual_location`, `company_url`) VALUES
(1, 'The Windrush Generation', 'In 1948, the British Nationality Act declared that all Commonwealth citizens (inhabitants of former British colonies), had the right to <mark>freely enter and settle in Britain</mark>. Due to the ‘depressed economic situation’ in Jamaica at this time, when an advertisement in the Daily Gleaner offered passage to Britain for £28.10, many West Indians seized the chance to seek further employment and education opportunities in the ‘Mother country’.  Following a 22-day journey from Jamaica, on June 22nd 1948, the SS Empire Windrush arrived in Britain, docking just outside of London in Tilbury, Essex.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Empire-Windrush.jpg\" alt=\"Windrush Generation\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The \'Empire Windrush\' arriving in London, England in 1948 bringing Immigrants from the Caribbean to the UK. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nStarting life as a German cruise boat, the Empire Windrush eventually wound up in Kingston, Jamaica, where it then set sail for the British Isles, officially carrying 492 Caribbean passengers, although this number is believed to be greater as the ship contained a number of stowaways. \r\n<br></br>\r\nOf this number, many had already visited British shores - 120 were in fact ex-servicemen who had fought with British forces during the war. As post-war prosperity kicked-in, British industry found itself lacking the manpower to meet economic expansion. <mark>Many British employers thus looked to the former colonies in order to supply the labour</mark> needed to facilitate the rejuvenation of British industry.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>From Jamaica to Britain</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nPassengers of the Empire Windrush and those that were to follow, set their sights on the British Isles for a number of reasons. For many, like Clinton Edwards who had served with the RAF during the war, “the opportunity for jobs was better than back home”. Arthur Curling, also a former member of the British Airforce, felt that after his experience of traveling outside of the Caribbean, Jamaica simply felt “too small”. Whilst many intended to settle in Britain permanently, others planned to move back after learning a trade or simply viewed Britain as a stepping stone on their way to America. But regardless of individual motivations for the journey, for those undertaking the now historic voyage, <mark>coming to Britain represented the start of a new chapter</mark>. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/WINDRUSH-GENERATION.jpg\" alt=\"Windrush Generation\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Jamaican immigrants welcomed by RAF officials from the Colonial Office after the ex-troopship HMT ‘Empire Windrush’ landed them at Tilbury. <i>(Picture: PA)</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nPrior to entering Britain, many passengers had self-organised employment and accommodation.  With the government apparently keen to ‘disperse’ the newcomers as quickly as possible, upon arrival those who had made such prior arrangements were issued free travel permits to get to them where they needed to go.\r\n<br></br>\r\nThose without such plans were transported from Tilbury to London and hastily sheltered at the <mark>Deep Shelter at Clapham South</mark>, which had been re-opened for the purpose.  180 steps below ground, this subterranean shelter had previously acted as a place of refuge for many Londoners during the blitz.  But in 1948, at the behest of the Colonial Office, it became the temporary home of 236 expectant individuals.\r\n<br></br>\r\nAt the opening of the shelter, the newcomers were greeted by a welcome tent where each resident was ‘checked-in’, allocated a bunk and issued with a blanket and linen sheet.  After descending into what one passenger described as “the bowels of South London,” the group became acquainted with their first British home-base.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/clapham_south_old9.jpg\" alt=\"Clapham South\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Jamaican immigrants using the shelter as a hostel in July 1948. <i>Source: subbrit.org.uk</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nFortunately, few of the deep shelter’s new inhabitants were subjected to these surroundings for too long. Utilising the local labour exchange in Cold harbour Lane, Brixton, within a month nearly all had secured accommodation and employment.  Taking up positions in a range of environments including the NHS and transport services, the new arrivals found work in essential industries that were key to post-war regeneration.\r\n<br></br>\r\nOutwardly, the Colonial Office congratulated themselves for a job well done. However, as had been the case since the imminence of the ship’s arrival, internal conversations were less encouraging.\r\nAfter learning of the Windrush’s imminent arrival, many alarmed MPs expressed their concern to Prime Minister Atlee, stating:\r\n“The British people fortunately enjoy a profound unity without uniformity in their way of life, and we are blest by the absence of a colour racial problem. <mark>An influx of coloured people domiciled here is likely to impair the harmony, strength and cohesion of our public and social life.</mark>”\r\n<br></br>\r\nHowever, after the war, in a bid to move away from a pre-war ‘imperial dominance’, Britain was eager to demonstrate its commitment to the creation of a fairer society. As part of such commitment, the Labour government desired to forge a new, more familial relationship with Commonwealth countries.  It was amidst this collaborative spirit that the 1948 Nationality Act and Commonwealth recruitment drives emerged.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/New-Arrivals.jpg\" alt=\"New Arrivals\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The new arrivals were interviewed by the Ministry of Labour and National Service Office to help them find work. <i>Source: Mirror.co.uk // Topfoto</i></q></sub>\r\n</p>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nUnfortunately, the unwelcoming attitude expressed by certain MPs was also manifest in numerous British newspapers. News of the hostility reached the Caribbean, prompting concern over the potentially negative treatment was awaiting migrants. In response the Atlee government was keen to publicly alleviate any unease.  As historian Kenneth Lunn notes, any indication of restrictions or attitudes “which smacked of a ‘colour bar’”, risked provoking charges of racism that the government wished to avoid.\r\n<br></br>\r\nWhilst the British government was anxious to avoid appearing unwelcoming, at the same time a governmental feeling existed within Whitehall that a precedent should not be set. Many MPs wished to avoid providing too warm a welcome. <mark>They did not want to run the risk of encouraging others to follow suit and turning the country into what was described as “an open reception centre for immigrants”</mark>.  A further governmental concern was that the migrants be dispersed across the country as soon as possible.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/New-arrivals-2.jpg\" alt=\"New Arrivals\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Underground bunk beds with Windrush passengers. <i>Source: BBC.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe logic being that if the new arrivals were scattered widely enough, their presence would be less likely to attract negative attention, such as had already been seen in port communities such as Liverpool which was home to an existing black community.  As the Windrush approached, tensions arose between the Colonial Office, the Home Office and the Ministry of Labour - each department was keen to avoid assuming responsibility for facilitating the newcomers’ imminent arrival.  On the outside an apparent open door policy prevailed. <mark>Behind closed doors tensions about the implications of the new arrivals were bubbling</mark>.\r\n<br></br>\r\nYet, no formal policy in relation to West Indian immigration was formulated. Despite a recorded deterioration in race relations during the immediate post war years, and an awareness of hostile public attitudes towards black settlement, the government failed to enact legislation against racial discrimination.  Concerns over the treatment of the West Indian migrants were voiced. Yet, for various reasons, no solid action was taken to safeguard the reception and treatment of migrant communities.\r\n<br></br>\r\nWithin this period of ambivalence, although the official line was that the new arrivals had been settled and dispersed with apparent ease, <mark>in reality the country’s new inhabitants received a less than warm welcome.</mark> Many experienced extreme racism and intolerance from certain areas of society, denied access to certain employment opportunities and better housing on basis of their skin-colour. As a result of this discrimination, many of the West Indian migrants ended up settling in “the meanest housing” of inner city London in areas such as Brixton and Notting Hill where they faced “slum landlords, high rents and overcrowding”.  Making the line the official governmental line of ‘success’ difficult to understand.\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><b>Long-term Impact</b></h2>\r\n <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe way post-war governmental approaches to immigration have shaped the longer-term experiences of the Windrush community. In light of the 2018 <mark>‘Windrush Scandal’</mark> and the wrongful deportation of a number of individuals, it is evident that the after-shocks of the poor treatement of the Windrush generation experienced in the years proceeding 1948 is still being felt today.\r\nFollowing the 1948 Nationality Act, those arriving from Commonwealth countries were legally British subjects, however for many who came to Britain between 1948 and 1971, the experience has not always reflected this. As British citizens, those arriving with the Windrush generation were not immigrants, but migrants. Yet following their arrival, race became a marker used to strip these legal citizens of social acceptance.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/We-are-not-illegal.jpg\" alt=\"We are Not Illegal\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Windrush scandal is a 2018 British political scandal concerning people who were wrongly detained, denied legal rights, threatened with deportation, and, in around 63 cases, wrongly deported from the UK. Many of those affected are members of the Windrush generation. <i>Image: © Peter Marshall / Global Look Press.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\nWhilst Britain had long been a multicultural country, the arrival of the Windrush signalled the advent of substantial and permanent black communities in Britain.  Headlines may have read ‘Welcome Home’, but in reality, beyond the initial arrival of the first new arrivals, there was a lack of governmental policy in place designed to maintain support and integration for those settling in Britain from Commonwealth nations.\r\n<br></br>\r\nDespite this, plans were in place to recruit from the Caribbean in order to satisfy the need for labour in key industries, such as London transport which was actively advertising vacancies in Barbados.  \r\n<br></br>\r\nBy 1958, there were around 125,000 Caribbean workers in Britain, with a disproportionate amount of these individuals represented in semi and unskilled roles. Due to the absence of official support, in addition to a concentration of black migrants in certain industries, migrants were left to secure housing through an “informal network of support”.  <mark>This led to a clustering of black migrants in certain urban areas, which made their presence seem greater and caused alarm to many of the local white population.</mark>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2><b>Racism</b></h2>\r\n <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nAs Caribbean migration grew, so too did the racist attitude of many white Britons towards the growing black communities. Claiming that the newcomers were taking jobs from capable White Britons, <mark>during the 1950s there was an increasingly hostile attitude towards black people.</mark> The growing concern over the ‘dangers of unrestricted immigration’ was reflected within the media, the tone of which had shifted from support of unrestricted migrant labour to one of suspicion. <mark>It was not uncommon for black citizens to face discrimination in a number of public environments including, hotels, shops, schools or housing.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/KBW.jpg\" alt=\"Keep Britain White\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Young lady points to \'Keep Britain White\' graffiti at the International Personnel training centre in Balham.  <i>Source: Neil Kenlock // Tate</i></q></sub>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nFascist groups such as <mark>Oswald Mosley’s fascist Union Movement,</mark> <mark>Colin Jordan’s White Defense League</mark> and <mark>the League of Empire Loyalists</mark> added fuel to the fire. Yet there was still no recourse from the law to address the mounting racism within the country, which led to violent clashes during the 1958 Notting Hill Riots.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Oswald-Mosley.jpg\" alt=\"Oswald Moseley\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Oswald Mosley, leader of the British Union of Fascists, at a rally in East London.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\nIn response to growing racial tension at the influx of new arrivals, <mark>in 1962, the Commonwealth Immigration Act was passed in order to curb the number of those travelling from Commonwealth countries into Britain.</mark>  The act introduced a system that required hopeful migrants to obtain government-issued work permits before they could enter.  But it was not until 1965 that policy directly addressing racial discrimination was made when the Race Relations Act came into effect making racial discrimination unlawful in public spaces.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/1958 Notting Hill race riots.jpg\" alt=\"Notting Hill Race Riots\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Notting Hill race riots were a series of racially motivated riots that took place in Notting Hill, England, between 29 August and 5 September 1958.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\nRelating to both British citizens and visitors, the law prohibited any form of discrimination based on a person’s colour, race or ethnic origins. Whilst there were those who resisted such reform, it was criticised for not going far enough. For example, it did not cover housing or employment where the issue was often most prevalent. This led to the passing of the Race Relations Act 1968 which sought to address areas such as housing, employment and advertising which were previously omitted.\r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1971 the Immigration Act gave all Commonwealth Citizens already living in the UK indefinite leave to remain. In a further bid to control the number of people settling in the UK, the law also put an end to freedom of movement for Commonwealth citizens.  However, the Home Office never issued paperwork for those granted leave to remain to confirm their status, nor did they keep a record of those affected by the act.\r\n<br></br>\r\nFast forward a number of decades and the <b>‘Windrush Scandal’</b> appears to be a part of the wider continuum of black British experience. <mark>After being invited to Britain to provide vital support in the post-war reconstruction efforts, many British citizens have found themselves having their legal status questioned.</mark>  In addition to the absence of records created and issued during the 1970s, it has come to light that in 2010 the landing cards completed by incoming Commonwealth citizens, which were being stored by the Home Office, had been destroyed.  This lack of paperwork has led to serious problems for many of the Windrush generation. In 2012, strict changes to immigration law designed to target illegal immigration required that people provide the documentation confirming their right to work, rent or have access to healthcare.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Hosstile-Environment.jpg alt=\"Hostile Environment\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The UK Home Office hostile environment policy is a set of administrative and legislative measures designed to make staying in the United Kingdom as difficult as possible for people without leave to remain, in the hope that they may \"voluntarily leave\".<i>Source: Wikipedia</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark>Although legal citizens, many of the Windrush generation unable to produce the necessary paperwork have suddenly found their legal status questioned.</mark> The number of those affected remains unclear, as many of the Windrush generation travelled on parental passports and never applied for travel documents of their own. After being born or living in Britain for decades, a number of individuals have been wrongfully threatened with deportation to countries they may have not seen for 50 years.\r\n<br></br>\r\nFor some, the image of hundreds of Caribbean-born individuals filing off the ship’s gangplank in 1948 has become synonymous with “the beginning of modern British multicultural society”.  It is estimated that following the arrival of the Windrush and its passengers in 1948, by 1971 nearly half a million West Indian-born individuals left their homes to settle in Britain. This Caribbean diaspora has come to be known as the Windrush Generation.\r\n<br></br>\r\nWhen this piece of Black & British history has been given close attention, there has been a tendency to depict the arrival of the Windrush as a watershed moment in the history of black migration to Britain, prompting questions of race and the formation of the modern British identity.  It has been depicted as the ‘symbolic point of origin’ from which narratives surrounding British citizens of African descent should stem.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark>According to this perspective, 1948 is extoled as the opening chapter of the tumultuous road to becoming contemporary multicultural Britain.</mark> However, recent years have witnessed concerted efforts to re-think this narrative. As Barnor Hesse reminds us in his book \"Unsettled Multiculturalisms\", the portrayal of Black Britain as a post-war phenomenon is misleading, overlooking the individual stories of people of African descent who settled in Britain prior to 1948.  Furthermore, it suggests that racial tension within Britain is a relatively ‘recent’ issue resulting from the demographic upheaval of the post-war years, when in fact the problem of racism in Britain has a much longer history. To gain a deeper understanding of Britain’s migration history is to gain a better understanding of our current identity. Failure to do so is to perpetuate the historical amnesia that leads to the ignorance and prejudice that we must work to eradicate.\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>', 'windrushgeneration.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, 0, 1, 0, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(2, 'Putney Bridge Pillbox', 'The Putney Bridge pillbox was built into the existing bridge during the Second World War. It is a hexagonal bricked two-storey structure – with small openings (embrasures) suitable for positioning firearms. These constructions were colloquially called <mark>‘Pillboxes’,</mark> in reference to their shape.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>Why were pillboxes built?</h2>\r\nIn 1940 over 28,000 pillboxes were hastily built in strategically important locations, like canals, junctions, and bridges, across Great Britain. They made up a series of defensive ‘stop-lines’. Pillboxes made up Britain’s final line of defence in the event of a German invasion – a very real threat in the aftermath of the evacuation of British and Allied troops from the beaches of Northern France in late May and early June 1940, known as the Dunkirk evacuation.\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe pillbox on Putney Bridge is of the type 22 design. Most structures followed set guidelines but were altered depending on the local area’s availability of materials and its environment. Many pillboxes were constructed from concrete, with walls up to 30cm thick! – one of the reasons approximately 6000 of them still survive hidden amongst British urban and rural landscapes today.', 'image.jpg', 0, NULL, 0, 0, '-0.2119135', '51.4678669', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(3, 'Windrush Square', 'Located in the heart of Brixton opposite the Edwardian town hall, Windrush Square is a public space in South London. Originally the space was part of Rushey Common before housing was built upon the site during the 19th century. \r\n<br><br>\r\nAfter the houses were demolished a public library was built by Henry Tate. Following his death in 1899, Tate’s widow presented the land to the council, to be transformed into a public garden – the Tate Library Garden. In 1998, the space adjoining the gardens was incorporated to create the Windrush Square, designed to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the landing of the SS Empire Windrush. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe ship landed in Tilbury, Essex in 1948, bringing 492 West Indian migrants who were to lay the foundations of Brixton’s large multi-ethnic community. The square was officially re-opened in 2010 by the London Mayor, Boris Johnson.', 'Windrush-Square-Brixton-.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 1, '-0.1173547', '51.4604743', 1, 0, 1, 0, 'London, UK', ''),
(4, 'Labour Exchange, Coldharbour Lane', 'The Labour Exchange (Job Centre) on Coldharbour Lane was a key location for the West Indian migrants travelling to Britain during the Windrush. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nWith many of the new arrivals who travelled on the SS Empire Windrush being temporarily housed in the Clapham South Deep Shelter, Coldharbour Labour Exchange became nearest port of call when it came to seeking employment. \r\n<br></br>\r\nThe site facilitated the supply of West Indian labour to various employers including London Transport and led to the founding of one of the West Indian communities in nearby Brixton.', 'DcMlFq-WAUmAFx.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 1, '-0.104282', '51.4666105', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(5, 'Deep Shelter, Clapham South', 'Many Londoners will walk past this odd fixture every day without realising the history held within the deep shelter at Clapham South. 180 steps down, this underground air-raid bunker was born in the midst of the blitz during World War II, providing shelter to London citizens seeking refuge.\r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1948, the shelter acted as a temporary home to the new arrivals who had traveled to Britain from the Caribbean on the SS Empire Windrush as part of the post war recruitment drive to rebuild Britain’s key industries.\r\n<br></br>\r\nToday, the shelter is open to the public as part of special guided tours showcasing Hidden London.', 'claphamsouthcopyrighttfl-.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 1, '-0.1474068', '51.4535249', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(6, 'Plague Pits', 'The disease we today term “the plague” is caused by the Yersinia pestis bacteria and has three identified strains: bubonic plague (affecting the lymphatic system), pneumonic plague (affecting the lungs), and septicaemic plague (affecting the blood). \r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark>Bubonic plague</mark> is perhaps the most well-known strain as it refers specifically to the disease’s most infamous symptom; the bubo. This is an often-painful swelling of infected lymph nodes in the groin, neck or armpit. Other symptoms vary according to the specific strain of the plague, but if suffering from the disease today one can expect flu-like symptoms that may quickly become fatal if untreated. This can, however, now be effectively treated with antibiotics and has a much higher survival rate than in previous centuries.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/First-plague-pit-image.jpg\" alt=\"Plague Pits\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>This plague patient is displaying a swollen, ruptured inguinal lymph node, or buboe. After the incubation period of 2-6 days, symptoms of the plague appear including severe malaise, headache, shaking chills, fever, and pain. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAlthough we know this particular disease simply as “the plague”, it has in fact been known by various other names throughout history. During the early modern period (approximately 1500 to 1750) it was known as the plague during various pandemics, but prior to this it was most often referred to as “the pestilence” by chroniclers. We know this medieval outbreak as “the Black Death”, but this is also a modern term. It can confusingly imply two separate diseases rather than two separate outbreaks; however recent DNA testing of medieval Black Death victims has confirmed the presence of the plague-causing bacteria <mark>Yersinia pestis</mark>.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h4> Causes </h4>\r\nThe disease was caused by flea bites transferring the disease to rodents that arrived on Britain’s shores from plague-ridden countries. It was understood during the plague’s peak that these ships appeared to carry the plague but unclear as to how – the germ theory had not yet been formed. <mark>The best explanation of contagion during this period was known as “miasma”</mark>; the inhaling of toxic or infectious gases. The relative understanding of contagion led to the quarantining of certain ships for 40 days to ensure they were free from disease before coming to shore. The practice originated from medieval Venice, and comes from the Italian for “40 days”: quranta giorni.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Yersinia-Perstis.jpg\" alt=\"Plague Pits\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>A scanning electron micrograph depicting a mass of Yersinia pestis bacteria in the foregut of an infected flea.  <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2><i>How do we know about the early modern plague?</i></h2>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h4>Bills of Mortality:</h4>\r\n\r\nThese are statistic reports produced to list numbers and causes of deaths in a specific area. Around plague pandemics similar publications known as the <mark>“Lord Have Mercy Upon Us”</mark> broadsheets were used specifically to communicate death tolls and other information on the plague around London. These publications demonstrate a rising culture of statistics around this period, possibly to install a sense of order around the rising panic. \r\n<br></br>\r\nThe Figure below tells us that <mark>3,880 people died from the plague</mark> between August 15th-22nd 1665 in this particular area of London. This accounts for a huge 73% of deaths in this specific week, giving us a rare statistic value of just how prevalent the disease was, and just how terrifying such a pandemic must have been in the absence of an effective treatment.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Bill-of-Mortality.jpg\" alt=\"Bill of Mortality\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Diseases and Casualties this Week, Bill of Mortality, 1665. <i>Source: Welcome Collection / Accessed June 3rd 2018.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAside from important information on the plague, the Bills of Mortality also give us an invaluable insight into contemporary disease culture. Some conditions are recognisable, such as “Consumption” or “Scurvy”, but some we can only guess at, such as “Rising of the Lights”. Indeed, one poor person is simply listed to have died “Suddenly”. Do we even know that every listed death by “Plague” is the plague as we know it? Unfortunately, the answer is most likely no. \r\n<br></br>\r\nCauses of death at this point were identified by “searchers” who did not have official medical training, but quickly checked corpses and passed the speculated cause of death on for the Bills of Mortality. Despite uncertainty over disease identification, the value of the publication as a source through which to view the plague or other diseases is not diminished. It gives us a chance to view these conditions as they existed and affected the population in 1665 rather than comparing them to modern equivalents, or even wonder if there is a modern equivalent. Just because we can identify the plague by its name in the early modern period does not mean it was experienced in the same way as it is today, and the unidentifiable conditions on the Bills of Mortality remind us of that. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Personal memoirs:</h4>\r\nAs much as Bills of Mortality tell us about how many people died of the plague, they tell us virtually nothing of personal experiences. Unfortunately, a primary source with this type of information is extremely hard to come by; if a person experienced plague it is unlikely that they would be concerned with writing it down. Indeed, although literacy rates appear to have steadily increased over this period, the majority of the population were if not completely illiterate, then only capable of reading. \r\n<br></br>\r\nThere are occasionally small glimpses of the disease within diaries kept at the time of the plague, but rarely at length. We see one of these in the writings of one of the most famous English diarists in history: Samuel Pepys.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Samuel.jpg\" alt=\"Samuel\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Samuel Pepys was famous for the diary he kept for a decade while still a relatively young man. It provides a combination of personal revelation and eyewitness accounts of great events, such as the Great Plague of London. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAlthough gaining fame for his account of the Great Fire of London, it is often forgotten that this event occurred around the same year as the final plague pandemic, 1665-66. Consequently, Pepys mentions his experiences with the plague but, as mentioned before, his lack of proximity is reflected in these experiences being limited to a line or two. On 14th September 1665 he wrote of one of these experiences: \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<mark><i>\"My meeting dead corpses of the plague, carried to be buried close to me at noonday through the City in Fanchurch Street. To see a person sick of the sores carried close by me by Gracechurch in a hackney-coach\"</i></mark>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nAlthough this seems to be a very limited excerpt, we can still learn several things from it. When looking specifically at plague pits, for example, the passage tells us that the dead were carried through Fanchurch Street (most likely modern-day Fenchurch Street, London, EC3M 4BS), meaning there may have been a burial pit nearby. As for contemporary symptoms, it tells us that the sores were possibly one of the most identifiable and diagnostic for the plague. The passage may be short, but is still an important piece of the puzzle. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Medical/Supernatural Treatises:</h4>\r\nThe prevalence of the plague in the 17th century led to many papers and reports being written on the disease by physicians, healers, supernaturalists and scientists alike (the distinctions between these different professions were much blurrier than they are today). These works were likely to be intended for circulation amongst the scholarly rather than for the general population; broadsheets tended to inform the literate masses, and ordinances from the monarch and reports from local councils were read out in public places for the rest. \r\n<br></br>\r\nAstrologer John Gadbury published his musings on causes of plagues in 1665. His explanations had a mainly supernatural basis, as can be seen by his focus on the alignments of the planets, and concerned various major plague outbreaks that had occurred in history.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<mark><i>\"In the year 1603, the Pestilence was inconsiderable in its increase, until the last week in June, and the month of July, at which times the fiery Planet Mars came to the opposite point of the Moon.\"</i></mark>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nGadbury’s discourse discusses the plague at length, and gives us some vague but usefully corroborative symptoms: \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark><i>\"Physicians tell us, that the Plague is a disease most Malignant and Pestilential ; a Fever in the highest in the highest degree, which doth putrifie and corrupt, both the Solid and Fluid parts of the body ; which have done, by an (almost) uncontrolable and unrepellable siccity, dries and destroys the Natural Powers, then seizeth or preyeth upon the vitals , and so lets in the everlasting Enemy, DEATH.\"</i></mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/John_Gadbury.jpg\" alt=\"Philosopher John Gadbury\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Philosopher John Gadbury.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThis particular source may seem somewhat indistinct and spiritual when attempting to piece together various bits of information on the physical aspects of the plague in history, such as its symptoms and how different geographical locations were affected. It is, however, still an extremely useful source; this is partly for the same reasons as the usefulness of the Bills of Mortality. \r\n<br></br>\r\nMuch in the same way the Bills of Mortality show us that individual experiences of historical disease may be so different from our modern ones that we are unable to properly empathise them, Gadbury’s treatise presents a valid contemporary view of the physical aspects of the plague that we may potentially find difficult to use. \r\n<br></br>\r\nIt demonstrates the inherent interlinking of natural and supernatural causes within disease culture at the time, as shown with the constant undertone of sin and judgement. Moreover, the significance of religion is made similarly obvious through this sinful narrative. \r\n<br></br>\r\nThe notion that supernatural explanations may be vital in understanding natural aspects of the plague can help us uncover details that may otherwise have gone unexplained if the focus were solely on modern interpretation of physical elements of the disease. \r\n<br></br>\r\nThis includes tiny details such as the layout and spacing of victims in a plague pit; the regular, careful positioning of the victims indicate that proper burials were vital even in densely filled plague pits, most likely because of the constant presence of religion and tradition, and the role of the parish. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<h4>Official documents</h4>\r\nPlague pandemics tended to cause disorder, panic and subversions of social orders <mark>(given that no-one, not even those that were wealthier, were safe from the disease)</mark>. Ordinances issued by the monarch can be seen as attempts to dampen this chaos through information and guidelines. \r\n<br></br>\r\nCharles II published <mark>“Rules and Orders”</mark> on the prevention of the plague in 1665 to control the contagious nature of the disease. The document is specifically for the instruction of “Justices of Peace, Mayors, Bayliffs, and other Officers”, i.e. those in charge of lay people.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Rules-and-Orders.jpg\" alt=\"Charles II, \"Rules and Orders\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Charles II, \"Rules and Orders.<i>Source: National Archives, Accessed June 12th 2018</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nBecause of this, the document is not necessarily concerned with how an individual may protect him or herself from sickening, but how households, villages, etc, can protect themselves. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIt is a practical document, meaning we can see what details were deemed to be important enough to pass on from the highest-level authority to his subjects. We can see various historical concepts covered in other sources, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\nMiasma (the belief that disease spread through bad-smelling air). Rules 6 & 7 dictate that “convenient Fumes to correct the Air be burnt” in public places, and that “no unwholsome Meats, stinking Fish, Flesh, musty Corn” may be sold.\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nSpecific symptoms that searchers should look out for. Rule no. 10 dictates that local areas should be prepared to identify and care for the sick and that searchers should identify the plague by the “usual… Swellings or Risings under the Ears or Arm-pits [buboes], or upon the Groynes; Blains, Carbuncles, or little Spots, either on the Breast or back, commonly called Tokens.”\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nThe significance of religion and the supernatural. As mentioned with regard to John Gadbury’s astronomical treatise on the plague, cures and explanations that we may think of spiritual rather than medical were used readily and expected to protect as effectively as any physical treatment. Rule no. 12 dictates that on any affected household undergoing quarantine should “have a Red Cross, and Lord have mercy upon us, in Capital Letter affixed on the door”. That such a practical report would include such religious treatments against the plague again shows how these acts were as important at the time as those more medical, such as quarantine. The final line of the report asks that everyone take heed of these orders and maintain regular prayers and fasts in order to reverse God’s punishment.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe report also gives us more information on the elusive plague pits. Rule no. 13 dictates where and how plague victims should be buried: \r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark><i>\"in some other convenient place [than church yards], and that a good quantity of unslaked Lime be put into Graves with such bodies, and that such Graves be not after opened within the space of a year or more, less they infect others.\"</i></mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\nAlso mentioned in the orders, that we have not seen in aforementioned primary sources, is the first glimpses of the welfare state. Given the belief that sin and punishment were the major causes of the plague pandemic, the orders ensure that “such visited poor may have sufficient Relief; want and nastiness being great occasions of the Infection.” \r\n<br></br>\r\nCoupled with the careful burials we see in plague pits, it can be ascertained that the plague may have fostered a culture of respect and care rather than one of isolation, which is often assumed from the fear of contagion. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Popular Literature</h4>\r\nOne of the most interestingly comprehensive overviews of the plague pandemic of 1665-6 comes from the author Daniel Defoe, in his novel entitled Journal of the Plague Year. The novel follows the main character, simply referred to as H. F., during the pandemic in London. \r\n<br></br>\r\nWhen compared to other primary sources used to understand the plague, Journal of the Plague Year certainly seems to corroborate. Defoe writes on the physical symptoms:\r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark><i>\"The swellings, which were generally in the neck or groin, when they grew hard and would not break, grew so painful that it was equal to the most exquisite torture; and some, not able to bear the torment, threw themselves out at windows”… “or otherwise made themselves away, and I saw several objects of that kind.\"</i></mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Plague-Victims.jpg\" alt=\"Plague Victims\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Plague Victims.<i>Source: Wikimedia</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nWe can liken this description of buboes to those given in other non-fiction sources, e.g., Charles II’s “Rules and Orders” and John Gadbury’s London’s deliverance predicted, being relatively detailed and graphic. This, however, also plays into the literary techniques of the novel, hence why it may be a slight exaggeration. To ‘make oneself away’ during this period, for example, literally meant to kill oneself. \r\n<br></br>\r\nSuicide was seen as a religious crime against God – self-murder – and so whether this would have regularly occurred in a population readily believed to be being punished for their sins with the plague anyway, is debatable. It is due to these images of Defoe’s imagination within the text that it is unclear where it lies on the fiction/non-fiction spectrum. \r\n<br></br>\r\nDespite Defoe’s guiding hand, the work is often read as non-fiction and used for various details on the physical aspects of the plague; online history guide Historic UK has used it as one of their sources to map the locations of various plague pits. Indeed, Journal of the Plague Year references death tolls, burial registers and plague pits that, to a certain extent, do seem to be grounded in reality, as with his dimensions of the Aldgate plague pit. \r\n<br></br>\r\nRegardless of whether we can cross-reference every detail given by Defoe on the plague, it provides an interesting contemporary popular view of how the disease was experienced. In other words, because the novel was written within living memory of plague year, Defoe would have had little reason to exaggerate or change objective details such as plague pit dimensions; these could easily have been checked. We can assume they are relatively accurate, and hence use it as the last important piece of the puzzle in the understanding of the early modern plague.\r\n<br></br>', 'pzk.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, 0, 1, 0, 0, '', ''),
(7, 'Saint Paul’s Cathedral', 'Beneath the grounds of a Church of England parish church known as St Paul’s most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThis is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year. The church is in Shadwell, East London, and is not to be confused with St Paul’s Cathedral in the city centre (another plague burial site).\r\n<br></br>\r\nDefoe describes the pit to have been one of five other plague pits for the parish of Stepney: There were no less than five other grounds made use of for the parish of Stepney at that time: one where now stands the parish church of St Paul, Shadwell, and the other where now stands the parish church of St John’s at Wapping, both which had not the names of parishes at that time, but were belonging to Stepney parish.”\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nFew specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: They dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. \r\n\r\n<br></br> \r\nA terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.', 'new.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 6, '-0.052122', '51.509536', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(8, 'Tothill Street (formerly Tuttle Fields)', 'Beneath the ground of a busy side street known as Tuthill Street most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 17th century diarist Samuel Pepys in his well-known journal. The street leads to Westminster Cathedral and was formerly the site of Tuttle Fields. These lay south of St. James’s Park and west of the River Thames, close to Christchurch Gardens where another plague pit has been rumoured to sit\r\n<br></br>\r\nPepys describes the pit to have been used to accommodate bodies that cannot afford to be buried in the newly-charging “New-Chapel”: I was much troubled this day to hear at Westminster how the officers do bury the dead in the open Tuttle-Fields, pretending want of room elsewhere; whereas the New-Chapel church-yard was walled in at the public charge in the last plague-time merely for want of room, and now none but such as are able to pay dear for it can be buried there.\r\n<br></br>\r\nFew specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but contemporary writer Daniel Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits in his semi-factual novel The Journal of the Plague Year in 1722, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: “they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nA terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.”', 'vlcsnap----hms-.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 6, '-0.131099', '51.499720', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(9, 'New Street (Previously Hand Alley)', 'Beneath the ground of a busy side street known as New Street most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year. The street branches of the main road of Bishopsgate Street and was formerly known as Hand Alley.\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe street branches of the main road of Bishopsgate Street and was formerly known as Hand Alley. Defoe describes the pit to have mainly been for the plague dead of the parish of Bishopsgate but was obviously large enough to take some neighbouring surplus: “The upper end of Hand Alley, in Bishopsgate Street, which was then a green field, and was taken in particularly for Bishopsgate parish, though many of the carts out of the city brought their dead thither also, particularly out of the parish of St All-hallows on the Wall.”\r\n<br></br>\r\nFew specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nA terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.\r\n<br></br>\r\nDefoe also interestingly describes an incident in the years following the plague epidemic of 1665-6 in which the pit was accidentally excavated: \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n“The houses in the same row with that house northward are built on the very same ground where the poor people were buried, and the bodies, on opening the ground for the foundations, were dug up, some of them remaining so plain to be seen that the women\'s skulls were distinguished by their long hair, and of others the flesh was not quite perished; so that the people began to exclaim loudly against it, and some suggested that it might endanger a return of the contagion; after which the bones and bodies, as fast as they came at them, were carried to another part of the same ground and thrown all together into a deep pit”.', 'image-.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 6, '-0.079528', '51.517216', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(10, 'Mount Mills, London', 'Beneath the ground of an open area of wasteland known as Mount Mills most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year. The area lies near the intersection of Gosworth Road and Percival Street, and is now used as a carpark.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nDefoe describes the pit to be a large overspill pit from neighbouring parishes: “A piece of ground beyond Goswell Street, near Mount Mill, being some of the remains of the old lines or fortifications of the city, where abundance were buried promiscuously from the parishes of Aldersgate, Clerkenwell, and even out of the city. This ground, as I take it, was since made a physic garden, and after that has been built upon.”\r\n<br><br>\r\nNo specifics on the dimensions of this plague pit are given in the text, but Defoe gives some detail on other comparable pits, such as one beneath Aldgate Underground Station: “they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. A terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nAs near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.”', 'kk.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 6, '-0.099504', '51.526092', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', '');
