(11, 'Aldgate Underground Station', 'Beneath the ground of Aldgate Underground Station most likely lies a burial ground occupied by victims of the 17th century plague. This is according to 18th century writer Daniel Defoe in his text Journal of the Plague Year, who wrote on the pit: “they dug the great pit in the churchyard of our parish of Aldgate. A terrible pit it was, and I could not resist my curiosity to go and see it. As near as I may judge, it was about forty feet in length, and about fifteen or sixteen feet broad, and at the time I first looked at it, about nine feet deep; but it was said they dug it near twenty feet deep afterwards in one part of it, till they could go no deeper for the water; for they had, it seems, dug several large pits before this.”', 'ald.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 6, '-0.071913', '51.515145', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(12, 'Sir Nigel Gresley\'s Statue', 'Sir Nigel Gresley designed the iconic Flying Scotsman and Mallard steam engines, which set new speed records and visually defined the ‘age of steam’, while he worked for the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) from 1923 -1941. The statue was commissioned by the Gresley Society Trust to commemorate the 75th anniversary of Gresley’s birth and was designed and created by Hazel Reeves.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Sir%20Nigel%20Gresley.jpg\" alt=\"Nigel Gresley\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Picture of Sir Nigel Gresley <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nFlying Scotsman was the first locomotive to reach 100mph on a test run on 30 November 1934. The Class A3 4-6-2 Pacific locomotive defines the ‘age of steam’, and the countries love for itcontinues today with people lining the route and queueing to see itduring its inaugural run, after a £4.2m 10-year long refit from King’s Cross to the National Railway Museum in York, on 25 February 2016. The engine is named after ‘The Flying Scotsman’ route it carried passenger trains along, which runs along the East Coast Mainline from King’s Cross to Edinburgh Waverly (from England’s capital to Scotland’s capital).\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/gesley-with-namesake.jpg\" alt=\"Nigel Gresley\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Sir Nigel Gresley with the Flying Scotsman <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nMallard broke the world speed record on 3 July 1938, which was previously held by the Flying Scotsman, by reaching 126mph. The Class A4 4-6-2 Pacific steam locomotive Mallard is a distinctive and striking blue steam engine that was in service until 1963. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/2011-04-24_SirNigelGresley.jpg\" alt=\"Nigel Gresley\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Picture of the Mallard Blue Steam Engine <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>The Statue</h2>\r\n\r\nGresley’s impact on British Railways, his engineering skills, and his work with the LNER has led to the installation a bronze statue commemorating the 75th anniversary of his birth. The statue commissioned by the Gresley Society Trust, designed and created by Hazel Reeves, was unveiled on the 5th April 2016. <mark>Originally this design was going to include a mallard duck on the ground next to Gresley to represent one of his famous creations, but the final decision was to not include this feature.</mark> The removal of the duck provoked online anger resulting in 3200 people signing a petition to have the duck reinstated, and some ‘protestors’ holding up rubber ducks on sticks at the unveiling, and placing a wooden duck in the space where it was originally proposed. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Statue_of_Sir_Nigel_Gresley,_King\'s_Cross_Station.jpg\" alt=\"Nigel Gresley Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Statue of Sir Nigel Gresley at Kings Cross Station. <i>Source: Alan Stanton / Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nLess noticeable, as you may not have access to the platform or you’re running to or from your train, an English Heritage Blue Plaque commemorating Gresley and his work for the LNER until his unexplained death in 1941 can be found on the wall of the former LNER offices next to platform 8. The plaque was originally placed on the western outside wall of the station in 1997, but was covered in 2004, removed in 2009 for the reconstruction of the station, and was finally placed in its current spot in 2013.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/stream_img.jpg\" alt=\"Nigel Gresley Statue\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Sculptor Hazel Reeves stands next to her statue of railway engineer Sir Nigel Gresley. <i> Credit: Press Association</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Demeaning.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, '-0.1241667', '51.5314028', 1, 1, 2, 0, '', ''),
(13, 'Sir Nigel Gresley plaque – Kings Cross', 'Only visible if you have tickets which permit you to enter the space for platforms 0-8 English Heritage Blue Plaque commemorating Sir Nigel Gresley. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe plaque was originally placed on the western outside wall of the station in 1997, but was covered in 2004, removed in 2009 for the reconstruction of the station, and was finally placed in its current spot in 2013.', '9705762192_418703a630_z.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 12, '-0.1244124', '51.5316509', 0, 1, 2, 0, '', ''),
(15, 'Downing Street', 'Downing Street today is seen as the Powerhouse of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland. It is where the Prime Minister and the Chancellor of the Exchequer live and where Cabinet meetings are usually held, namely in the Cabinet Room of 10 Downing Street, the Prime Minister\'s official residence.\r\n<br></br>\r\nWhat isn’t well known is that Downing Street didn’t become the residence of the Prime Minister until 1732. So, what was there before then?\r\nIn the middle ages Downing Street itself didn’t even exist. It’s vague what was on the site originally but there is evidence towards a brewhouse called ‘The Axe’ that was owned by the Abbey of Abingdon. By the 16th Century ‘The Axe’ sadly fell into disuse.\r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1581 Sir Thomas Knyvet built the first residential house roughly on the site of Number 10. <mark>It was known as ‘The House on the Back’</mark> at the time. Sir Thomas Knyvet was a favourite of Queen Elizabeth I and was actually the person responsible for arresting Guy Fawkes after the gunpowder plot against King James I of England and VI of Scotland.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/The_Old_Palace_of_Whitehall_by_Hendrik_Danckerts.jpg\" alt=\"Palace\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Palace of Whitehall by Hendrick Danckerts c. 1660–1679. Viewed from the west side of St James\'s Park, the \"House at the Back\" is on the far right; the octagonal building next to it is the Cockpit. <i>Source: Hendrick Danckerts / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Sir George Downing</h2>\r\nIt wasn’t until the 1680’s when Sir George Downing, 1st Baronet, started to build in Downing Street. Downing started to acquire land around the site through leases to build a row of townhouses and a cul-de-sac. Sir Christopher Wren was even brought in to design the houses. \r\n<br></br>\r\nAlthough the houses were large, they were built quickly and cheaply and built on soft soil with shallow foundations. Even the fronts had facades with lines painted on the surface to imitate brick mortar. It is said that Sir George Downing never lived in the townhouses himself and retired to Cambridge where he died a few months after they were completed in 1684.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Portrait%20of%20Sir%20George%20Downing%20painted%20c.%201675–1690%20by%20Thomas%20Smith,%20The%20Fogg%20Museum.jpeg\" alt=\"George Downing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Portrait of Sir George Downing painted c. 1675–1690 by Thomas Smith, The Fogg Museum Thomas Smith (d. 1691, active 1670s–1680s) <i>Source:  Harvard Art Museums.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nRight before Downing Street became the official residence of the Prime Minister - or the First Lord of the Treasury as it was known then - the last person to live in one of the three properties which comprise of 10 Downing Street today was called Mr. Chicken. There is no other information on Mr. Chicken other than his name and that he moved out in 1732 after Sir Robert Walpole convinced him to. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nIt was after he moved out that King Charles II presented both houses to Walpole as a personal gift. Walpole didn’t accept the property as a gift unless the King made it available to him and all future First Lords of the Treasury in their official capacity. This title can be seen engraved on the letterbox on the black front door today even though the title ‘Prime Minister’ was introduced in 1905.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/800px-Robertwalpole.jpg\" alt=\"George Downing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Sir Robert Walpole accepted George II\'s gift of the house at the back and two Downing Street houses on behalf of the office of First Lord of the Treasury. Workshop of Jean-Baptiste van Loo. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe public are unable to go past the security gates at Downing Street where police from the Diplomatic Protection Group have checked every person attempting to enter the street since 1989.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Gates-at-the-main-entrance-of-Downing-Street,-Westminster,-London..jpg\" alt=\"The Gates\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Gates at the Main Entrance of Downing Street, Westminister, London.  <i>Source: Garry Knight / Entrance of Downing Street / Available on Flickr.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nHowever, if you want to have a chance of catching a glimpse of the Prime Minister she usually leaves for Parliament between 11:00am and 11:30am every Wednesday and if you are very lucky you might see Larry the Cat, a brown and white tabby who is the Chief Mouser for 10 Downing Street and was picked for the job from Battersea Dogs and Cats Home.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/1200px-Barack_Obama_and_Gordon_Brown_in_10_Downing_Street.jpg\" alt=\"Indoors\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>President Barack Obama is welcomed to 10 Downing Street in London by British Prime Minister Gordon Brown, April 1, 2009.<i>Source: Official White House Photo by Pete Souza.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n', '10_Downing_Street_2010.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, '-0.126289', '51.503181', 1, 1, 0, 0, '', ''),
(16, 'Bomber Command Memorial', 'Sequestered away on the western side of London’s picturesque Green Park stands a monument devoted to the commemoration of Britain’s most controversial Second World War heroes: the members of RAF Bomber Command. \r\n<br></br>\r\nVisitors to the park may be surprised to discover an impressive, classic portico style marble structure waiting for them. Inside the building stands a poignant sight as seven 9ft tall bronze men form the centre piece of the monument. The memorial has been designed to be more than just another pretty London shrine; it’s primary purpose is to ensure there is a permanent tribute to the 55,573 Bomber Command servicemen who died in the defence of both the city and Britain. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Bomber_Command_Memorial_-_panoramio.jpg\" alt=\"Bomber Command Memorial\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Members of RAF Bomber Command. <i>Source: Available on Flickr / Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe monument holds several interesting features – the first being the buildings open nature, ensuring the men are exposed to the sky, allowing light to cascade down and illuminate them. This clever blend of architecture and symbolism becomes even more powerful at night if visitors look up and spot the phrase “per ardua ad astra”. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe Latin motto used by the RAF during the war translates as: “through adversity to the stars”. Another feature is the structure’s ceiling, constructed using salvaged sections of a Handley Page Halifax III aircraft used by Bomber Command. The plane in question was shot down over Belgium during an operation that cost the lives of eight crewmen on the 28th of May 1944. Its incorporation into the memorial adds a poignant connection to the past.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/2013-05-12_London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg\" alt=\"Bomber Command Memorial\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Exterior of the Memorial in 2013. <i>Source: Tim Rademacher / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Controversies</h2>\r\nCommemoration of RAF Bomber Command remains a controversial topic thanks to the operations they were charged to undertake during the closing phases of the war. Some historians have questioned whether the bombing of civilian targets such as Dresden were the only way to speed up Allied victory. While Winston Churchill boldly proclaimed that Britain’s bombers would provide the means of victory in 1940 – a quote that can be found on the inside western wall of the memorial – they have ultimately been minimalised and airbrushed out of British memory due to the murky nature of their mission.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Fotothek_df_ps_0000010_Blick_vom_Rathausturm.jpg\" alt=\"Bombing Dresdan\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Dresden, 1945, view from the city hall (Rathaus) over the destroyed city. <i>Source: Deutsche Fotothek / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIt is perhaps for this reason that along the monuments northern side is an engraving that alludes to this difficult subject; “this memorial also commemorates those of all nations who lost their lives in the bombings of 1939-1945.” It is no accident that that the seven bronze men have been immortalised in sombre contemplation, as each of the seven men walk away from their mission it seems they are reflecting on the impossibly difficult act they have undertaken in the name of peace - humanising them once again. It seems that the monument has been created in part to rehabilitate Britain’s forgotten heroes, as well as being mindful of the civilians killed by their actions.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/this memorial.jpg\" height=\"auto\" width=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The Memorial. <i>Source: Tim Rademacher / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nOpened in 2012 by Her Majesty the Queen, it had taken sixty-six years for the 125,000 men of Bomber Command to receive the acknowledgment. The members of RAF Bomber Command played a pivotal role in the defence of London; they now stand watch again over the Capitol.\r\n', 'London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, '-0.148922', '51.503389', 1, 1, 2, 0, '', ''),
(17, 'Roman wall at Cooper\'s Row', 'For 1600 years London was a walled city, covering a square mile from what is now Tower Hills to Blackfriars. Originally built as a defensive structure, the city wall was constructed by the Romans to protect the strategically important town of Londinium from the Picts. Much of the wall was dismantled during the 1700s, however hardy sections can still be glimpsed, standing proudly as bastions of London’s ancient past.\r\n<br><br>\r\nUnbeknownst to many, a substantial portion of the wall remains within the courtyard of The Grange City Hotel on Cooper’s Row. The Roman wall here survives up to a height of 14.5 feet (4.4 metres) and is characterised by the normal arrangement of regular courses of dressed rag-stone, inter-spaced approximately every four courses with red tile bonding layers. \r\n<br></br>\r\nAs with much of London’s Roman wall, this section remained in use for many years after the Romans fled the city and abandoned Roman Britannia. During the Medieval period the wall was heightened by 21 feet (6.2 metres) and it is this part of the wall that still remains visible above modern ground level at Cooper’s Row.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe double staircase climbing visibly up the wall hints at the wall’s continued significance as a defensive structure, an impression strengthened by the arched loopholes which were to be used by archers should the city come under attack. Following the Medieval period, the wall began to lose its importance as a defensive structure and was slowly swallowed up by surrounding buildings. However, it is evident that some parts of the wall still retained an element of significance during this time, with Cooper’s Row itself owing its name to the coopers (barrel makers) who stored their casks in recesses of the city wall in this area.', 'wall14.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, '-0.076010', '51.509944', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(23, 'John Snow Public House', 'Situated at the junction of Lexington Street and Broadwick Street is The John Snow, a public house that has honoured its nineteenth-century namesake since 1958. This site proves both a historic and modern appreciation for the work on public health by Dr John Snow, making it an important piece of London’s medical and social history. Snow was credited with advancing epidemiology (the study of the spread of disease) and moving past outdated theories of contagion. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/John_Snow_memorial_and_pub.jpg\" alt=\"Dr John Snow\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Outside the pub on the corner was the pump which infected so many in the area with cholera and which led Snow to determine the reasons for cholera\'s spread.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe pub itself stands on Broadwick Street, previously known as Broad Street, around which Snow famously surveyed an outbreak of cholera in 1854. After successfully tracing the disease back to a contaminated water pump the handle was removed and instances of cholera, although already declining, continued to wane.\r\n<br></br>\r\nA replica of this handleless pump was erected nearby on Broadwick Street in 1992 and was, along with The John Snow and various commemorative plaques in the area, a popular icon of the physician’s important contributions to public health. The replica was removed in 2015 due to ongoing building improvements, however has yet to return and is instead marked by a piece of red granite. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/John-Snow.jpg\" alt=\"Dr John Snow\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Dr. John Snow (1813-1858), British physician.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\nBorn to a farming family in York, England in 1813, it can definitely be said that Snow was from humble beginnings. A commemorative plaque and water pump similar to those on Broadwick Street mark his origins in North Street, York, over 200 miles north of The John Snow in the capital. At the age of fourteen Snow worked as a medical apprentice in Newcastle, England, and witnessed the Newcastle cholera epidemic of 1831-32. Whether this peaked his interest in the prevalent and deadly disease is unclear, but nevertheless Snow went on to train as a physician in the years following. \r\n<br></br>\r\nHis prowess within medicine is evident from his various memberships of colleges and societies: the Royal College of Surgeons; the Westminster Medical Society (later the Medical Society of London); and a founding member of the London Epidemiological Society. During his life he published his findings in several papers, both on his epidemiological studies and pioneering experimentation on medical anaesthetic. \r\n<br></br>\r\nSnow’s curiosity of health and disease also infiltrated his personal life; he was a vegetarian, teetotaler, and purified his water through distillation. These quirks supposedly aided his health and he campaigned for them to be recognised, going as far as to refer to alcohol as a “physical evil” in an address given in 1836. Despite his health-conscious lifestyle, Snow died an early death aged only 45. The cause of death is speculated over; suggestions range from a stroke, to over-exposure to experimental chemicals, and even his extreme health-habits. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>Cholera and the Broad St. Pump</h2>\r\n\r\nCholera in the 1800s was rife due to poor sanitation and a lack of knowledge as to how exactly it could be contracted. Pandemics hit England and Scotland several times throughout the century and caused widespread panic due to the fast-acting nature of the disease. The main symptoms of cholera are vomiting and diarrhea, leading quickly to dehydration and potentially death when untreated. Anxiety over contagion lead to a Board of Health releasing local reports on supposed disease prevention. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark>The leading theory on how cholera spread was known as “miasma”, meaning “pollution” or bad air.</mark> It was thought that diseases could be spread by foul-smelling, toxic gases - a logical theory as disease appeared to spread faster around open sewage, rotten meat, rats, and generally poor conditions. The germ theory at this point had yet to be discovered, meaning advice tended towards moving away from the pollution.\r\n<br></br>\r\nJohn Snow published his contrary speculations on how cholera seemed to spread in his 1849 pamphlet entitled “On the Mode of Communication of Cholera”. He put forward that miasmic theory did not sufficiently explain the spreading pattern and time of symptoms known with cholera, meaning that the disease may not be spread by bad smells or inhalation of contaminated air.\r\n<br></br>\r\nHe posed that perhaps open sewers coming into contact with drinking water was to blame. After several case studies of parishes around the Thames, and also cities further afield, Snow published a more comprehensive text on his new theory. \r\n<br></br>\r\nInterestingly, of the several case studies looked at by Snow, the outbreak on Broad St. was one that did not originally fit his hypothesis. He tested the drinking water of the area and found it to be relatively pure, meaning he “hesitated to come to a conclusion”. After retesting, however, he found that the impurity of the water fluctuated from high to low, meaning his theory of water contamination causing the outbreak may have still been possible. \r\n<br></br>\r\nAfter acquiring a list of deaths from the Soho General Register Office Snow plotted the number of deaths caused by cholera in the area on a map, and found them to be concentrated around a water pump on Broad Street (only 10 of 83 deaths that he counted at this point occurred in houses closer to a different street pump than Broad Street - half of these cases informed Snow they drank from the Broad Street pump anyway, another 3 were likely to have attended a school near the pump). \r\n<br></br>\r\n<h6>Snow describes the famous conclusion and consequence:</h6>\r\n<i>The result of the inquiry was then was, that there had been no particular outbreak or increase in cholera, in this part of London, except among the persons that were in the habit of drinking the water of the above-mentioned pump well.I had an interview with the Board of Guardians of St. James’s parish, on the evening of Thursday, 7th September, and presented the above circumstances to them. In consequence of what I said, the handle of the pump was removed the following day. </i>\r\n<br></br>\r\nJohn Snow’s focus on practical prevention of cholera, rather than fruitlessly studying the disease itself, slowly ushered in a new era of public health. His understanding of water contamination as opposed to miasmic theory was slow to be accepted as it was a huge shift in thinking and had huge repercussions on everyday life (in the location of cesspits, for example). It would not be until Robert Koch discovered the bacterium responsible for cholera almost three decades later that Snow’s research was more readily accepted. \r\n\r\n<h2>Anaesthesia</h2>\r\nAlongside his research into the spread of cholera, John Snow is also credited with bringing medical anaesthesia into fashion. Having experimented using both ether and chloroform on animals, Snow studied the benefits and potential risks of both. He built on various designs of other scientists to perfect an “anaesthetic inhaler”, where the patient could simply breath in without worrying about correct concentrations and dosages. \r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1853 Snow administered chloroform to Queen Victoria during the birth of her eighth child, Leopold. Due to reservations over the new anaesthetic inhaler Snow used the “open-drop method”; where material would be placed over the patient’s nose and mouth and chloroform dropped on the surface so the patient can inhale the vapour. Snow’s casenotes describe the Queen after the birth to have been “very cheerful and well, expressing herself much gratified with the effect of the chloroform.” \r\n<br></br>\r\nHesitancies over numbing the pain of childbirth existed prior to this event due to biblical emphasis on the ‘curse of Eve’: having given into temptation in the Garden of Eden Eve would be cursed to have pain in childbirth. Some believed that the easing of this pain was deliberately going against the word of God, however Queen Victoria’s example paved the way for further use of medical anaesthesia in other types of surgery and dentistry as well as obstetrics.  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'john_snow.jpg', 1, 1, 0, 0, '-0.1387813', '51.5132742', 1, 1, 0, 0, '', ''),
(24, 'Hidden Little Compton Street', 'When exploring a city, we are often told to “look up” to admire the architecture of the buildings frequently taken for granted. I am telling you to look down. Walk into the middle of Charing Cross Road where an island opposes Old Compton Street and look down into the grate. A rusted and faded blue sign lingers beneath the busy road, marking the territory as “Little Compton Street”. How the sign got there is still a mystery, but we do know where it used to be.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Little-Compton-Street.jpg\" alt=\"Little Compton Sign\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>A traffic island on London’s Charing Cross Road. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe portion of Old Compton Street <mark>between Greek Street and Charing Cross Road</mark> was the domain of this humble Victorian street sign. Archival evidence dating back to 1763 speaks of assault charges and bail, however, insurance documents show that the street itself was wholly unremarkable such as a milliner at number 7 and a tobacconist at number 12.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nIt was at one of the many pubs along this street that two poets are said to have frequented on a regular basis to overdose on gin and absinthe. Around 1872, Paul Verlaine and Arthur Rimbaud ﬂed their native France to escape Verlaine’s wife and son and to embark upon what would <mark>become a volatile, torrid, and eventually life-threatening aﬀair.</mark> The exact location of this pub has been debated but the general consensus is that the Hibernia Stores on 5-7 Old Compton Street (now 23-25 Old Compton Street) was the setting for their frivolity.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/800px-Henri_Fantin-Latour_-_By_the_Table_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg\" alt=\"Little Compton Lovers\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Around 1872, Paul Verlaine (seated, far left) and Arthur Rimbaud (seated, second to left) ﬂed their native France to escape Verlaine’s wife and son and to embark upon what would become a volatile, torrid, and eventually life-threatening aﬀair. <i>Source: Painting by Henri Fantin-Latour / Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nA map dated March 1889, 16 years after the departure of Rimbaud and Verlaine, detail the layout of the miniature street. Complete with house numbers, we see that the area was ﬂooded with shops which are now restaurants and bars. The public house, on the other hand, still stands, over 200 years later. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Insurance%20plan%20map,%201889,%20showing%20shops%20(S),%20dwellings%20(D),%20hardware%20stores%20(H.W.)%20and%20a%20public%20house%20(P.H.).jpg\" alt=\"Little Compton Insurance Maps\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Insurance plan map, 1889, showing shops (S), dwellings (D), hardware stores (H.W.) and a public house (P.H.) <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe underground street sign now serves as a location prompt to utility workers as they scuttle beneath the whirring of the world overhead. However it is also a reminder that the romantic past of London shines through its electric urbanisation.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n', 'littlecamp.jpg', 1, 1, 0, 0, '-0.1294837', '51.5138757', 1, 1, 0, 0, '', '');
