(25, 'The Women’s Suffrage Movement', 'Throughout history, women have been subject to discrimination and mistreatment. As the world has evolved and progressed life has gradually improved for women thanks to the devoted, brave and determined efforts of women’s activists. <mark>In the early twentieth century the women\'s suffrage movement led this fight in the United Kingdom.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe 1832 Great Reform Act, defined British voters primarily as ‘male persons\'. Women were not permitted to vote due to their husbands, or male relatives, being responsible to represent their views in all political matters. This was the first time it had explicitly been stated by law that women were not allowed to vote. In that same year, <mark>the first petition on women’s suffrage was presented to Parliament by Mary Smith</mark>.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Mary-Smith.jpg\" alt=\"Mary Ellen Smith\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Mary Ellen Smith, from a 1918 publication. She was the first female Speaker in the British Empire.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nOver thirty years later, the election of John Stuart Mill in 1865 gave the suffragists hope for change and recognition, as Mill was believed to support the right for women to vote. However, <mark>the all-male House of Commons rejected John Stuart Mill’s Second Reform Bill petition, which contained over 1500 signatures</mark>. This petition, which would have allowed women to vote on the same property terms as men, was rejected by 194 votes to 73. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/John-Stuart-MIll.jpg\" alt=\"John Stuart Mill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Painting of John Stuart Mill. A member of the Liberal Party, he was also the first Member of Parliament to call for women\'s suffrage. <i>Source: George Frederic Watts / Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAfter the dismissal of this amendment, the women’s suffrage campaign gained momentum. This was evident in the formation of several formal suffrage societies across England and Ireland, which then amalgamated to form the National Society for Women\'s Suffrage (NSWS). <mark>The first public meeting about women’s suffrage was held in Manchester\'s Free Trade Hall in 1868</mark>. Among the audience was 15-year-old Emmeline Goulden, who was to become an ardent campaigner for women\'s rights, and who would later become the wife of Dr. Pankhurst, becoming Mrs Emmeline Pankhurst<.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/The_Free_Trade_Hall,_Manchester.jpg\" alt=\"The Free Trade Hall\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The first public meeting about women’s suffrage was held in Manchester\'s Free Trade Hall in 1868.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>The Suffragists</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nLittle progress was made by the suffragettes during the following years. In 1869, the Municipal Franchise Act provided single women ratepayers rights to vote in local elections; twenty-five years later, the 1895 Local Government Act permitted women who owned property the right to vote in local elections. Women, however, recognised that more could – and needed to – be done to grant them their basic political freedoms. Owing to the failure of the 1884 Third Reform Act and the ineffectiveness of the National Society for Women\'s Suffrage (NSWS), the NUWSS (National Union of Women\'s Suffrage Societies) spearheaded by Millicent Fawcett, was formed in 1897. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark>Known as ‘suffragists’</mark>, they employed a fair and legal approach in their campaign of convincing the government to give voting rights to middle-class property-owning women. This involved peace walks, petitions, confronting Members of Parliament, sharing pamphlets, conducting speeches, and letter writing campaigns. Their peaceful and gradualist nature was not only a reflection of their leader, who did not want women to be considered unfit for politics due to unruly behaviour, but also due to the structure of the leadership of the union which <mark>comprised mainly of middle-class women that were cautious of not ruining their reputation.</mark> \r\n</p>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Millicent-fawcett.jpg\" alt=\" Millicent Fawcett\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Picture of Millicent Fawcett at a speech.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Emmeline Pankhurst & the WSPU</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nImpatient with the gradualist approach, factions were created in the National Union of Women\'s Suffrage Societies. <mark>In 1903, some members of the union, led by Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughters Christabel and Sylvia, set up a separate society that became known as the Women\'s Social and Political Union (WSPU).</mark> Pankhurst believed drastic measures were required, and further claimed it would take an active organisation with working-class women to draw attention to the cause. This was the birth of a militant campaign with “Deeds not Words!” and “Votes for Women!” adopted as slogans.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Pankhurst-and-her-daughters.jpg\" alt=\"Pankhurst and her daughters.jpg\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>In 1903, some members of the union, led by Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughters Christabel and Sylvia, set up a separate society that became known as the Women\'s Social and Political Union (WSPU). <i>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n</p>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>The Suffragettes</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<mark>In October 1905, the arrest of Christabel Pankhurst and Annie Kenney at liberal meeting held at the Manchester Free Trade Hall marked the beginning of the militant campaign.</mark> Having interrupted the meeting of prominent liberal politicians by asking them what their stands were about women’s voting rights, they were charged with obstruction and spitting on a police officer. On refusal to pay the fine imposed by the court, they went to prison and this generated publicity for the cause. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Annie_Kenney_and_Christabel_Pankhurst.jpg\" alt=\"Annie and Christabel Pankhurst.jpg\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Annie Kenney and Christabel Pankhurst were dedicated suffragettes who paved the way for others. They were the first to be arrested, in Manchester in 1905.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<mark>In 1906, the Daily Mail coined the name ‘suffragette’ to describe the predominantly younger women who advocated more radical tactics.</mark> The “ette” ending was supposed to belittle Annie Kenney and her fellow WSPU members. Instead, the WSPU proudly adopted the name, saying \"suffraGETtes\" (stressing the GET while they pronounced the term), to imply that they were adamant to achieve their goals. From 1909, the sale of the \"Pank-A-Squith\" (Pankhurst and Asquith) board game was used to raise money and gain publicity for the cause. The board game’s principle strategy required players to lead their suffragette figure from their home to Parliament, past the obstacles faced from Prime Minister H. H. Asquith, and the Liberal government.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/banners.jpg\" alt=\"WSPU\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>WSPU Members making banners<i>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIt may be surprising to discover that the suffrage campaign was not simply a feminine movement, meaning that principles were not only fought for by women. <mark>Many men were committed to the cause, and actively participated in the campaign.</mark> Notable examples include Frederick Pethick-Lawrence, George Lansbury MP, and Keir Hardie MP who regularly raised the issue of women enfranchisement in the House of Commons. \r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1906, James Keir Hardie introduced Frederick and Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence to Emmeline Pankhurst.<mark> An apartment in Clement’s Inn, between Lincoln’s Inn Fields and Aldwych was home to them both, and it became the headquarters of the fledgling Women’s Social and Political Union (WSPU)</mark>. With the organisation only admitting female members, Frederick was not an official member. As a barrister, he represented WSPU in legal matters and stood bail for more than one-hundred members.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/1.jpg\" alt=\"Clement Inn\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Mrs Emmeline Pankhurst and Mrs Mabel Tuke photographed in Mrs Pankhurst\'s office in Clements Inn.<i>Source: LSE Library / Available on Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Frederick and Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence</h4>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe couple contributed to the proper structure and organisation of WSPU, with Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence being credited as the originator of the WSPU campaign colours, purple, white and green; she memorably described as ‘purple for dignity, white for purity and green for hope’ in 1908. They were also committed in giving WSPU sizeable financial contributions. In 1907, Frederick founded the WSPU periodical, ‘Votes for Women’ with Emmeline and himself as joint editors. This periodical, which sold over 20,000 copies each week, helped recruit WSPU members and win public support for the cause. \r\n<br></br>\r\nIn 1912, large-scale smashing of shop windows along Oxford Street, led to the arrest of the couple even though they had nothing to do with the event. They were made culpable for the event and sentenced to nine-months’ imprisonment. Sued for the cost of the damage, they went in to a period of bankruptcy. With Emmeline in Holloway Prison, and Frederick in Brixton Prison, both were force-fed, and subjected to ill-treatment. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<mark>In October 1912, Emmeline and Frederick were expelled from the WSPU for they were no longer in agreement with the extreme militant tactics.</mark> Despite the split, they were still loyal and committed to the cause. Both continued to edit and publish ‘Votes for Women’ and their Clement’s Inn home in London which served as office for WSPU continued to serve as a recuperating clinic for suffragettes who had just been released from the prison.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Pethick-couple.jpg\" alt=\"The Couple\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Frederick Pethick Lawrence (far left) and His wife, Emmeline (far right). <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Sophia - The Suffragette Princess</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nBorn in Belgravia in 1876, Princess Sophia Duleep Singh, the daughter of an exiled Punjabi Maharaja and the treasured goddaughter of Queen Victoria, was a prominent woman of colour and a pivotal figure in the women’s suffrage movement. It was not until she and her sisters sneaked into India in 1903, to see the celebration of the accession of King Edward VII, that she changed from a vacuous socialite to a political activist. \r\n<br></br>\r\nOn her visit to India, she came face to face with all that her family had lost, saw abject poverty and experienced racism at first hand. She attributed these factors to the severity of the British colonial rule. <mark>In 1909, Singh came back to England with an awakened sense of dispossession, and discovered the appeal for votes for women irresistible, and so she soon joined the Women’s Social and Political Union.</mark>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Sophia-and-Her-Sisters.jpg\" alt=\"Sophia\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>The last of the empire: Daughters of Maharajah Duleep Singh; Bamba, Catherine and Sophia — photographed in 1892. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAs a suffragette, Singh donated and raised vast amounts of money for the organisation, including when violence and arson attacks were prominent. Singh vandalised her census paper, defied court judgments awarded against her, and as a member of the Women’s Tax Resistance league, refused to pay her taxes. Living in Hampton Court in an apartment in Faraday House, given to her by Queen Victoria, she sold the suffragette’s newspaper ‘The Vote’ outside Hampton Court. \r\n<br></br>\r\nOn one occasion, she threw herself at Prime Minister Asquith’s car, slamming a ‘Votes for Women’ pamphlet against his window but was released without charge. Despite Singh\'s activism as a suffragette, <mark>she was never arrested as she was a royal and her arrest would have attracted maximum attention to an ‘unwanted’ political cause</mark>. Singh marched next to Emmeline on 18 November 1910, an event that would become known as the Black Friday.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Sophia-selling-paperss.jpg\" alt=\"Sophia\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Princess Sophia Duleep Singh selling subscriptions for the Suffragette newspaper outside Hampton Court in London, April 1913. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>\r\n<h2>Suffragettes, Violence and Militancy</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nMembers of the Suffragettes were prepared to use violence to reach their designed goal of women’s political freedoms. Their militant tactics involved the interruption of anti-suffrage ministers, arson attacks on post box contents and empty public places, and window smashing. <mark>To protest the Church of England, who were not in support of women’s voting rights, the WSPU were known to place bombs inside Westminster Abbey, St. Paul’s Cathedral and other Anglican churches.</mark> \r\n<br></br>\r\nGolf courses, cricket pitches, horse racing tracks and places where the affluent frequented were also destroyed when unattended. On 19 February 1913, one of the two bombs which was targeted at Pinfold Manor in Surrey, which was being built for Chancellor of the exchequer, David Lloyd-George, exploded, causing significant damage. Further targets included train stations, houses of anti-suffrage ministers, and libraries.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sufragettes-arson-attacks.jpg\" alt=\"Destruction\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Police survey Saunderton Railway Station after a suffragette arson attack, March 9th, 1913. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Black Friday</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nIn 1908, owing to the absence of Prime Minister Herbert Asquith, 500,000 activists rallied through Hyde Park in London and proceeded towards Downing Street. <mark>Suffragettes continued to damage property in Downing Street and further chained themselves to railings at the Prime Minister’s residence to gain the Prime Minister’s attention.</mark> On 18 November 1910, despite making it to the second reading, Prime Minister Herbert Asquith decided not to proceed with the Conciliation Bill, which would have provided women with the ability to vote. This response was met with a protest from suffragettes, who viciously protested outside Parliament. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/march.jpg\" alt=\"Destruction\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>In 1908, owing to the absence of Prime Minister Herbert Asquith, 500,000 activists rallied through Hyde Park in London and proceeded towards Downing Street. <i>Source: BBC</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nDue to the involvement of police and male vigilantes, the protest resulted in failure. Many women became injured and some protesters lost their lives for the cause. Many male and female protesters were also arrested during the rally. Marked as the <mark>‘Black Friday of British women’s suffrage campaign’,</mark> the rally on 18 November 1910 gained publicity and sympathetic support for the WSPU, and increased support from newspapers through pictures of unarmed women being assaulted.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/The Daily Mirror.jpg\" alt=\"The Daily Mirror\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>The front page of The Daily Mirror, 19 November 1910, showing a suffragette on the ground, having been hit by a policeman. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n<p>\r\n<h2>Boycotting the Census</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nOn the 2nd April 1911, the Suffragette organisation urged women to boycott the census, which was controlled by the Liberal government. With the rallying call of, <mark>“If women don’t count, neither shall they be counted”,</mark> the censuses boycott emerged from the Women’s Freedom League campaign for non-violent ‘passive resistance’ against the government. This saw many women deface their census schedule, or spend the night away from home to avoid being counted. Women kept moving from place to place, hid, or gathered at the home of a census resister. One house in Manchester resulted in it being renamed “census lodge”, as it housed many census evaders. \r\n<br></br>\r\nIn London, some gathered for a midnight picnic of roast fowl, sweetmeats and tea at Wimbledon Common. Others spent the night walking, talking and singing at Trafalgar Square. A vegetarian restaurant in Covent Garden stayed open to provide refreshments. In many parts of the nation – namely Cardiff, Bristol, Liverpool, Ipswich, Cheltenham, Reading and Maidstone – <mark>suffragettes hosted overnight events with the sole purpose of boycotting the census.</mark> \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Census.jpg\" alt=\"Boycotting the Census\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Suffragettes gathered in Manchester Census Lodge to Boycott the 1911 Census. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nMany women vandalised the census by defacing their forms or by completing them with inappropriate answers. One notable example includes Mary Howey of Hertfordshire, who inscribed a large “votes for women” on her form, and listed her occupation as “artist and suffragette”. Another example includes Miss Davies, a suffragette from Birkenhead who wrote on her form the name of a male servant, and added that there were no other persons present within the home. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/census-slip.jpg\" alt=\"Boycotting the Census\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>The Census form has been returned blank and in place of household details, a large \'Votes for Women\' flyer has been stuck. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe same night, Emily Wilding Davison, who would tragically lose her life two years later, hid in a broom cupboard in the Houses of Parliament for 46 hours. Though caught and arrested she was released without charge. Boycotting the census showed a lot of courage as protesters expected a fine of £5 or a month’s imprisonment. However, no person was prosecuted, theoretically due to the large-scale number of suffragettes involved, and due to the criticism, that would have occurred if this was the case.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nNevertheless, public outrage towards the suffragettes was present. A letter to The Times labelled the boycott as a \"crime against science\", while the political magazine Punch joked: \"the suffragettes have definitely taken leave of their census\". Despite many women boycotting the census, their efforts were negligible in nullifying the census as many were counted while on the streets and some households listed the name of their missing occupants. Nevertheless, whilst it did not nullify the census results it gave public attention to the injustices of the British voting system, the suffragette movement and its campaign for ‘Votes for Women’. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Force Feeding the suffragettes</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nBetween 1905 and 1914, around 1000 suffragettes had been arrested and given prison sentences of anywhere from 3 days to several months. However, suffragettes were willing to go to prison, and some used hunger strikes as a powerful tool to protest their arrest and to demand the status of political suffragettes in custody. <mark>The Government’s response to hunger strikes were to force-feed those who participated, this involved individuals being strapped down and a tube unpleasantly forced down the throat or nostril to ensure that food could be pumped into the stomach.</mark>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/forcefeeding.jpg\" alt=\"Boycotting the Census\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Forceful Feeding through the nose of women suffragists prisoners pronounced as dangerous by many leading members of the medical profession. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nForce feeding suffragettes not only caused a public outcry, as forced feeding was traditionally used to feed criminal inmates, but the demeaning and dangerously invasive procedure damaged the long-term health of victims. For example, Lady Constance Lytton, who disguised herself as a ‘Jane Warton’ to gather evidence on differential treatment, was force-fed several times and never fully recovered from her ordeal. Lytton suffered a stroke in 1912 and died in 1923. This ultimately gained publicity for the women’s suffrage campaign.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>The Cat and Mouse Act</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nIn 1913, with the motive of preventing suffragettes from dying as martyrs in police custody, the government introduced the Prisoners Temporary Discharge for Ill Health Act, commonly known as the ‘Cat and Mouse Act’. <mark>It was designed to provide for the release of suffragettes whose hunger strikes and forced feeding had brought them illness, as well as their arrest and re-imprisonment as soon as they had regained strength.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\nIn response to the ‘Cat and Mouse Act’, Edith Garrud, who was one of the western world’s first female martial arts teachers, taught self-defence classes that protected women from being rearrested and sent back to jail. Garrud was known to protect prominent members, such as Emmeline Pankhurst. Members of Garrud’s classes orchestrated the \"escapes\" of several suffragettes from police surveillance during 1913 and early 1914. The \"Battle of Glasgow\" was one of the notable events in which suffragettes were violent with the police. This saw about thirty suffragettes clash with an estimated fifty police officers on the stage of St. Andrew\'s Hall in Glasgow, Scotland.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Cat-and-Mouse-Act.jpg\" alt=\"Boycotting the Census\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>The Cat and Mouse Act gained notoriety amongst women\'s suffrage organisations in the UK in the early 1910s. <i>Source: Schlesinger Library on the History of Women in America</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Emily Wilding Davidson: The \"Suffragette\" Derby</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nOn 4th June 1913, the London born Emily Wilding Davidson, who had been arrested nine times and force-fed forty-nine times, decided to disrupt the Epsom Derby to draw attention to the women’s suffrage campaign. <mark>Davidson famously stepped out in front of Anmer, a horse owned by King George which resulted in her being knocked down.</mark> She died after four days due to a fractured skull and internal injuries. Owing to reports, it was not clear if she intended to kill herself for the cause. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Emily.jpg\" alt=\"Emily Davidson\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>In 1906, Emily Davison joined Emmeline Pankhurst\'s \"Women\'s Social Political Union (WSPU). She was a brave and sometimes violent campaigner. She broke up meetings and carried out arson attacks.  <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nWith a return train ticket and a ticket to a dance slated for the evening in her bag, reports suggested she possibly wanted to attach a WSPU banner to the horse’s bridle. Her death was iconic to the women’s suffrage campaign and she became a martyr to the cause. Thousands of women attended her funeral and lined the streets as her coffin was moved to its final resting place. She was laid to rest at Morpeth, Northumberland, and her grave was inscribed with the suffragette’s “Deeds Not Words” slogan.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/derby.jpg\" alt=\"Emily Davidson\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>On June 4, Emily Wilding Davison stepped onto the track at the Epsom Derby and collided with King George V’s horse, Anmer. She suffered a fractured skull and died four days later died days later. <i>Image: Arthur Barrett/Hulton Archive/Getty Images</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>The First World War</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nIn August 1914, the First World War began. As a result, the Government released the suffragette prisoners, and Emmeline Pankhurst convinced her fellow suffragettes to suspend their militant activities and actively support the government in war efforts as a united nation. <mark>Around one-million women took up men’s work while they fought in the Great War.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/World-War-5.jpg\" alt=\"World War\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Emmeline Pankhurst convinced her fellow suffragettes to suspend their militant activities and actively support the government in war efforts as a united nation. <i> Image: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nWhether it was due to the sympathy, the support the suffrage got from the public or women’s vital contribution during the war, one thing was certain; a new reform had to be passed to modernise political standings and include women in the nation’s vital political decisions. Many of the returning soldiers were no longer entitled to vote, as they did not meet existing property qualifications.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/World-war.jpg\" alt=\"World War\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>A female munitions worker in a British factory during World War One, which was one of the catalysts for women finally getting the vote.  <i> Image: Tom Marshall/mediadrumworld.com</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe need for the enfranchisement of women was also finally recognised by most members of parliament from all three major parties. Therefore, on 6th February 1918, the Representation of the People Act was passed. This extended suffrage to men over the age of twenty-one (removing most property qualifications), British women over the age of 30 that were property owners, members of the local government register, and university graduates. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<h2>...and Finally</h2>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nOn 21st November 1918, the Parliament (Qualification of Women Act) 1918 was passed. This allowed women to be elected to Parliament. The main reason for the age differential was to ensure that, following the loss of men in the war, women did not become the majority voters. Even though just over eight million women met this criterion, it only represented forty-percent of the total population of women in the nation. Furthermore, in 1928, the Representation of the People (Equal Franchise) Act granted all women over the age of twenty-one voting rights. <mark>This was the first time that women had achieved electoral equality with men.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/woman.jpg\" alt=\"Freedom\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><sub><q>Finally in 1918, Parliament passed an act granting the vote to women over the age of 30 who were householders, the wives of householders, occupiers of property and graduates of British universities. About 8.4 million women gained the vote.  <i> Image: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>', 'womansufferage.jpg', 1, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, 0, 1, 0, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(26, 'Suffragette Memorial - ChristChurch Gardens London', 'A picturesque scroll is located here at Christchurch gardens to commemorate the two largest organisations present in the fight for women\'s political freedoms: The Women\'s Social and Political Union, and the Women\'s Freedom League.', 'SuffragetteMemorial-ChristChurchGardensLondon.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.1348329', '51.4982036', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(27, 'Statue of Millicent Fawcett', 'Millicent Fawcett is nationally renowned as a prominent campaigner for the political rights of women in the first half of the Twentieth Century. This statue of Fawcett is the first statue of a female within Parliament Square. This statue is also significant for including the name and pictures of up to fifty-eight prominent Suffragettes, or Suffragette supporters. ', 'StatueofMillicentFawcett.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.1270455', '51.5006009', 0, 0, 2, 0, '', ''),
(28, 'Monument to Emmeline Pankhurst', 'Similarly, Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughter Christabel Pankhurst can be commemorated in Victoria Tower Gardens, where a statue of Emmeline was erected in 1930.', 'emmelinepankhurststatue2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 25, '-0.1253285', '51.4979196', 1, 0, 2, 0, '', ''),
(29, 'George Lansbury Stone', 'As a vicious fighter for the rights of women, who merits recognition, George Lansbury\'s plaque is located here on 39 Bow Road. This is the former childhood home of the Labour politician Lansbury, whose unwavering support of the Women\'s Social and Political Union resulted in brief imprisonment. ', 'GeorgeLansburyStone.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.0273469', '51.5267492', 0, 0, 2, 0, '', ''),
(30, 'Caxton Hall', 'Caxton Hall was previously used by the Suffragettes as a base for the Women\'s Social and Political Union, the leading political group in the fight for women\'s rights. The WSPU has been linked to the organisation of hunger strikes, vandalism or arson. It is believed that Caxton Hall was used while the women members of the WSPU protested the male governing bodies of Westminster, notably through marches in Parliament Square.', 'CaxtonHall.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.1349106', '51.4985576', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(31, 'Annie Besant Plaque', 'Formally a factory of female workers, this building has been renovated into living accommodation for the residents of London. One thing that is less known about this building, however, is that this factory had a unique heritage associated with the suffragette movement. A plaque for Annie Besant is situated here in memory of her unwavering determination in the fight for women\'s working rights.', 'AnnieBesantPlaque.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 25, '-0.0223754', '51.5311017', 0, 0, 2, 0, '', ''),
(32, 'St George\'s Church', 'Famous for sacrificing her life by throwing herself under the King\'s house on June 14, 1913, Emily Davidson was remembered and commemorated at St George\'s Church on Bloomsbury Way by thousands before her burial in Northumberland.', 'St.GeorgesChurch.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.1245691', '51.5175917', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(33, 'Brompton Cemetery -Emmeline Pankhurst grave', 'Emmeline Pankhurst was a leading individual in the Suffragette movement. Her grave is located within Brompton Cemetery, where she can be respectfully remembered and commemorated by members of the public.', 'BromptonCemetery-emmelinepankhurstgrave2.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.1891906', '51.4839606', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(34, 'Minnie Lansbury Memorial', 'Minnie Lansbury, the first wife of Edgar Lansbury, died in 1922 while imprisoned for a dispute regarding tax in an area of poverty. Landsbury joined the Suffragette movement in 1915, and was elected alderman for a Labour Council in 1919. Her efforts and bravery are commemorated and remembered through a clock in her name located on Bow Road. Angela Lansbury, daughter of Edgar Lansbury, famously contributed a donation to ensure the restoration of the clock in 2008.', 'MinnieLansburyMemorial.jpg', 0, 0, 0, 25, '-0.0281776', '51.5271379', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(35, 'The National Gallery', 'Founded in 1824, The National Gallery is one of the World’s most visited Art Museums and houses a collection of over 2,300 paintings which date from the mid-13th Century to the 1900’s.\r\n\r\n<br><br><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\nThe Gallery holds a collection of paintings from a range of important historical artistic movements, by prolific painters such as Jan Van Eyck, Michelangelo, Rembrandt, Monet and Van Gogh, to name just a few! \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFor any art enthusiasts out there, The National Gallery is a MUST when visiting the city. It is also worth noting, that the National Portrait Gallery (which we have a separate Museum checklist on) is also right around the corner, so be sure not to miss out on some incredible, and important historical pieces on your next visit to Trafalgar Square! \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/the-national-gallery-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"The National Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The National Gallery <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Entry Fee: </h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThis Gallery is free to enter. Temporary exhibitions may, however, have an admission free, so please check online before visiting.\r\n\r\n<h4>Opening times:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nFrom Monday-Sunday, the Gallery is open from 10am-6pm. On Fridays the Gallery is open later from 10am-pm.\r\n\r\n<h4>Photography allowed:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, Photography is allowed in the Gallery. However, please do not use flash due to the delicate condition and age of some of the paintings. (Photography in temporary exhibitions may be different, so please ask a museum steward upon your visit).\r\n\r\n<h4>Interactive technology:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nDue to the age of the Gallery, there are no interactive technologies available.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Facilities for kids:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA range of family audio tours of the gallery are available, so please see the link below if you are interested in possibly booking one of these tours.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/families/family-tours\" target=\"_blank\"> Family Tours </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Guides:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, The Gallery does offer a range of audio tours which cover both the main collection and special exhibitions. Please see the link below for more information:  \r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/audio-guides\" target=\"_blank\"> Guides </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<h4>1. The Water-Lily Pond (1899) By Claude-Oscar Monet </h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/the-national-gallery-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"The National Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Water-Lily Pond <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAs the World’s most famous Impressionist artists, of course, Monet had to make an appearance amongst the must-see paintings at the National Gallery. Born in 1840 in Paris, France, Monet was a founder of French impressionist painting and practitioner of the movements philosophy of expressing one’s individual perception of nature- hence the unique and iconic style of painting which we all recognise in Monet’s work today. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAs a result of this, Monet was heavily inspired by nature and created a variety of stunning pieces influenced by the beauty of his home in Giverny, The Water-Lily Pond which is currently on display at the National Gallery is in fact, one of those paintings. At the end of his life, Monet found the subject matter for his art in the gardens of his home, specifically, the water-lily pond and the beautiful Japanese Bridge he constructed across it. This piece is one of seventeen other paintings which Monet began to paint in 1899, which feature the beautiful pond and bridge. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>2. Sunflowers (1888) By Vincent Van Gogh:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/the-national-gallery-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"The National Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Sunflowers (1888) By Vincent Van Gogh <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSticking with the impressionist theme, is this beautiful iconic painting by Vincent Van Gogh, a Dutch post-impressionist painter, who is one of he most famous and influential figures in the history of Western Art. Creating about 2,100 pieces of art in just ten years, Van Gogh’s paintings are characterised by their bold colours, expressive brush-strokes, and a tragic and complex personal history behind them. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nBorn in 1853 in Zundert, Netherlands, Van Gogh had a history of Mental Illness and following a lack of commercial success when he was alive, he lived a life of poverty and subsequently committed suicide in 1890 aged just thirty-seven. Van Gogh painted Sunflowers in 1888, and the painting is primarily yellow- which he associated with hope and friendship.  \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nHe suggested that his four Sunflowers canvases express an ‘idea symbolising gratitude’, and was thought to have been pleased with the outcome, as he hung the painting in the guest bedroom of his home in Arles in anticipation of the arrival of his friend, Paul Gauguin (A French post-impressionistic artist)  \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>3. The Arnolfini Portrait (1434) By Jan Van Eyck </h4><p class=\"text-justify\"> \r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/the-national-gallery-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"The National Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Arnolfini Portrait (1434) By Jan Van Eyck <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPainted in 1434 by EARLY Netherlandish painter Jan Van Eyck, The Arnolfini Portrait is considered one of the most original and complex paintings in Western art due to its beauty, iconography and picture space-with Eycks complex use of the mirror. Painted on an oak panel using oil paints, this portrait depicts Giovanni di Nicolao Arnolfini and his wife to record their wedding. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nArnolfini was a member of an Italian merchant family from Lucca, who was living in Bruges- the interior is well-appointed suggesting an element of wealth. A fun-fact about the painting is if you look closely, just above the mirror, there are words written in Latin, which basically translates to ‘Jan van Eyck was here, 1434’. This quirky feature is not accidental as Van Eyck would often inscribe his pictures in a witty way.  \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h4>Food and Drink facilities:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, there are food and drink facilities at the National Gallery. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe National Dining Rooms offer stunning views across Trafalgar Square and the Menu offers the best in British Produce. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe National Café offers all day dining, with a self-service Café. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThere is also an Espresso Bar which offers visitors a range of hot-drinks and cakes. \r\n\r\n<br>\r\n<h4>Tours:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA free daily guided tour is available daily from 2-3pm, which gives visitors a 60-minute taster tour of the collection. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/families/family-tours\" target=\"_blank\"> Family Tours </a>\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Nearest station/Tube:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe nearest tube stations are Charing Cross (approx. a 3-5-minute walk) and Leicester Square (approx. a 6-minute walk).\r\n\r\n<h4>Bus routes:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nRoutes 3, 6, 9, 11, 13, 15, 23, 24, 87, 91, 139, and 176 stops at Trafalgar Square.\r\n\r\n<h4>Postcode/address:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe National Gallery, Trafalgar Square, London WC2N 5DN.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/the-national-gallery-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"The National Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Leonardo da Vinci, The Virgin of the Rocks <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nVisitors with disabilities can get discounts on tickets for temporary exhibitions and can also bring an escort free of charge.\r\n<br> <br>\r\nThere is a single parking space on Orange Street for Blue Badge holders only. Please book at-least 48 hours in advance by calling 020 7747 2590.\r\n<br><br>\r\nMore general information about Accessibility can be found via the link below; \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/access\" target=\"_blank\"> Access </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe Gallery offers British Sign Language-interpreted talks on paintings for visitors who are deaf or hard-of-hearing. \r\n<br>\r\nAll Information Desks have induction loops, and large print transcripts for the Exhibitions are also available to collection when you visit.\r\n<br>\r\nPlease ring the number below to order one; \r\n<br>\r\n020 7747 2885\r\n<br>\r\nPlease see link below for more in-depth information about accessibility at the Gallery; \r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/access/deaf-or-hard-of-hearing-visitors\" target=\"_blank\"> For Deaf or Hard of Hearing Visitors </a>\r\n \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted: </h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nAn audio tour featuring 23 highlight paintings from the collection, offering detailed and evocative descriptions of art works. This tour is available free of charge. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nDescriptive folders are available at the Portico Information Desk and can be made available at other desks on request, prior to, or during visits. These are free to use but must be returned. Each folder focuses on two paintings including descriptive text and interpretation in either large print (featuring photographic reproductions of close-up sections of the painting) or Braille (including tactile images).\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nAssistance Dogs are welcome at the Gallery, and Water is available upon request. \r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nArt sessions for visitors who are blind and partially sighted are also available at the Gallery.  \r\n<br><br>\r\nPlease see link below for more in-depth information about accessibility at the Gallery; \r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/access/blind-and-partially-sighted-visitors\" target=\"_blank\"> For Blind or Partially Sighted Visitors </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/the-national-gallery-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"The National Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The National Gallery <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\nThe Getty, Sainsbury Wing, National Café and Pigott Education Centre entrance all have level access (The Main Portico entrance does not, as it is a Grade 1 listed building and cannot be adapted)\r\n<br> <br>\r\nWheelchairs are available at the Gallery, if you require one please book advance via the number below;\r\n<br><br>\r\n020 7747 2590 \r\n<br><br>\r\nSeating is available all around the Gallery, and stools are available from the information desk and Sainsbury Wing cloakroom upon request (you are also welcome to bring a folding stool).\r\n<br> <br>\r\nPlease see link below for more in-depth information about accessibility at the Gallery;\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/visiting/access/visitors-with-mobility-access-requirements\" target=\"_blank\"> For visitors with mobility impairments </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'the-national-gallery-image1-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1601986', '51.4862408', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(37, 'Big Ben', 'Rising majestically from the north end of the Palace of Westminster is the \'Clock Tower\' as it was originally called, this changed in 2012 when it was renamed \'Elizabeth Tower\' in recognition of Queen Elizabeth II\'s Diamond Jubilee. However, to millions of people around the world it will always be called \'Big Ben\'.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>A picture of Big Ben. <i>Source: James Cullen // Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\'Big Ben\' is actually the name for the largest of the 5 bells contained within Elizabeth Tower, it weighs 13.7 tonnes and at one point was the largest bell in England standing over 2.2 metres tall and 2.7 metres wide.  It was cast at the Whitechapel Bell Foundry in East London on 10th April 1858.  The chimes you hear on the hour are believed to have been inspired by an aria (I Know that My Redeemer Liveth) in Handels \'Messiah\'. Try saying these words over the chimes.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>The Clock tower, standing 96 meters tall. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe Clock Tower was completed on 31 May 1859, it stands 96 metres tall and contains 11 floors. 334 steps take you up to the belfry, however, under renovation plans a lift will be installed for visitors not quite fancying the climb.  Although currently closed for the renovation, tours are believed to be resuming in 2020 if everything goes to schedule. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe tower was designed by the rather grand sounding Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin, an English architect who also designed the interior of the Palace of Westminster as well as churches in England, Ireland and as far away as Australia.  He died in 1852 and never seen his finished masterpiece.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\nEach clock face on the tower is 23ft (seven metres) in diameter and composed of around 312 sections of opal glass. An hour hand is 9.2ft (2.8m) in length; a minute hand is 14ft (4.3m).\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/big-ben-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Big Ben\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Big Ben Clock Face. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nBy looking at Big Ben you can easily tell when parliament is in session.  Above the clockface is a light called the \'Ayrton Light\', this is illuminated during the times parliament is in session.  At present it has been switched of due to renovation works.<br><br>\r\nBig Ben is sure to remain a cultural British icon for many years to come.  It has however skirted with catastrophe. During the Second World War a German bomb clipped the top of the tower during a raid doing minor structural damage but thankfully not enough to bring her down.\r\n', 'big-ben-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1246254', '51.5007292', 1, 1, 0, 0, 'Westminster, London, UK', '');
