(43, 'National Army Museum', 'Adjacent to the Royal Hospital Chelsea (the home of the Chelsea pensioners) the National Army Museum is the central museum for the history of the British Army. Reopened in 2017 after a £23.74 million re-development programme, the museum is the perfect location for those wishing to explore the extensive and thought-provoking history of the British Army through five themes ‘Soldier, Army, Battle, Society and Insight’. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is also worth noting that the museum is interactive in its exploration of important themes, which makes it a unique and ideal location for families and schools to visit.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-1.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>The National Army Museum was first conceived in the late 1950s, and owes its existence to the persistent hard work of Field Marshal Sir Gerald Templer, who did most of the fundraising for it. <i>Source: Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-2.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>It was established by Royal Charter in 1960, with the intention of collecting, preserving, and exhibiting objects and records relating to the Regular and Auxiliary forces of the British Army and of the Commonwealth, and to encourage research into their history and traditions. <i>Source: National Army Museum // Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-3.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>The museum tells the story of the British Army from the time of the Battle of Agincourt to the early 21st century. <i>Source: National Army Museum </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Entry Fee: </h4>\r\nThis museum is free to enter. \r\n<h4>Opening times:</h4>\r\nThe museum is open Monday-Sunday (10am-5:30pm)  \r\n<h4>Photography allowed:</h4>\r\nYes, photography is allowed at this museum. However, flash is not allowed due to the age of some of the exhibits.\r\n<h4>Interactive technology:</h4>\r\nYes, this museum provides a wonderful and interactive experience for visitors by using technology to obtain an uniquely personal journey through the museums several themes.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/exhibition.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>A book on the work of Abram Games during the Second World War, written by his daughter Naomi Games, will be available to purchase in The Shop at £16.99. #AbramGames <i>Source: National Army Museum </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Facilities for kids:</h4>\r\nAs previously mentioned, the museum is unique in its use of technology and interactive exhibits which make important topics relatable and more understandable for younger audiences. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/families\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Families </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Guides:</h4>\r\nA guidebook is available to buy in the souvenir shop, or online. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h1>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h1> \r\n\r\n<h4>1. Napoleon’s Horse ‘Marengo’ (1831):</h4> \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Napoleon-Horse-Marengo.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Napoleon\'s horse Marengo, National Army Museum, London. <i>Source: National Army Museum // Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYes, you saw that right, the Skeleton of Napoleon’s actual horse is on display in the Battle gallery of the museum! As horses were historically crucial to aiding soldiers in battle, it comes as no surprise that Marengo saw the notorious Emperor through some of his greatest triumphs and defeats in his history as ruler of France.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA grey Arab horse by breed, Marengo was named after the French victory at Marengo (in Italy) in 1800, however, he was captured by the British following French defeat at Waterloo and died in 1831. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>2. The Robes of Lawrence of Arabia (1916):</h4> \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/The-Robes-of-Lawrence-of-Arabia.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Robes belonging to T.E Lawrence: These are the actual robes worn by Colonel Thomas Edward Lawrence (1888 - 1935) during the first world war. He was also know as Lawrence of Arabia. <i>Source: National Army Museum // Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFew soldiers have greater legend and cultural iconography attached to them quite like Colonel TE Lawrence, otherwise known as Lawrence of Arabia. Posted to Hejaz (in modern Saudi Arabia) in the First World War liaise with the Hashemite forces, Lawrence’s unique diplomatic skills and willingness to adapt to the cultural norms of his foreign allies made him popular amongst Arab leaders, which led to the great success of his campaign and gave birth to the consequential legend.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLawrence’s adoption of Arab dress and culture was unique for the period and fascinated the public, sealing the distinct imagery we now see in films such as ‘Lawrence of Arabia’ (1962). The silk robe on display in the museum was worn by Lawrence in 1916, and the jambiya dagger attached to the robe was awarded to him following the attack of Aqaba – Don’t miss out on seeing a real glimpse into the legend in the ‘Army’ gallery of the museum.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>3. Signboard from ‘Hellfire Corner’ in Ypres (1918)</h4> \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Signboard-from-Hellfire-Corner-in-Ypres.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Wooden painted signboard from \'Hellfire Corner\' at Ypres, 1918. This sign was used to mark \'Hellfire Corner\', a busy junction on the Menin Road, which ran from Ypres in Belgium to the frontline trenches. It was a very dangerous place, being within easy range of the German guns. <i>Source: National Army Museum // Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWooden painted signboard from \'Hellfire Corner\' at Ypres, 1918. This sign was used to mark \'Hellfire Corner\', a busy junction on the Menin Road, which ran from Ypres in Belgium to the frontline trenches. It was a very dangerous place, being within easy range of the German guns.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs we are now in the final year of the centenary of the First World War it only seems fitting to mention this signboard, which is a clear representation of the destruction caused by war and a symbol of why we must continue to remember all those who have lost their lives as a result.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocated in Ypres (Belgium) British soldiers dubbed a busy junction on a road that led to the trenches ‘Hellfire Corner’ where this exact signboard stood. The damage to the sign is a testament to its location’s namesake, as a dozen bullet holes are scattered across the board, acting as a clear reminder of the human cost of warfare.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Food and Drink facilities:</h4> \r\nYes, this museum has a café (Open Monday to Friday 10am-4pm and Saturday to Sunday 10am-5pm) \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Tours:</h4> \r\nA highlights tour guide is available on the National Army Museum website (please see the link below) \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/plan-visit/highlights-tour\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Highlights </a>\r\n<br />\r\nGroup and private tours are also available (please see the link below) \r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/plan-visit/groups/enquiry-form\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Group Tours </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Nearest station/Tube:</h4> \r\nThe nearest tube station is Sloane Square, which is a 10-minute walk from the museum. \r\n\r\n<h4>Bus routes:</h4> \r\nBus 107 stops outside the museum.\r\n\r\n<h4>Postcode/address:</h4> \r\nNational Army Museum, Royal Hospital Road, Chelsea, London, SW3 4HT.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-4.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br> <sub><q>Visitors in Special Forces Exhibition <i>Source: National War Museum </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-5.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <br><sub><q>Special forces exhibition <i>Source: National War Museum </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/national-army-museum-6.jpg\" alt=\"National Army Museum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <br><sub><q>Inside the National Army Museum <i>Source: National War Museum </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> \r\nInduction loops are provided in all public areas of the museum such as the Welcome Desk, the Templer Study Centre and the Foyle Centre.\r\n<br /> \r\nIn addition, when audio is used in the galleries an induction loop is also available.\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h4> \r\nNo direct information can be found on the National Army Museum’s website, so please contact the Museum on the below number or by filling in the form also available from the link below.\r\n<br />\r\n<a href=\"https://www.nam.ac.uk/contact-nam\" target=\"_blank\"> National Army Museum / Contacts </a>\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4>\r\nFixed seating is available throughout all of the museum’s galleries, as well as a lift which is accessible on and to every floor. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nAssistance dogs are welcome, and disabled access toilets are located on the ground and lower ground floor.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'national-army-museum.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1623873', '51.4862408', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(44, 'Hyde Park Bombing memorial', 'On Tuesday the 20th of July 1982, members of the Provisional Irish Republican Army attacked the streets of the British capital as they executed a carefully prepared and deadly plan. At approximately 10:40 in the morning, a blue Morris Marina, which had been loaded with a nail bomb containing 25 lbs of gelignite and 30 lbs worth of nails, was remotely detonated. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Household_Cavalry_Memorial.jpg\" alt=\"Hyde Park\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The memorial is located at the site of the blast and records the names of the eleven soliders and seven horses that lost their lives. <i>Source: WikiCommons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe ensuing blast had been tenaciously setup with the specific intention of killing as many British military personnel as possible. The attack that day marked the first time a remote control improvised explosive device had been used on the UK mainland, with components taken from a remote control car having been incorporated into the process to maximise the potential damage.\r\n<br></br> \r\nVisitors taking a peaceful stroll through one of Central London’s largest and most famous Royal parks could easily be forgiven for forgetting the bloody events that the site bore witness to in the not too distant past. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nApart from the presence of a humble memorial plaque, nothing else suggests that Hyde Park, a place of natural beauty, played such a large role in the Troubles.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/AfterBlast.jpg\" alt=\"Hyde Park\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Taken shortly after the blast, you can see the remains of the Blue Morris Marina in the background on the left hand side of the picture. \r\n <i>Source: Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nTragically, 4 members of the The Blues and Royals - who had been marching past by as they conducted the daily Changing of the Guard - were killed by the blast. Eighteen others also suffered non-fatal injuries, while 7 horses belonging to the Blues and Royals also lost their lives in the attack. The explosion was the first of two bombs to be detonated in London that day, with a second attack happening in Regent’s Park only a few hours later. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/aftertheblast2.jpg\" alt=\"Hyde Park\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>This picture was taken shortly after the initial blast and shows the carnage caused in the attack. In the foreground is the smouldering remains of the car where the 30 lb device was placed.\r\n <i>Source: Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the aftermath of the terrorist attacks, the Provisional IRA claimed full responsibility and issued a statement to the world that mirrored a speech Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher had made only a few months before Britain had entered the Falklands War. The statement explicitly cited Article 51 of the UN statute and demanded that the Irish people should be given sovereign and national rights.  \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Hyde_Park_Bombing_Horses.jpg\" alt=\"Hyde Park\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>This is the iconic image of the Hyde Park attack of 1982 and shows the seven horses that were killed in the blast. The picture also highlights the accuracy with which the IRA triggered the device to cause maximum damage to passing soldiers. \r\n <i>Source: Flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAn electrician from Crossmaglen in Northern Ireland named Gilbert “Danny” McNamee is the only person to currently have ever been detained for the Hyde Park attack. McNamee ultimately only served 12 years of his 25-year sentence before being released from prison following the Good Friday Agreement. In 1998 the Court of Appeal then fully overturned McNamee’s conviction following the release of a Channel 4 documentary. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/VrJL-KzEcGw\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nA small memorial cut into the side of Hyde Park now serves as a permanent reminder of the events of that day. Members of the public who time their visit to the site, in accordance with the Household Cavalry’s Changing of the Guard, will also be able to witness troops pay their fallen comrades an amorous tribute. Each time the Cavalrymen pass the memorial, they conduct an eyes-left and salute with swords, while those playing musical instruments also pause until they have passed the scene. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'hydepark-memorial.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.1660703', '51.5056508', 0, 1, 1, 0, 'LFMA', ''),
(45, 'IRA Harrods bombing', 'The Provisional Irish Republican Army struck a heavy blow to the heart of the city of London on the 17th of December, shattering the festive atmosphere with a calculated and deadly terrorist attack.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nAn undercover cell of the militant group chose the run up to Christmas as the ideal moment to strike at the UK establishment as a part of their campaign against the British economy. \r\n<br></br>\r\nAt around 12:44 in the afternoon, the London office of the Samaritans received a chilling coded message from an IRA volunteer. The message informed them that a bomb, rigged with a timer, had been placed within a car outside the London branch of the Harrods department store. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/emergency_at_harrods.jpg\" alt=\"Harrod Memorial\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Emergency services outside Harrods after the bombing on December 17 1983 <i>Source: PA Wire </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThirty seven minutes later, while the Metropolitan Police were still in the process of evacuating the area, a blue 1972 Austin 1300 GT exploded. The blast had a devastating impact as it ripped through the crowded street, three members of the police, as well as three members of the public were all killed in the ensuing chaos. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/remains_harrod.jpg\" alt=\"Harrod Memorial\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Remains in the foreground of the Austin 1100 used in the car bomb <i>Source: PA Wire </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHad it not been for the fact the Police officer’s squad car had been positioned between the Austin and the store, and subsequently took the brunt of the blast, the massive 30 lb bomb would have surely created many more casualties. \r\n<br></br>\r\nNaturally, the terrorist attack received widespread public condemnation due to the fact innocent civilians had been targeted and killed. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe attack also damaged the IRAs standing internationally and was met with anger from leading political figures such as American President Ronald Reagan.     \r\n<br></br>\r\nHowever, what is perhaps surprising is the fact the Harrods bombing was also condemned by the IRA Army Council, who in a statement claimed the attack had not been sanctioned by them. The group stated that, <mark> ‘We regret the civilian casualties, even though our expression of sympathy will be dismissed. Finally, we remind the British Government that as long as they maintain control of any part of Ireland then the Irish Republican Army will continue to operate in Britain until the Irish people are left in peace to decide their own future.’ </mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/harrods-memorial.jpg\" alt=\"Harrod Memorial\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Met Commissioner Sir Bernard Hogan-Howe lays a wreath at the memorial service <i>Source: PA Wire </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nVisitors to Oxford Street can pay their respects to those who fell on the 17th of December 1983 outside the Harrods department store. Two memorial plaques now immortalise the names of the people who lost their lives that day. Their memory also lives on through a yearly prize given to journalism students who attend the University of Oxford.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe award was established in honour of Philip Geddes, a journalist who was notified about the bomb alert and had attended at the scene to report on it but tragically lost his life in the explosion.\r\n', 'harrods.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.1619722', '51.4994722', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(46, 'PIRA attack: January 1976', 'The peaceful quietness of the early evening was abruptly shattered on the 29th of January 1976, as the Provisional Irish Republican Army ramped up their military campaign of terror on the streets of the British capital.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Provisional-IRA-attack-January-1976.jpg\" alt=\"Jan 1976 Attack\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br />\r\n<sub><q>Foubert\'s Place W1, At the junction with Kingly Street <i>Source: Robin Sones </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe night heralded a clear increase in scope and boldness in the IRA’s offensive, in the short space of only a few hours the group managed to detonate 12 bombs in the area around Oxford Street. While an additional 13th device was later discovered in a HMV department store. \r\n<br></br>\r\nBy the standards of the IRA the bombs were relatively small, weighing on average between 3 and 5 lbs, most were reported to have only caused small fires as a result of this. \r\n<br></br>\r\nA taxi driver was the only recorded person to be injured, as an explosion at the junction between Foubert’s Place and Kingly Street caused debris and glass to pelt his vehicle, he was later discharged from hospital after making a full recovery.\r\n<br></br>\r\nWhile the IRA would launch more successful and deadly attacks in the future, the events of that night should not be forgotten, they perfectly demonstrate the groups determination and desire to see their mission come to fruition. \r\n', 'ira-january-1976.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.1401667', '51.5133333', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(47, 'IRA London Mortar attack', 'Throughout the Troubles the Provisional Irish Republican Army (IRA) earned itself a fierce reputation for its proficiency with weapons, in its quest to fulfil its deepest desire it employed and constructed a vast arsenal. A carefully planned terrorist attack on the 7th of February 1991 effectively demonstrated this capability to its fullest. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/London-Westminster-Statue-and-Downing-St.jpg\" alt=\"Mortar\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe IRA’s choice of target on that day was a fairly predictable one, numerous assassination attempts on several members of the British government had been undertaken with varying levels of success during the struggle. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/downing_st_mortar.jpg\" alt=\"Mortar\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The IRA claimed responsibility for the attack with a statement issued in Dublin, saying “Let the British government understand that, while nationalist people in the six counties [Northern Ireland] are forced to live under British rule, then the British Cabinet will be forced to meet in bunkers <i>Source: BBC </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat makes the February attack remarkable is the method they employed, homemade mortars had been deployed on a regular basis in Northern Ireland but had never been used on the British mainland. Thanks to the deployment of two of the IRAs most proficient weapons experts, that was about to change.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/MortarTest-1994.jpg\" alt=\"Mortar\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>This is a test firing of a Mark 15 Barrack Buster Mortar used by the IRA in the mid 90\'s. It carried around 75 kg (165 lb) of home-made explosives and had a range of 75 to 275 metres (246 to 902 ft). The IRA used the Mark 10 design during the Downing Street attack, which had a smaller explosive charge between 44-200 pounds (20 -100 Kgs) of explosives but had multiple barrels.  <i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRendezvousing with several IRA Active Service Units (ASU) members in Britain, the pair were able to construct a Mark 10 homemade mortar and install it into a modified Ford Transit van. The vehicle, having been bought prior to the attack, had been modified to allow mortar shells to pass through its roof. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nHaving this sophisticated weapon at their disposal gave the IRA the option to undertake a risky attack, one that would allow them to strike at the very heart of the British government; 10 Downing Street. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/mortar.jpg\" alt=\"Mortar\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>This a multiple barrel Mark 10 mortar setup that has been installed on the back of a pickup truck to attack a police station in Northern Ireland. A similar setup to this would have been used during the attack on Downing Street.  <i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nOn the morning of the 7th the entire British Cabinet, including Prime Minister John Major, had been meeting in Downing Street to discuss the ongoing Gulf War, however their talks were abruptly cut short at 10:08 am as the IRA’s attack was finally put into action.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThree giant 4½ foot long shells - each weighing 140 pounds - were launched from the back of the van. The Ford Transit had been positioned only a few hundred yards behind Number 10 at the junction between Horse Guards Avenue and Whitehall. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nTo make the job of tracking down the IRA agents that bit harder the van had been rigged with a timed incendiary device, which upon detonation, promptly engulfed the van in flames and destroyed all forensic evidence. Two of the mortars failed to find their mark, landing harmlessly on Mountbatten Green, however one of the shells landed only a mere 30 feet away from the War Cabinet’s meeting spot. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n4 people received minor injuries as debris was sent rocketing into the air, but thankfully no one was seriously hurt or killed. What is remarkable is the fact the members of the cabinet were able to reconvene and resume their meeting only 10 minutes after the incident had unfolded. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nWhile the IRA failed to complete their mission on this occasion, the events of the 7th serve as a reminder of their tenacity and dedication to their cause. Visitors to Downing Street can be reminded of the power of the IRA when they look upon the police guarded gates leading on to the street, both were installed in the 1980s as a reaction to the deadly power of the group. \r\n\r\n', 'downing-street-attack.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.126364', '51.503182', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(48, 'IRA Honourable Artillery Company Attack', 'During the Troubles the Provisional Irish Republican Army earned itself a formidable reputation as an efficient force to be reckoned with, as it routinely brought terror to the streets of London for over 30 years. However not all of the groups plans were executed exactly how they had been envisioned, as was the case of an attack carried out on the 9th of June 1990.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/HAC_MainBuilding.jpg\" alt=\"Artillery Company Attack\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>On 9 June 1990, the Provisional IRA detonated a time bomb inside the Armoury House hall of the Honourable Artillery Company\'s military barracks in London, England. Nineteen people, all young civilians and mostly students, were injured in the blast. <i>Source: Wikimedia</i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nShortly before midnight, a timed explosive that had been planted on the roof of the Honourable Artillery Company’s military barracks in London exploded. The bomb had been put there by a volunteer IRA member roughly an hour before, as part of the groups renewed offensive on the British mainland. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n19 people were injured by the subsequent blast as glass and debris rained down on the occupants of the barracks’ bar, only the unique structure of the buildings roof ensured the IRA’s attempt to inflict heavier casualties failed.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nFurthermore, the event can be considered to be one of the groups bigger failures thanks to the people that found themselves caught up in the terrorist attack. The barracks had been selected as a target due to its status within the British military and the potential damage that could be inflicted upon that group. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nOn any other Saturday night the venue would have been full of Territorial Army reserve soldiers and the IRA would have gotten their desired outcome. However, on the 9th of June it had been occupied by approximately 30 Cambridge University students, all of whom were celebrating the 21st birthday of one of their classmates at a black-tie event.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Armoury_House.jpg\" alt=\"Artillery Company Attack\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Armoury House, the building where the bomb occurred. <i>Source: Wikimedia</i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nCaptain Venn - the father of the birthday boy - had told reporters after the attack that the partygoers weren’t even meant to be in the barracks’ bar, and had only moved their for one final drink at the end of the party. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIn all likelihood the IRA had never intended to attack regular citizens on the 9th of June, therefore the attack on the Honourable Artillery Company barracks can be observed as a rare and uncharacteristic mistake on the part of the Provisional Irish Republican Army.  \r\n\r\n\r\n', 'IRA-Honourable-Artillery-Company-Attack.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.088492', '51.522994', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(49, 'RIRA MI6 attack', 'Although the Troubles may have come to an official end with the signing of the Good Friday Agreement, not everyone was satisfied with its outcomes. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe Real Irish Republican Army (RIRA), a splinter paramilitary group formed from the shadows of the Provisional IRA, continued to plague the streets of London in the early 21st century.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/rira_m16_attacks.jpg\" alt=\"RIRA M16 Attacks\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>On Wednesday 20 September 2000, the Real Irish Republican Army carried out an attack on MI6 in Vauxhall, Lambeth, London. <i>Source: BBC </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n \r\nThe RIRA had already conducted two audacious attacks on the British Capital in the summer of 2000, their third assault would prove to be their boldest attack on UK soil to date. Their target was the SIS building, a symbolic structure in the London skyline that housed the headquarters of the nations central foreign intelligence service, MI6. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAny attack that could damage the institutes reputation within British society was a tantalising prospect for the RIRA.\r\nTheir mode of attack would end up being a landmark event in British history. Situated in the nearby Spring Gardens at 9:45 pm on the 20th of September, three members of the paramilitary organisation launched a 2.8kg RPG-22 anti tank rocket at the SIS building. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bbc-mi6-bomb.jpg\" alt=\"RIRA M16 Attacks\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Damage caused by the missile attack on the MI6 building <i>Source: BBC </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe RIRA‘s attack was remarkable due to the fact it marked the first time a RPG-22 had been seen or used within the United Kingdom. However, the results of the launch were anything but remarkable. Despite being only 300 meters away from the building the rocket did minimal damage to the structure and subsequently failed to injure any people within.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIt has also been speculated that the RIRA members failed to hit their intended target; the buildings delicate satellite equipment. Instead the missile smacked harmlessly into the side of the bomb proof eighth floor.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe RPG-22, which had been discarded in Spring Park, was later traced back to a stockpile of weapons purchased by the RIRA in June of 2000. While the attack thankfully did minimal damage, it served as a scary reminder of the threat that the dissident Irish Republican Army could pose, even in peacetime. ', 'RIRA-MI6-attack.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.1209167', '51.4873889', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(50, 'IRA Walton’s Restaurant Attack', 'On the 18th of November 1975, the Provisional Irish Republican Army (IRA) conducted a chilling terrorist attack designed specifically to kill and scare members of the British public. Their target was Walton’s Restaurant, which at the time was located in the Chelsea region of London. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe establishment was famous for attracting affluent members of British society, and was packed with over 70 unknowing clientele at 9 o\'clock that evening. The attack was a marked change in the IRA’s approach to bombings; this time there was no coded message, and no evacuation or subsequent chance for civilians to escape. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nUnlike the people inside the restaurant, the IRA volunteer who threw the bomb at the West End business knew exactly what was about to happen. Two civilians were killed and twenty-three others were injured as the 3 lb bomb flew through the restaurant\'s window and exploded. Despite the deceptively small size of the bomb, the device was crafted in a way that would maximise its deadly potential.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/walton-restaurant-bombing.jpg\" alt=\"Walton Restaurant Bombing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>On 18 November 1975 an Irish Republican Army (IRA) unit nicknamed the Balcombe Street Gang without warning threw a bomb into Walton’s Restaurant in Walton Street, Knightsbridge, London, killing two people and injuring almost two dozen others. <i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBecause the explosive was packed with miniature ball bearings it is clear that its one and only objective was to kill and maim as many members of the public as possible, any additional damage to the property was only a secondary and distant consequence.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe attack had been conducted by the Balcombe Street Gang, named for their final Wild West style showdown with the authorities only a few weeks after the Walton’s Restaurant attack. The members of the group were highly trained and exceptionally proficient soldiers and weapons makers, and had consequently earned an infamous reputation with the Metropolitan Police. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe attack on Walton’s had been a calculated assault designed specifically to target the ‘ruling classes’ of Britain, during the Troubles the IRA had often targeted business that were linked with the UK establishment in an attempt to scare the public and inflict heavy financial losses. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Walton_Restaurant_1975_bombing.jpg\" alt=\"Walton Restaurant Bombing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Aftermath of Waltons Restaurant bombing in London\'s West End. <i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBetween October 1974 and December 1975, the Balcombe Street Gang carried out 40 attacks, in total they were responsible for injuring over 400 people and the deaths of 18 others. In addition to this they also inflicted potentially millions of pounds worth of damage to London businesses and buildings. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe gang would finally become undone only a few weeks after the Walton’s Street incident. An attack on a restaurant in the Mayfair area of London resulted in a city wide car chase and a subsequent six-day siege centred around a block of flats on Balcombe Street. The gang were later detained and charged with sentences adding up to over 600 years worth of jail time, they were however released and returned to Ireland following the Good Friday agreement.\r\n', 'Waltons-Restaurant.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.1682222', '51.49375', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', ''),
(51, '1993 Bishopsgate IRA bombing', 'In the early hours of the 24th of April 1993, two Provisional Irish Republican Army (IRA) volunteers from one of the groups Active Service Units (ASU) parked an Iveco tipper truck at 99 Bishopsgate, near to the junction with Wormwood Street. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe vehicle had been stolen a month earlier from the Newcastle-under-Lyme area of Staffordshire and had undergone a series of alterations in the intervening time since. Chief of which was the installation of a gigantic 1 tonne ANFO (ammonium nitrate/fuel oil) bomb, a device often referred to as a fertiliser bomb and more commonly used in heavy industries such as coal mining and quarrying. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bishopsgate_bombing_1993.jpg\" alt=\"Bishop\'s Gate Bombing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Wormwood Street in London after the IRA had detonated a truck bomb on April 24, 1993.<i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe explosive - having been transported all the way from the infamous South Armagh heartlands of the IRA’s operations - had been created as part of the groups economic war with Britain, an ongoing struggle designed to cripple the UK economy and force the creation of a free and unified Ireland. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe deployment of such a powerful bomb on British soil clearly demonstrates the IRA’S intention to inflict massive damage on a scale that had been rarely seen in the UK beforehand. After the traditional one hour warning had been issued to the Metropolitan Police, this time from a phone box in County Armagh in Northern Ireland, the bomb was finally detonated at 10:27 am. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe subsequent blast was devastating, a large mushroom cloud billowed out above the 15-foot wide crater that had been created when the device detonated. Due to the fact the attack had been undertaken on a weekend ensured that casualties were kept to a minimum, with one news photographer losing their life, while an additional 44 people were injured. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bishopgate-bombing.jpg\" alt=\"Bishop\'s Gate Bombing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The crater. A 1 tonne ANFO bomb made by the IRA’s South Armagh Brigade had been smuggled into England and was placed in the truck disguised underneath a layer of tarmac. <i>Source: City of London Police </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bishopgate-bombing-2.jpg\" alt=\"Bishop\'s Gate Bombing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Despite a warning being sent beforehand, one person was killed and 44 were injured by the blast on the 24th of April 1993. <i>Source: City of London Police </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bishopgate-bombing-3.jpg\" alt=\"Bishop\'s Gate Bombing\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>It\'s estimated the bomb caused £350 million worth of damage. <i>Source: City of London Police </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWhile the loss of human life was thankfully small, the damage to the City’s infrastructure and finances were anything but, pictures taken in the aftermath harken back and are reminiscent to those taken at the height of the London Blitz. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAt the time of the attack the Bishopsgate bombing was financially the most damaging terrorist attack in history, with an estimated £1bn worth of damage having been done to the UK economy. This sad achievement would only be surpassed on the 11th of September 2001 and the infamous terrorist attacks of that day.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nWhile there is no permanent reminder or memorial commemorating the events of the 24th of April, the day did act as a turning point for the British authorities and financial sector of London. A prompt change in attitude can be observed when analysing the security of the city following the Bishopsgate attack. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nFor example, from the 3rd of July 1993 a new ‘ring of steel’ initiative was introduced in order to allow the police to better monitor traffic coming into the Capital.', 'Wormwood-Street-London-Irish-Republican-Army.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 41, '-0.082616', '51.516285', 0, 0, 1, 0, '', '');
