(59, 'The Clifton Suspension Bridge', 'The Clifton Suspension Bridge was designed by the prolific Victorian engineer Isambard Kingdom Brunel and first opened to the public over 150 years ago, after a long period of construction.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn 1829 a competition was opened to design a bridge to cross the river Avon and gorge, funded by the Society of Merchant Venturers from an initial bequest from William Vick, a Bristol wine merchant in the year 1753. The first round of entries saw all the designs rejected, including that from a 23 year old Brunel.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOne year later the competition re-opened and Brunel’s design won. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Construction of the bridge</h4>\r\nWork on the bridge began in 1831, but it was hindered by cold weather, riots and financial issues; at one point the project was abandoned completely before restarting and The Times reported that Bristolians must have felt its completion was “an unattainable ideal- a sort of phantom project that haunted the shores of the Avon…” These issues meant that when Brunel died in 1859 he never saw the bridge completed.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWilliam Henry Barlow and John Hawkshaw took over the venture upon Brunel’s death and the bridge was finally opened to a jubilant crowd of 150,000 people on 8 December 1864. At the time it was the longest and highest chain bridge in the world (The Times, 9 December 1864).\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/clifton-suspension-bridge1.jpg\" alt=\"The Clifton Suspension Bridge\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>The construction of the Leigh Tower in Somerset and the Clifton Tower in Gloucestershire. Brunel’s original plans included sphinxes atop the towers, but these were never built <i>Source: Clifton Suspension Bridge Trust </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/opening-of-the-bridge.jpg\" alt=\"The Clifton Suspension Bridge\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Opening of the bridge, The Illustrated London News, 17 December 1864, Vol. 45, No. 1292, p. 597.\r\nFrom The Illustrated London News Historical Archive, 1842-2003 <i>Source: History Today </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Legacy</h4>\r\nToday, the bridge is an icon of the City of Bristol and is crossed daily by around 11,000 vehicles. It is managed by the Clifton Suspension Bridge Trust and is grade I listed.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Opening times/ access:</h4>\r\nThe Observatory Hill in Clifton offers fantastic views of the bridge. The Visitor’s Centre, on the Leigh Woods side of the bridge, is free and open 10:00 – 17:00 every day. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFree tours of the bridge are on Saturdays at 3pm. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere is a £1 toll to cross the bridge in a vehicle under 4 tonnes, but pedestrians and cyclists can cross for free. \r\nPre-booked historical tours also run to the Leigh Woods Vaults, a series of vaulted chambers under the Leigh Tower.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese are limited and can be booked via:\r\n<a href=\"https://www.cliftonbridge.org.uk.\" target=\"_blank\"> The Clifton Suspension Bridge </a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Find out more:</h4>\r\nJ. Christopher, Brunel in Bristol (2003).\r\n<br />\r\n“Opening Of The Clifton Suspension bridge.\" The Times, 9 December 1864, p. 7. The Times Digital Archive.\r\n', 'Clifton_Suspension_Bridge.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-2.6299998\r\n', '51.4549291', 1, 1, 0, 0, '', ''),
(61, 'Caistor Roman Town, Venta Icenroum\r\n', 'The Roman town of Venta Icenorum ‘market place of the Iceni’ was established c.70 AD as the capital of the Iceni tribe – the tribe made infamous in 61 AD when their queen, Boudicca, led a revolt against Roman rule. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDuring the Roman occupation large parts of Britain were organised into civitas reipublicae, which were political communities formed from the local citizens in a district. This process formalised the Iron Age tribal districts into permanent Roman administrative units which were ruled and managed from the civitas capital.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn response to the Boudiccan revolt, the Romans decided it would be prudent to establish a new civitas capital, Venta Icenorum, in this troublesome area to prevent further issues.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Boadicea_Haranguing_the_Britons.jpg\" alt=\"Venta Icenroum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>An engraving by William Sharp published in 1793, based on Boadicea Haranguing the Britons (called Boudicca, or Boadicea) by John Opie <i>Source: wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWhilst Venta Icenroum was never elaborate, it became an important trading centre. Trade allowed the town to grow in wealth, thereby permitting the construction of major public buildings, such as a forum, basilica and baths. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSimilarly, Venta Icenorum was not so modest that it did not benefit from the mod-cons of the day, the town was also supplied with running water, evidenced by the discovery of wooden water pipes and drains uncovered during excavations at the site.  \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhilst much of Venta Icenorum lays preserved under the ground, visitors can view the remains of the town’s defensive walls and ditches, which still protectively encircle the site.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/venta_cartoon_representation.jpg\" alt=\"Venta Icenroum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A cartoon reconstruction of the building of the Roman town wall in the late AD 200s. Because the wall was built through the town rather than around it, several buildings were demolished to make way for the new defences. The remains of these buildings and the existing ground surface were then levelled to form the foundation on which the wall was built. <i>Source: john peterson // flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe remains of tower-like bastions, designed as both watch towers and as platforms to mount artillery, indicates the walls were not merely there to demarcate the town’s boundaries, they were also a means of defence should there be further local uprisings. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOf these bastions, only one now survives, near the site of the west gate, however evidence of others can still be glimpsed in front of the south wall. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nVenta Icenorum remained occupied throughout the Roman occupation, however once Rome’s forces were withdrawn in 5th century AD, the town was abandoned and remained uninhabited during subsequent historical periods.\r\n <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe site is in the care of Norfolk Archaeological Trust and is open all year round – entrance is free. Visitors can follow several walks around the Roman defences and the Caistor Roman Town free augmented reality app (available on Google Play and the App Store) allows visitors to see a reconstruction of the town on the landscape and examine some of the artefacts found there.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Venta_Icenorum_view_from_southwall.jpg\" alt=\"Venta Icenroum\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Venta Icenorum view from the south wall <i>Source: wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFree parking is available a short walk from the site, however additional facilities can be found only 3.5 miles away in the city of Norwich.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br />\r\nHistoric England (n.d.) ‘Venta Icenorum’, Pastscape, online.\r\n<a href=\"https://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=132757\" target=\"_blank\"> Venta Icenroum </a> \r\n', 'Venta_Icenorum_-_Market_Place_of_the_Iceni.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '1.2911621', '52.5835036', 1, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(63, 'Battle of Britain Monument', 'A monument on the Victoria Embankment, commissioned and paid for by the Battle of Britain Historical Society, commemorates those who were part of the Battle of Britain in 1940 during the Second World War. \r\n\r\nThis 82ft long memorial made of both granite and bronze was installed in 2005, and was unveiled on 18th September that year by HRH Prince Charles and the Duchess of Cornwall, marking the 65th anniversary of the event. \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/battle-of-britain-monument-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Battle of Britain Monument\">\r\n<sub><q>The Battle of Britain Monument in London is a sculpture on the Victoria Embankment overlooking the River Thames in central London, England which pays tribute to those who took part in the Battle of Britain during World War II. <i>Source: Bas Boerman // Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n \r\n\r\nThe sculptor, Paul Day wanted the monument designed with two large panels facing in opposing directions - one panel commemorates the achievements of the armed force, while the other remembers the wider effect of the War on the British nation. \r\n\r\nThe imagery of the monument therefore depicts several scenes not only of the battle, with allied airmen running towards their planes to intercept the Luftwaffe, but also of other elements of the War. \r\n\r\nThis includes spotters of enemy planes, ground technical staff, women in munition factories, and people caught up in The Blitz in London. A comprehensive list of the different elements of the memorial\'s imagery can be found <a href=\"http://bbm.org.uk/the-monument/background/description-of-monument-scenes/\" target=\"_blank\"> here.</a>\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/battle-of-britain-monument-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Battle of Britain Monument\">\r\n<sub><q>A part of the Battle of Britain Monument, along Victoria Embankment. The quote is from a 1940 speech by Winston Churchill and reads: \"Never in the field of human conflict was so much owed by so many to so few.\" <i>Source: Daniele Nicolucci // Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\nThe monument features a famous quote in a wartime speech in 1940 by Winston Churchill, British Prime Minister from 1940-1945, where he refers to the work of the air force during the Battle of Britain: <i> \'never in the history of human conflict was so much owed by so many to so few\'. After this speech the Battle of Britain airmen were popularly referred to as \'The Few\'.</i>  \r\n\r\nThe two parts of the monument feature the names of the 2,936 airmen and ground crew from 14 different countries who were engaged in combat during the Battle.  The full list of these airman, with biographies of around 2,000 of them can be found <a href=\"http://bbm.org.uk/the-airmen\" target=\"_blank\"> here.</a>\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/battle-of-britain-monument-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Battle of Britain Monument\">\r\n<sub><q>Close Up of the monument. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore details of the Battle of Britain, the memorial, and the process of creating and unveiling it can be found at  <a href=\"https://bbm.org.uk\" target=\"_blank\"> the official website.</a> .\r\n\r\nYou can also see a 360 degrees view of part of the monument <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V_CyrFyBwFQ\" target=\"_blank\"> here.</a> \r\n\r\n<br><br><br><br>\r\n', 'Battle-of-britain-header-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1233611', '51.5030278', 1, 1, 2, 0, '79 Whitehall, Westminster, London UK', ''),
(64, 'Welwyn Roman Baths', 'Lying hidden beneath the A1(M) motorway just off the Welwyn by-pass, Welwyn Roman Baths are the fascinating 3rd century remains of the bathing complex that once formed part of the Dicket Mead Roman villa. \r\n\r\nThe villa has not been fully excavated, however it is believed to have been occupied for 150 years during which time it was a self-sufficient farm that included a main residence, bath house, outbuildings and minor dwellings. \r\n\r\nThe remains of the baths lie encased and protected in a steel vault that was constructed 9 metres underground, an ingenious structure that can be reached through a steel tunnel that guides visitors on their journey through time to the Roman past below.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Welwyn Roman Baths\"> <sub><q>Welwyn Roman Baths. <i>Source: Matt Brown // flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhilst bathing was a social pastime in Roman Britain, with many people visiting the local bath house to wash, gossip and complete business transactions, private baths were still coveted by the elite. \r\n\r\nThey may have been smaller than public baths, however in a society where power and hierarchy was everything, private baths allowed their owners to bathe with only those they deemed to be suitable. \r\n\r\nArchitecturally, private baths were very similar to their larger counterparts and included the requisite warm room (tepidarium), hot room (caldarium) and cold room (frigidarium). Remarkably well-preserved examples of all three rooms can be viewed at Welwyn, along with a hypocaust (underfloor heating) system which was used to circulate hot air around the complex.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Welwyn Roman Baths\"> <sub><q>Welwyn Roman Baths. <i>Source: Matt Brown // flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccompanying the remains of the baths are numerous Roman finds from the site and local area, including building materials, painted panels, ceramic figures and a 1st century skeleton of a woman who is believed to have been a victim of ritual human sacrifice. \r\n\r\nAdditionally, a permanent exhibition tells the story of the site including its excavation in the 1960s and 70s by the Welwyn Archaeological Society.\r\n\r\nThe site is managed by Welwyn Hatfield Museum Service and is open weekends, bank holidays and school holidays between January and November. There is a fee to visit the site (Adult &#163;3.50, Child 50p), however they do offer a 50% discount for a second adult living at the same address.\r\n\r\nFree parking is available on site, as well as visitor toilets and a picnic area and refreshments can be bought from nearby Welwyn Village.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Welwyn Roman Baths\"> <sub><q>Welwyn Roman Baths. <i>Source: Matt Brown // flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<hr><hr>\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>De la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br />\r\nHistoric England (n.d.) \'Welwyn Roman Baths\', Pastscape, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.britainexpress.com/counties/herts/roman/welwyn-roman-baths.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Click Here </a> \r\n<br />\r\nRoss, D. (n.d.) \'Welwyn Roman Baths\', Britain Express, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.britainexpress.com/counties/herts/roman/welwyn-roman-baths.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Click Here </a> \r\n<br />\r\nWelwyn Hatfield Museum Service (n.d.) Roman Baths Welwyn, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.welhat.gov.uk/media/5248/Welwyn-Roman-Baths-Guide-English-/pdf/wrb_english_guide.pdf?m=634786535820000000\" target=\"_blank\"> Click Here </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br><br><br><br>\r\n', 'Welwyn-Roman-Baths-image2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.2102497', '51.8281645', 0, 1, 1, 0, 'Welwyn Garden City, Hertfordshire, England', ''),
(65, '29 Hanbury Street', 'If you’re partial to a bit of vintage shopping or a proper curry, chances are you’ve wandered down Brick Lane, which means you’ve probably walked along Hanbury Street too as it connects Brick Lane with Commercial Street.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAnnie Chapman, the second victim of Jack the Ripper, was killed in the backyard of 29 Hanbury Street. She died aged 47 and was buried at Manor Park Cemetery; since her grave was buried over, a plaque now commemorates the approximate burial site.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Jack the Ripper portrayed wearing a deerstalker hat and long overcoat. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nHer family life was far from idyllic. Her eldest daughter died age 12 from meningitis and her son was born disabled and put into a care home. She and her husband John both turned to drink to ease their woes. After mutually separating around 1885, John paid her 10 shillings a week to support her, she also sold her crochet work and flowers so she didn’t need to prostitute herself until her husband died around Christmas 1886.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe hallway of number 29 was treated as a public thoroughfare. It was not uncommon to see the front door wide open, even at night, and the back door never seemed to be locked. Anyone could go through to the yard as and when they pleased and people often kipped in the passage, landing, and stairs. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>29 Hanbury Street Passageway. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe house was split between tenants with the ground floor front room occupied by a cat’s meat vendor (to clarify, this was someone who sold meat to feed cats) and the first floor rooms rented by the Richardsons.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAn amateur detective took a tour of the Whitechapel murder sites and published his commentary in a series of instalments in The Sheffield Weekly Telegraph. His trip to Hanbury Street was published on the 10th November 1888 - about a month after Annie’s murder. The language used is powerful. The disparity between the East End and the rest of London is painfully clear as the author describes the pickpocket population:\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark>“They are the scum of the criminal class; they are the offspring of the foulest and most unbridled passions; they are the noxious fungi of the worst type of humanity.”</mark>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>September 1888 newspaper implicating a character they referred to as “Leather Apron” in the murder. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAccording to him, the area is filthy, squalid, full of prostitutes with beaten and bruised faces, and the majority of inhabitants are drunk. A large foreign community have flocked here too: predominantly Poles, Russians, and Germans. People don’t live here, he says, they “exist”. The street also reeked of fish due to the sheer amount of fried fish shops along the long road.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe evolution of Hanbury Street is undeniably impressive; you could even see it as a kind of redemption. The devastating poverty has been replaced by a rich and vibrant street art scene, with quirky shops and quality eateries. Despite the cultural renovation, the buildings remain much unchanged since the late 1800s. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/hanbury-street-image4.jpg\" alt=\"Hanbury Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Annie Chapman\'s plaque near her burial location in Manor Park Cemetery. <i>Source: Whitechapeljack </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNumber 29 has been replaced by the iconic looming Truman Brewery, plonked down during the 1970s. Instead of beer and ale, the building now brews a lively gamut of events and markets. Don’t worry though, pints are still available at the surrounding bars.', 'hansberry-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '-0.072561', '51.520362', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(66, 'Berner Street and Dutfield\'s Yard', 'Compared to most of the Jack the Ripper murder sites, Berner Street is amongst those that have changed the most. The original buildings were demolished and replaced with a primary school. Even the name of the street has been erased and instead we walk along Henriques Street. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nSimilarly to the majority of Whitechapel, this area was not affluent by any stretch of the imagination. Charles Booth’s Poverty Map shows Berner Street to be “Mixed. Some comfortable others poor” and “Poor. 18s to 21s a week for moderate family”. 18 shillings is worth about £73.84 in today’s money, and 21 shillings, or 1 guinea, is approximately £86.15 in terms of purchasing power.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/berner-street-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Berner Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A view of the murder site in Berner Street. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nA short walk up from the Fairclough Street junction on the left hand side lay a small yard, accessed by a gate.  Nestled in between buildings either side, Dutfield’s Yard was home to businesses such as cart makers, cigarette makers, and tailors, the International Men’s Working Educational Club, and a smattering of other dwellings and cottages. It was also the final outing for Elizabeth Stride who was Jack the Ripper’s third victim on 30th September 1888.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMuch of what we know of Elizabeth’s life hails from official documents. Originally from Torslanda, Sweden, Elisabeth Gustafsdotter moved to Gothenburg in 1862 and was registered as a prostitute in March 1865. A month later she also gave birth to a stillborn daughter and from October and November she was treated at a hospital for venereal disease.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/berner-street-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Berner Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <br><sub><q>Sketch of Elizabeth Stride, also known as Long Liz. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor unknown reasons, she emigrated to London to work as a domestic servant, as alleged by Michael Kidney - her partner with whom Elizabeth had an on-and-off relationship from 1885.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAfter marrying Thomas Stride on 7th March 1869, the couple set up a coffee shop in Poplar which seemed to fair well until 1875 when it was bought by John Dale. By 1882 her marriage had fallen apart and she made a living predominantly through sewing and cleaning, with occasional sex work. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nEven though she cohabited with Michael Kidney, it was not rare for her to spend a few nights in the lodging houses, especially 32 Flower and Dean Street. Her lodgers described her as a quiet and kind woman, although she did often appear before the Thames Magistrate Court on account of drunk and disorderly behaviour. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOn the 26th September 1888, a group of women sat in the kitchen of no. 32 talking about the Whitechapel murders, greatly worried they were at risk of becoming victims themselves. Dr Barnado later confirmed that Elizabeth was in fact one of the women he saw at this gathering. Three days later, at 1am on the 30th, her body was discovered by Louis Diemschutz on the north side of Dutfield’s Yard - now part of the school playground.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/berner-street-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Berner Street\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A photo of the grave of Elizabeth Stride. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIn life she had few friends or family so her funeral was very modest. Mr Hawkes, the undertaker at the East London Cemetery, paid for her funeral with funds from the church. Her grave is no. 15509 and can still be visited today.\r\n', 'dutfield-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '-0.065553', '51.513780', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(67, 'Buck’s Row - Jack the Ripper’s First Murder', 'Nestled between Whitechapel station, Whitechapel Sports Centre, and Swanlea School lies Durward Street. In 1888, however, it went by the name Buck’s Row and was the site of the first accepted Jack the Ripper murder. On the morning of 31st August 1888, Mary Ann Nichols, known as Polly, was found towards the middle of the street on the south side pavement, a few metres down from the old boarding school continues to stand tall today. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMarried to William Nichols in 1864, Polly was clearly unsettled in her domestic life. As stated in the London Daily News (3/9/1888), she separated from her husband “four or five times, if not six” according to William. The newspaper also reveals that she left her husband because he “‘turned nasty’ over another man”. This gives us the impression that Polly was obviously unhappy in her relationship. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bucks-row-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Bucks Row\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A grim discovery <i>Source: Wikimedia</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf she left William because of some kind of altercation, this suggests an intolerance on her part to aggressive and potentially abusive behaviour - traits that women admire and strive to embody today. In an age where women were expected to endure anything and everything in a marriage, Polly was able to leave her family and take care of herself. She left her husband for the final time in 1881, and by 1882 she had begun to support herself through sex work. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWilliam found out about her new means of income and consequently refused to continue paying her alimony.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBetween April 1882 and May 1888 she was mainly staying at Lambeth Workhouse, with short stints with family or other workhouses around East London. Having survived as an alcoholic for many years now, she tried hard to improve her life by taking up work as a domestic servant for the Cowdry family in Wandsworth. She wrote a caring letter to her father around May 1888 (quoted in the London Daily News 3/9/88):\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark><i>\"I just write to say you will be glad to know that I am settled in my new place, and going all right up to now. My people went out yesterday and have not returned, so I am left in charge. It is a grand place inside, with trees and gardens back and front. All has been newly done up. They are teetotalers and religious so I ought to get on. They are very nice people, and I have not too much to do. I hope you are all right and the boy has work. So good bye for the present.\"</i></mark>\r\n<br />\r\nfrom yours truly,\r\n<br />\r\nPolly\r\n<br />\r\n<i>\"Answer soon, please, and let me know how you are.\"</i>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bucks-row-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Bucks Row\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Mary Ann Nichols - Illustrated Police News, Sept 8, 1888. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAs part of the inquest into her murder, her father expressed that he “was not aware that she had any enemies. She was always too good for that. Her only fault was being too good.”\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was buried in the City of London Cemetery where a memorial plaque now commemorates her.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bucks-row-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Bucks Row\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Mary Ann Nichols grave marker on Gardens way in the Memorial Gardens to the northeast of the Traditional Crematorium in the City of London Cemetery. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe evolution of this historical street does not just stop at a name change though. By the end of this year the Crossrail works should be complete and an impressive refurbished Whitechapel station will merge with its Victorian parent, with a bridge connecting it to Durward Street. According to the proposed plans, this bridge will intersect with where Polly’s body was found.\r\n', 'bucks-row-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '-0.060378', '51.520047', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(68, 'Castle Alley', 'The autumn months of 1888 sent the East End into continuous terror; no one knew when Jack the Ripper would strike again. After the death of Mary Jane Kelly on the 9th November, the murders seemed to desist, but Whitechapel was still far from safe. On 17th July 1889, a body was found at 12:50am in Castle Alley. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNowadays, the site is on the west pavement where Pomell Way meets Old Castle Street. Alice McKenzie was around 40 years old when she was killed under a gas street lamp here. It rained shortly after she was abandoned. She had earned the nickname Clay Pipe due to her penchant for smoking and indeed, her clay pipe was found underneath her body.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/castle-street-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Castle Alley\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q> Site of murder is next door to the Wash House, to the left of the second ‘L’ in ‘Alley’. <i>Source: Insurance Plan of London Vol. XI: sheet 318. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPolicemen vigilantly patrolled through this alley on their beats and rarely left it unattended for more than five minutes, meaning whoever took Alice’s life knew the schedules of the police rounds. In typical Whitechapel murder fashion, there was no trace nor any clue as to who the killer was or where they had escaped to. A resident of the washhouse, the back of which faced the murder, said she heard nothing until the police whistle and someone knock on her door. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nAlice’s injuries were eerily similar to the victims of Jack the Ripper: her throat had been cut, her skirts crumpled up beneath her chin to reveal abdominal cuts. These wounds, however, were not as deep as the ones inflicted the year before. Given the climactic severity of the wounds found on Mary Kelly, this lighter touch with Alice seems highly dubious. Dr Bagster Phillips, who also attended the examinations of Mary Jane Kelly, Annie Chapman, and Elizabeth Stride, attested that the cause of death was blood loss not strangulation as in the previous cases, and also the injuries were unlike what he had seen before.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/castle-street-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Castle Alley\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>View of Old Castle Street with Castle Alley in the distance. The light coloured building on the right is the Whitechapel Baths & Wash House. Alice was found on the pavement just in front of the building after.   <i>Source: Ripperologist, The Journal of Jack the Ripper, East End and Victorian Studies, 138, June 2014.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAt the inquest, the coroner revealed that if this wasn’t the work of Jack the Ripper, it was likely a copycat. This opinion is echoed in the East London Observer which also notes that Alice matched many criteria of the Ripper crimes, including living in a lodging house and being a prostitute. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAlice’s profession has not been confirmed however and her partner of six years, John McCormack as well as an acquaintance, Margaret Franklin, claimed that she was a washerwoman and charwoman in the Jewish community which was predominant in this area. She is described as industrious and hard-working.  Another testimony, from Elizabeth Ryder who lived at the same house in 54 Gun Street, said Alice was usually in bed by 10pm thus also discounting the assumption Alice was a prostitute.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe news of her death was international. Newspapers in North America, Jamaica’s Daily Gleaner, and Mexico’s El Foro reported on the crime, encouraging them to recall Jack the Ripper’s spree. The East London Observer even announced that the Théâtre du Château d’Eau at 50 rue de Malte in Paris would host a production based on the ominous perpetrator.', 'old-castle-street-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '-0.073482', '51.515689', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(69, 'City of London Cemetery', 'Until the mid 19th century, London churchyards and cemeteries were struggling with overcrowding, that is, until the City of London Cemetery opened its gates in 1856. With over 200 acres of land, this beautifully landscaped sanctuary homes the spirits of London’s mayors, artists, servicemen, and ordinary citizens. Anyone can be buried here regardless of religion or district.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPerhaps the most notable of burials here belong to Mary Ann Nichols and Catherine Eddowes: the  first and third victims of Jack the Ripper. Mary was buried on the 6th September in public grave 210752, which lies on the edge of the Memorial Garden; she is commemorated by a plaque as part of the cemetery’s heritage trail. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/city-of-london-image1.jpg\" alt=\"City of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Mary Ann Nichols grave at City of London Cemetery. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nJust over a month later on the 8th October, Catherine was buried in square 318 of public grave 49336. This spot has been transformed into a section of the Memorial Gardens used for cremated remains so Catherine now rests in front of Memorial Bed 1849, by Garden Way. Her grave is also marked with a plaque. Visitors regularly leave flowers and tokens on their grave markers.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/city-of-london-image2.jpg\" alt=\"City of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Catherine Eddowes grave at City of London Cemetery. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nEdith Thompson, one of the last women to be hanged in the UK, is connected to the cemetery. She was married to Percy Thompson but began an affair with Frederick Bywaters. In 1922 Frederick stabbed Percy to death whilst he and his wife were on their way home from a show in Piccadilly Circus. Both Frederick and Edith were arrested for Percy’s murder. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThey had kept correspondence which revealed that Edith had previously attempted to kill her husband but failed. Following a controversial and difficult trial, Edith was later executed at Holloway Prison and Frederick at Pentonville Prison on the 9th January 1923. Percy Thompson was buried at the City of London Cemetery.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/city-of-london-image3.jpg\" alt=\"City of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>From left to right, Freddy Bywaters, Edith Thompson, and the victim, Percy Thompson. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNot all the burials are such grim reminders, however. Throughout the grounds there lie exquisite memorials to an enormous gamut of figures, such as the Piano Lady grave dedicated to Gladys Spencer, a local music and dance teacher who passed in 1931, aged 34. Her grave features a Classical style female elegantly draped over the keys of a grand piano.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/city-of-london-image4.jpg\" alt=\"City of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Asleep on her grand piano. Gladys Spencer, a pianist who died age 34 in 1931 City of London cemetery. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe grounds house Dame Anna Neagle, a British film and stage actress during the mid-20th century who rose to international celebrity due to her role as Queen Victoria in Victoria the Great (1937) and the sequel Sixty Glorious Years (1938). She went on to feature in Hollywood films too, most notably Spring in Park Lane (1948). \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was mostly known for playing strong women in her films and won a number of awards. She passed away in 1986 and was buried next to her husband in the cemetery; their grave was also unveiled by Princess Anne in March 2014.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/city-of-london-image5.jpg\" alt=\"City of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Anna Neagle, with Paul Hartman and Ray Bolger, in the film Sunny. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere is also a stunning sculptural reproduction of Rubens’ Descent from the Cross to memorialise David Vigiland. Made from a 25 ton block of Carrara marble, the Vigiland memorial commemorates a seaman who died in Mombasa during the Second World War in 1946 and was reinterred in the City of London Cemetery in 1952.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/city-of-london-image6.jpg\" alt=\"City of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>A memorial to the sailor David Vigiland (1926-1946) in the City of London Cemetery, London, UK. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'maryann-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '0.044419', '51.557847', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(70, 'George Yard', 'Bank holidays have always been a cause for celebration and enjoyment; the 6th August 1888 was no exception. What may have started out as a pleasant day for most, ended in grief and shock for some. Crime was a constant concern in East London and around 1-2 murders a month were reported.  The news of the Bank Holiday murder spread like wildfire across London.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMartha Tabram was like many other women in the East End. Born in 1849, she drank heavily and tried to earn a living through selling trinkets and prostitution. She received most of her money through an allowance from her separated husband, Henry Tabram, whom she married when she was 20 years old. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/george-yard-image1.jpg\" alt=\"George Yard\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Finding The Body of Martha Tabram. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nShe also bore him two sons in 1871 and 1872. It is alleged that she suffered from fits, precisely why we do not know, but her later partner, Henry Turner, knew that the fits were exacerbated by drinking. Henry Tabram gave her 12 shillings for three years before reducing it to half a crown (2s 6d). This harsh deduction was due to the fact that Martha was living with Henry Turner, who worked as a carpenter.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was living at Satchell’s Lodging House at 19 George Street in Spitalfields in August 1888 and was working on the streets that evening. She and a colleague had picked up clients and parted ways shortly before midnight. Martha went into George Yard, now Gunthorpe Street, and was found on the first floor landing of George Yard Buildings early the next morning. Alfred Crow was returning from work as a cab driver when he saw her body, but as he thought it was a homeless person, he continued up to bed.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/george-yard-image2.jpg\" alt=\"George Yard\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>The Murder at George\'s Yard, Whitechapel road. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBooth’s poverty map shows the Yard buildings to be ‘fairly comfortable’, however the other side of the street is black, meaning that these dwellings were the very poorest and housed criminals. The red building on the left hand side when facing north, just up the street from Canon Barnett Primary School, is the approximate site of Martha’s death.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/george-yard-image3.jpg\" alt=\"George Yard\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Charles Booth’s Poverty Map of London. <i>Source: Wikicommons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe contemporary newspapers connected Martha’s murder to that of Emma Smith, who was viciously attacked by a gang in April, and later when Mary Ann Nichols was killed. They all came under the umbrella of the <mark> ‘Whitechapel Murders’</mark> and some considered all three to be the doing of one individual. There is still debate as to whether Martha was a victim of Jack the Ripper as the majority of her wounds were to her stomach and groin, which became a “trademark” of the murderer. Furthermore, a large cut about 3x1 inches was incised into her abdomen. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nShe was stabbed a total of 39 times with a small blade. As there were no signs of strangulation as would be typical of a Ripper victim, it was concluded that she died of blood loss. The first known victim, Mary Ann Nichols, was found in the same pose which further connects the two murders. Martha is often considered the first true victim of Jack the Ripper.\r\n', 'george-yard-buildings-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '-0.071643', '51.516839', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', ''),
(71, 'Miller\'s Court - Dorset Street', 'There are only a few minute pockets of London that Charles Booth considered to be of the ‘lowest class’, ‘vicious’ and ‘semi-criminal’. Dorset Street and its narrow alleyways harboured this notorious reputation. Thick strokes of black coat the street on Booth’s poverty map from the late 19th century. The notebooks linked to this map describe Dorset Street as “the worst street in respect of - poverty, misery, vice - of the whole of London. A cesspool into which had sunk the foulest & most degraded.” \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nLodging houses, colloquially called doss houses, dominated the pavements and thus giving it the nickname ‘Dosset Street’. Miller’s Court was a small courtyard, accessed through an archway, featuring small rooms for rent. These were built by the lodging house landlord John Miller who owned numbers 30, 27, and 26, as he wanted to capitalise on the demand for cheap accommodation. The houses at 30 and 27 were later acquired by John McCarthy during the 1880s and 1890s.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe gentrification of the Spitalfields area in recent years has seen an end to the extreme poverty and horrific crimes and Dorset Street is no more. In 2015, the construction of the new Fruit and Wool Exchange began, consuming the space between Brushfield Street and White’s Row.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/millers-court-image1.jpg\" alt=\"Miller\'s Court\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q> Mary Jane Kelly, Newspaper sketch, c. 1888. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nBorn around 1863 in Ireland, Mary Jane Kelly moved to London from Cardiff by 1884 and may have worked in a West End brothel. From there, it is possible she left with a client for France. The large English communities there had a high demand for prostitutes. The brothels were like traps; the women couldn’t go out without a chaperone, the money they earned was seldom enough, and leaving completely was scarcely an option. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMary returned to England quite quickly and ended up in Whitechapel. How and why she went there, along with much of her life, is unknown to us. From early 1888, Mary lived in Miller’s Court with Joseph Barnett, her partner with whom she had lived since 1887. In Summer 1888, Joseph lost his job and couldn’t support Mary anymore; she turned to prostitution and their relationship fell apart. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/millers-court-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Miller\'s Court\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q> Contemporary sketch of John McCarthy. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nJoseph continued to visit and send her money as often as possible. Her neighbour, Lizzie Albrook, recalled that “about the last thing she said was, <mark>‘Whatever you do, don’t you do wrong and turn out as I have.’</mark> ... She told me too she was heartily sick of the life she was leading, and wished she had money enough to go back to Ireland, where her people lived. I don’t believe she would have gone out as she did if she had not been obliged to do so in order to keep herself from starvation.” \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe macabre tourism we see today began soon after her murder by Jack the Ripper. McCarthy was offered £25 for a month’s use of the room by a showman and another expressed a desire to buy the bloodstained bed. Mary’s funeral, however, was an emotional affair with crowds throughout the streets. She is buried at St Patrick’s Cemetery in Leytonstone.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/millers-court-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Miller\'s Court\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q> A close up view of Mary Kelly\'s grave with flowers around the headstone. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'millers-court-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 73, '-0.075037', '51.518615', 0, 1, 1, 0, '', '');
