(128, 'Parliament Hill', 'In an area of open parkland in the south-east corner of Hampstead Heath in north-west London there is still a strong feeling of being very much a part of countryside. And yet, when standing at the viewpoint of Parliament Hill there is this sudden shift of being miles away from the big city. Approximately 6 miles out of the city of London the 791-acre heath, which is an amalgam of the grounds of several large houses that were once in the area, is the summit of Parliament Hill which provides a fantastic view towards London and is a focal point for locals and visitors alike.\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Parliament-Hill-hiddenhistory-london.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>The Land</h2>\r\n\r\nIt has been long suspected that the mound on top of the hill was a Bronze Age (2500 until c. 800 BC) burial barrow. The hill itself was part of a manor in 1133 during Henry I reign. He decided to give the land to Baron Richard de Balta. A grant was confirmed by Westminster to Richard de Balta of ‘land of the fee of Westminster of Hampstead’ for rent of two pounds a year. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThis also included Abbot William de Humez (1214-22) being assigned the two-pound rent ‘from the manor of Hampstead’ to the abbey’s kitchen. It’s not clear if the grant was of the whole manor or of the estate within it. During Henry II reign the manor appears to have been passed onto Alexander de Barentyn who was the King’s butler. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nAs time went on the plots of land in the manor were sold off. Especially in the early 19th century. Although the hill remained mainly common land, The Metropolitan Board of Works (which was created to help provide infrastructure to cope with London’s rapid growth) acquired Hampstead Heath for the people in 1875, which didn’t include Parliament Hill. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_during_sunset.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The area that was known as Traitors\' Hill, may have acquired its current name during the English Civil Warin the 17th century. When it was occupied by troops loyal to the English Parliament. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThirteen years later Parliament Hill was added to Hampstead heath for £300,000. The Manorial rights of the land remained in private hands until the mid-20th century. The manorial rights lapsed under Sir Spencer Pocklington Maryon Wilson. Though the estate itself was purely a formal position without any real power. It was then passed on to Shane Gough, 5th Viscount Gough. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nHampstead Heath including Parliament Hill was host to livestock. The cattle were reared to be sold through Smithfields the London meat market up until the 1940’s. The grass there today is bred farm grasses, which just shows a legacy from a time when the heath was an agricultural resource. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nGreater London Council managed Parliament Hill, which, was then taken over by Camden Council until 1989 when the City of London Corporation took ownership. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_romantic_scene.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>A legend states that this was the site from where Guy Fawkes and Robert Catesby, of the Gunpowder Plot on November the 5th 1605, planned to watch the destruction of Parliament. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>What’s in the Name?</h2>\r\n\r\nIn ancient times, long before Parliament Hill got its name it was referred to as Traitors Hill, possibly due to it being an execution site. A legend states that the hill is connected with the Gunpowder plot to blow up Parliament. It’s believed that Guy Fawkes and Robert Catesby planned to watch Parliament being destroyed from the top of the hill on the 5th of November 1605. As intriguing as this is, especially in relation to the name Traitors Hill, the theory is unsubstantiated.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIt was also suggested that the name Traitors Hill came about in the mid-17th century during the English Civil War. Troops loyal to Parliament would occupy the hill. With the modern houses of Parliament seen from the viewpoint, those who were against King Charles I and his views on the Irish insurrection would use the hill as a point of defence. It isn’t clear, if the name changed during the civil war or after but the name ‘Parliament Hill’ did come into existence. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Gunpowder_Plot_conspirators_hidden_history.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>A contemporary engraving of eight of the thirteen conspirators, by Crispijn van de Passe; Catesby is second from the right. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>It’s not just about the View.</h2>\r\n\r\nParliament Hill is best known for its viewpoint at the top. Measuring 98.1 metres (322 ft) high, providing beautiful views across London. The view, which can be captured in one panorama, is one of three viewing locations on Hampstead heath that has been identified in Greater London Authority\'s London View Management Framework.This is in recognition of the significant views towards St Pauls Cathedral and Victoria Tower at the Palace of Westminster. The viewpoint is also at times referred to as “kite hill” due to the popularity of flying kites on a sunny day.However, there is more to the area then meets the eye. Parliament Hill not only has some key landmarks but also holds various sporting events. It is also home to a flock of Flamingos. \r\n \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kite_flying.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The viewpoint is also at times referred to as “kite hill” due to the popularity of flying kites on a sunny day.. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>The Parliament Hill Lido.</h2>\r\n\r\nThe Parliament Hill Lido can be found at the bottom of the hill next to Gospel Oak railway station. The pool turned 80 years old in 2018 and is popular with locals as a place to exercise or just cool off in an outdoor pool. On the 20th of August 1938 the now Grade II-listed Lido was opened. At the time it was the most expensive of the 13 outdoor pools in London County Council that was built between 1920 and the outbreak of the Second World War. When it originally opened diving-boards adorned its sides as well as a slide. However, today the offering is more simplistic.In 1990, Historic England listed the lido under the Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990 as amended for its special architectural or historic interest. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn 2005 the Lido underwent an extensive refurbishment. It now boasts a new stainless-steel liner (the only one of its kind in an outdoor pool in the UK) and reflective qualities that not only help retain heat, but also gives the water an extra shimmer. The pool isn’t just for families and wetsuit-clad fitness fiends, the lido will also be used for forthcoming triathlons. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_lido_hidden_history_london.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Built in 1938 and Grade II-listed, this is the only stainless steel lined outdoor pool in the country. Diving into it is like entering a giant shiny metal bowl. <i>Source: Dominick Tyler from the Book Wild Swim</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Parliament Hill Bandstand.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\nOut of everything to see at Parliament Hill there is nothing that has as much history as the Bandstand. The bandstand that stands today was actually built in the 1990’s as the original was rundown. The original however, was based on the other side of Kite Hill on the banks of Highgate Ponds in the early 1900’s. The Bandstand was the subject of many attractive posters and black and white snapshots, which proved that the spot was quite the tourist attraction and as a place to see and be seen.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nToday’s bandstand can be found next to the Farmers Markets and Cricket ground. The current design is based on the original. There is no particular record of when the original and sizeable circular seating area around disappeared from Parliament Hill Fields, however there was a post-war carbuncle that was certainly in operation in the current location from the 1950’s.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/bandstand_at_parliament_hill_hidden_history.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>The bandstand that stands today was actually built in the 1990’s as the original was rundown. <i>Source: Julian Osley / Bandstand, Parliament Hill Fields</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIn the late 1960’s Camden Council organised a series of free concerts at the bandstand. Beginning in September 1968, on a rainy Wednesday the Jefferson Airplane and Fairport Convention played to only a few hundred tuned-in people. The following summer the council progressed their free Camden Festival concept further by putting on three weekly parties throughout May. The first band to perform at the festival was Pink Floyd. The band were squeezed into the corrugated iron shed while battling the feedback from their PA. <mark>The following week the crowd doubled in size.</mark>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThis was partly due to John Peel mentioning the events on his radio shows and by week three Fleetwood Mac played with 25,000 people turning up. Sadly, Fleetwood Mac only played a couple of songs before being forced off the stage due to a group of people causing trouble.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nIn recent years more celebrities have brought attention to the bandstand. In 2006 Booker Prize-winning local author Alan Hollinghurst fought a long and ultimately fruitless battle to have a programme of Sunday afternoon brass, jazz and Japanese music performed at the bandstand blocked. The grounds of the “intolerable noise nuisance” ABBA’s Benny Anderson also brought international attention to the bandstand by performing some of the pop classics he penned in a ‘comeback gig’ as part of a Swedish cultural celebration. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Parliament_Hill_hiddenhistory_london_bandstand.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nTo hear more about the Pink Floyd gig ‘The Archive’ has documented stories of those who were present which, can be accessed <a href=\"http://www.ukrockfestivals.com/pinkfloyd5-9-69.html\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a>\r\nThe bandstand today is a focal point for a lot of the Heath events and like previous generations of school kids it is still a popular meeting spot during the week. The heath’s famous lone bagpiper still plays out tunes at the bandstand during most of the early mornings. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<h2>Parliament Hill School.</h2>\r\n\r\n<mark>The Community School for Girls opened in 1906.</mark> As of 2013 the secondary school and sixth form for girls had 1,266 students enrolled with ages between 11 and 18. The school is part of the successful SASWAP sixth form consortium, which focuses strongly on the academic qualifications.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/parliament_hill_school.jpg\" alt=\"Parliament Hill\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Parliament Hill School is a secondary school and sixth form for girls located in the Borough of Camden in London, England. In 2013, there were 1,250 students on roll, between the ages of 11 and 18. <i>Source: Parliament Hill School / Facebook</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nOther amenities at Parliament Hill are grass tennis courts, an athletics track, a cricket pitch, angling and cycling facilities and there is even an area for bowls and croquet. Beside the cricket pitch is the Parliament Hill London Farmers Market, which is open every Saturday from 10am-2pm. On the other side there is an adventure playground for the kids. \r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nParliament Hill is one of the focal points of Hampstead Heath overall and provides Londoners a small piece of the countryside while living in the capital city. There are even parts of the hill that are still unmown in the summer which are crisscrossed by a network of pathways. Parliament Hill can be seen as a less popular place to visit compared to other sites, however, it provides a natural haven to north Londoners and its history is rich for those who wish to seek it.\r\n', 'Parliament-Hill-Header-image.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1618931', '51.5596682', 1, 1, 0, 0, '', ''),
(129, 'Museum of London', 'First established in 1976, the Museum of London is amongst the most popular of London’s museums as its collection covers the capitals history as far back as the prehistoric sight of the city, right up to the modern London we see today. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocated a stone through away from St Paul’s Cathedral and on the sight of the London Wall, the museum provides visitors with a fascinatingly extensive insight into the evolution of the capital through some of the best and worst periods in British History. The museum of London is a definite must-see for visitors wishing to obtain a more in-depth insight into London’s history, and is a perfect day out for families too. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-gecko.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Museum of London Exterior <i>Source: Francesco Camardo // Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<h4>Entry Fee: </h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThis museum is free to enter. Any exhibitions and events however, may be subject to admission fees. \r\n\r\n<h4>Opening times:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe museum is open Monday-Sunday (10am-6pm) \r\n\r\n<h4>Photography allowed:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, photography is allowed at this museum. However, flash is not allowed due to the age of some of the exhibits.\r\n\r\n<h4>Interactive technology:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, this museum has interactive technology. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Roman_London.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <br><sub><q>You could discover how Londinium came to life and what daily life was like for Romans in the city 2,000 years ago <i>Source: Museum of London</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h4>Facilities for kids:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, this museum has a variety of different facilities available for children. For example, volunteer run ‘hands on history’ sessions are run by volunteers which give children the chance to interact hands-on with historical artefacts. \r\n<br />\r\n\r\nPlease see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/families/visit-museum-london\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Families </a>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Guides:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA full floor plan and guide (in several languages) are available online to download. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/museum-london/plan-your-visit/floor-plan\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Floor Plan </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<h4>1. Bucklersbury Mosaic (250 AD):</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Bucklersbury-Mosaic.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Large mosaic floor with semi-circular end, from Bucklersbury, 3rd century AD, Queen Victoria Street, Londinium, Roman London, Museum of London <i>Source: Flickr</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThis beautiful multi-coloured roman pavement was first discovered in Bucklersbury (in the City of London) in 1869. The mosaic has survived almost completely intact, and its few missing sections have been restored. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOriginally a heating system would have passed underneath this mosaic floor, consisting of a central channel radiating with smaller channels which hot air would pass through to go up inside the walls through the tiles. Don’t miss this incredible piece of ancient history in the Roman London gallery. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>2. Unic Taxi (1908):</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/unic-taxis-hidden-history.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>The Unic taxi was the first licenced petrol-driven taxi to arrive in London in 1903, with this specific vehicle being licensed for the use of taxi in 1908 <i>Source: Mike Peel // Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThe Unic taxi was the first licenced petrol-driven taxi to arrive in London in 1903, with this specific vehicle being licensed for the use of taxi in 1908. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe early Edwardian period saw a technological revolution, with the mass development of motor vehicles bringing over 2,000 motor-cabs to the city which threatened the traditional modes of transportation such as horse-drawn hansoms and four wheeled growlers. See for yourselves the beautiful predecessor of the modern taxi in the ‘Modern London’ gallery.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>3. London 2012 Cauldron:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/london_2012_cauldron_hidden_history.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Thomas Heatherwick’s London 2012 Cauldron is the star of this gallery. With dramatic footage and exclusive testimony, we recapture its journey from design to the climactic opening and closing ceremonies. <i>Source: Source: Museum of London</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nOn the night of the 27th July 2012, the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic cauldron (designed by Thomas Heatherwick) was revealed for the first time to the world. At the climax of the incredible opening ceremony, the cauldrons 204 stems dramatically rose up in the air to form a beautiful feature in the centre of the Olympic stadium in Stratford, which became a defining moment of the ceremony. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo this day, the 2012 Olympics remains an pivotal historical landmark in British history- So don’t miss this wonderful atmospheric installation with light, sound and video nestled in the centre of the ‘Modern London’ floor.\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Food and Drink facilities:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, this museum has several food and drink facilities such as London Wall Bar and Kitchen, Benugo Entrance Hall Café and Benugo Sackler Hall Café. There is also a museum lunch space for families to bring their own food and drink. \r\n\r\n<h4>Tours:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nGuided tours and talks are available at this museum however, there is a fixed charge for the different tours. Please see the link below for more information: \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/application/files/1614/7888/5118/Group_tours_201617.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"> Museum of London / Tours </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Nearest station/Tube:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe nearest stations to the Museum of London are Barbican station (5-minute walk) and St Paul’s station (5-minute walk) \r\n\r\n<h4>Bus routes:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nBuses 4, 8, 25, 56, 100, 172, 242, 521 all stop near the museum. \r\n\r\n<h4>Postcode/address:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nMuseum of London, 150 London Wall, London EC2Y 5HN\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/museum-of-london-interior.jpg\" alt=\"Museum of London\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>How revolutions in technology, fashion, and culture have transformed London <i>Source: Museum of London</i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThere are a small number of disabled parking spaces for Blue and Orange Badge holders although spaces must be booked in advance. Please call 02078145552 to book, or email: \r\n\r\n<a href = \"mailto: access@museumoflondon.org.uk\"> acesss@museumoflondon.org.uk</a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nAssistance dogs are welcome to museum and portable induction loops are available at the front desk. Some of the theatres are fitted with induction loop systems, and there is a selection of subtitled and BSL interpreted videos in the galleries. \r\n<br /> \r\nFree monthly BSL and captioned tours are also available each month. \r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nMagnifying glasses are available from the information desks, as well as large print guides for the permanent and major exhibitions. Free monthly gallery tours for visitors with visual impairments are also available. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nWheelchairs and mobility scooters are available to borrow during your visit, please book them in advance from the above number. Folding seats are also available to borrow at any time. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nLifts and escalators are available from street level near the London Wall roundabout, as well as a lift and staircase at noble street. Fully accessible toilets and lifts are available on all floors of the museum. \r\n\r\n', 'museum-of-london.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.096676', '51.517809', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(130, 'Freemasons Hall & London Museum', 'Located on Great Queen Street, the site of the current Freemasons’ Hall has been the headquarters for English and Welsh Freemasons since 1775. The current building was built in 1932 in memorial to the 3,000 members of the Freemasons who were killed in the First World War. It is still an active location for Freemason meetings, events and ceremonies. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe building is one of the UK’s finest examples of Art Deco architecture and is an important location for the preservation of the history of Freemasonry, with a library and museum which are free and open to visitors. Hidden in plain sight to visitors of the city, the current museum space was opened in 2016 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Freemasonry and follows the ‘Three Centuries of English Freemasons’ beginning in 1717 to the present day.\r\n<br><br>\r\nOn display in the gallery are a collection of fascinating objects, books and documentations such as ceremonial jewels, early constitutions and the standout golden ‘Grand Masters Throne’ which was created for King George IV in 1791, an object which cannot be missed. Down the hall from the museum is the library, also open to visitors, which offers a collection of over 65,000 books which cover the dense history of British Freemasonry where visitors can sit and read, use the computers and even search their own family histories for links to Freemasonry.\r\n<br></br>\r\nFor those interested in the history of the hall itself, free tours are offered up to five times per day and are an excellent chance for visitors to see inside the Grand Temple and ceremonial areas still used by the Freemason’s today.', 'Freemasons_Hall_London.JPG', 1, NULL, 0, 0, '-0.121531', '51.515178', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(131, 'Ham Hill', 'Originally an Iron Age hillfort, Ham Hill was one of the first native settlements to be ceased by the Claudian invasion forces in 43 AD. The remains of this fort \r\n<br><br>\r\nindicate it was an immense structure, with a circumference of 3 miles and an area of 210 acres, consequently the Roman\'s conquest of the site is likely to have been a significant cog in the invasion machine. \r\n<br><br>\r\nFurthermore, its location on the top of a hill ensured that the Romans were able to establish a permanent fortification and effective vantage point from which to quash and manage the local Durotriges tribe. \r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image2.jpg\" alt=\"Ham Hill\"> <br><sub><q>Ham Hill War Memorial.. <i>Source: Steve // flickr </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA significant number of Roman military artefacts have been found both on Ham Hill and in the surrounding area, with the majority identified as legionary in origin. \r\n<br><br>\r\nConsequently, whilst there are no physical remains of the Roman fort, the quality and quantity of the finds, along with the site\'s dominance over the surrounding area, makes it very likely that a fort was built here. \r\n<br><br>\r\nFurthermore, the absence of the expected v-shaped defensive ditches or building foundations usually found at the sites of Roman forts is most likely a result of the site only being used during the initial stages of the Claudian campaigns. \r\n<br><br>\r\nOnce the invasion forces had conquered the south of Britain, they quickly moved on to Wales and Northern Britain, levelling and abandoning forts they no longer required as they left to prevent re-use by any local dissident forces.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image3.jpg\" alt=\"Ham Hill\"> <sub><q>A mountainous view of Ham Hill. <i>Source: Wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhilst Ham Hill had strategic significance during the early years of the Roman occupation, it was not used again until after the Romans left Britain in 5th century AD. \r\n<br><br>\r\nArchaeological finds from the site and surrounding area suggest the presence of various settlements from as early as the Saxon period, however evidence has failed to confirm whether the fort was used as a military base again. \r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image4.jpg\" alt=\"Ham Hill\"> <br><sub><q>Sunset at Ham Hill <i>Source: Wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe site is managed by South Somerset District Council and is open all year round, weather permitting - \'entrance is free\'. There is extensive free parking available and plenty of hilly landscapes, leafy woodlands and grassy meadows to explore. \r\n<br><br>\r\nToilets are available at the Ham Hill Centre and refreshment facilities can be found at the Price of Wales pub which is located nearby. \r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/ham-hill-image5.jpg\" alt=\"Ham Hill\"> <br><sub><q>Landscape of Ham Hill <i>Source: Wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h4>Secondary sources</h4>\r\nArchaeology Magazine Online (2013) \'Ham Hill\'s Ramparts Excavated\', Archaeology, online \r\n<a href=\"https://www.archaeology.org/news/1277-130906-england-ham-hill-iron-age-ramparts\" target=\"_blank\"> Click Here</a>\r\n<br />\r\nDe la Bedoyere, G. (2013) Roman Britain: A New History, Thames & Hudson Ltd., London.\r\n<br />\r\nRoman Britain (n.d.) \'Ham Hill\', Roman Britain, online \r\n<a href=\"http://www.roman-britain.co.uk/places/ham_hill.htm\" target=\"_blank\"> Click Here</a>\r\n<br />\r\nSomerset Military Museum (n.d.) \'Ham Hill Hillfort\', Somerset Military History, online\r\n<a href=\"http://www.sommilmuseum.org.uk/ham-hill-hillfort/\" target=\"_blank\">Click Here</a>\r\n<br />\r\nHam Hill<a href=\"http://www.historic-uk.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/ham-hill.jpg\" target=\"_blank\"> Click Here</a>\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n', 'Ham_Hill_Image1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-2.744622', '50.948775', 1, 1, 0, 0, 'Somerset, England', ''),
(132, 'The ARP Stretcher Fences', 'A peculiar site peppered around London are odd looking metal fences. To a casual passer-by the oddness would not be picked up on but have a closer look and you can see metal fences that have peculiar curves in their horizontal bars. \r\n\r\nThese are not a fancy design template ordered up en masse in post-war Britain but are in fact recycled WWII Air Raid Precautions Department (ARP) steel stretchers that have been recycled as street fencing. The unusual curves are the stretcher handles.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Arp Stretchers\"> <sub><q>Arp Stretchers converted into fences. <i>Source: Wikimedia </i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n60,000 of these stretchers were produced during WWII to cater for expected casualties from German bombing raids and come the end of the conflict they were very much surplus to requirements.\r\n  \r\nAt this point London was rebuilding and upcycling these stretchers was seen as a fantastic opportunity to replace metal railings that had (during the war) been collected to use towards the war effort.  \r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Arp Stretchers\"> <sub><q>Stretchers in use <i>Source: wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSadly, the number of surviving metal stretcher fences is falling due to their upkeep and the effects of the weather on them over the years but a lot of examples still exist today.\r\n\r\nIf you find yourself in the following areas be sure to keep an eye out for the wartime stretcher fences.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/arp-stretchers-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Arp Stretchers\"> <sub><q>Stretcher fences at Down\'s estate. <i>Source: Wikimedia commons </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />', 'arp-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 0, 0, 'London, UK', ''),
(133, 'Brighton Palace Pier', 'Brighton Palace Pier, opened on 20 May 1899, was built as a pleasure pier to entertain and delight the high number of visitors brought by Britain’s growing railway network. Designed by Richard Saint George Moore on behalf of the Brighton Marine and Palace Pier Company, it was the third pier to be built in Brighton; alongside the Old Chain Pier and the West Pier. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe latter of these was also a pleasure pier, making Brighton the ultimate sea-side resort.\r\nIn 1891 construction of the Palace Pier began, but was slow due to financial problems. During a storm in 1896 the Old Chain Pier was destroyed, its debris causing much damage to the new pier and delaying construction further. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Public-Advertisement-Palace-Pier.jpg\" alt=\"Brighton Palace Pier\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <br> <sub><q>Advertisement for Palace Pier amusements, 3 September 1903 <i>Source: Brighton Pier</i></q></sub>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Features of the pier.</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe Palace Pier cost an astonishing £137,000 to build and was 1500 feet long (457.2 metres). In its early years it featured illuminated archways, as well as rooms for reading, dining, and smoking. There was a landing place for steam boats and a section for bathers, free between 7am and midday (Brighton Gazette - 3 September 1903). \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA 1500 seat theatre opened at the seaward end of the pier in April 1901, and after it was refurbished in 1911 it hosted an array of music hall stars. A pleasure garden was added in the centre of the pier in 1910. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n  \r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Brigton-Palace-Pier.jpg\" alt=\"Brighton Palace Pier\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br> <sub><q>Illustration of the Brighton Palace Pier shortly before it opened, 11 January 1899 (The Sketch) <i>Source: Brighton Pier</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Brigton-Palace-Pier-1.jpg\" alt=\"Brighton Palace Pier\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"><br> <sub><q>Brighton Palace Pier in 1901 <i>Source: James Gray Collection / The Regency Society</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>The twentieth century and beyond</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe pier continued to develop its entertainment functions; the 1930s saw the introduction of dodgems and a big wheel. During World War Two the pier was closed and guarded by soldiers to prevent its use as a landing point by enemy troops. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter the War the Palace Pier continued to attract visitors, becoming ever more prominent as its popular neighbour, the West Pier, began to fall into disrepair following a change in ownership in the 1960s. New arcade games like Space Invaders were introduced in the 1980s, propelling the pier into the modern age. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday the pier is 1733 feet long (525 metres) and still privately owned; it features video arcades, slot machines, sea-side stalls and a fairground and is an iconic part of the sea-front.\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Visitor Information:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe pier is open every day, except for Christmas day. Opening times are between 10:00 and 22:00 in the summer months (1 April and 31 October), and 10:00 and 17:00 in \r\n\r\nthe winter months (1 November to 31 March). For detailed opening times for rides and amusements visit: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.brightonpier.co.uk.\" target=\"_blank\"> Brighton Pier </a>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Find out more:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://piers.org.uk/\" target=\"_blank\"> National Piers Society </a>\r\n\r\nWest Pier Trust,<a href=\"https://www.westpier.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\"> West Pier </a> The West Pier Centre is located in one of the seafront arches across from the old pier.\r\n', 'Brighton-Palace-Pier-2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1389267', '50.8168555', 1, 1, 0, 0, 'Brighton', ''),
(134, 'The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice', 'Sitting against an adjoining wall in Postman’s Park – aptly named as it was once the site of the headquarters of the General Post Office where the postmen used to go during their breaks – this little-known monument remembers the lives of 62 people who died selflessly trying to save another. \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nThis memorial to everyday heroism and self-sacrifice was proposed by the painter and sculptor, George Frederic Watts, in a letter to the editor of The Times in 1887 as part of the celebrations of Queen Victoria’s Golden Jubilee. He, like many wealthy people in the late Victorian period, believed in the need for social reform for the poor in England, and in turn saw a need to actively remember the heroism of ‘ordinary’ people. In his letter he wrote:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<mark> “The character of a nation as a people of great deeds is one, it appears to me, that should never be lost sight of. It must surely be a matter of regret when names worthy to be remembered and stories stimulating and instructive are allowed to be forgotten… It is not too much to say that the history of Her Majesty’s reign would gain a lustre were the nation to erect a monument, say, here in London, to record the names of these likely to be forgotten heroes”. <small> George Frederic Watts</small>\r\n</mark>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/George_Frederic_Watts\'s_Memorial_to_Heroic_Self_Sacrifice.jpg\" alt=\"The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nDespite this initial suggestion for the memorial, it wasn’t officially opened until 30 July 1900. In 1898, Watts was invited by the vicar of St Botolph’s church – the space being their former churchyard – to create the monument in the now public park. So, in 1899 the construction began of the 50ft long 9ft high shelter by J. Simpson and Son for the tablets at the cost of £402. Benches were also installed to encourage the public to stay a little longer. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSpace was made available for 120 tablets (in rows of 24), though only 54 tablets have been installed so far. Each tablet is made up of small tiles and records the name(s) of the deceased with the details and date of the events making them worthy of remembrance. Only 4 of these plaques were installed when the monument was opened. The remainder of the first row included 9 installed in 1902, and 11 more along with T. H. Wren’s memorial to Watts in 1905 following his death the year before. All 24 of these tablets were designed by the ceramicist William De Morgan. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Postman\'s_Park_Wall_of_Heroes.jpg\" alt=\"The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nA further 29 tablets were designed by Royal Doulton, 24 of which were installed altogether in 1908 filling a second row. Another 5 Doulton-style tablets were added on the next row from 1919-1930, which included replacement of a De Morgan tablet with incorrect information. A further tablet in the original De Morgan style created by Fred Passenger was slotted into the old spot for the incorrect tablet in 1931. Finally, the 54th tablet was added much later in 2009, commemorating Leigh Pitt who died saving a boy from drowning in 2007.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nOne of the people featured in the memorial is Alice Ayres, who died in 1885 while trying to save three children under her care from an upper-story of a burning house. Two of the three children survived, and Alice died in the process of trying to save herself as she fell awkwardly after jumping out the window. She was one of the most famous additions to the memorial and had already been commemorated in other ways across the country around the time of her death – this included in memorials, artwork and a street was renamed after her near to where she died on Union Street in 1936. Her name was also used as an alias in the play (and 2004 film) Closer.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/alice-ayres.jpg\" alt=\"The Watts Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Alice Ayres (pictured above) was an English nursemaid honoured for her bravery in rescuing the children in her care from a house fire. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nIf you find you want to get to know them better, we absolutely recommend you that you read  <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Heroes-Postmans-Park-Self-Sacrifice-2015-09-01/dp/B01FKUO11S/\" target=\"_blank\">Dr John Price’s Heroes of Postman’s Park: Heroic Self-Sacrifice in Victorian London,</a> where he delves into the lives of each person remembered in the memorial. You can hear him in an interview about his research here. You can also follow the Friends of Watts Memorial on Twitter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/wattsmemorial\" target=\"_blank\">@WattsMemorial </a> to see upcoming events and to find out how you can support them.\r\n', 'watts-memorial-app.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.097334', '51.516742', 1, 1, 0, 0, '', ''),
(135, 'Nelson\'s Column', 'Nelson’s death at Trafalgar secured his position as one of Britain’s most heroic figures. His signal “England expects that every man will do his duty” has been regularly quoted, paraphrased and referenced right up to the modern day. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is because of that, that Admiral Nelson has had numerous monuments erected in his honour cementing not only his memory but also his legacy. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/Horatio_Nelson_painting_hidden_history_uk.jpg\" alt=\"Nelson\'s Column\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Vice-Admiral Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson was a British flag officer in the Royal Navy. He was noted for his inspirational leadership, grasp of strategy, and unconventional tactics, which together resulted in a number of decisive British naval victories, particularly during the Napoleonic Wars. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\nThe monument itself takes centre stage in Trafalgar Square towering at 18 ft. 1 in (5.5m). As the main feature of Trafalgar square the column plays host to thousands of tourists, performances and protest rallies. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo many it represents more than what Britain has achieved. The monument itself was built between 1840 and 1843. Designed by William Railton the construction made out of Dartmoor granite weighed around 2,500 tonnes. \r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/nelson\'s_column_slide1_hidden_history_london.jpg\" alt=\"Nelson\'s Column\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\">\r\n<sub><q>Nelson’s Column cost £47,000 to built in the 1840s, which is the equivalent of between £3 million and £4 million today. Most of the money came from private investors, with the Tsar of Russia footing more than a quarter of the bill on his own. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nBorn Horatio Nelson on the 29th September 1758 in Burnham Thorpe Norfolk, he was the 6th of 11 children of a clergyman. Joining the navy at the tender age of 12, he moved swiftly through the ranks and became Captain at 20. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\nOver the years Nelson led the English to many victories however, that came at a cost. <mark>By 1797 he had lost sight in his right eye and also had lost his right arm.</mark>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBefore the Battle of Trafalgar on 21 October 1805 Nelson sent out the famous signal to his fleet <mark>“England expects that every man will do his duty”.</mark>\r\nA few hours later while leading the attack on the combined French and Spanish fleet a musket shot fired from the fighting top of the French ship Redoubtable badly wounded him. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/fall_of_nelson_horatio_Battle_of_Trafalgar_hh_hidden_history_london.jpg\" alt=\"Nelson\'s Column\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\"> <sub><q>Painter Denis Dighton\'s imagining of Nelson being shot on the quarterdeck of Victory. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\nThree hours later he passed away from his wound. Once the battle was over, his body was preserved in brandy while heading back to England where he was given a state funeral.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n25 years after Nelson’s Column was erected Sir Edwin Landsser was asked to design 4 lions to be added to the base of the monument. Plagued with delays and prevarication the statues that stand today, although in the same position are not identical. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'nelsons-column-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.127716', '51.507759', 1, 1, 2, 0, '', '');
