(136, 'Sutton Hoo', 'The Anglo Saxon Royal Cemetery at Sutton Hoo is a unique 6th to 7th century burial ground of high status individuals. Around twenty earthen burial mounds make up the cemetery and, while they may seem unremarkable from the surface, archaeologists have discovered far more beneath the surface. These mounds were designed to be seen and to make a statement about the status of the individuals interred beneath them.\r\n<br><br>\r\nUnfortunately, many of the mounds were damaged as a result of being robbed during the Tudor period something which is woefully common for visible burial mounds as they would often be looted in pursuit of  \'treasure\'. Since then, however, numerous investigations have taken place surrounding the mounds. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe first proper excavation was conducted in 1939 by self-taught archaeologist Basil Brown, commissioned and organised by the landowner, Edith Pretty. It was this first dig that uncovered the great ship burial of Mound One and made Sutton Hoo a centre of archaeological exploration ever since. \r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sutton Hoo\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Helmet from the Sutton Hoo ship-burial, England. 7th century AD.<i>Source: British Museum // Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h2>Burial Mounds</h2><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe most famous of the mounds is Mound One, where an immense 90ft ship burial was first unearthed in 1939. There are actually two ship burials at Sutton Hoo - the lesser known being under Mound Two. Unfortunately, this burial was disturbed by looters, but iron ship rivets reveal the presence of a small boat under the mound. This style of burial reflected contemporary practices in 7th century Sweden, showing a connection between Anglo Saxons in (what is now known as) East Anglia and cultures elsewhere in northern Europe. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe funerals would have been performative with lavish grave goods, ceremony and the construction of the immense mounds would have been made by hand. Not only was the burial packed with an abundance of rich grave goods, but the committal of an entire ship to the ground would have been an amazing spectacle. It would have cemented in their memory the royal status and significance of the individual buried. \r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\"><br>\r\n<sub><q> Burial mound at Sutton Hoo, Suffolk, UK. This mound has been reconstructed to its supposed original height. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\nWhile we cannot be sure exactly who was buried, it is generally accepted that this is the likely resting place of Raedwald, ruler of the East Angles and the first king to rule as overlord over England as a whole. \r\n<br><br>\r\nAccording to Bede\'s Historia Ecclesiastica, Rædwald was amongst the earliest Anglo Saxon rulers in England to be baptised and he is credited with playing a significant role in the establishment of Christianity within the ruling classes. His new faith, however, earned the disapproval of his household and queen, who tried to coax him back to his pagan Gods (Plunkett 2005). \r\n<br><br>\r\nRædwald maintained elements of his pagan lifestyle and allowed the East Angles to worship both the Christian and the traditional Anglo-Saxon religions if they desired, something the devout Bede criticised him for. \r\n<br><br>\r\nAs a result of the immense wealth, status and religious associations of the individual under Mound One, it’s clear to see why Raedwald is such a strong candidate.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h2>Artefacts in focus</h2><p class=\"text-justify\"> \r\nFortunately, not all the mounds were looted and this meant that, upon excavation, archaeologists uncovered a trove of rich grave goods in their original position. These grave goods (objects placed in a grave alongside a body) can be used to give us an insight into the wealth of the individual. \r\n<br><br>\r\nFor example, the grave is full of military equipment and valuable weapons, indicating their role as a warrior king within Anglo Saxon society. Similar equipment is found underneath Mound Seventeen, where a young warrior is poignantly buried alongside their horse and an abundance of weapons – their horse would have been sacrificed for the funeral which would have been a spectacular albeit grisly ritual display. \r\n<br><br>\r\nChristian faith is also demonstrated in several of the items that accompanied the individual to the grave. These objects are amongst the main reasons that the grave is thought to belong to Rædwald. \r\n<br><br>\r\nAs religious beliefs can play such a huge part in people’s understanding of death and the afterlife, objects with religious motifs and associations are common finds, especially at times of religious transition such as Anglo Saxon period. \r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\"><br>\r\n<sub><q> Burial chamber of the Sutton Hoo ship-burial, England. Reconstruction shown in the Sutton Hoo Exhibition Hall.<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\nFor example, ten nested silver bowls from the Eastern Empire were found alongside two Byzantium silver spoons with the names of the Apostles ‘Paul’ and ‘Saul’ engraved on them, in Greek. These are suggested to be possible baptismal gifts, buried as a symbol of Raedwald’s conversion to Christianity. There are also symbols of crosses on brooches, and a secret chamber hidden in the back of the gold Great Buckle that may have housed a Christian relic. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe Great Buckle is an incredible example of master goldsmithing, with interwoven ribbon animal decoration and fine detailing. Perhaps the most exquisite artefacts found in the grave are a pair of fine filigree worked shoulder clasps, inlayed with garnets, millefiori designs, interlacing ribbon animal decoration and filigree surrounds. The motifs on the buckle are packed full of Anglo Saxon symbolism, cementing Raedwald’s cultural identity.\r\n<br><br>\r\n \r\nThe Sutton Hoo helmet is perhaps the most recognisable artefact from the grave. As well as its striking appearance and precious materials, it is laden with symbolism. It has been argued that the helmet makes reference to one-eyed Odin from Norse Mythology (Price and Mortimer 2014), due to imagery represented across northern Europe. If you look closely, you will notice a deliberate absence of gold foils over the left eye of the helmet and over the left eye of an animal head near the crow. \r\n<br><br>\r\n \r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\" ><br>\r\n<sub><q>Sutton Hoo helmet reconstructed. <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\nIn the low light of a feasting hall, this would result in the illumination of the right eye, and the casting of a shadow over the left – a powerful allusion to Odin and possibly declaring the wearer to be of the same status as the pagan god.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe placement of drinking horns (a common Anglo Saxon grave good) in the grave may have also served to create an image of the “worthy dead” (Pollington 2011: 21) as the possession and use of feasting equipment marked an individual’s place within society. The feasting equipment and lyre paint an image of a mead hall, full of music and celebration, with Rædwald as the gracious host. The funeral itself may have included some mead-fuelled celebration of the life of the deceased. Evidence of funerary feasting at the grave-side is common at Anglo Saxon burial sites (Lee 2007), and it may have been part of a transitionary ritual to aid passing into the afterlife.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h2>Ghosts in the sand</h2><p class=\"text-justify\"> \r\n\'Taphonomy’ is the study of the preservation, decay or changes to archaeological material after it has been deposited in the ground. A detailed, forensic approach to excavation and study of excavated material allows archaeologists to reconstruct the story of what has happened to organic material before, during and after burial. <mark>Soil conditions, burrowing animals, climate and even gnawing dogs can have a huge impact on survival of organic material.</mark>\r\n<br><br>\r\nAt Sutton Hoo, the acidic soil conditions meant that the great oak ship did not survive its 1400 years in the soil and the bones of Raedwald had long-since decayed. How, then, did archaeologists claim to ‘find’ the great ship burial and burials? \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Sand Bodies of Sutton Hoo.<i>Source: P.M.Sabin Moore Blog </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\nGhosts of the organic materials appeared as staining in the acidic yellow sand - archaeologists have to have a keen eye for changes in soil colour and texture, so they were able to spot these anomalies and excavate around them, creating ‘sand people’ (similar in appearance to some of the Pompeii casts) or identifying the structure of the ship. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThese were inhumation burials, but cremation burials were also uncovered at Sutton Hoo. Cremations are likely to have been the earliest at the site (Carver 1998) and are found under several mounds, as well as in the surrounding area. \r\n<br><br>\r\nAs well as visible staining, decaying organic material can leave invisible traces of phosphates in the soil. In 1967, soil analysis from Mound One revealed a significant spike in the phosphate levels, indicating that there had once been a body in the grave but it had dissolved in the acidic environment.\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h3>Visiting Sutton Hoo</h3> \r\n<p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sutton-hoo-image7-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Bill Slim Statue\"><br>\r\n<sub><q>Sutton Hoo Exhibition Hall with Helmet sculpture.  <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\nMany of the artefacts from across the Sutton Hoo site can be seen in the British Museum, but replicas and original are also housed in the Sutton Hoo visitor centre. \r\n<br><br>\r\nDue to a development project currently being undertaken at the National Trust site, the visitor centre and cemetery reopen to the public from late spring to early summer of 2019. A viewing platform is also being constructed at the National Trust site, so visitors will be able to fully appreciate the significance of the burial ground.\r\n<br><br>\r\n(Learn more: www.nationaltrust.org.uk/sutton-hoo/projects/releasing-the-story-of-sutton-hoo). \r\n <br>\r\nPlan your visit, follow updates on the development or visit Sutton Hoo roadshow events through the National Trust website: https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/sutton-hoo\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'sutton-hoo-header-image-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '1.3384194', '52.0893194', 1, 1, 0, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', 'www.hidden-history.com'),
(139, 'William Morris Gallery', 'Located ‘Water House’ the former family home of William Morris himself in Walthamstow, the William Morris Gallery is the only public gallery which is dedicated to Morris – a famous Victorian designer, craftsman, socialist, writer and founder of the arts and crafts movement which took place throughout the 1800s. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image7-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>William Morris Gallery <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nExploring the many layers of Morris’ life, the Gallery is the perfect location for those who are interested in the historical progression of arts and crafts, or those who are a fan of the many famous Morris & Co prints which are still world renown to this day!  Featuring a plethora of fabrics, rugs, wallpapers, furniture and prints designed by Morris, his friends and family, the Gallery is a brilliant day out for adults and children a-like and the beautiful large gardens surrounding the property would be the ideal location for a spring/summer trip!\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Entry Fee: </h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThis museum is free to enter and the temporary exhibition ‘The Enchanted Garden’ is also free to visit. \r\n<br /><br>\r\n\r\n<h3>Opening times:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe museum is open Tuesday-Sunday (10am-5pm)\r\n<br /><br>\r\n<h3>Photography allowed:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, photography is allowed in this museum as well as the temporary exhibition. Please be considerate when using flash however, due to the age of some of the objects (ask a member of staff if you\'re unsure)\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br>\r\n\r\n<h3>Interactive technology:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, this museum features interactive technologies which help visitors to explore Morris’ life and his relationship with the local area in Walthamstow.\r\n<br /><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h2>1. St James’s Silk Damask: </h2> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>St James’s Silk Damask <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis beautifully striking piece of fabric holds an incredible and royal history! Designed by William Morris in 1883 this luxurious fabric was designed for the Armoury and Tapestry rooms in St James’s Place in London, which of course made it a firm favourite amongst his other customers as well. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe fabric had multiple uses, and could be used for wall-coverings, curtains or as a background for embroidery however, its most important use may very well be when the fabric was used to reupholster George V’s coronation throne in 1911! A copy of Morris and Co’s catalogue ‘The Coronation Thrones and Other Royal Furniture’ below the silk shows and image of the stunning reupholstered throne where the fabric most definitely is the most striking feature! \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>2. Circular Chair (Late 1850s): </h2> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Circular Chair<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI know what youre thinking, why on earth am I mentioning a chair? Well, this chair is an incredible and ‘hidden’ piece of history, which through a modern-day eye is a discreet symbol of Morris’ rejection of Victorian convention and his interpretation of re-thinking furniture design. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThis chair was a one-off and was designed by Morris’ for his London lodgings when he first moved to the city, and its solid construction and painted panels were designed to recreate a medieval look, which would continue to inspire Wallis’ creations. The chair was created to protest against the highly finished and elaborate designs of furniture which were in fashion during this time, and Morris’ attempt to create a unique yet classic design, which was to become the theme of the arts and crafts movement. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h2>3. The Titanic Fabric (1912): </h2> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Titanic Fabric<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the early twentieth Century, Morris and Co had designed a beautiful green furnishing fabric called ‘Utrecht Velvet’. The woven mohair pile, stamped with floral designs, was a hardwearing fabric which made it suitable for upholstery. \r\n\r\n<br> <br>\r\n\r\nIts design, colour and feel made it internationally appealing and a popular commercial choice, so it is therefore, unsurprising that it was used to furnish the first-class accommodations aboard the RMS Titanic in 1912. A section of the fabric can be seen on display at the Gallery, and above it a picture of a first-class cabin aboard the Titanic where the fabric stands out amongst the grandeur of the room. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image4b-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Titanic Fabric<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Facilities for kids:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nAs previously mentioned, this museum features interactive technology which is ideal for children, as well as interactive activities for children to engage with the processes used to create some of the objects apart of the arts and crafts movement and histories. The museum also offers family events, so please see the link below for more information: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.wmgallery.org.uk/whats-on/at-a-glance\">Click Here</a> \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h3>Food and Drink facilities:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, there is a restaurant/ tea room called ‘The Larder’ at the Gallery where breakfast, lunch and afternoon tea are served. The Tea Room is open Tuesday to Sunday (10am-4:30pm).\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<h3>Guides:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA guide book can be purchased for £3 upon entry to the museum, and knowledgeable attendants are in most of rooms within the museum should you need any help or like to know more about any of the exhibits.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br /><br>\r\n\r\n<h3>Tours:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nCuratorial tours are available upon booking a group visit to the gallery at a set price, please see the link below for more information. \r\n<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.wmgallery.org.uk/visit/group-visits\">Tours</a>\r\n<br>\r\nFree introductory community welcome tours are also available to registered charities, social enterprises and constituted charitable groups in Waltham Forest and neighbouring boroughs. \r\n<br>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.wmgallery.org.uk/visit/community-welcome-tours\">Community Tours</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>William Morris Gallery<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Nearest station/Tube:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe nearest station to the gallery is Walthamstow Central, which is an approximately 12-15-minute walk away. \r\n\r\n<h3>Bus routes:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nFrom Walthamstow Central station take buses: \r\n34, 97, 215, 275 or 357 to Bell Corner (5-6 minutes). \r\n<br>\r\nFor more information on travel and directions to the gallery, please see the link below. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.wmgallery.org.uk/visit/getting-here\">Travel/Directions</a>\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n<h3>Postcode/address:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nWilliam Morris Gallery, Lloyd Park, Forest Road, London E17 4PP.\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA more detailed guide to the Galleries accessibility arrangements is available via the link below. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.accessable.co.uk/venues/william-morris-gallery\">Accessibilty</a>\r\n\r\n \r\n<br>\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nAn induction loop and large print labels are available at reception. Please contact the museum via the links below if you require British Sign Language interpretation to take part in any of the galleries talks and events.\r\n<br>\r\nA BSL introduction to the gallery is also available, as well as a pre-booked speech to text tour. \r\n \r\n\r\n<br>\r\n<h3>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\"> Braille and Touch tours are available by appointment, so please call or email via the number and email below for more in-depth information and booking enquiries: \r\n020 8496 1485 \r\nemail:\r\n<a href=\"mailto:mhairi.muncaster@walthamforest.gov.uk.?Subject=Hello\" target=\"_top\">Send Mail</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/william-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"William Morris Gallery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>William Morris Gallery<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe William Morris Gallery is fully accessible, with an accessible entrance, toilets and lift access to all floors. \r\nThe gallery has three Blue Badge parking bays however, its gates are kept locked to prevent unauthorised parking so therefore, Blue badge holders asked to call the Gallery on the below number upon arrival or in advance. \r\n<br><br>\r\n020 8496 1470 \r\n<br><br>\r\nTwo manual wheelchairs for visitors to borrow so again, please do contact the gallery if you would like to reserve one for your visit.\r\n\r\n', 'william-image1-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1601986', '51.4862408', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(140, 'Sir John Soane\'s Museum', 'Sir John Soane’s museum is a home to an eclectic mix of paintings, architectural pieces and antiquities collected by the famous architect himself throughout his lifetime. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nAiming to bring the nature of the ‘Grand Tour of Europe’ throughout the eighteenth century back to London, Soane collected a plethora of ancient treasures and artefacts which have intricately displayed in a chaotic fashion throughout every inch of the museum. The museum offers a unique experience, and is well worth a visit when visiting the area. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image1-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Sir John Soane’s Museum <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Entry Fee: </h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nFree entry.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Opening times:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nOpen Wednesday to Sunday, 10:00 to 17:00. Last entry at 16:30.\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>Photography allowed:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nNo, unfortunately photography is not allowed in the museum.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<h4>1. Egyptian sarcophagus of King Seti (or Sety) :</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Egyptian sarcophagus of King Seti <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe ancient Egyptian sarcophagus of King Seti (or Sety) located in the catacombs (Ask one of the museum attendants for the fascinating back story – or read our blog post on the museum) \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image2b-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Egyptian sarcophagus of King Seti <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h4>2. Admiral Van Tromp’s barge:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Admiral Van Tromp’s barge <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n‘Admiral Van Tromp’s barge at the entrance to the Texal, 1645’ – an important maritime painting by JMW Turner, which is located in the north drawing room (JMW Turner was a close friend of Soane!) \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>3. 5th-century BC sculpture </h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>5th-century BC sculpture <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nHidden away amongst the jumble of the Colonnade, is a 5th-century BC sculpture of a goddess that originally adorned the Erechtheion (an important temple located opposite the acropolis in ancient Athens) see if you can spot her headless figure! \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Facilities for kids:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nno, there are no specifically dedicated facilities for children in the museum. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Food and Drink facilities:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nno, unfortunately there are no food and drink facilities on sight. However, the museum has partnered with Benugo to offer visitors with discount vouchers for the Fields Bar & Kitchen which is located just opposite the Museum.\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Guides:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA guide book can be purchased for £3 upon entry to the museum, and knowledgeable attendants are in most of rooms within the museum should you need any help or like to know more about any of the exhibits.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Tours:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, tours are available for the private apartments of the Soane family which are not usually open to the public. Tours of the ‘highlights’ of the museum itself are led by an expert curator, and are available for a fee of £12.50 pp. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image7-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Sir John Soanes Museum <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Nearest station/Tube:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nHolborn station is a five-minute walk, and Temple station a 15-minute walk.\r\n\r\n<h4>Bus routes:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nBuses 1, 59, 68, 91, 168, 171, 188, 243, 521, and X68 stop on Kingsway. Buses 8, 25, and 242 stops on High Holborn.\r\n\r\n<h4>Postcode/address:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n13 Lincoln\'s Inn Fields, London WC2A 3BP.\r\n\r\n<br></br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nInduction loops are offered at both the front desk and in the museum shop, and if visitors are attending lectures or museum events then induction loops can be set up before visiting if staff are made aware upon booking. \r\n\r\n<br>\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Blind or partially sighted:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nAudio or touch tours of the museum are available for pre-booking before the visit and large-print copies of exhibition labels and panels are available for borrowing throughout the duration of your visit. The museum also offers a large-print or braille version of our short guide to the museum.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe museum advises visitors to visit during the day, due to their minimal usage of artificial light to preserve the collection. However, torches or additional overhead lighting can be offered to visitors upon their visit. \r\n<br><br>\r\nA guide dog policy has been developed by the museum, through advice from the Guide Dogs Association. If you use an assistance dog, they recommend leaving them with staff in a designated safe space (where they’ll have plenty of water) during your visit. To bring your dog with you into the Museum, you have to be accompanied by a member of staff, both for your dog’s safety and your own. The museum therefore, ask that visitors let staff know before visiting by calling 020 7405 2107. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/sir-john-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Sir John\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Sir John Soanes Museum <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThere is an Internal and external platform lift available for step-free access to the Museum. Please call ahead so that a member of staff can be on hand to operate the lift as, due to the Grade 1 listing, the lift cannot be in a public space.  \r\n<br><br>\r\nIf you are using crutches or a walking stick, you should be able to go everywhere inside the museum. However, some spaces are too narrow for walking frames. If you would like to borrow one of the museums custom wheelchairs, please call ahead and ask.\r\n<br><br> \r\nStandard wheelchairs are usually too big for the narrow corridors and doorways of the museum, so visitors with wheelchairs larger than 41cm wide, 84cm deep and a height of 82cm, will be asked to transfer to one of the museums specially manufactured narrow wheelchairs. The Museum can be narrow and difficult to manoeuvre in; so therefore, require that a member of staff pushes you throughout your visit.\r\n<br><br>\r\nSuch resources are limited so therefore, require that visitors with disabilities call at least 24 hours ahead. To organise your visit, please call 020 7405 2107 \r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors with learning difficulties</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nEasy read information guides developed by members of The Camden Advocacy Project are available from the link below, with printed copies also available to borrow in the museum as well.\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.soane.org/your-visit/accessibility\">Visit/Accessibilty</a>', 'sir-john-image5-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1196586', '51.5170382', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(141, 'Imperial War Museum', 'Founded in 1917, the Imperial War Museum was originally created to record and act as a testimony to the civil and military war effort and sacrifice of the British people and its Empire during the First World War. As the world’s leading museum of war, the Imperial War Museum gives voice to the extraordinary experiences of ordinary people throughout the history of warfare and provides a unique opportunity for visitors to walk in the footsteps of those who sacrificed so much. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nDisplayed across six floors exploring warfare from the First World War up until modern day conflict, the museums vast collection makes for an interesting day out for all the family – Don’t miss it. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/imperial-war-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Imperial War Museum\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Imperial War Museum <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Entry Fee: </h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nMuseum to this entry is free. Temporary exhibitions may however, be subject to a fixed fee.\r\n\r\n<h4>Opening times:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nMonday to Sunday (10am-6pm)\r\n\r\n<h4>Photography allowed:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n– Yes, photography is allowed at this museum. However, please be cautious when using flash due to the age of some of the exhibits. \r\n\r\n<h4>Interactive technology:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, this museum has interactive technology which helps bring to life some complex issues and topics. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Facilities for kids:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, this museum is well equipped to facilitate and educate younger audiences. A £4 guide is available in the museum gift shops which is tailored to children aged 7 up. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>Guides:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nA guidebook is available from the museum giftshops, and an extensive floor plan is available to view on the link below: \r\n<a href=\"https://www.iwm.org.uk/sites/default/files/publicdocument/iwm_floor_plan_2014.pdf \" target=\"_blank\"> Imperial War Museum </a>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Top 3 things not to be missed:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<h4>1. Piece of the Berlin Wall (1989):</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/imperial-war-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Imperial War Museum\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Piece of the Berlin Wall<i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nLocated outside the entrance of the Imperial War Museum, is a small section of the Berlin Wall taken the Leuschnerdamm in the Kreuzberg district that shows the power graffiti by ‘Indiano’ that reads ‘CHANGE YOUR LIFE’.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nFollowing the end of the Second World War, Berlin was divided into four zones of occupation controlled by Britiain, Soviet Union, France and the United States which allowed access to Berlin only available through specific corridors from West Germany. The Soviet Blockade of Berlin in 1948 resulted in the division of the city into two separate units, and a the ‘Berlin wall’ was erected in 1961 to control the two territories causing mass devastation, death and political controversy. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Wall was breached on the evening of 9th November 1989 and was gradually dismantled in stages thereafter, freeing the two zones from opposing control. – don’t miss this incredible piece of European history on your visit to the museum. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>2. V1 flying bomb and V2 rocket (C.1944):</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/imperial-war-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Imperial War Museum\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>V1 flying bomb and V2 rocket <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe V1 flying bomb (also known as a doodle bug) was a notorious weapon of the Second World War, it was first launched to bomb London in June 1944 with the intention to undermine British morale to turn the tide of war in favour of Germany. Thousands of doodlebugs were launched against London, and they subsequently became notorious for their distinct sound and sudden silence before exploding and causing mass devastation on the city. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe V2 rocket was launched in September of the same year and was known for being much larger and more dangerous than the V1 due to its silent nature that continued until its landing. Don’t miss these incredible weapons of War, which contributed to so much of the devastation inflicted on London during the Blitz. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<h4>3. The Lord Ashcroft Gallery </h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/imperial-war-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Imperial War Museum\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Lord Ashcroft Gallery <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlthough this is not an individual exhibit to see, this incredible gallery deserves a mention amongst the top 3 things not to miss at the IWM. As the world’s largest collection of Victoria Crosses, alongside a significant collection of George Crosses, this exhibition tells the story of over 250 extraordinary people who acted with courage and bravery throughout the history of British warfare. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWith the medals and accounts of figures such as Odette Sansom (SOE Agent) and Corporal Matt Croucher to name just a few, this gallery explores the concept of bravery and what motivates people to undertake acts of heroism in the face of conflict. Located on the fifth floor of the museum, this gallery is a must-see for all visitors who wish to have an insight into individual and heroic stories. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h4>Food and Drink facilities:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, there is a café located on the ground floor, open 10am-5:30pm. \r\n<br>\r\n<h4>Tours:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nYes, tours are available at the museum. Please see the link below for more information:  \r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.iwm.org.uk/events/iwm-london-tours\" target=\"_blank\"> Imperial War Museum/Tours </a>\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Nearest station/Tube:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThe nearest tube station is Lambeth North, which is approximately a 10-minute walk from the museum.\r\n\r\n<h4>Bus routes:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nBuses 3, 12, 53, 148, 159, 344, 360, 453 and C10 stop outside the museum. \r\n\r\n<h4>Postcode/address:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nImperial War Museum, Lambeth Rd, London, SE1 6HZ.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/imperial-war-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Imperial War Museum\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Imperial War Museum <i>Source: Wikimedia Commons. </i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Accessibility:</h3> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nThere are no specific details on accessibility for visitors who are deaf or hard of hearing. Please contact the below number if you have any further enquiries:  Please call 020 7416 5000 to book.\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors who are Deaf or hard of hearing:</h4> <p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nGuide and assistance dogs are welcome in the museum and large print texts guides are available for certain exhibitions. Please ask the information desk on level 0 for more information. \r\n<br><br>\r\nA BSL introductory film with subtitles is available at the start of the First World War Galleries, as well as tactile exhibits. (Also available in the Holocaust Exhibition) \r\n<br><br>\r\nAudio descriptive handset guides, as well as descriptive tours of the First World War galleries are available. (again, please ask at the information desk or book in advance on the below number) \r\n020 7091 3157 \r\n \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n\r\n<h4>Visitors with Mobility Impairments:</h4><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\nStep-free access to the museum is available via the West Entrance, and free parking is available on site for blue badge holders (spaces are subject to availability, so please call the number 020 7416 5000 at least two working days in advance).\r\n\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n\r\nLifts are wheelchair accessible with braille signage, and wheelchairs are also available for loan (again, please phone the above number to book in advance).', 'imperial-war-image1-mobile.jpg', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.1940006', '51.5157811', 1, 1, 4, 0, 'London, United Kingdom', ''),
(142, 'Wojtek ‘the Soldier Bear’ Memorial', 'In Princes Street Gardens just of Princes Street you will find Wojtek the Soldier Bear memorial. Unveiled on November 7th 2015 the bronze statue commemorates Wojtek a brown bear as well as the Polish soldiers who fought in WW2. \r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\nThe story begins in Iran in 1942 when members of the Polish 2nd Corps adopted an orphaned bear cub.  He quickly became one of the men, drinking beer, wrestling with the soldiers and swimming but more importantly he became a valuable resource in carrying supplies.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/wojtek-image1-mobile.jpg\r\n\" alt=\"Wojtek\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><qWojtek the Soldier Bear  <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nDue to a rule forbidding soldiers taking pets to the front lines he was enlisted in the 22nd Artillery Transport Company of the 2nd Corps and given the rank of Private, he had his own identification number and paybook. \r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\nAt the Battle of Monte Cassino Wojtek was kept back near an artillery firing line and was observed to carry crates of shells back and forward to the gun emplacements. So enamoured were the Polish soldiers of Wojtek that the image of a bear carrying an artillery shell became the official emblem of the 22nd Company.\r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\nWhen the war ended in 1945 Wojtek was transported to Berwickshire Scotland with the rest of the 22nd Company and upon demobilization in 1947 he was passed to Edinburgh Zoo where he lived until his death in 1963.  \r\n\r\n<br><br> \r\n\r\n\r\nWojtek is still fondly remembered both by the Poles and Scottish alike and the memorial in Edinburgh is a fitting tribute to the brave Polish forces of WW2 and of one very special bear.', 'wojtek-image1-mobile.jpg\r\n', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-3.202096', '55.950781', 1, 1, 2, 0, 'Edinburgh, UK', ''),
(143, 'Kensal Green Cemetery', 'Located in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea, Kensal Green Cemetery was first opened in 1833 and is special for not only being the first of the ‘Magnificent Seven’ to be built, but also because it was London’s first ever commercial cemetery. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlthough primarily a cemetery and crematorium, Kensal Green also holds two separate conservation areas in its grounds, which have consequently attracted thirty-three different species of bird as well as an array of wildlife, trees and plants.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image1-mobile.JPG\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Kensal Green Cemetary <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nMany have called Kensal Green Cemetery ‘The Belgravia of Death’ for its prestigious register of aristocrats, royalty, and endless notable figures, and it has also been noted by many as being the most remarkable of all seven cemeteries for its beautiful array of architectural styles, tombs and catacombs – all of which we will now explore in the top five things you cannot miss at Kensal Green Cemetery. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nTop 5 must see sights at Kensal Green Cemetery\r\n\r\n<h3>1. The Catacombs:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image2-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Catacombs <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nFascinatingly, Kensal Green Cemetery is home to three separate Catacombs systems which makes it unique amongst the other cemeteries of its kind. The first, Catacomb A, is located beneath the North Terrance Colonnade which is unfortunately now sealed off. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe second, Catacomb Z is beneath the Dissenters’ Chapel and suffered significant bomb damage during the Second World War which means it too, is closed to further deposits.  Lastly, located in the centre of the cemetery beneath the Anglican Chapel is Catacomb B, although this catacomb is currently not maintained by the cemetery staff, it can be visited as a part of a guided tour of the cemetery. \r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Chapel also has a working coffin-lift (catafalque) which was restored by The Friends of Kensal Green Cemetery in 1997.\r\n\r\n \r\n<h3>2. The Grave of Charles Blondin (1824-1897):</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image3-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Grave of Charles Blondin <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\nBorn in 1824 in St Omer, France, Charles Blondin was a famed tightrope walker and acrobat. Blondin toured the United States of American in 1885 and owed his fame to crossing the 1,100ft Niagara Falls Gorge on a tightrope in 1859. Blondin repeated this challenge several times, often including theatrical variations into the routine, such as being blindfolded, on stilts and even carrying a man (his manager Harry Colcord) on his back!\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 1861 he appeared at the Crystal Palace in London, with a routine of somersaults on stilts again, on a tightrope and continued his routine throughout the UK. In 1897, Blondin sadly died of diabetes at the age of 72 and was buried in Kensal Green Cemetery alongside his second wife, Charlotte Lawrence. \r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. West London Crematorium:</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image4-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>West London Crematorium <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nLike many other cemeteries, Kensal Green Cemetery is also home to the famous ‘West London Crematorium’ which was developed in the eastern part of the grounds in 1939. \r\n<br><br>\r\nSimilarly maintained by the General Cemetery company, the crematorium has played its part in a number of notable cremations which include Hollywood icon Ingrid Bergman (1915-1982), actor and director Alan Rickman (1946-2016) and lead singer of Queen Freddie Mercury (1946-1991) who is commemorated by a small plinth under his real name, Farrokh Bulsara. \r\n\r\n<h3>4. The Sarcophagus of Princess Sophia (1777-1848)</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image5-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>The Sarcophagus of Princess Sophia <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDaughter of King George III (Mad King George) and Queen Charlotte, Princess Sophia was born in 1777 and led a relatively cloistered life due to her father’s possessiveness (as he preferred his daughters to his sons) and insanity and mother’s strictness. When her father died, Princess Sophia was allowed greater freedom under the Regency of her brother, the Prince of Wales, although she still could not escape the royal institution through marriage. \r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\nSophia fell deeply in love with Major-General Thomas Garth who was a British Army officer and chief equerry to her father King George III, and it was believed that during the winter of 1799 at Windsor Castle Sophia conceived his illegitimate son Thomas Garth junior (1800-1873). \r\n<br><br>\r\nIn her final years, Sophia resided in the household of Princess Victoria of Kent (the future Queen Victoria) where Victoria’s infamous comptroller, Sir John Convoy, who took advantage of her senility and blindness by bullying her into spying on both the Kensington household, as well her two brothers, all whilst he stole most of her inheritance.\r\n<br><br>\r\nSophia sadly died in 1848 at Kensington Palace and was buried in Kensal Green Cemetery upon her wish to be near her brother, Prince Augustus Frederick who lies on the opposite side of the path.\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n<h3>5. Dissenters’ Chapel and The Reformers Memorial</h3><p class=\"text-justify\">\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image6-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Dissenters’ Chapel and The Reformers Memorial <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nLocated in the E corner of the cemetery is the Greek revival ‘Dissenter Chapel’, which was built for all non-Anglican denominations/ non-believers. Since the cemetery was a favoured spot for nonconformists, free-thinkers and atheists etc, this chapel became the ‘it’ place for a number of them to be buried in, which was unique for the period. \r\n<br><br>\r\nThe chapel is currently being used as the office for the Friends of Kensal Green Cemetery, however it can also be used for secular and dissenting funeral services. Following on from the Dissenters’ Chapel is The Reformers’ Memorial which was erected in 1885 by Joseph Corfield, in memorial ‘to the memory of men and women who had generously given their time and means to improve the conditions and enlarge the happiness of all classes of society’. \r\n<br><br>\r\nComprised of 75 social reformers and activists, the memorial is a testimony to a plethora of incredible people who used their positions to try a shape Victorian society for the better. The Reformers’ Memorial is located in the non-conformist section of the cemetery, which was created to be a burial area for those who did not conform to the governance of usages of the established Church of England. \r\n<br><br>\r\nAs previously mentioned, many of those ‘non-conformists’ were radicals, atheists such as Elizabeth Fry, William Cobbett and Robert Owen. \r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://hidden-history.com/public/assets/images/kensal-green-image-mobile.jpg\" alt=\"Kensal Green Cemetery\">\r\n<br>\r\n<sub><q>Kensal Green Cemetary <i>Source: Wikicommons.</i></q></sub>\r\n<br><br>', 'kensal-green-image1-mobile.JPG', 1, 0, 0, 0, '-0.2195541', '51.528066', 1, 1, 1, 0, 'London, UK', '');
